=2003}}\n* {{cite book|last=Tracy|first=Walter|author-link=Walter Tracy|title=Letters of Credit: A View of Type Design|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y8NssjbqNcsC&pg=PA194|date=2003|publisher=D.R. Godine|isbn=978-1-56792-240-0}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*Berthold pages: [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-book/proplus/ AG Book Pro+], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-book-rounded/proplus/ AG Book Rounded], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-book-stencil-et-al/pro/ AG Book Stencil et al], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-old-face/pro/ AG Old Face], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-schoolbook/pro/ AG Schoolbook], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/akzidenz-grotesk/proplus/ Akzidenz-Grotesk Pro+], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/akzidenz-grotesk-next-family/pro/ Akzidenz-Grotesk Next]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110719030422/http://www.sanskritweb.net/fontdocs/#Akzidenz Akzidenz Grotesk sample books] digitised by Ulrich Stiehl\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/n1ke/albums/72157629429950223 Berthold specimens from c. 1913], showing Schattierte-Grotesk and co-branding mentioning Berthold and Bauer\n* ''Fonts in Use'' coverage: [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/76/akzidenz-grotesk Akzidenz-Grotesk], [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/31705/akzidenz-grotesk-condensed AG Condensed], [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/7248/ag-book AG Book], [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/574/standard Standard] (for American uses)\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/stewf/sets/72157661987768480 Probe 429A] (c. 1960 specimen, photographed by Stephen Coles/Thomas Maier)\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/101656904@N05/sets/72157679746685343 Berthold exklusiv 013: Akzidenz-Grotesk] (1980s Berthold specimen, for phototypesetting)\n* [http://magazines.iaddb.org/issue/GG/1937-08-01/edition/null/page/5 Berthold advertisement from 1937] not showing Akzidenz-Grotesk. The advert showcases \"modern and successful\" faces, illustrating the eclipse of Akzidenz-Grotesk in this period.\n* [http://magazines.iaddb.org/issue/GG/1959-01-01/edition/null/page/68 1959 advert] announcing the arrival of Akzidenz-Grotesk on the Linotype hot metal system\n\n[[Category:Berthold typefaces]]\n[[Category:Grotesque sans-serif typefaces]]\n[[Category:Letterpress typefaces]]\n[[Category:Photocomposition typefaces]]\n[[Category:Typefaces with infant variants]]\n[[Category:Digital typefaces]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1898]]\n[[Category:Linotype typefaces]]\n", "name_user": "Blythwood", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add a source here", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akzidenz-Grotesk"}
{"title_page": "Jehovah's Witnesses", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|Christian denomination}}\n{{Infobox Christian denomination\n| name          = Jehovah's Witnesses\n| image         = Jw headquart.jpg\n| imagewidth    =\n| caption       = World headquarters in [[Warwick, New York|Warwick]], New York\n| main_classification = [[Restorationism|Restorationist]]\n| structure     = [[Organizational structure of Jehovah's Witnesses|Hierarchical]]<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Cobb v. Brede |court=California Superior Court, San Mateo County|date=February 22, 2012|quote=I am general counsel for the National Organization of Jehovah's Witnesses out of Brooklyn, New York. ... We are a hierarchical religion structured just like the Catholic Church}}</ref>\n| orientation   = [[Premillennialism|Premillennialist]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2019|page=164|isbn=9781538119525|quote=Jehovah's Witnesses are pre-millennialist}}</ref>\n| theology      =  [[Nontrinitarianism|Nontrinitarian]]\n| founder       = [[Charles Taze Russell]]<ref name=\"Gale\" />\n| founded_date  = 1870s\n| founded_place = [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|headquarters  = [[Warwick, New York|Warwick]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| governance    = [[Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses|Governing Body]]\n| branched_from = [[Bible Student movement]]\n| separations   = [[Jehovah's Witnesses splinter groups]]\n| area          = Worldwide\n| congregations = 119,712\n| members       = 8,683,117\n| footnotes     = Statistics from ''2019 Grand Totals''<ref name=\"report2018\" />\n| website       = {{URL|https://jw.org/}}\n}}\n\n'''Jehovah's Witnesses''' is a [[Millenarianism|millenarian]] [[Restorationism|restorationist]] [[Christian cult]] with [[Nontrinitarianism|nontrinitarian]] beliefs distinct from mainstream [[Christianity]].<ref>Sources for descriptors:\n*''Millenarian'': {{cite book|last=Beckford|first=James A.|authorlink=James A. Beckford|title=The Trumpet of Prophecy: A Sociological Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Basil Blackwell|location=Oxford|year=1975|isbn=978-0-631-16310-7|ref=harv|pages=118\u2013119, 151, 200\u2013201}}\n*''Restorationist'': {{cite journal|last1=Stark|first1=Rodney|last2=Iannaccone|first2=Laurence R.|authorlink1=Rodney Stark|authorlink2=Laurence Iannaccone|title=Why the Jehovah's Witnesses Grow so Rapidly: A Theoretical Application|journal=[[Journal of Contemporary Religion]]|date=1997|volume=12|issue=2|pages=133\u2013157|doi=10.1080/13537909708580796|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/6295/f3db6a97bbd6909aa18df688e24a8fe945a9.pdf|accessdate=December 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228112238/https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/6295/f3db6a97bbd6909aa18df688e24a8fe945a9.pdf|archive-date=December 28, 2017|url-status=dead}}\n*''Christian'': {{cite web|title=Who is a Christian?|url=http://www.religioustolerance.org/chr_defn.htm|website=www.religioustolerance.org|publisher=[[Ontario Consultants on Religious Tolerance]]|accessdate=December 27, 2017}} {{cite web|title=Religious Landscape Study|url=http://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study|website=Pew Research Center's Religion & Public Life Project|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|accessdate=December 27, 2017|date=May 11, 2015}}{{cite book|title=World Almanac and Book of Facts|publisher=Infobase Learning|location=New York, NY|year=2011|isbn=978-1-60057-133-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/worldalmanacbook01newy/page/704 704\u2013705]|url=https://archive.org/details/worldalmanacbook01newy/page/704}}\n*''Denomination'': {{cite news|title=Jehovah's Witnesses at a glance|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/witnesses/ataglance/glance.shtml|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[BBC]]|date=September 29, 2009}}{{cite web|title=Jehovah's Witness|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/Jehovah's+Witness|website=TheFreeDictionary.com|publisher=[[The American Heritage Dictionary]]|accessdate=December 27, 2017}}{{cite web|title=Imprisoned for Their Faith: Jehovah's Witnesses in Auschwitz|url=http://auschwitz.org/en/museum/news/imprisoned-for-their-faith-jehovahs-witnesses-in-auschwitz,351.html|website=auschwitz.org|publisher=[[Auschwitz-Birkenau State Museum]]|accessdate=December 27, 2017|date=February 5, 2004}}</ref> The group reports a worldwide membership of approximately 8.68&nbsp;million adherents involved in [[evangelism]] and an annual [[Jehovah's Witnesses practices#Memorial of Christ's death|Memorial]] attendance of over 20&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"report2018\">{{cite web|title=2019 Grand Totals|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2019|url=https://www.jw.org/en/library/books/2019-service-year-report/2019-grand-totals/}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses are directed by the [[Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses]], a group of [[Elder (Christianity)#Jehovah's Witnesses|elders]] in [[Warwick, New York|Warwick]], New York, United States, which establishes all doctrines<ref>{{cite book|last=Beckford|first=James A.|authorlink=James A. Beckford|title=The Trumpet of Prophecy: A Sociological Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Basil Blackwell|location=Oxford|year=1975|isbn=978-0-631-16310-7|ref=harv|pages=221|quote=Doctrine has always emanated from the Society's elite in Brooklyn and has never emerged from discussion among, or suggestion from, rank-and-file Witnesses.}}</ref> based on its interpretations of the [[Bible]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|editor=Paul Lagasse|title=Jehovah's Witnesses|encyclopedia=The Columbia Encyclopedia|url=https://archive.org/details/columbiaencyclop00laga|edition=6th|year=2000|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-7876-5015-5|quote=The Witnesses base their teaching on the Bible}}</ref><ref name=\"Penton 1997 61\u201362\" /> They believe that the destruction of the present world system at [[Armageddon]] is imminent, and that the establishment of [[Kingship and kingdom of God|God's kingdom]] over the earth is the only solution for all problems faced by humanity.<ref name=\"Britannica Concise Encyclopedia\">{{cite book|title=Britannica Concise Encyclopedia|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.|year=2007|chapter=Jehovah's Witness|isbn=978-1-59339-293-2}}</ref>\n\nThe group emerged from the [[Bible Student movement]] founded in the late 1870s by [[Charles Taze Russell]], who also co-founded [[Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|Zion's Watch Tower Tract Society]] in 1881 to organize and print the movement's publications.<ref name=\"Gale\">{{cite encyclopedia|editor=Stanley I. Kutler|editor-link=Stanley Kutler|title=Jehovah's Witnesses|encyclopedia=Dictionary of American History|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/philosophy-and-religion/christianity/protestant-denominations/jehovahs-witnesses#1G23401802183|edition=3rd|year=2003|publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons|location=New York|isbn=978-0-684-80533-7}}</ref> A [[Watch Tower Society presidency dispute (1917)|leadership dispute]] after Russell's death resulted in several groups breaking away, with [[Joseph Franklin Rutherford]] retaining control of the Watch Tower Society and its properties.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Embryonic State of a Religious Sect's Development: The Jehovah's Witnesses|journal=Sociological Yearbook of Religion in Britain|editor=Michael Hill|year=1972|issue=5|pages=11\u201312|quote=Joseph Franklin Rutherford succeeded to Russell's position as President of Zion's Watch Tower Tract Society, but only at the expense of antagonizing a large proportion of the Watch Towers subscribers. Nevertheless, he persisted in moulding the Society to suit his own programme of activist evangelism under systematic central control, and he succeeded in creating the administrative structure of the present-day sect of Jehovah's Witnesses.}}</ref> Rutherford made significant organizational and doctrinal changes, including adoption of the name ''Jehovah's witnesses''<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=1 November 1961|page=654|title=Bearers of the Fear-inspiring Name|publisher=Watch Tower Society|quote=in 1931, ... embracing the name ... Jehovah's witnesses}}</ref><ref group=\"note\">Based on [https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=isaiah+43%3A10-12&version=ASV Isaiah 43:10&ndash;12 (ASV)], the name was restyled as Jehovah's Witnesses (with capital W) in the 1970s.</ref> in 1931 to distinguish them from other Bible Student groups and symbolize a break with the legacy of [[Charles Taze Russell#Theology and teachings|Russell's traditions]].<ref name=\"name1\" /><ref name=\"name2\" /><ref name=\"name3\" /><ref>{{cite journal|author=Leo P. Chall|title=Sociological Abstracts|volume=26|issue=1\u20133|journal=Sociology of Religion|year=1978|page=193|quote=Rutherford, through the Watch Tower Society, succeeded in changing all aspects of the sect from 1919 to 1932 and created Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014a charismatic offshoot of the Bible student community.}}</ref>\n\nJehovah's Witnesses are best known for their door-to-door preaching, distributing literature such as ''[[The Watchtower]]'' and ''[[Awake!]]'', and for refusing [[military service]] and [[blood transfusion]]s. They consider the use of [[Names of God in Christianity|God's name]] vital for proper worship. They reject [[Trinity|Trinitarianism]], [[Christian conditionalism|inherent immortality]] of the [[Soul (spirit)|soul]], and [[Christian views on Hell|hellfire]], which they consider to be unscriptural doctrines. They do not observe [[Christmas]], [[Easter]], [[birthday]]s or other holidays and customs they consider to have [[paganism|pagan]] origins incompatible with Christianity.<ref>{{cite book|author=Franz, Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|pages=274\u20135|isbn=978-0-914675-16-7}}</ref> They prefer to use their own Bible translation, the ''[[New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures]]'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Edwards|first=Linda|title=A Brief Guide to Beliefs|publisher=Westminster John Knox Press|year=2001|location=Louisville, Kentucky|pages=[https://archive.org/details/unset0000unse_s5t3/page/438 438]|isbn=978-0-664-22259-8|quote=The Jehovah's Witnesses' interpretation of Christianity and their rejection of orthodoxy influenced them to produce their own translation of the Bible, ''The New World Translation''.|url=https://archive.org/details/unset0000unse_s5t3/page/438}}</ref> although their literature occasionally quotes and cites other Bible translations.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=When Was Ancient Jerusalem Destroyed?\u2014Part One|magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 2011|page=26|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2011736|quote=Jehovah's Witnesses produce a reliable Bible translation known as the ''New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures''. However, if you are not one of Jehovah's Witnesses, you may prefer to use other translations when considering Bible subjects. This article quotes from a number of widely accepted Bible translations.}}</ref><ref>Chryssides, George D. ''Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses'', pg. 100 \"Although it is the preferred translation by the Witnesses, they remain willing to use other translations in house-to-house ministry and in countries where a NWT has not yet been published\".</ref> Adherents commonly refer to their body of beliefs as \"The Truth\" and consider themselves to be \"in the Truth\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Singelenberg|first=Richard|title=It Separated the Wheat From the Chaff: The 1975 Prophecy and its Impact Among Dutch Jehovah's Witnesses|journal=Sociological Analysis|volume=50|issue=Spring 1989|pages=23\u201340|year=1989|quote='The Truth' is Witnesses' jargon, meaning the Society's belief system.|doi=10.2307/3710916|jstor=3710916}}</ref> They consider secular [[society]] to be morally corrupt and under the influence of [[Satan]], and most limit their social interaction with non-Witnesses.<ref>{{cite book|last=Penton|first=M.J.|authorlink=James Penton|title=Apocalypse Delayed: The Story of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1997|isbn=978-0-8020-7973-2|ref=harv|pages=280\u2013283|quote=Most Witnesses tend to think of society outside their own community as decadent and corrupt ... This in turn means to Jehovah's Witnesses that they must keep themselves apart from Satan's 'doomed system of things.' Thus most tend to socialize largely, although not totally, within the Witness community.}}</ref> [[Church discipline|Congregational disciplinary actions]] include ''[[Jehovah's Witnesses and congregational discipline#Disfellowshipping|disfellowshipping]]'', their term for formal expulsion and [[shunning]], a last resort for what they consider serious offences.<ref>{{cite book|last=Chryssides|first=George D.|authorlink=George Chryssides|title=Exploring New Religions|publisher=Continuum|year=1999|location=London|pages=5|isbn=978-0-8264-5959-6|quote=The Jehovah's Witnesses are well known for their practice of 'disfellowshipping' wayward members.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses: Continuity and Change|last=Chryssides|first=George D.|publisher=Routledge|year=2016|isbn=9781409456087|location=|pages=139, 140|quote=The transgressor is invariably given the opportunity to repent and to be counselled for his or her weaknesses: disfellowshipping is a last resort, and is effectively a formal recognition that a Witness has placed himself or herself beyond the pale, and does not accept the fundamental teachings and practices of the organisation.}}</ref> Baptized individuals who formally leave are considered ''disassociated'' and are also shunned. Disfellowshipped and disassociated individuals may eventually be reinstated if deemed repentant.<ref name=\"shepherd\">{{cite book|title=Shepherd the Flock of God|page=119|publisher=Watch Tower Society|quote=The committee should be careful to allow sufficient time, perhaps many months, a year, or even longer, for the disfellowshipped person to prove that his profession of repentance is genuine.}}</ref>\n\nThe group's position regarding [[Conscientious objector|conscientious objection]] to military service and refusal to [[salute]] state symbols (like [[national anthem]]s and [[flag]]s) has brought it into conflict with some governments.<ref name=aa>{{cite web|author=|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201306170026.html |title=Tanzania: Dons Fault Court Over Suspension of Students (Page 1 of 2) |publisher=allAfrica.com |date=June 17, 2013 |accessdate=June 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=cit>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecitizen.co.tz/magazine/sound-living/-/1843780/1958398/-/s1lvpy/-/index.html |title=How much of our religion must we bring to school? |work=The Citizen |first=Esther |last=Kibakaya |date=August 18, 2013 |accessdate=June 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102008085|title=Flag Salute, Voting, and Civilian Service|work=Watchtower ONLINE LIBRARY|access-date=July 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101983034#h=17|title=Flag Salute, Anthems and Voting|work=Watchtower ONLINE LIBRARY|access-date=July 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Those About to Die|date=1958|first=Daniel P.|last=Mannix|page=135}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Render Unto Caesar, The Flag-Salute Controversy|date=1962|page=32|first=David R.|last=Manwaring}}</ref> Consequently, some Jehovah's Witnesses have been persecuted and their activities are banned or restricted in some countries. Persistent [[Supreme Court cases involving Jehovah's Witnesses by country|legal challenges by Jehovah's Witnesses]] have influenced legislation related to [[Civil and political rights|civil rights]] in several countries.<ref>[[Gary Botting]], ''Fundamental Freedoms and Jehovah's Witnesses'' (Calgary: University of Calgary Press, 1993), pg 1\u201313.</ref>\n\nThe organization has [[Criticism of Jehovah's Witnesses|received criticism]] regarding biblical translation, doctrines, and alleged coercion of its members. The Watch Tower Society has made various unfulfilled predictions about major biblical events such as Christ's [[Second Coming]], the advent of [[God's Kingdom]], and [[Armageddon]]. Their policies for [[Jehovah's Witnesses' handling of child sex abuse|handling cases of child sexual abuse]] have been the subject of various formal inquiries.\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n{{Christianity|expand-nontrinitarian=yes|portalicon=ichthys}}\n\n===Background (1870\u20131916)===\n{{See also|Bible Student movement}}\n[[File:C.T. Russell.gif|left|182px|thumb|[[Charles Taze Russell|Pastor Russell]], founder of the [[Bible Student movement|Watch Tower Society]]]]\nIn 1870, [[Charles Taze Russell]] and others formed a group in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]] to study the Bible.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rogerson|first=Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable & Co, London|year=1969|pages=6|isbn=978-0094559400}}</ref> During the course of his ministry, Russell disputed many beliefs of mainstream Christianity including immortality of the soul, hellfire, predestination, the fleshly return of Jesus Christ, the Trinity, and the burning up of the world.<ref name=\"beckford1874\">{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|page=2}}</ref> In 1876, Russell met [[Nelson H. Barbour]]; later that year they jointly produced the book ''[[Three Worlds (book)|Three Worlds]],'' which combined restitutionist views with [[end time]] prophecy. The book taught that God's dealings with humanity were divided [[Dispensationalism|dispensationally]], each ending with a \"harvest,\" that Christ had returned as an invisible spirit being in 1874<ref name=\"beckford1874\" /> inaugurating the \"harvest of the Gospel age,\" and that 1914 would mark the end of a 2520-year period called \"the Gentile Times,\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Crompton|first=Robert|title=Counting the Days to Armageddon|publisher=James Clarke & Co|year=1996|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-227-67939-5|pages=37\u201339}}</ref> at which time world society would be replaced by the full establishment of God's kingdom on earth.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Bible Examiner|date=October 1876|title=Gentile Times: When Do They End? |pages=27\u201328 |quote=The seven times will end in A.D. 1914; when Jerusalem shall be delivered forever ... when Gentile Governments shall have been dashed to pieces; when God shall have poured out of his fury upon the nations and they acknowledge him King of Kings and Lord of Lords.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Studies in the Scriptures|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1897|page=xii|volume=IV The Battle of Armageddon}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Time is at Hand|last=Russell|first=Charles|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society |year=1889|page=101}}</ref> Beginning in 1878 Russell and Barbour jointly edited a religious journal, ''Herald of the Morning''.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|last1=Botting|first1=Heather|last2=Botting|first2=Gary|publisher=University of Toronto Press |year=1884|page=36}}</ref> In June 1879 the two split over doctrinal differences, and in July, Russell began publishing the magazine ''[[The Watchtower|Zion's Watch Tower and Herald of Christ's Presence]]'',<ref name=\"Holden18\">{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=18}}</ref> stating that its purpose was to demonstrate that the world was in \"the last days,\" and that a new age of earthly and human restitution under the reign of Christ was imminent.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Zion's Watch Tower|date=July 1, 1879|page=1 |title=Prospectus|quote=This is the first number of the first volume of \"Zion's Watch Tower,\" and it may not be amiss to state the object of its publication. That we are living \"in the last days\"\u2014\"the day of the Lord\"\u2014\"the end\" of the Gospel age, and consequently, in the dawn of a \"new\" age. }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1879, ''Watch Tower'' supporters gathered as autonomous congregations to study the Bible topically. Thirty congregations were founded, and during 1879 and 1880, Russell visited each to provide the format he recommended for conducting meetings.<ref>{{cite book|title=1975 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|chapter=Part 1 &mdash; United States of America|year=1975|page=38|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/301975002}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Zion's Watch Tower|date=September 1884|pages=7\u20138|title=The Ecclesia.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Russell|first=Charles|title=Studies in the Scriptures|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1904|volume=VI The New Creation|pages=195\u2013272}}</ref> In 1881, ''Zion's Watch Tower Tract Society'' was presided over by [[William Henry Conley]], and in 1884, Russell incorporated the society as a non-profit business to distribute tracts and Bibles.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Russell|first=Charles |magazine=Zion's Watch Tower|date=April 25, 1894 |title=A Conspiracy Exposed |pages=55\u201360 |quote=This is a business association merely ... it has no creed or confession ... it is merely a business convenience in disseminating the truth. }}</ref><ref>''Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses'' by [[George D. Chryssides]], Scarecrow Press, 2008, page xxxiv, \"Russell wanted to consolidate the movement he had started. ...In 1880, Bible House, a four-story building in Allegheny, was completed, with printing facilities and meeting accommodation, and it became the organization's headquarters. The next stage of institutionalization was legal incorporation. In 1884, Russell formed the Zion's Watch Tower Tract Society, which was incorporated in Pennsylvania... Russell was concerned that his supporters should feel part of a unified movement.\"</ref><ref>''Religion in the Twentieth Century'' by Vergilius Ture Anselm Ferm, Philosophical Library, 1948, page 383, \"As the [unincorporated Watch Tower] Society expanded, it became necessary to incorporate it and build a more definite organization. In 1884, a charter was granted recognizing the Society as a religious, non-profit corporation.\"</ref> By about 1900, Russell had organized thousands of part- and full-time [[colporteur]]s,<ref name=\"Holden18\" /> and was appointing foreign [[missionaries]] and establishing branch offices. By the 1910s, Russell's organization maintained nearly a hundred \"pilgrims,\" or traveling preachers.<ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=19}}</ref> Russell engaged in significant global publishing efforts during his ministry,<ref>''A Chronology and Glossary of Propaganda in the United States'' Greenwood Press: 1996. pg. 35: \"Russell is naturally media literate, and the amount of literature he circulates proves staggering. Books, booklets, and tracts are distributed by the hundreds of millions. This is supplemented by well-publicized speaking tours and a masterful press relations effort, which gives him widespread access to general audiences.\"</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=26\u201329}}</ref> and by 1912, he was the most distributed Christian author in the United States.<ref>''The Overland Monthly'', January 1910 pg. 130</ref><ref>W.T. Ellis, ''The Continent'', McCormick Publishing Company, vol. 43, no. 40, October 3, 1912 pg. 1354</ref>\n\nRussell moved the Watch Tower Society's headquarters to [[Brooklyn]], New York, in 1909, combining printing and corporate offices with a house of worship; volunteers were housed in a nearby residence he named ''Bethel''. He identified the religious movement as \"Bible Students,\" and more formally as the [[Bible Student movement#International Bible Students Association|International Bible Students Association]].<ref>''Religious Diversity and American Religious History'' by Walter H. Conser, Sumner B. Twiss, University of Georgia Press, 1997, page 136, \"The Jehovah's Witnesses...has maintained a very different attitude toward history. Established initially in the 1870s by Charles Taze Russell under the title International Bible Students Association, this organization has proclaimed...\"</ref> By 1910, about 50,000 people worldwide were associated with the movement<ref>The New Schaff\u2013Herzog Encyclopedia of Religious Knowledge, 1910, vol 7, pg 374</ref> and congregations re-elected him annually as their \"pastor.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=26}}</ref> Russell died October 31, 1916, at the age of 64 while returning from a ministerial speaking tour.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rogerson|first=Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable & Co, London|year=1969|page=31|isbn=978-0094559400}}</ref>\n\n===Reorganization (1917\u20131942)===\n[[File:J.F. Rutherford.gif|thumb|right|182px|[[Joseph Franklin Rutherford|Joseph F. Rutherford]], founder of Jehovah's Witnesses]]\nIn January 1917, the Watch Tower Society's legal representative, [[Joseph Franklin Rutherford]], was elected as its next president. His [[Watch Tower Society presidency dispute (1917)|election was disputed]], and members of the Board of Directors accused him of acting in an autocratic and secretive manner.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=53}}</ref><ref>A.N. Pierson et al., ''Light After Darkness'', 1917, page 4.</ref> The divisions between his supporters and opponents triggered a major turnover of members over the next decade.<ref name=\"Penton 1997 61\u201362\" >{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=58,&nbsp;61\u201362}}</ref><ref name=\"crompton101\" >{{cite book|last=Crompton|first=Robert|title=Counting the Days to Armageddon|publisher=James Clarke & Co|year=1996|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-227-67939-5|pages=101\n}}</ref> In June 1917, he released ''The Finished Mystery'' as a seventh volume of Russell's ''[[Studies in the Scriptures]]'' series. The book, published as the posthumous work of Russell, was a compilation of his commentaries on the Bible books of [[Book of Ezekiel|Ezekiel]] and [[Book of Revelation|Revelation]], plus numerous additions by Bible Students Clayton Woodworth and George Fisher.<ref>{{Citation|title = The Bible Students Monthly|volume = 9|issue = 9|pages = 1, 4| quote=The following article is extracted mainly from Pastor Russell's posthumous volume entitled \"THE FINISHED MYSTERY,\" the 7th in the series of his STUDIES IN THE SCRIPTURES and published subsequent to his death.}}</ref><ref>Lawson, John D., ''American State Trials'', vol 13, Thomas Law Book Company, 1921, pg viii: \"After his death and after we were in the war they issued a seventh volume of this series, entitled \"The Finished Mystery,\" which, under the guise of being a posthumous work of Pastor Russell, included an attack on the war and an attack on patriotism, which were not written by Pastor Russell and could not have possibly been written by him.\"</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Crompton|first=Robert|title=Counting the Days to Armageddon|publisher=James Clarke & Co|year=1996|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-227-67939-5|pages=84\u201385|quote=One of Rutherford's first actions as president ... was, without reference either to his fellow directors or to the editorial committee which Russell had nominated in his will, to commission a seventh volume of ''Studies in the Scriptures''. Responsibility for preparing this volume was given to two of Russell's close associates, George H. Fisher and Clayton J. Woodworth. On the face of it, their brief was to edit for publication the notes left by Russell ... and to draw upon his published writings ... It is obvious ... that it was not in any straightforward sense the result of editing Russell's papers, rather it was in large measure the original work of Woodworth and Fisher at the behest of the new president.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Finished Mystery|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1917|chapter-url=http://www.strictlygenteel.co.uk/finishedmystery/fmtitles.html|chapter=Publisher's Preface|quote=But the fact is, he did write it. This book may properly be said to be a posthumous publication of Pastor Russell. Why?... This book is chiefly a compilation of things which he wrote and which have been brought together in harmonious style by properly applying the symbols which he explained to the Church.}}</ref> It strongly criticized Catholic and Protestant clergy and Christian involvement in the [[World War I|Great War]].<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=55}}</ref> As a result, Watch Tower Society directors were jailed for [[sedition]] under the ''[[Espionage Act of 1917|Espionage Act]]'' in 1918 and members were subjected to mob violence; the directors were released in March 1919 and charges against them were dropped in 1920.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rogerson|first=Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable & Co, London|year=1969|page=44|isbn=978-0094559400}}</ref>\n\nRutherford centralized organizational control of the Watch Tower Society. In 1919, he instituted the appointment of a director in each congregation, and a year later all members were instructed to report their weekly preaching activity to the Brooklyn headquarters.<ref name=\"Franz, Raymond 2007\">{{cite book|author=Franz, Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|chapter=Chapter 4|isbn=978-0-914675-16-7}}</ref> At an international convention held at [[Cedar Point]], Ohio, in September 1922, a new emphasis was made on house-to-house preaching.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom|chapter=7. Advertise the King and the Kingdom! (1919-1941)|publisher=Watch Tower Bible & Tract Society|year=1993|pages=72\u201377|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101993008}}</ref> Significant changes in doctrine and administration were regularly introduced during Rutherford's twenty-five years as president, including the 1920 announcement that the Hebrew patriarchs (such as [[Abraham]] and [[Isaac]]) would be resurrected in 1925, marking the beginning of [[Christ]]'s [[Millennialism|thousand-year earthly Kingdom]].<ref name=\"Rutherford1920\">{{cite book|last=Rutherford|first=Joseph F.|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die!|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uFn7PQJeorwC&pg=PA89|year=1920|publisher=International Bible Students Association|location=Brooklyn, New York|isbn=978-1-4116-2898-4|pages=89\u201390}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Chryssides|first=George D.|authorlink=George Chryssides|title=How Prophecy Succeeds: The Jehovah's Witnesses and Prophetic Expectations|journal=International Journal for the Study of New Religions|volume=1|issue=1|pages=27\u201348|year=2010|issn=2041-952X|doi=10.1558/ijsnr.v1i1.27}}</ref><ref name=\"christian144\">{{cite book|last=Franz|first=Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|year=2007|page=144|isbn=978-0-914675-16-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Salvation|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|chapter=|year=1939|page=76|others=as cited in ''Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom''}}</ref> Because of disappointment over the changes and [[Watch Tower Society unfulfilled predictions#1925: Resurrection of the patriarchs|unfulfilled predictions]], tens of thousands of defections occurred during the first half of Rutherford's tenure, leading to the formation of several Bible Student organizations independent of the Watch Tower Society,<ref>{{cite book|last=Rogerson|first=Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable & Co, London|year=1969|pages=39, 52|isbn=978-0094559400}}</ref><ref>Herbert H. Stroup, ''The Jehovah's Witnesses'', Columbia University Press, New York, 1945, pg 14,15: \"Following his election the existence of the movement was threatened as never before. Many of those who remembered wistfully the halcyon days of Mr Russell's leadership found that the new incumbent did not fulfill their expectations of a saintly leader. Various elements split off from the parent body, and such fission continued throughout Rutherford's leadership.\"</ref><ref name=\"Penton, 1997, 58\" >{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=wmsdmva7u6kC&id=38SYXalMLeQC&pg=PA58 58], [https://books.google.com/books?id=wmsdmva7u6kC&id=38SYXalMLeQC&pg=PA61 61]}}</ref><ref name=\"Gruss2001\">{{cite book|last=Gruss|first=Edmond C.|title=Jehovah's Witnesses: Their Claims, Doctrinal Changes, and Prophetic Speculation. What Does the Record Show?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kSZL8BWc9KcC&pg=PA218|year=2001|publisher=Xulon Press|isbn=978-1-931232-30-2|page=218}}</ref> most of which still exist.<ref>Reed, David, [https://web.archive.org/web/20110909064529/http://journal.equip.org/articles/whither-the-watchtower- Whither the Watchtower?] ''Christian Research Journal'', Summer 1993, pg 27: \"By gradually replacing locally elected elders with his own appointees, he managed to transform a loose collection of semi-autonomous, democratically run congregations into a tight-knit organizational machine controlled from his office. Some local congregations broke away, forming such groups as the Chicago Bible Students, the Dawn Bible Students, and the Laymen's Home Missionary Movement, all of which continue to this day.\"</ref> By mid-1919, as many as one in seven of Russell-era Bible Students had ceased their association with the Society, and as many as three-quarters by the end of the 1920s.<ref name=\"Penton, 1997, 58\" /><ref>''Thirty Years a Watchtower Slave'', William J. Schnell, Baker, Grand Rapids, 1956, as cited by Rogerson, page 52. Rogerson notes that it is not clear exactly how many Bible Students left, but quotes Rutherford (''Jehovah'', 1934, page 277) as saying \"only a few\" who left other religions were then \"in God's organization\".</ref><ref>''The Present Truth and Herald of Christ's Epiphany'', P.S.L. Johnson (April 1927, pg 66). Johnson stated that between late 1923 and early 1927, \"20,000 to 30,000 Truth people the world over have left the Society.\"</ref><ref>Tony Wills (''A People For His Name'', pg. 167) cites ''The Watch Tower'' (December 1, 1927, pg 355) in which Rutherford states that \"the larger percentage\" of original Bible Students had by then departed.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Gruss|first=Edmond C.|title=Apostles of Denial: An Examination and Expos\u00e9 of the History, Doctrines and Claims of the Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/stream/ApostlesOfDenial/1970_Apostles_Of_Denial#page/n275/mode/1up|year=1970|publisher=Presbyterian and Reformed Publishing Co.|isbn=978-0-87552-305-7|pages=265}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 1931, at a convention in [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]], Ohio, Rutherford introduced the new name \u2013 ''Jehovah's witnesses'' \u2013 based on [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] 43:10: \"'You are my witnesses,' declares Jehovah, 'Yes, my servant whom I have chosen, So that you may know and have faith in me And understand that I am the same One. Before me no God was formed, And after me there has been none.'\" (New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures 2013 Edition) \u2014which was adopted by resolution. The name was chosen to distinguish his group of Bible Students from other independent groups that had severed ties with the Society, as well as symbolize the instigation of new outlooks and the promotion of fresh evangelizing methods.<ref name=\"name1\">{{cite book|author=Rogerson, Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable|location=London|year=1969|page=55|quote=In 1931, came an important milestone in the history of the organization. For many years Rutherford's followers had been called a variety of names: 'International Bible Students', 'Russellites', or 'Millennial Dawners'. In order to distinguish clearly his followers from the other groups who had separated in 1918 Rutherford proposed that they adopt an entirely new name\u2014''Jehovah's witnesses''.}}</ref><ref name=\"name2\">James A. Beckford, ''The Trumpet of Prophecy'', 1975, page 30, \"The new title symbolized a break with the legacy of Russell's traditions, the instigation of new outlooks and the promotion of fresh methods of administering evangelism.\"</ref><ref name=\"name3\">{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watch Tower|title=A New Name|date=October 1, 1931|page=291|quote=Since the death of Charles T. Russell there have arisen numerous companies formed out of those who once walked with him, each of these companies claiming to teach the truth, and each calling themselves by some name, such as \"Followers of Pastor Russell\", \"those who stand by the truth as expounded by Pastor Russell,\" \"Associated Bible Students,\" and some by the names of their local leaders. All of this tends to confusion and hinders those of good will who are not better informed from obtaining a knowledge of the truth.}}</ref> In 1932, Rutherford eliminated the system of locally elected elders and in 1938, introduced what he called a \"theocratic\" (literally, ''God-ruled'') organizational system, under which appointments in congregations worldwide were made from the Brooklyn headquarters.<ref name=\"Franz, Raymond 2007\"/>\n\nFrom 1932, it was taught that the \"little flock\" of 144,000 would not be the only people to survive Armageddon. Rutherford explained that in addition to the 144,000 \"anointed\" who would be resurrected\u2014or transferred at death\u2014to live in heaven to rule over earth with Christ, a separate class of members, the \"great multitude,\" would live in a paradise restored on earth; from 1935, new converts to the movement were considered part of that class.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|page=31}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=71\u201372}}</ref> By the mid-1930s, the timing of the beginning of Christ's presence (Greek: ''parous\u00eda''), his enthronement as king, and the start of the \"[[end times|last days]]\" were each moved to 1914.<ref>{{cite book|last=Crompton|first=Robert|title=Counting the Days to Armageddon|publisher=James Clarke & Co|year=1996|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-227-67939-5|pages=109\u2013110}}</ref>\n[[File:NathanHomerKnorr-WTPres.png|thumb|right|182px|[[Nathan Homer Knorr|Nathan H. Knorr]], the third president of the [[Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|Watch Tower Society]]]]\nAs their interpretations of the Bible evolved, Witness publications decreed that saluting national flags is a form of idolatry, which led to a new outbreak of mob violence and government opposition in the United States, [[Canada]], [[Germany]], and other countries.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|page=35}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Garbe|first=Detlef|title=Between Resistance and Martyrdom: Jehovah's Witnesses in the Third Reich|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|year=2008|location=Madison, Wisconsin|pages=145|isbn=978-0-299-20794-6}}</ref>\n\nWorldwide membership of Jehovah's Witnesses reached 113,624 in 5,323 congregations by the time of Rutherford's death in January 1942.<ref>{{cite book|title=1943 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watch Tower Bible & Tract Society|year=1942|pages=221\u2013222}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses in the Divine Purpose|publisher=Watch Tower Bible & Tract Society|year=1959|pages=312\u2013313}}</ref>\n\n===Continued development (1942\u2013present)===\n{{See also|Development of Jehovah's Witnesses doctrine|Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n[[Nathan H. Knorr|Nathan Knorr]] was appointed as third president of the Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society in 1942. Knorr commissioned a new translation of the Bible, the ''[[New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures]]'', the full version of which was released in 1961. He organized large international assemblies, instituted new training programs for members, and expanded missionary activity and branch offices throughout the world.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=47\u201352}}</ref> Knorr's presidency was also marked by an increasing use of explicit instructions guiding Witnesses in their lifestyle and conduct, and a greater use of [[Church discipline|congregational judicial procedures]] to enforce a strict moral code.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=52\u201355}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=89\u201390}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1966, Witness publications and convention talks built anticipation of the possibility that Christ's thousand-year reign might begin in late 1975<ref name=\"Georgie\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cesnur.org/2010/to-chryssides.htm|title=\u2018They keep changing the dates\u2019: Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses Changing Chronology - Cryssides|website=www.cesnur.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=George D.|last=Chryssides|authorlink=George Chryssides|title=Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0-8108-6074-2|ref={{harvid|Chryssides|Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses}}|page=19}}</ref> or shortly thereafter.<ref name=\"Penton, 1997, 95\" >{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=95}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather|author2=[[Gary Botting]]|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|pages=[https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott/page/46 46]|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Awake!|publisher=Watch Tower Bible & Tract Society|page=14|date=October 8, 1968|quote=\"Does this mean that the above evidence positively points to 1975 as the complete end of this system of things? Since the Bible does not specifically state this, no man can say... If the 1970s should see intervention by Jehovah God to bring an end to a corrupt world drifting toward ultimate disintegration, that should surely not surprise us.\"|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Our Kingdom Ministry]]|date=May 1974|title=How Are You Using Your Life?|page=63|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/201974163|quote=Reports are heard of brothers selling their homes and property and planning to finish out the rest of their days in this old system in the pioneer service. Certainly, this is a fine way to spend the short time remaining before the wicked world's end.|ref=harv}}</ref> The number of baptisms increased significantly, from about 59,000 in 1966 to more than 297,000 in 1974. By 1975, the number of active members exceeded two million. Membership declined during the late 1970s after expectations for 1975 were proved wrong.<ref>{{cite book |title=Crisis of Conscience |author=Franz, Raymond |chapter=1975\u2014The Appropriate Time for God to Act |pages=[https://archive.org/details/crisisofconscien00raym/page/237 237\u2013253] |chapter-url=http://users.volja.net/izobcenec4/coc/9.pdf |accessdate=July 27, 2006 |chapter-format=PDF |isbn=978-0-914675-23-5 |url-status=dead |year=2002 |url=https://archive.org/details/crisisofconscien00raym/page/237 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Singelenberg, Richard|url=http://www.watchtowerinformationservice.org/index.php/dates/the-1975-prophecy-and-its-impact-among-dutch-jehovahs-witnesses/|title=The '1975'-prophecy and its impact among Dutch Jehovah's Witnesses|journal=Sociological Analysis|issue=1|year=1989|pages=23\u201340|volume=50|doi=10.2307/3710916|jstor=3710916|ref=harv}} Notes a nine percent drop in total publishers (door-to-door preachers) and a 38 per cent drop in pioneers (full-time preachers) in the Netherlands.</ref><ref name=\"Stark\">{{cite journal|journal=[[Journal of Contemporary Religion]]|title=Why the Jehovah's Witnesses Grow So Rapidly: A Theoretical Application|url=http://www.kotiposti.net/raamattu/jt/doc/study-why-jw-grow-so-rapidly.pdf|year=1997|pages=142\u2013143|format=PDF|accessdate=July 16, 2013|author=Stark and Iannoccone|ref=harv|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412073649/http://www.kotiposti.net/raamattu/jt/doc/study-why-jw-grow-so-rapidly.pdf|archive-date=April 12, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=January 30, 1982|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Defectors Feel 'Witness' Wrath: Critics say Baptism Rise Gives False Picture of Growth|author=Dart, John|page=B4}} Cited statistics showing a net increase of publishers worldwide from 1971 to 1981 of 737,241, while baptisms totaled 1.71 million for the same period.</ref> Watch Tower Society literature did not state dogmatically that 1975 would definitely mark the end,<ref name=\"Penton, 1997, 95\" /> but in 1980 the Watch Tower Society admitted its responsibility in building up hope regarding that year.<ref name=\"Hans\" >{{cite book|last=Hesse|first=Hans|title=Persecution and Resistance of Jehovah's Witnesses During the Nazi-Regime|publisher=Edition Temmen c/o|year=2001|location=Chicago|pages=296, 298|isbn=978-3-861-08750-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=The Watchtower|date=March 15, 1980|pages=17\u201318|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1980207|quote=With the appearance of the book ''Life Everlasting\u2014in Freedom of the Sons of God'', ... considerable expectation was aroused regarding the year 1975. ... there were other statements published that implied that such realization of hopes by that year was more of a probability than a mere possibility. It is to be regretted that these latter statements apparently overshadowed the cautionary ones and contributed to a buildup of the expectation already initiated. ... ''persons having to do with the publication of the information'' ... contributed to the buildup of hopes centered on that date.|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe offices of elder and ministerial servant were restored to Witness congregations in 1972, with appointments made from headquarters<ref>{{harvnb|Chryssides|Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|pages=32,112}}</ref> (and later, also by branch committees). It was announced that, starting in September 2014, appointments would be made by traveling overseers. In a major organizational overhaul in 1976, the power of the Watch Tower Society president was diminished, with authority for doctrinal and organizational decisions passed to the [[Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses|Governing Body]].<ref>{{harvnb|Chryssides|Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|page=64}}</ref> Since Knorr's death in 1977, the position of president has been occupied by [[Frederick William Franz|Frederick Franz]] (1977\u20131992) and [[Milton George Henschel|Milton Henschel]] (1992\u20132000), both members of the Governing Body, and since 2000 by others who are not Governing Body members. In 1995, Jehovah's Witnesses abandoned the idea that Armageddon must occur during the lives of the generation that was alive in 1914 and in 2010 changed their teaching on the \"generation\".<ref>{{Citation|journal=Newsweek|volume=236|issue=3146|pages=24|title=Apocalypse Later|date=December 18, 1995|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/104359|author=Joel P. Engardio|bibcode=2017NewSc.236Q..24L|doi=10.1016/S0262-4079(17)31969-3}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|p=317}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-11-04-me-64883-story.html|title=Jehovah's Witnesses Abandon Key Tenet : Doctrine: Sect has quietly retreated from prediction that those alive in 1914 would see end of world.|date=November 4, 1995|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jw.org/en/publications/magazines/w20140115/let-your-kingdom-come/|title=\"Let Your Kingdom Come\"\u2014But When? - Study|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|website=Official website of Jehovah's Witnesses}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\n{{Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n{{Main|Organizational structure of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\nJehovah's Witnesses are organized [[Hierarchy|hierarchically]], in what the leadership calls a \"theocratic organization\", reflecting their belief that it is God's \"visible organization\" on earth.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=January 15, 2001|page=16|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2001049|title=Overseers and Ministerial Servants Theocratically Appointed|quote=Theocratic appointments come from Jehovah through his Son and God's visible earthly channel, \"the faithful and discreet slave\" and its Governing Body.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 1967 |title=Following Faithful Shepherds with Life in View |pages=591\u201392 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1967723 |quote=Make haste to identify the visible theocratic organization of God that represents his king, Jesus Christ. It is essential for life. Doing so, be complete in accepting its every aspect. We cannot claim to love God, yet deny his Word and channel of communication. Therefore, in submitting to Jehovah's visible theocratic organization, we must be in full and complete agreement with every feature of its apostolic procedure and requirements.}}</ref><ref name=\"pentongov\" >{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=211}}</ref> The organization is led by the [[Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses|Governing Body]]\u2014an all-male group that varies in size, but since January 2018 has comprised eight members,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jw.org/en/jehovahs-witnesses/faq/governing-body |title=What Is the Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses? |website=Official website of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania}}</ref> all of whom profess to be of the \"anointed\" class with a hope of heavenly life\u2014based in the Watch Tower Society's Warwick headquarters.<ref>{{cite book|title=2007 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|author=Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|pages=4, 6|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/302007001}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather & Gary|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2}}</ref> There is no election for membership; new members are selected by the existing body.<ref>{{cite book|last=Franz|first=Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|page=123|isbn=978-0-914675-17-4}}</ref> Until late 2012, the Governing Body described itself as the representative<ref name=\"GB2008\">{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 15, 2008 |title=How the Governing Body Is Organized |page=29 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2008367 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 15, 2008 |title=Seek God's guidance in all things |page=11 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2008282}}</ref> and \"spokesman\" for God's \"[[faithful and discreet slave]] class\" (then approximately 10,000 self-professed [[Jehovah's Witnesses and salvation#The 'anointed'|\"anointed\" Jehovah's Witnesses]]).<ref>{{cite book|last=Franz|first=Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|page=153|isbn=978-0-914675-17-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=2010 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2010|chapter=Preaching and Teaching Earth Wide &mdash; 2009 Grand Totals|page=42|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/302010015}}</ref> At the 2012 Annual Meeting of the Watch Tower Society, the \"faithful and discreet slave\" was defined as referring to the Governing Body only.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jw.org/en/news/events-activities/annual-meeting-report-2012|title=Annual Meeting Report|website=Official website of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=The Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania}}</ref> The Governing Body directs several committees that are responsible for administrative functions, including publishing, assembly programs and evangelizing activities.<ref name=pentongov /> It appoints all branch committee members and traveling overseers, after they have been recommended by local branches, with traveling overseers supervising circuits of congregations within their jurisdictions. Traveling overseers appoint local elders and ministerial servants, and while branch offices may appoint regional committees for matters such as [[Kingdom Hall]] construction or disaster relief.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=101,&nbsp;233\u2013235}}</ref> The leadership and supporting staff lives in properties owned by the organization worldwide referred to as \"Bethel\" where they operate as a religious community and administrative unit.<ref>{{harvnb|Chryssides|Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|pages=17\u201318}}</ref> Their living expenses and those of other full-time volunteers are covered by the organization along with a basic monthly [[stipend]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Penton |first=M. James |date=2015 |title=Apocalypse delayed: the story of Jehovah's Witnesses |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zNfTBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA326 |edition=3rd |publisher=University of Toronto Press |pages=326, 460\u2013461 |isbn=978-1442616059 |ref=harv | quote=For many years they received only $14 per month, but that has been increased during the last several decades to $100 or more per month, and their clothing allowance has also been increased significantly. Barbara Anderson relates that she and her husband received $100 a month, were given board and room, and had a yearly clothing allowance of $250 during the years they were at Bethel until they left in 1997. Although Bethelites may receive somewhat more today, they are certainly not paid anything like 'real wages.'}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather|author2=[[Gary Botting]]|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|pages=[https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott/page/32 32]|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2|quote=Missionaries, circuit overseers, district overseers, special pioneers, and branch-office workers receive small allowances each month. }}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Watchtower Society |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of American Religion and Politics |pages=466|quote=The religious order of Jehovah's Witnesses caters to the needs of all volunteers who have taken a vow of poverty and obedience. }}</ref>\n\nEach congregation has a body of appointed unpaid male elders and ministerial servants. Elders maintain general responsibility for congregational governance, setting meeting times, selecting speakers and conducting meetings, directing the public preaching work, and creating \"judicial committees\" to investigate and decide disciplinary action for cases involving sexual misconduct or doctrinal breaches.<ref name=\"alternative\">{{Citation|last=Gallagher|first=Eugene V.|last2=Ashcraft|first2=W. Michael|title=Introduction to New and Alternative Religions in America|place=Westport, Connecticut|publisher=Greenwood Press|volume=2|year=2006|page=69|isbn=978-0-275-98712-1}}</ref> New elders are appointed by a traveling overseer after recommendation by the existing body of elders. Ministerial servants\u2014appointed in a similar manner to elders\u2014fulfill clerical and attendant duties, but may also teach and conduct meetings.<ref name=pentongov /> Witnesses do not use ''elder'' as a title to signify a formal clergy-laity division,<ref>{{cite book|last=Taylor|first=Elizabeth J.|title=Religion: A Clinical Guide for Nurses|publisher=Springer Publishing Company|year=2012|pages=163|isbn=978-0-8261-0860-9}}</ref> though elders may employ [[ecclesiastical privilege]] regarding confession of sins.<ref>{{cite book|publisher=Watch Tower Society|title=Pay Attention to Yourselves and to All the Flock|year=1981|page=147}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/file-list/Case%20Study%2029%20-%20Transcript%20-%20Jehovahs%20Witnesses%20-%20Day%20147%20-%2027072015.pdf|title=\"Case Study 29: Transcript (day 147)\", page 16, ''Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse'', 27 July 2015.}}</ref>\n\n[[Baptism]] is a requirement for being considered a member of Jehovah's Witnesses. Jehovah's Witnesses do not practice infant baptism,<ref>{{cite book|last=Hoekema|first=Anthony A.|authorlink=Anthony A. Hoekema|title=The Four Major Cults|publisher=William B. Eerdmans|location=Grand Rapids, Michigan|year=1963|isbn=978-0-8028-3117-0|ref=harv|pages=291}}</ref> and previous baptisms performed by other denominations are not considered valid.<ref name=\"RFbaptism\">{{cite book|author=Franz, Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|pages=116\u2013120|isbn=978-0-914675-16-7}}</ref> Individuals undergoing baptism must affirm publicly that dedication and baptism identify them \"as one of Jehovah's Witnesses in association with God's spirit-directed organization,\"<ref name=\"RFbaptism\" /> though Witness publications say baptism symbolizes personal dedication to God and not \"to a man, work or organization.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Chryssides|Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|page=14}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=What Does the Bible Really Teach|chapter=Baptism and Your Relationship With God|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|page=182|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102005148|quote=Going beneath the water symbolizes that you have died to your former life course. Being raised up out of the water indicates that you are now alive to do the will of God. Remember, too, that you have made a dedication to Jehovah God himself, not to a work, a cause, other humans, or an organization.}}</ref> Their literature emphasizes the need for members to be obedient and loyal to Jehovah and to \"his organization,\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Franz|first=Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|pages=449\u2013464|isbn=978-0-914675-16-7}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=32}}, \"The structure of the movement and the intense loyalty demanded of each individual at every level demonstrates the characteristics of totalitarianism.\"</ref><ref group=note>Raymond Franz (''In Search of Christian Freedom'', 2007, p.449) cites various Watch Tower Society publications that stress loyalty and obedience to the organization, including:<br /> {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 1967|title=Following Faithful Shepherds with Life in View|page=591|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1967723|quote=Make haste to identify the visible theocratic organization of God that represents his king, Jesus Christ. It is essential for life. Doing so, be complete in accepting its every aspect.}}<br /> {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=September 1, 2006 |title=Jehovah's Word Is Alive - Highlights From Book Five of Psalms |page=15 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2006643 |quote=Have we formed a loyal attachment to the organization that Jehovah is using today?}}<br /> {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=June 15, 2006|title=Your Reminders Are What I Am Fond Of |page=26 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2006446 |quote=We too should remain faithful to Jehovah and to his organization regardless of injustices we suffer and regardless of what others do.}}<br /> {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 15, 2006 |title=Are You Prepared for Survival? |page=22 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2006366 |quote=Just as Noah and his God-fearing family were preserved in the ark, survival of individuals today depends on their faith and their loyal association with the earthly part of Jehovah's universal organization.}}<br /> {{cite book|title=Worship The Only True God|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2002|page=134|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102002074|quote=Jehovah is guiding us today by means of his visible organization under Christ. Our attitude toward this arrangement demonstrates how we feel about the issue of sovereignty ... By being loyal to Jehovah's organization, we show that Jehovah is our God and that we are united in worship of him.}}</ref> stating that individuals must remain part of it to receive God's favor and to survive Armageddon.<ref>{{cite book|title=You Can Live Forever in Paradise on Earth|chapter=30. What You Must Do to Live Forever|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1989|page=255|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989120|quote=It is simply not true that all religions lead to the same goal. (Matthew 7:21\u201323; 24:21) You must be part of Jehovah's organization, doing God's will, in order to receive his blessing of everlasting life.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 15, 1983 |title=You Can Live Forever in Paradise on Earth\u2014But How? |page=12 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1983124 |quote=Jehovah is using only one organization today to accomplish his will. To receive everlasting life in the earthly Paradise we must identify that organization and serve God as part of it.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=November 15, 1992 |title=Serving Jehovah Loyally |page=21 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1992845 |quote=I determined to stay by the faithful organization. How else can one get Jehovah's favor and blessing?\" There is nowhere else to go for divine favor and life eternal.}}</ref>\n\n===Publishing===\nThe organization produces a significant amount of literature as part of its evangelism activities.<ref name=\"pub_titans\">{{cite magazine|last=Meyers|first=Jim|date=October 2010|title=Jehovah's Witnesses &mdash; Publishing Titans|url=https://archive.org/download/Newsmax/TourDeGardeNewsmax.pdf#page=2|format=PDF|magazine=Newsmax|location=West Palm Beach, FL|publisher=Newsmax Media}}</ref> The Watch Tower Society has produced over 227 million copies of the ''New World Translation'' in whole or in part in over 185 languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jw.org/en/publications/bible|title=Online Bible|publisher=The Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|website=Official website of Jehovah's Witnesses}}</ref> ''[[The Watchtower]]'' and ''[[Awake!]]'' are the most widely distributed magazines in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-most-widely-read-magazine-in-the-world-is-the-monthly-pub-of-jehovahs-witnesses-2010-9?IR=T|title=Did You Know The Most Widely Circulated Magazine In The World Is The Monthly Publication Of Jehovah's Witnesses?|author=Joe Pompeo|date=September 30, 2010|work=Business Insider}}</ref> Translation of Witness publications is done by over 2,000 volunteers worldwide, producing literature in 1,000 languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jw.org/en/news/jw/region/global/Jehovahs-Witnesses-Reach-New-Preaching-Milestone-JWORG-Now-Features-Content-in-1000-Languages/|title=Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses Reach New Preaching Milestone\u2014JW.ORG Now Features Content in 1,000 Languages|publisher=The Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|website=Official website of Jehovah's Witnesses}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=God's Kingdom Rules!|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|chapter=8. Tools for Preaching &mdash; Producing Literature for the Worldwide Field|year=2014|page=79|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102014247}}</ref> Publications are also available online at the organization's official website.\n\n===Funding===\nMuch of their funding is provided by [[donation]]s, primarily from members. There is no [[tithe|tithing]] or collection.<ref name=\"Hans\" /> In 2001 ''[[Newsday]]'' listed the Watch Tower Society as one of [[New York City|New York]]'s forty richest corporations, with revenues exceeding $950 million.<ref name=\"pub_titans\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/business/technology/at-the-top-nyc-company-profiles-nyc-40-1.365255|title=AT THE TOP / NYC COMPANY PROFILES / NYC 40|website=Newsday}}</ref> The organization reported for the same year that it \"spent over $70.9 million in caring for special pioneers, missionaries, and traveling overseers in their field service assignments.\"<ref>{{cite book|title =2002 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2002|page=31|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/302002003}}</ref><ref group=\"note\">{{cite book|title=2013 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|page=178|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/302013019|quote=During the 2012 service year, Jehovah's Witnesses spent over $184 million in caring for special pioneers, missionaries, and traveling overseers in their field service assignments.}}</ref>\n\n==Beliefs==\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses beliefs}}\n\n===Sources of doctrine===\nJehovah's Witnesses believe their denomination is a restoration of [[Christianity in the 1st century|first-century Christianity]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Van Voorst, Robert E.|title=RELG: World (with Religion CourseMate with eBook Printed Access Card)|publisher=Cengage Learning|page=288|year=2012|isbn=978-1-1117-2620-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QvNWxEEaf50C&pg=PT303}}</ref> [[Doctrine]]s of Jehovah's Witnesses are established by the [[Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses|Governing Body]], which assumes responsibility for [[exegesis|interpreting]] and applying scripture.<ref name=\"Penton 1997 61\u201362\" /><ref>{{cite book|title=Organized to Do Jehovah's Will|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2015|pages=17\u201319|chapter=Remember Those Who Are Taking the Lead Among You|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102014933}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=March 15, 1990 |title=Cooperating With the Governing Body Today |page=19 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1990204}}</ref> The Governing Body does not issue any single, comprehensive \"statement of faith\", but prefers to express its doctrinal position in a variety of ways through publications published by the Watch Tower Society.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|page=119}}</ref> Their publications teach that doctrinal changes and refinements result from a process of progressive [[revelation]], in which God gradually reveals his will and purpose,<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|title=Focus on the Goodness of Jehovah's Organization|page=22|date=July 15, 2006|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2006525|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=March 1, 1965 |title=Impart God's Progressive Revelation to Mankind |pages=158\u2013159 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1965166}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=165\u2013171}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 15, 1995 |title=Flashes of Light\u2014Great and Small |page=15 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1995363}}</ref> and that such enlightenment or \"new light\"<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=December 1, 1981 |title=The Path of the Righteous Does Keep Getting Brighter |pages=26\u201331 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1981889}}</ref> results from the application of [[reason]] and [[biblical studies|study]],<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=165}}</ref> the guidance of the [[holy spirit]], and direction from [[Jesus Christ]] and [[angels]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Rutherford|first=Joseph|title=Preparation|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1933|pages=64, 67|quote=Enlightenment proceeds from Jehovah by and through Christ Jesus and is given to the faithful anointed on earth at the temple, and brings great peace and consolation to them. Again Zechariah talked with the angel of the Lord, which shows that the remnant are instructed by the angels of the Lord. The remnant do not hear audible sounds, because such is not necessary. Jehovah has provided his own good way to convey thoughts to the minds of his anointed ones ... Those of the remnant, being honest and true, must say, We do not know; and the Lord enlightens them, sending his angels for that very purpose.}}</ref> The Society also teaches that members of the Governing Body are helped by the holy spirit to discern \"deep truths\", which are then considered by the entire Governing Body before it makes doctrinal decisions.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 2010 |title=The Spirit Searches into the Deep Things of God |page=23 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2010524|quote=When the time comes to clarify a spiritual matter in our day, holy spirit helps responsible representatives of 'the faithful and discreet slave' at world headquarters to discern deep truths that were not previously understood. The Governing Body as a whole considers adjusted explanations. What they learn, they publish for the benefit of all.}}</ref> The group's leadership, while disclaiming divine inspiration and [[infallibility of the Church|infallibility]],<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Do We Need Help to Understand the Bible?|magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 15, 1981|page=19|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1981127|quote=\"True, the brothers preparing these publications are not infallible. Their writings are not inspired as are those of Paul and the other Bible writers. (2 Tim. 3:16) And so, at times, it has been necessary, as understanding became clearer, to correct views. (Prov. 4:18)\"}}</ref> is said to provide \"divine guidance\"<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 15, 2011 |title=Do You See the Evidence of God's Guidance? |pages=3\u20135|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2011286|quote=How, then, do we react when we receive divine direction? Do we try to apply it \"right afterward\"? Or do we continue doing things just as we have been accustomed to doing them? Are we familiar with up-to-date directions, such as those regarding conducting home Bible studies, preaching to foreign speaking people, regularly sharing in family worship, cooperating with Hospital Liaison Committees, and conducting ourselves properly at conventions? ... Do you clearly discern the evidence of divine guidance? Jehovah uses his organization to guide us, his people, through \"the wilderness\" during these last days of Satan's wicked world.}}</ref> through its teachings described as \"based on God's Word thus ... not from men, but from Jehovah.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=September 15, 2010 |title=Unity Identifies True Worship |page=13 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2010683}}</ref><ref name=\"voice\">{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=June 15, 1957 |title=Overseers of Jehovah's People |pages=369\u2013375 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1957446|quote=Let us now unmistakably identify Jehovah's channel of communication for our day, that we may continue in his favor ... It is vital that we appreciate this fact and respond to the directions of the \"slave\" as we would to the voice of God, because it is His provision.}}</ref>\n\nThe entire Protestant [[Biblical canon|canon of scripture]] is considered the [[Biblical inspiration|inspired]], [[Biblical inerrancy|inerrant]] word of God.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=172}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses consider the Bible to be [[Criticism of the Bible#The Bible and science|scientifically]] and [[The Bible and history|historically]] accurate and reliable<ref>{{cite book|title=All Scripture is Inspired of God|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1990|page=336|chapter=Archaeology and the Inspired Record|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101990136}}</ref> and interpret much of it [[Biblical literalism|literally]], but accept parts of it as [[Allegorical interpretation of the Bible|symbolic]].<ref>{{cite book|title=All Scripture is Inspired of God|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1990|page=9|chapter=All Scripture Is Inspired of God and Beneficial|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101990061}}</ref> They consider the Bible to be the final authority for all their beliefs,<ref>{{cite book|title=Reasoning From The Scriptures|chapter=Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1989|pages=199\u2013208|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989239}}</ref> although sociologist Andrew Holden's [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] study of the group concluded that pronouncements of the Governing Body, through Watch Tower Society publications, carry almost as much weight as the Bible.<ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=67}}, \"Materials such as ''The Watchtower'' are almost as significant to the Witnesses as the Bible, since the information is presented as the inspired work of theologians, and they are, therefore, believed to contain as much truth as biblical texts.\"</ref> Regular personal Bible reading is frequently recommended; Witnesses are discouraged from formulating doctrines and \"private ideas\" reached through Bible research independent of Watch Tower Society publications, and are cautioned against reading other religious literature.<ref name=\"Bevindependent\">James A. Beverley, ''Crisis of Allegiance'', Welch Publishing Company, Burlington, Ontario, 1986, {{ISBN|0-920413-37-4}}, pages 25\u201326, 101, \"For every passage in Society literature that urges members to be bold and courageous in critical pursuits, there are many others that warn about independent thinking and the peril of questioning the organization ... Fear of disobedience to the Governing Body keeps Jehovah's Witnesses from carefully checking into biblical doctrine or allegations concerning false prophecy, faulty scholarship, and injustice. Witnesses are told not to read books like this one.\"</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=March 15, 2006 |title=Keep Clear of False Worship! |pages=27\u201331 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2006208|quote=True Christians keep clear of false worship, rejecting false religious teachings. This means that we avoid exposure to religious programs on radio and television as well as religious literature that promotes lies about God and his Word.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 1, 1984|page=31|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1984330|title=Questions From Readers\u2014Why do Jehovah's Witnesses decline to exchange their Bible study aids for the religious literature of people they meet|quote=So it would be foolhardy, as well as a waste of valuable time, for Jehovah's Witnesses to accept and expose themselves to false religious literature that is designed to deceive.}}</ref> Adherents are told to have \"complete confidence\" in the leadership, avoid skepticism about what is taught in the Watch Tower Society's literature, and \"not advocate or insist on personal opinions or harbor private ideas when it comes to Bible understanding.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=September 2007 |title=Question Box |page=3 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202007325|quote=Throughout the earth, Jehovah's people are receiving ample spiritual instruction and encouragement at congregation meetings, assemblies, and conventions, as well as through the publications of Jehovah's organization. Under the guidance of his holy spirit and on the basis of his Word of truth, Jehovah provides what is needed so that all of God's people may be fitly united in the same mind and in the same line of thought and remain stabilized in the faith. Surely we are grateful for Jehovah's spiritual provisions in these last days. Thus, the faithful and discreet slave does not endorse any literature, meetings, or Web sites that are not produced or organized under its oversight. }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=August 1, 2001 |title=Make Your Advancement Manifest |page=14 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2001563 |quote=Since oneness is to be observed, a mature Christian must be in unity and full harmony with fellow believers as far as faith and knowledge are concerned. He does not advocate or insist on personal opinions or harbor private ideas when it comes to Bible understanding. Rather, he has complete confidence in the truth as it is revealed by Jehovah God through his Son, Jesus Christ, and the faithful and discreet slave.}}</ref><ref>Testimony by Fred Franz, Transcript, Lord Strachan vs. Douglas Walsh, 1954. page 123, Q: \"Did you imply that the individual member has the right of reading the books and the Bible and forming his own view as to the proper interpretation of Holy Writ? A:\" .... No....The Scripture is there given in support of the statement, and therefore the individual when he looks up the Scripture and thereby verifies the statement,...search[es] the Scripture to see whether these things were so.\"</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 15, 1981 |title=Do We Need Help to Understand the Bible? |page=19 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1981127|quote=Jesus' disciples wrote many letters to Christian congregations, to persons who were already in the way of the truth. But nowhere do we read that those brothers first, in a skeptical frame of mind, checked the Scriptures to make certain that those letters had Scriptural backing, that the writers really knew what they were talking about. We can benefit from this consideration. If we have once established what instrument God is using as his 'slave' to dispense spiritual food to his people, surely Jehovah is not pleased if we receive that food as though it might contain something harmful. We should have confidence in the channel God is using.}}</ref> The organization makes no provision for members to criticize or contribute to official teachings<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=84, 89, 92, 119\u2013120}}</ref> and all Witnesses must abide by its doctrines and organizational requirements.<ref name=\"w89_0401_1\">{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 1, 1986 |title=Questions From Readers |pages=30\u201331 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1986249}}</ref>\n\n===Jehovah===\n[[File:YHWH.svg|thumb|left|142px|The [[Tetragrammaton]]]]\nJehovah's Witnesses emphasize the use of God's name, and they prefer the form ''[[Jehovah]]''&mdash;a vocalization of [[God in Christianity|God]]'s name based on the [[Tetragrammaton]].<ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=24}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor-last1=Ringnes|editor-first1=Hege Kristin|editor-last2=S\u00f8dal|editor-first2=Helje Kringlebotn|title=Jehovas vitner: en flerfaglig studie|language=Norwegian|publisher=Universitetsforlaget|year=2009|location=Oslo|page=27|isbn=978-82-15-01453-1|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Holden, A.|year=2002|title=Cavorting With the Devil: Jehovah's Witnesses Who Abandon Their Faith|page=Endnote [i]|publisher=Department of Sociology, Lancaster University, Lancaster LA1 4YL, UK|url=http://www.lancaster.ac.uk/fass/resources/sociology-online-papers/papers/holden-cavorting-with-the-devil.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=April 4, 2017}}</ref> They believe that Jehovah is the only true God, the creator of all things, and the \"Universal Sovereign\". They believe that all worship should be directed toward him, and that he is not part of a [[Trinity]];<ref>{{cite book|author=Alan Rogerson|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die|publisher=Constable|year=1969|page=87}}</ref> consequently, the group places more emphasis on God than on Christ.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|page=105}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Revelation Its Grand Climax|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1988|page=36|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101988007|quote=In the songbook produced by Jehovah's people in 1905, there were twice as many songs praising Jesus as there were songs praising Jehovah God. In their 1928 songbook, the number of songs extolling Jesus was about the same as the number extolling Jehovah. But in the latest songbook of 1984, Jehovah is honored by four times as many songs as is Jesus. This is in harmony with Jesus' own words: 'The Father is greater than I am.' Love for Jehovah must be preeminent, accompanied by deep love for Jesus and appreciation of his precious sacrifice and office as God's High Priest and King.}}</ref> They believe that the [[Holy Spirit in Christianity|Holy Spirit]] is God's applied power or \"active force\", rather than a person.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alan Rogerson|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die|publisher=Constable|year=1969|page=90}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 2009|page=5|title=What is the Holy Spirit?|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2009721|quote=There is a close connection between the holy spirit and the power of God. The holy spirit is the means by which Jehovah exerts his power. Put simply, the holy spirit is God's applied power, or his active force.}}</ref>\n\n===Jesus===\n\nJehovah's Witnesses believe that [[Jesus in Christianity|Jesus]] is God's only direct creation, that everything else was created through Christ by means of God's power, and that the initial unassisted act of creation uniquely identifies Jesus as God's \"only-begotten Son\".<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|page=262}}</ref> Jesus served as a [[Redeemer (Christianity)|redeemer]] and a [[Ransom theory of atonement|ransom sacrifice]] to pay for the sins of humanity.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=276\u2013277}}</ref> They believe Jesus died on a [[Instrument of Jesus' crucifixion|single upright post]] rather than the traditional [[Crucifixion of Jesus|cross]].<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=372}}</ref> Biblical references to the [[Michael (archangel)|Archangel Michael]], [[Abaddon]] (Apollyon), and [[Christ the Logos|the Word]] are interpreted as names for Jesus in various roles.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|page=270}}</ref> Jesus is considered to be the only [[Intercession|intercessor]] and [[high priest]] between God and humanity, and appointed by God as the king and judge of his kingdom.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=November 15, 1995 |title=Stay in the \"City of Refuge\" and Live! |page=19 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1995844 }}</ref> His role as a mediator (referred to in 1 Timothy 2:5) is applied to the 'anointed' class, though the 'other sheep' are said to also benefit from the arrangement.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=188\u2013189}}</ref>\n\n===Satan===\nJehovah's Witnesses believe that [[Devil in Christianity|Satan]] was originally a perfect [[angel]] who developed feelings of self-importance and craved worship. Satan influenced [[Adam and Eve]] to disobey God, and humanity subsequently became participants in a challenge involving the competing claims of Jehovah and Satan to universal sovereignty.<ref name=\"pentonsatan\" >{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=188\u2013190}}</ref> Other angels who sided with Satan became [[demon]]s.\n\nJehovah's Witnesses teach that Satan and his demons were cast down to earth from heaven after October 1, 1914,<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=298\u2013299}}</ref> at which point the [[end time]]s began. They believe that Satan is the ruler of the current world order,<ref name=\"pentonsatan\" /> that human society is influenced and misled by Satan and his demons, and that they are a cause of human suffering. They also believe that human governments are controlled by Satan,<ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=25}}</ref> but that he does not directly control each human ruler.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 1, 2004|page=5|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2004241|title=Identifying the Wild Beast and Its Mark|quote=This does not mean, however, that every human ruler is a direct tool of Satan.}}</ref>\n\n===Life after death===\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses and salvation}}\nJehovah's Witnesses believe death is a state of non-existence with no [[consciousness]]. There is no [[Christian views on hell|Hell]] of fiery torment; [[Christian views on Hades|Hades]] and [[Sheol]] are understood to refer to the condition of death, termed the ''common grave''.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=322\u2013324}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses consider the [[Soul (spirit)|soul]] to be a life or a living body that can die.<ref name=\"hoeksin\">{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=265\u2013269}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses believe that humanity is in a [[Christian views of sin#Protestant views|sinful]] state,<ref name=\"hoeksin\" /> from which release is only possible by means of Jesus' shed blood as a ransom, or [[substitutionary atonement|atonement]], for the sins of humankind.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=186}}</ref>\n\nWitnesses believe that a \"little flock\" of 144,000 selected humans go to heaven, but that the majority (the \"other sheep\") are to be resurrected by God to a cleansed earth after Armageddon. They interpret [[Book of Revelation|Revelation]] 14:1\u20135 to mean that the number of Christians going to heaven is limited to exactly 144,000, who will rule with Jesus as kings and priests over earth.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=193\u2013194}}</ref> They believe that baptism as one of Jehovah's Witnesses is vital for salvation<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|edition=study|date=March 2016|page=4|title=Young Ones&mdash;Are You Ready to Get Baptized|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2016201|quote=It is a great privilege to get baptized as one of Jehovah's Witnesses. Moreover, baptism is a requirement for Christians, and it is a vital step toward gaining salvation.}}</ref> and that only they meet scriptural requirements for surviving Armageddon, but that God is the final judge.<ref name=onlyjw>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=September 1, 1989 |title=Remaining Organized for Survival Into the Millennium |page=19 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1989647|quote=Only Jehovah's Witnesses, those of the anointed remnant and the 'great crowd,'as a united organization under the protection of the Supreme Organizer, have any Scriptural hope of surviving the impending end of this doomed system dominated by Satan the Devil. }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title =You Can Live Forever in Paradise on Earth|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1989|page=255|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989120|quote=Do not conclude that there are different roads, or ways, that you can follow to gain life in God's new system. There is only one ... there will be only one organization\u2014God's visible organization\u2014that will survive the fast-approaching 'great tribulation.' It is simply not true that all religions lead to the same goal. You must be part of Jehovah's organization, doing God's will, in order to receive his blessing of everlasting life.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=November 1, 2008 |title=Our Readers Ask: Do Jehovah's Witnesses Believe That They Are the Only Ones Who Will Be Saved? |page=28 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2008814|quote=Jehovah's Witnesses hope to be saved. However, they also believe that it is not their job to judge who will be saved. Ultimately, God is the Judge. He decides. }}</ref> During Christ's [[Millennialism|millennial reign]], most people who died prior to Armageddon will be resurrected with the prospect of living forever; they will be taught the proper way to worship God to prepare them for their final test at the end of the millennium.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=315\u2013319}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title =Insight on the Scriptures|volume=1|chapter=Declare Righteous|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1988|page=606|chapter-url=http://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1200001142}}</ref>\n\n===God's Kingdom===\nJehovah's Witnesses believe that [[Kingdom of God|God's Kingdom]] is a literal government in heaven, ruled by Jesus Christ and 144,000 \"spirit-anointed\" Christians drawn from the earth, which they associate with Jesus' reference to a \"new covenant\".<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=January 15, 2012 |title=A Royal Priesthood to Benefit All Mankind |pages=26\u201330 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2012046 }}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=295\u2013296}}</ref> The kingdom is viewed as the means by which God will accomplish his original purpose for the earth, transforming it into a paradise without sickness or death.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alan Rogerson|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die|publisher=Constable|year=1969|page=106}}</ref> It is said to have been the focal point of Jesus' ministry on earth.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 15, 2000 |title=God's Kingdom\u2014Earth's New Rulership |page=10 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2000763 }}</ref> They believe the kingdom was established in heaven in 1914,<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|page=298}}</ref> and that Jehovah's Witnesses serve as representatives of the kingdom on earth.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alan Rogerson|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die|publisher=Constable|year=1969|page=105}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=November 1, 1993 |title=Daniel's Prophetic Days and Our Faith|pages=8\u20139 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1993802|quote=In 1914 the appointed times of the nations ended, and the time of the end for this world began. The Davidic Kingdom was restored, not in earthly Jerusalem, but invisibly in \"the clouds of the heavens.\" ... Who would represent on earth the restored Davidic Kingdom? ... Without any doubt at all, it was the small body of anointed brothers of Jesus who in 1914 were known as the Bible Students but since 1931 have been identified as Jehovah's Witnesses. }}</ref>\n\n===Eschatology===\n{{Main|Eschatology of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\nA central teaching of Jehovah's Witnesses is that the current world era, or \"system of things\", entered the \"[[End time|last days]]\" in 1914 and faces imminent destruction through intervention by God and Jesus Christ, leading to deliverance for those who worship God acceptably.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|page=297}}</ref> They consider all other present-day religions to be false, identifying them with \"[[Whore of Babylon#Jehovah's Witnesses|Babylon the Great]]\", or the \"harlot\", of Revelation&nbsp;17,<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=286}}</ref> and believe that they will soon be destroyed by the [[United Nations]], which they believe is represented in scripture by the [[Jehovah's Witnesses and the United Nations|scarlet-colored wild beast]] of Revelation chapter 17. This development will mark the beginning of the \"[[great tribulation]]\".<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 2013|pages=4&ndash;5|title=Tell Us, When Will These Things Be?|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2013530|quote=In the larger fulfillment, the \"standing\" will occur when the United Nations (the modern-day \"disgusting thing\") attacks Christendom (which is holy in the eyes of nominal Christians) and the rest of Babylon the Great. The same attack is described at Revelation 17:16-18. That event will be the beginning of the great tribulation.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|title=Apocalypse\u2014When?|date=February 15, 1986|page=6}}</ref> Satan will subsequently use world governments to attack Jehovah's Witnesses, an action that will prompt God to begin the war of [[Armageddon]], during which all forms of government and all people not counted as Christ's \"sheep\" will be destroyed. After Armageddon, God will extend his heavenly kingdom to include earth, which will be transformed into a paradise similar to the [[Garden of Eden]].<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=180}}</ref> Most of those who had died before God's intervention will gradually be resurrected during the [[Millenarianism|thousand year]] \"judgment day\". This judgment will be based on their actions after resurrection rather than past deeds. At the end of the thousand years, Christ will hand all authority back to God. Then a final test will take place when Satan is released to mislead perfect mankind. Those who fail will be destroyed, along with Satan and his demons. The end result will be a fully tested, glorified human race on earth.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=307\u2013321}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=November 1, 1952|page=670|title=Questions From Readers|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1952809}}</ref>\n\nJehovah's Witnesses believe that Jesus Christ began to rule in heaven as king of God's kingdom in October 1914, and that Satan was subsequently ousted from heaven to the earth, resulting in \"woe\" to humanity. They believe that Jesus rules invisibly, from heaven, perceived only as a series of \"signs\". They base this belief on a rendering of the Greek word ''[[parousia]]''\u2014usually translated as \"coming\" when referring to Christ\u2014as \"presence\". They believe Jesus' presence includes an unknown period beginning with his inauguration as king in heaven in 1914, and ending when he comes to bring a final judgment against humans on earth. They thus depart from the mainstream Christian belief that the \"[[second coming]]\" of [[Matthew 24]] refers to a single moment of arrival on earth to judge humans.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=17\u201319}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 1992|page=16|title=The Messiah's Presence and His Rule|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1992723}}</ref>\n\n==Practices==\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses practices}}\n\n===Worship===\n[[File:Reuni\u00e3o em Sal\u00e3o do Reino.jpg|thumb|right|Worship at a [[Kingdom Hall]]]]\nMeetings for worship and study are held at [[Kingdom Hall]]s, which are typically functional in character, and do not contain religious symbols.<ref name=holdenhall /> Witnesses are assigned to a congregation in whose \"territory\" they usually reside and attend weekly services they refer to as \"meetings\" as scheduled by congregation elders. The meetings are largely devoted to study of Watch Tower Society literature and the Bible. The format of the meetings is established by the group's headquarters, and the subject matter for most meetings is the same worldwide.<ref name=holdenhall>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|pages=64\u201369}}</ref> Congregations meet for two sessions each week comprising four distinct meetings that total about three-and-a-half hours, typically gathering mid-week (two meetings) and on the weekend (two meetings). Prior to 2009, congregations met three times each week; these meetings were condensed, with the intention that members dedicate an evening for \"family worship\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2010|page=6|chapter=Highlights of the Past Year|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/302010009}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 15, 2011|title=Christian Families\u2014\"Keep Ready\" |page=14 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2011364 }}</ref> Gatherings are opened and closed with [[kingdom songs]] ([[hymns]]) and brief prayers. Twice each year, Witnesses from a number of congregations that form a \"circuit\" gather for a one-day assembly. Larger groups of congregations meet once a year for a three-day \"regional convention\", usually at rented stadiums or auditoriums.<ref>{{cite book|title=Organized to Do Jehovah's Will|year=2015|pages=63&ndash;64|publisher=Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society}}</ref> Their most important and solemn event is the commemoration of the \"Lord's Evening Meal\", or \"[[Jehovah's Witnesses practices#Memorial of Christ's death|Memorial of Christ's Death]]\" on the date of the Jewish [[Passover]].<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|page=292}}</ref>\n\n===Evangelism===\n{{See also|Jehovah's Witnesses publications}}\n[[File:Jehovah's Witnesses outside the British Museum 02.jpg|thumb|Jehovah's Witnesses outside the British Museum, 2017]]\nJehovah's Witnesses are perhaps best known for their [[Proselytism|efforts to spread their beliefs]], most notably by visiting people from house to house,<ref>{{cite book|last=Crompton|first=Robert|title=Counting the Days to Armageddon|publisher=James Clarke & Co|year=1996|location=Cambridge|pages=5|isbn=978-0-227-67939-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Rogerson|first=Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable & Co, London|year=1969|pages=1|isbn=978-0094559400}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Whalen|first=William J.|title=Armageddon Around the Corner: A Report on Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=John Day Company|year=1962|location=New York|page=15,18}}</ref> distributing literature published by the Watch Tower Society in 700 languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jw.org/en/jehovahs-witnesses/activities/publishing/global-printing/|title=Global Printing\u2014Helping People to Learn About God|publisher=Watch Tower Society}}</ref> The objective is to start a regular \"Bible study\" with any person who is not already a member,<ref>{{harvnb|Ringnes|S\u00f8dal|2009|p=43}}</ref> with the intention that the student be baptized as a member of the group;<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Be \"Intensely Occupied\" With Your Ministry|quote=Your goal is to help the student achieve greater insight into the truth, qualify as an unbaptized publisher, and become a dedicated and baptized Witness of Jehovah|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=April 2001|page=3|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202001124}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=What Does the Bible Really Teach?|chapter=18&mdash;Baptism and Your Relationship With God|pages=174\u2013183|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102005148}}</ref> Witnesses are advised to consider discontinuing Bible studies with students who show no interest in becoming members.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=October 1996|title=Question Box: How long should a formal Bible study be conducted with an individual in the Knowledge book?|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/201996367|quote=We want people to receive a basic knowledge of the truth. Yet it is expected that within a relatively short period of time, an effective teacher will be able to assist a sincere average student to acquire sufficient knowledge to make an intelligent decision to serve Jehovah... Appreciation for taking in even a basic knowledge of the truth should motivate the student to attend Christian meetings. This could lead the student to giving some clear evidence of his desire to serve Jehovah. If such spiritual appreciation is not evident after the study in the ''Knowledge'' book has been conducted for an extended period, it may be advisable to discontinue the study.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather|author2=[[Gary Botting]]|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|pages=[https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott/page/77 77]|quote=The society states explicitly that all Bible studies should quickly show signs of 'real progress' to be deemed worthy of pursuit ... unless the potential converts are willing to give clear indication that they accept both the doctrines and the consequent responsibilities of attending meetings and going from door to door themselves, the study should be discontinued.|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2}}</ref> Witnesses are taught they are under a biblical command to engage in public preaching.<ref>{{cite book|title=Bearing Thorough Witness About God's Kingdom|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2009|page=63|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102009050|quote=Do you obey the command to bear thorough witness, even if the assignment causes you some apprehension?}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=December 15, 2008 |title=Determined to bear thorough witness |page=19 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2008923|quote=When the resurrected Jesus spoke to disciples gathered in Galilee, likely 500 of them, he commanded: 'Go therefore and make disciples of people of all the nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and of the Son and of the holy spirit, teaching them to observe all the things I have commanded you.' That command applies to all true Christians today. }}</ref> They are instructed to devote as much time as possible to their ministry and are required to submit an individual monthly \"Field Service Report\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather|author2=Gary Botting|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|page=[https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott/page/52 52]|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=December 2002 |title=Do You Contribute to an Accurate Report? |page=8 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202002448 |quote=Jehovah's organization today instructs us to report our field service activity each month ... At the end of the month, the book study overseer makes sure that all in the group have followed through on their responsibility to report their activity.}}</ref> Baptized members who fail to report a month of preaching are termed \"irregular\" and may be counseled by elders;<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=May 1984 |title=Regularity in Service Brings Blessings |page=7 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/201984167 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Helping Irregular Publishers|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=December 1987|page=7|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/201987447|ref=harv}}</ref> those who do not submit reports for six consecutive months are termed \"inactive\".<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=October 1982|page=1|title=Keep the Word of Jehovah Moving Speedily|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/201982361|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n===Ethics and morality===\n{{See also|Jehovah's Witnesses and congregational discipline#Discipline involving \"serious sin\"|label 1= Jehovah's Witnesses list of \"serious sins\"}}\nAll sexual relations outside of marriage are grounds for expulsion if the individual is not deemed repentant;<ref>{{cite book|author=Chryssides, G.D.|year=1999|title=Exploring New Religions|page=103|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-304-33651-7}}</ref><ref name=\"The Watchtower 1998, page 16\">{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=August 1, 1998 |title=Imitate Jehovah\u2014Exercise Justice and Righteousness |page=16 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1998563 }}</ref> [[homosexuality|homosexual]] activity is considered a serious sin, and [[same-sex marriage]]s are forbidden. [[Abortion]] is considered [[murder]].<ref name=\"holdenmorals\" >{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|pages=26\u201327, 173}}</ref> [[Suicide]] is considered to be \"self-murder\" and a sin against God.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=June 15, 2002|pages=30, 31|title=Questions From Readers|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2002447}}</ref> Modesty in dress and grooming is frequently emphasized. [[Gambling]], drunkenness, illegal drugs, and tobacco use are forbidden.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=152,&nbsp;180}}</ref> Drinking of [[alcoholic beverage]]s is permitted in moderation.<ref name=\"holdenmorals\" />\n\nThe family structure is [[Patriarchy|patriarchal]]. The husband is considered to have authority on family decisions, but is encouraged to solicit his wife's thoughts and feelings, as well as those of his children. Marriages are required to be [[Monogamy|monogamous]] and legally [[Civil registry|registered]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=''The Bible's Viewpoint'' What Does It Mean to Be the Head of the House?|magazine=Awake!|date=July 8, 2004|page=26|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/102004484}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 15, 1984|page=11|title=Christian Weddings That Bring Joy|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1984284}}</ref> Marrying a non-believer, or endorsing such a union, is strongly discouraged and carries religious sanctions.<ref>{{cite book|title=Shepherd the Flock of God|pages=37\u201338, 124\u2013125}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=March 15, 1982|page=31|title=How should individual Christians and the congregation as a whole view the Bible advice to marry \"only in the Lord\"?|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1982212}}</ref>\n\n[[Divorce]] is discouraged, and remarriage is forbidden unless a divorce is obtained on the grounds of [[adultery]], which they refer to as \"a scriptural divorce\".<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=110\u2013112}}</ref> If a divorce is obtained for any other reason, remarriage is considered adulterous unless the prior spouse has died or is since considered to have committed [[sexual ethics|sexual immorality]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Insight on the Scriptures|chapter=Adultery|page=53|volume=1|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1200000123}}</ref> Extreme physical abuse, willful non-support of one's family, and what the denomination terms \"absolute endangerment of spirituality\" are considered grounds for legal separation.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Awake|date=July 8, 1993 |title=Marriage\u2014Why Many Walk Out |page=6 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/101993482 |quote=A legal divorce or a legal separation may provide a measure of protection from extreme abuse or willful nonsupport.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Watchtower|date=November 1, 1988|page=22|title=When Marital Peace Is Threatened|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1988807}}</ref>\n\n===Disciplinary action===\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses and congregational discipline}}\nFormal discipline is administered by congregation elders. When a baptized member is accused of committing a [[Mortal sin#Jehovah's Witnesses|serious sin]]\u2014usually cases of sexual misconduct<ref name=\"alternative\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=54\u201355}}</ref> or charges of [[apostasy]] for disputing Jehovah's Witness doctrines<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=106\u2013108}}</ref><ref name=\"Muramoto\">{{cite journal|author=Osamu Muramoto|title=Bioethics of the refusal of blood by Jehovah's Witnesses: Part 1. Should bioethical deliberation consider dissidents' views?|journal=Journal of Medical Ethics|date=August 1998|volume=24|issue=4|pages=223\u2013230|pmc=1377670|pmid=9752623|doi=10.1136/jme.24.4.223}}</ref>\u2014a judicial committee is formed to determine guilt, provide help and possibly administer discipline. [[Jehovah's Witnesses and congregational discipline#Disfellowshipping|Disfellowshipping]], a form of [[shunning]], is the strongest form of discipline, administered to an offender deemed unrepentant.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 15, 1988 |title=Discipline That Can Yield Peaceable Fruit |pages=26\u201331 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1988287 }}</ref> Contact with disfellowshipped individuals is limited to direct family members living in the same home, and with congregation elders who may invite disfellowshipped persons to apply for reinstatement;<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|title=Display Christian Loyalty When a Relative Is Disfellowshipped|pages=3\u20134|date=August 2002|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202002285}}</ref> formal business dealings may continue if contractually or financially obliged.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|title=Disfellowshipping-How to View It|date=September 15, 1981|page=24|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1981688}}</ref> Witnesses are taught that avoiding social and spiritual interaction with disfellowshipped individuals keeps the congregation free from immoral influence and that \"losing precious fellowship with loved ones may help [the shunned individual] to come 'to his senses,' see the seriousness of his wrong, and take steps to return to Jehovah.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Keep Yourselves in God's Love|chapter=Appendix: How to Treat a Disfellowshipped person|pages=207\u2013209|year=2008|publisher=Jehovah's Witnesses|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102008083}}</ref> The practice of shunning may also serve to deter other members from dissident behavior.<ref name=\"Holden163\">{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=163}}</ref> Members who disassociate (formally resign) are described in Watch Tower Society literature as wicked and are also shunned.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=September 15, 1981 |title=Disfellowshiping\u2014How to View It |page=23 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1981688 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 15, 2011 |title=Do You Hate Lawlessness? |page=31|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2011129 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Crisis of Conscience|author=Franz, Raymond|page=358}}</ref> Expelled individuals may eventually be reinstated to the congregation if deemed repentant by elders in the congregation in which the disfellowshipping was enforced.<ref name=\"shepherd\" /> Reproof is a lesser form of discipline given formally by a judicial committee to a baptized Witness who is considered repentant of serious sin; the reproved person temporarily loses conspicuous privileges of service, but suffers no restriction of social or spiritual fellowship.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=January 1, 1983 |title=Questions From Readers |pages=30\u201331 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1983008 }}</ref> [[Jehovah's Witnesses and congregational discipline#Marking|Marking]], a curtailing of social but not spiritual fellowship, is practiced if a baptized member persists in a course of action regarded as a violation of Bible principles but not a serious sin.<ref group=note>A common example given is a baptized Witness who dates a non-Witness; see {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 1999 |title=Questions From Readers |page=30 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1999527 }}</ref>\n\n===Separateness===\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses and governments}}\nJehovah's Witnesses believe that the Bible condemns the mixing of religions, on the basis that there can only be one truth from God, and therefore reject interfaith and ecumenical movements.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=December 15, 1953|title=Should the Religions Unite?|magazine=The Watchtower|pages=741\u2013742|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1953921}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|date=February 1, 1952|title=Is Interfaith God's Way?|magazine=The Watchtower|page=69|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1952081}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|page=202}}, \"The ideological argument states that, since absolute truth is unitary and exclusive of all relativisation, there can only 'logically' be one human organization to represent it. Consequently, all other religious organizations are in error and are to be strictly avoided. The absolutist view of truth further implies that, since anything less than absolute truth can only corrupt and destroy it, there can be no justification for Jehovah's witnesses having any kind of association with other religionists, however sincere the motivation might be.\"</ref> They believe that only Jehovah's Witnesses represent true Christianity, and that other religions fail to meet all the requirements set by God and will soon be destroyed.<ref>{{cite book|title=What Does The Bible Really Teach?|page=145|chapter=Worship That God Approves|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102005145}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses are taught that it is vital to remain \"separate from the world.\" The Witnesses' literature defines the \"world\" as \"the mass of mankind apart from Jehovah's approved servants\" and teach that it is morally contaminated and ruled by Satan.<ref>{{cite book|title=World|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1989|page=|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989279}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 1989 |title=Live a Balanced, Simple Life |page=11 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1989523 }}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=12}}</ref> Witnesses are taught that association with \"worldly\" people presents a \"danger\" to their faith,<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 15, 1994|page=23|title=Keep Your Distance When Danger Threatens|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1994124|quote=Steering Clear of Danger ... We must also be on guard against extended association with worldly people. Perhaps it is a neighbor, a school friend, a workmate, or a business associate. ... What are some of the dangers of such a friendship? We could begin to minimize the urgency of the times we live in or take a growing interest in material rather than spiritual things. Perhaps, because of a fear of displeasing our worldly friend, we would even desire to be accepted by the world.}}</ref> and are instructed to minimize social contact with non-members to better maintain their own standards of morality.<ref name=holdensocial >{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|pages=109\u2013112}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Franz|first=Raymond|authorlink=Raymond Franz|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|page=409|isbn=978-0-914675-17-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=March 15, 2006 |title=Each One Will Carry His Own Load |page=23 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2006206 }}</ref><ref>Bryan R. Wilson, \"The Persistence of Sects\", ''Diskus'', Journal of the British Association for the Study of Religions, Vol 1, No. 2, 1993, \"They have extensive contact with the wider public, [in Britain in 1989, 108,000 publishers undertook 23 million hours of house-calls]. Yet, they remain little affected by that exposure\u2014they confine their contacts to their single-minded purpose and avoid all other occasions for association.\"</ref> Attending [[university]] is discouraged and [[Vocational school|trade schools]] are suggested as an alternative.<ref>{{cite book|first=George D.|last=Chryssides|authorlink=George Chryssides|title=Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0-8108-6074-2|page=47|quote=Most Witnesses do not pursue higher education. It is not forbidden but is a matter of conscience. Higher education creates the risk of detracting from one's spiritual work and can result in harmful associations with fellow students who may lack integrity. It is therefore recommended that, if possible, Witnesses who undergo should continue to live at home. Those who seek education beyond school level are urged to consider their motives for doing so: education should not be for personal status or for a high salary}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Parents-What Future Do You Want for Your Children?|magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 2005|pages=26\u201331|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2005726}}</ref>\n\nJehovah's Witnesses believe their highest allegiance belongs to God's kingdom, which is viewed as an actual government in heaven, with Christ as king. They remain politically neutral, do not seek public office, and are discouraged from voting, though individual members may participate in uncontroversial community improvement issues.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=November 1, 1999 |title=Questions From Readers |page=28 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1999807|quote=As to whether they will personally vote for someone running in an election, each one of Jehovah's Witnesses makes a decision based on his Bible-trained conscience and an understanding of his responsibility to God and to the State. }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=March 1, 1983 |title=Questions From Readers |page=30 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1983169 }}</ref> Although they do not take part in politics, they respect the authority of the governments under which they live.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jw.org/en/jehovahs-witnesses/faq/political-neutrality|title=Why Do Jehovah's Witnesses Maintain Political Neutrality?|publisher=Watch Tower Society}}</ref> They do not celebrate religious holidays such as Christmas and Easter, nor do they observe birthdays, national holidays, or other celebrations they consider to honor people other than Jesus. They feel that these and many other customs have pagan origins or reflect a nationalistic or political spirit. Their position is that these traditional holidays reflect Satan's control over the world.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date= |title=Reasoning From The Scriptures |page=178 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989235 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=August 15, 2009 |title=Keep Yourselves in God's Love |page=22 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2009604 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=September 15, 1968 |title=The Seriousness of It |page=6 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1968686 }}</ref> Witnesses are told that spontaneous giving at other times can help their children to not feel deprived of birthdays or other celebrations.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 15, 1992 |title=Work to Preserve Your Family Into God's New World |page=21 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1992763 }}</ref>\n\nThey do not work in industries associated with the military, do not serve in the armed services,<ref>{{cite book|title=Worship the Only True God|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2002|page=159|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102002078}}</ref> and refuse national military service, which in some countries may result in their arrest and imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jw-media.org/kor/20071004.htm|title=Korea government promises to adopt alternative service system for conscientious objectors|date=October 4, 2007|website=Jehovah's Witnesses Official Media Web Site|publisher=Office of Public Information of Jehovah's Witnesses|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091224152134/http://www.jw-media.org/kor/20071004.htm|archivedate=December 24, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> They do not salute or pledge allegiance to flags or sing [[national anthems]] or patriotic songs.<ref>{{cite book|title=Education|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2002|pages=20\u201323|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101995044}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses see themselves as a worldwide brotherhood that transcends national boundaries and ethnic loyalties.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Owens|first=Gene|title=Trials of a Jehovah's Witness.(The Faith of Journalists)|journal=Nieman Reports|date=September 1997}}</ref> Sociologist Ronald Lawson has suggested the group's intellectual and organizational isolation, coupled with the intense indoctrination of adherents, rigid internal discipline and considerable persecution, has contributed to the consistency of its sense of urgency in its apocalyptic message.<ref>Ronald Lawson, \"Sect-state relations: Accounting for the differing trajectories of Seventh-Day Adventists and Jehovah's Witnesses\", ''Sociology of Religion'', Winter 1995, \"The urgency of the Witness's apocalyptic has changed very little over time. The intellectual isolation of the Witness leaders has allowed them to retain their traditional position, and it is they who continue to be the chief purveyors of the radical eschataology ....This commitment (to principle) was bolstered by their organizational isolation, intense indoctrination of adherents, rigid internal discipline, and considerable persecution.\"</ref>\n\n===Rejection of blood transfusions===\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses and blood transfusions}}\nJehovah's Witnesses refuse [[blood transfusion]]s, which they consider a violation of God's law based on their interpretation of [[Acts 15|Acts&nbsp;15]]:28,&nbsp;29 and other scriptures.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=i}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Reasoning From the Scriptures|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1989|pages=70\u201375|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989215}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=91}}</ref> Since 1961 the willing acceptance of a blood transfusion by an unrepentant member has been grounds for expulsion from the group.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=BMJ|title=Bioethical aspects of the recent changes in the policy of refusal of blood by Jehovah's Witnesses|date=January 6, 2001|pages=37\u201339|pmid=11141155|doi=10.1136/bmj.322.7277.37|author=Muramoto, O.|volume=322|issue=7277|pmc=1119307|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1993|page=183|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101993015}}</ref> Members are directed to refuse blood transfusions, even in \"a life-or-death situation\".<ref>{{cite book|title=United in Worship of the Only True God|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1983|pages=156\u2013160|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101983100}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Bowman|first=R. M.|author2=[[E. Calvin Beisner|Beisner, E. C.]]|author3=Ehrenborg, T.|title=Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Zondervan|year=1995|page=[https://archive.org/details/jehovahswitnesse00bowm_0/page/13 13]|isbn=978-0-310-70411-9|url=https://archive.org/details/jehovahswitnesse00bowm_0/page/13}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather|author2=Gary Botting|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|pages=[https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott/page/29 29\u201330]|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses accept non-blood alternatives and other medical procedures in lieu of blood transfusions, and their literature provides information about non-blood medical procedures.<ref>{{cite book|title=How Blood Can Save Your Life|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1990|pages=13\u201317|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101990002}}</ref>\n\nThough Jehovah's Witnesses do not accept blood transfusions of whole blood, they may accept some [[Blood plasma fractionation|blood plasma fractions]] at their own discretion.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=June 15, 2000|title=Questions From Readers\u2014Do Jehovah's Witnesses accept any medical products derived from blood?|magazine=The Watchtower|page=30|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2000447|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Sniesinski|journal=Anesthesia & Analgesia|title=Coagulopathy After Cardiopulmonary Bypass in Jehovah's Witness Patients: Management of Two Cases Using Fractionated Components and Factor VIIa|url=http://www.freeminds.org/doctrine/sniecinski_analgesia2.pdf|date=April 2007|volume=104|doi=10.1213/01.ane.0000250913.45299.f3|format=PDF|accessdate=December 30, 2008|pmid=17377078|last2=Chen|first2=EP|last3=Levy|first3=JH|last4=Szlam|first4=F|last5=Tanaka|first5=KA|issue=4|ref=harv|pages=763\u20135|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|date=August 2006|title=The Real Value of Blood|magazine=Awake!|page=11|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/102006283|ref=harv}}</ref> The Watch Tower Society provides pre-formatted [[Power of attorney#Durable power of attorney|durable power of attorney]] documents prohibiting major blood components, in which members can specify which allowable fractions and treatments they will personally accept.<ref>{{cite book|title=Durable Power of Attorney form|publisher=Watch Tower Society|date=January 2001|page=1}} Examples of permitted fractions are: [[Interferon]], [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Immune_Serum_Globulins Immune Serum Globulins] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106083752/http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Immune_Serum_Globulins |date=January 6, 2008 }} and [[Factor VIII]]; preparations made from [[Hemoglobin]] such as [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Polyheme PolyHeme] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723234940/http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Polyheme |date=July 23, 2008 }} and [[Hemopure]]. Examples of permitted procedures involving the medical use of one's own blood include: [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Intraoperative_blood_salvage cell salvage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706171315/http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Intraoperative_blood_salvage |date=July 6, 2008 }}, [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Acute_Normovolemic_Hemodilution hemodilution] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907143504/http://noblood.org/wiki/Acute_Normovolemic_Hemodilution |date=September 7, 2008 }}, [[heart lung machine]], [[dialysis]], [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Epidural_Blood_Patch epidural blood patch] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905212647/http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Epidural_Blood_Patch |date=September 5, 2008 }}, [[plasmapheresis]], [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Blood_cell_scintigraphy blood labeling or tagging] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106084037/http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Blood_cell_scintigraphy |date=January 6, 2008 }} and [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Platelet_Gel platelet gel] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106083757/http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Platelet_Gel |date=January 6, 2008 }} ([[autologous]])</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|date=November 2006|title=Our Kingdom Ministry|format=PDF|pages=5\u20136|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202006400|ref=harv}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses have established [[Jehovah's Witnesses and blood transfusions#Hospital Liaison Committees|Hospital Liaison Committees]] as a cooperative arrangement between individual Jehovah's Witnesses and medical professionals and hospitals.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Jehovah's Witnesses and Medical Profession Cooperate|magazine=Awake!|date=November 22, 1993|pages=24\u201327|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/101993847}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/article.aspx?articleID=070515_1_A9_hThef38217|title=Kim Archer, \"Jehovah's Witness liaisons help surgeons adapt\", ''Tulsa World'', May 15, 2007.}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Main|Demographics of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n[[File:JWStats1931-2015.png|366px|right]]\nJehovah's Witnesses have an active presence in most countries, but do not form a large part of the population of any country.\n\nFor 2018, Jehovah's Witnesses reported approximately 8.7&nbsp;million ''publishers''\u2014the term they use for members actively involved in preaching\u2014in about 120,000 congregations.<ref name=\"report2018\" /> For the same year, they reported over 2&nbsp;billion hours spent in preaching activity, and conducted Bible studies with more than 10 million individuals (including those conducted by Witness parents with their children<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=November 2003|title=Question Box&ndash;Should a family Bible study be reported to the congregation?|publisher=Watch Tower Society|page=3|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202003406}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=September 2008|title=Question Box&mdash;May both parents report the time used for the regular family study?|page=3|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202008324}}</ref>).<ref name=\"report2018\" /> Jehovah's Witnesses estimate their worldwide annual growth since 2018 to be 1.3%.<ref name=\"report2018\" />\n\nThe official published membership statistics, such as those mentioned above, include only those who submit reports for their personal ministry;<ref name=\"jwmediastats\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jw-media.org/aboutjw/article41.htm |title=Jehovah's Witnesses Official Media Web Site: Our History and Organization: Membership |publisher=Office of Public Information of Jehovah's Witnesses |quote=While other religious groups count their membership by occasional or annual attendance, this figure reflects only those who are actively involved in the public Bible educational work [of Jehovah's Witnesses]. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204211516/http://www.jw-media.org/aboutjw/article41.htm#membership |archivedate=December 4, 2012}}<!-- This quote addresses a common question; please do not remove--></ref> official statistics do not include ''inactive'' and ''disfellowshipped'' individuals or others who might attend their meetings. As a result, only about half of those who self-identified as Jehovah's Witnesses in independent demographic studies are considered ''active'' by the faith itself.<ref>{{cite journal|title=U.S. Religious Landscape Survey Religious Affiliation: Diverse and Dynamic|publisher=Pew Forum on Religion &amp; Public Life|date=February 2008|pages=9, 30|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thearda.com/Denoms/D_1101.asp|title=Advent Christian Church- Religious Groups - The Association of Religion Data Archives|publisher=}}</ref> The 2008 US [[Pew Research Center|Pew Forum on Religion & Public Life]] survey found a low retention rate among members of the denomination: about 37% of people raised in the group continued to identify themselves as Jehovah's Witnesses;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1716987,00.html|title=America's Unfaithful Faithful|first=David Van|last=Biema|date=February 25, 2008|via=content.time.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pewforum.org/files/2013/05/report-religious-landscape-study-full.pdf |title=PEW Forum on Religion and Public Life. U.S. Religious Landscape Survey: Religious Affiliation: Diverse and Dynamic |access-date=June 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417032920/http://www.pewforum.org/files/2013/05/report-religious-landscape-study-full.pdf |archive-date=April 17, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the next lowest retention rates were for Buddhism at 50% and Catholicism at 68%. The study also found that 65% of adult Jehovah's Witnesses in the US are converts.<ref name=\"pewfact\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2016/04/26/a-closer-look-at-jehovahs-witnesses-living-in-the-u-s|title=A closer look at Jehovah's Witnesses living in the U.S.|publisher=Pew Research Center}}</ref>\n\n==Sociological analysis==\n{{See also|Sociological classifications of religious movements}}\nSociologist [[James A. Beckford]], in his 1975 study of Jehovah's Witnesses, classified the group's organizational structure as ''Totalizing'', characterized by an assertive leadership, specific and narrow objectives, control over competing demands on members' time and energy, and control over the quality of new members. Other characteristics of the classification include likelihood of friction with secular authorities, reluctance to co-operate with other religious organizations, a high rate of membership turnover, a low rate of doctrinal change, and strict uniformity of beliefs among members.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=92, 98\u2013100}}</ref> Beckford identified the group's chief characteristics as ''historicism'' (identifying historical events as relating to the outworking of God's purpose), ''absolutism'' (conviction that Jehovah's Witness leaders dispense absolute truth), ''activism'' (capacity to motivate members to perform missionary tasks), ''rationalism'' (conviction that Witness doctrines have a rational basis devoid of mystery), ''authoritarianism'' (rigid presentation of regulations without the opportunity for criticism) and ''world indifference'' (rejection of certain secular requirements and medical treatments).<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=196\u2013207}}</ref>\n\nSociologist [[Bryan R. Wilson]], in his consideration of five religious groups including Jehovah's Witnesses, noted that each of the denominations:<ref>Bryan R. Wilson, \"The Persistence of Sects\", ''Diskus'', Journal of the British Association for the Study of Religions, Vol 1, No. 2, 1993</ref>\n# \"exists in a state of tension with the wider society;\"\n# \"imposes tests of merit on would-be members;\"\n# \"exercises stern discipline, regulating the declared beliefs and the life habits of members and prescribing and operating sanctions for those who deviate, including the possibility of expulsion;\"\n# \"demands sustained and total commitment from its members, and the subordination, and perhaps even the exclusion of all other interests.\"\n\nA sociological comparative study by the [[Pew Research Center]] found that Jehovah's Witnesses in the [[United States]] ranked highest in statistics for getting no further than high school graduation, belief in God, importance of religion in one's life, frequency of religious attendance, frequency of prayers, frequency of Bible reading outside of religious services, belief their prayers are answered, belief that their religion can only be interpreted one way, belief that theirs is the only one true faith leading to eternal life, opposition to abortion, and opposition to homosexuality. In the study, Jehovah's Witnesses ranked lowest in statistics for having an interest in politics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewforum.org/2008/06/01/u-s-religious-landscape-survey-religious-beliefs-and-practices|title=Religious Beliefs and Practices|work=U.S. Religious Landscape Survey|publisher=Pew Research Center|accessdate=December 14, 2017|date=June 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/compare/educational-distribution/by/religious-tradition/|title=Educational distribution by religious group|work=U.S. Religious Landscape Survey|publisher=Pew Research Center|accessdate=December 14, 2017|date=June 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/religious-tradition/jehovahs-witness|title=Jehovah's Witnesses|work=U.S. Religious Landscape Survey|publisher=Pew Research Center|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> It was also among the most ethnically diverse religious groups in the US.<ref name=\"pewfact\"/><!--The small sample size of JWs (215) in comparison to other groups surveyed\u2014over 9000 Evangelicals, over 8000 Catholics, over 7000 'mainline' churches, etc, total 35556) may skew these results-->\n\n==Opposition==\nControversy surrounding various beliefs, doctrines and practices of Jehovah's Witnesses has led to opposition from governments, communities, and religious groups. Religious commentator Ken Jubber wrote that \"Viewed globally, this persecution has been so persistent and of such intensity that it would not be inaccurate to regard Jehovah's Witnesses as the most persecuted group of Christians of the twentieth century.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Jubber|first=Ken|title=The Persecution of Jehovah's Witnesses in Southern Africa|journal=Social Compass|volume=24|issue=1|pages=121\u2013134|year=1977|doi=10.1177/003776867702400108}}</ref>\n\n===Persecution===\n{{Main|Persecution of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n{{See also|Persecution of Jehovah's Witnesses in Nazi Germany}}\n[[File:Purple Triangle.JPG|thumb|right|Jehovah's Witness prisoners were identified by [[purple triangle]] [[Nazi concentration camp badges|badges in Nazi concentration camps]].]]\nPolitical and religious animosity against Jehovah's Witnesses has at times led to [[mob action]] and [[government]] oppression in various countries.\nTheir stance regarding political neutrality and their refusal to serve in the military has led to imprisonment of members who refused conscription during [[World War II]] and at other times where [[national service]] has been compulsory. Their religious activities are currently banned or restricted in some countries, including [[China]], [[Vietnam]] and some Islamic states.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1993|page=490|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101993030}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1991|page=222|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/301991017}}</ref>\n\n* In 1933, there were approximately 20,000 Jehovah's Witnesses in [[Nazi Germany]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Penton|first=James|title=Jehovah's witnesses and the third reich|url=https://archive.org/details/jehovahswitnesse0000pent_f0s7|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=2004|isbn=978-0802086785|page=[https://archive.org/details/jehovahswitnesse0000pent_f0s7/page/376 376]}}</ref> of whom about 10,000 were imprisoned. Of those, 2,000 were sent to [[Nazi concentration camps]], where they were identified by [[purple triangle]]s; as many as 1,200 died, including 250 who were executed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Garbe|first=Detlef|title=Between Resistance and Martyrdom: Jehovah's Witnesses in the Third Reich|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|year=2008|location=Madison, Wisconsin|page=484|isbn=978-0-299-20794-6}}</ref><ref name=Shulman>Shulman, William L. ''A State of Terror: Germany 1933\u20131939''. Bayside, New York: Holocaust Resource Center and Archives.</ref><ref>[http://www.holocaust-trc.org/Jehovah.htm Holocaust Education Foundation website].</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Hesse|first=Hans|title=Persecution and Resistance of Jehovah's Witnesses During the Nazi Regime|publisher=Edition Temmen|year=2001|location=|isbn=978-3-86108-750-2|page=12}}</ref>\n* In [[Canada]] during World War II, Jehovah's Witnesses were interned in camps<ref>{{cite book|last=Kaplan|first=William|title=State and Salvation|location=Toronto|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1989}}</ref> along with political dissidents and people of Chinese and Japanese descent.<ref>{{cite news|last=Yaffee|first=Barbara|title=Witnesses Seek Apology for Wartime Persecution|work=The Globe and Mail|date=September 9, 1984|page=4}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses faced discrimination in [[Quebec]] until the [[Quiet Revolution]], including bans on distributing literature or holding meetings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canlii.org/en/ca/scc/doc/1953/1953canlii3/1953canlii3.html|title=Saumur v Quebec (City of)|last=Supreme Court of Canada|date=|website=|series=[1953] 2 SCR 299|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706012152/http://www.canlii.org/en/ca/scc/doc/1953/1953canlii3/1953canlii3.html|archive-date=July 6, 2011|url-status=dead|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canlii.org/en/ca/scc/doc/1959/1959canlii50/1959canlii50.html|title=Roncarelli v Duplessis|last=Supreme Court of Canada|date=|website=|series=[1959] SCR 121|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112043742/http://www.canlii.org/en/ca/scc/doc/1959/1959canlii50/1959canlii50.html|archive-date=January 12, 2013|url-status=dead|access-date=}}</ref>\n* In 1951, about 9,300 Jehovah's Witnesses in the [[Soviet Union]] were deported to [[Siberia]] as part of [[Operation North]] in April 1951.<ref name=\"passat\">\u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041f\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0442 .\"\u0422\u0440\u0443\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u044b \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b (1940\u20131950)\". \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430: \u0418\u0437\u0434. Terra, 1994 {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n* In April 2017, the [[Supreme Court of Russia]] labeled Jehovah's Witnesses an extremist organization, banned its activities in [[Russia]] and issued an order to confiscate the organization's assets.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-religion-jehovah-s-idUSKBN17M1ZT|title=Russian court bans Jehovah's Witnesses as extremist|publisher=delfi.lt |accessdate=April 20, 2017|newspaper=Reuters|date=April 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAuthors including [[William J. Whalen|William Whalen]], Shawn Francis Peters and former Witnesses [[Barbara Grizzuti Harrison]], Alan Rogerson and William Schnell have claimed the arrests and mob violence in the United States in the 1930s and 1940s were the consequence of what appeared to be a deliberate course of provocation of authorities and other religious groups by Jehovah's Witnesses. Whalen, Harrison and Schnell have suggested Rutherford invited and cultivated opposition for publicity purposes in a bid to attract dispossessed members of society, and to convince members that persecution from the outside world was evidence of the truth of their struggle to serve God.<ref>{{cite book|last=Peters|first=Shawn Francis|title=Judging Jehovah's Witnesses: Religious Persecution and the Dawn of the Rights Revolution|url=https://archive.org/details/judgingjehovahsw0000pete|url-access=registration|publisher=University Press of Kansas|year=2000|pages=[https://archive.org/details/judgingjehovahsw0000pete/page/82 82], 116\u20139|isbn=978-0-7006-1008-2}}</ref><ref>Barbara Grizzuti Harrison, ''Visions of Glory'', 1978, chapter 6.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Whalen|first=William J.|title=Armageddon Around the Corner: A Report on Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=John Day Company|year=1962|location=New York|page=190}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Schnell|first=William|title=30 Years a Watchtower Slave|publisher=Baker Book House, Grand Rapids|year=1971|pages=104\u2013106|isbn=978-0-8010-6384-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Rogerson|first=Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable & Co, London|year=1969|page=59|isbn=978-0094559400}}</ref> Watch Tower Society literature of the period directed that Witnesses should \"never seek a controversy\" nor resist arrest, but also advised members not to co-operate with police officers or courts that ordered them to stop preaching, and to prefer jail rather than pay fines.<ref>{{cite book|title=Advice for Kingdom Publishers|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1939|pages=5\u20136, 14}}</ref>\n\n===Legal challenges===\n{{Main|Supreme Court cases involving Jehovah's Witnesses by country}}\nSeveral cases involving Jehovah's Witnesses have been heard by Supreme Courts throughout the world.<ref>[[Gary Botting]], ''Fundamental Freedoms and Jehovah's Witnesses'' (Calgary: University of Calgary Press, 1993)</ref> The cases generally relate to their right to practice their religion, displays of patriotism and military service, and blood transfusions.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1993|pages=679\u2013701|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101993041}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, legal challenges by Jehovah's Witnesses prompted a series of state and federal court rulings that reinforced judicial protections for civil liberties.<ref>Botting, ''Fundamental Freedoms and Jehovah's Witnesses'', pp. 1\u201314; Shawn Francis Peters, ''Judging Jehovah's Witnesses'', University Press of Kansas: 2000, pages 12\u201316.</ref> Among the rights strengthened by Witness court victories in the United States are the protection of religious conduct from federal and state interference, the right to abstain from patriotic rituals and military service, the right of patients to refuse medical treatment, and the right to engage in public discourse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knocking.org/Jehovahs_Witness_History_Civil_Rights.html|title=Jehovah's Witnesses and civil rights|publisher=Knocking.org|accessdate=August 16, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901075011/http://www.knocking.org/Jehovahs_Witness_History_Civil_Rights.html|archivedate=September 1, 2012}}</ref> Similar cases in their favor have been heard in Canada.<ref>Botting, ''Fundamental Freedoms...'', pp. 15\u2013201</ref>\n\n==Criticism and controversy==\n{{Main|Criticism of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\nJehovah's Witnesses have received criticism from mainstream Christianity, members of the medical community, former members and commentators regarding [[Jehovah's Witnesses beliefs|their beliefs]] and [[Jehovah's Witnesses practices|practices]]. The movement has been accused of doctrinal inconsistency and reversals, failed predictions, mistranslation of the Bible, harsh treatment of former members and autocratic and coercive leadership. Criticism has also focused on their rejection of [[blood transfusion]]s, particularly in life-threatening medical situations, and failing to report cases of [[sexual abuse]] to the authorities. Many of the claims are denied by Jehovah's Witnesses and some have also been disputed by courts and religious scholars.\n\n===Free speech and thought===\nDoctrines of Jehovah's Witnesses are established by the Governing Body.<ref name=\"Holden22\">{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=22}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/case-studies/case-study-29-jehovahs-witnesses|title=Case Study 29: Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses|date=July 27, 2015|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse}}</ref> The denomination does not tolerate dissent over doctrines and practices;<ref name=\"voice\" /><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 1967 |title=Following Faithful Shepherds with Life in View |page=591 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1967723 |quote=Make haste to identify the visible theocratic organization of God that represents his king, Jesus Christ. It is essential for life. Doing so, be complete in accepting its every aspect ... in submitting to Jehovah's visible theocratic organization, we must be in full and complete agreement with every feature of its apostolic procedure and requirements.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 1, 2007 |title=Loyal to Christ and His Faithful Slave |page=24 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2007245 |quote=When we loyally submit to the direction of the faithful slave and its Governing Body, we are submitting to Christ, the slave's Master.}}</ref><ref name=\"Beckford dissent\">{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=89, 95, 103, 120, 204, 221}}</ref> members who openly disagree with the group's teachings are expelled and shunned.<ref name=\"Muramoto\" /> Witness publications strongly discourage followers from questioning doctrine and counsel received from the Governing Body, reasoning that it is to be trusted as part of \"God's organization\".<ref name=\"Beckford dissent\" /><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=January 15, 1983 |title='Exposing the Devil's Subtle Designs' and 'Armed for the Fight Against Wicked Spirits' |pages=18\u201327 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1983046 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=August 15, 1981 |title=Serving Jehovah Shoulder to Shoulder |page=28 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1981609 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 1, 1952 |title=Jehovah's Theocratic Organization Today |pages=79\u201381 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1952083 }}</ref> It also warns members to \"avoid independent thinking\", claiming such thinking \"was introduced by Satan the Devil\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Exposing the Devil's Subtle Designs|magazine=The Watchtower|date=January 15, 1983|pages=27|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1983046|quote=From the very outset of his rebellion Satan called into question God's way of doing things. He promoted independent thinking. ... How is such independent thinking manifested? A common way is by questioning the counsel that is provided by God's visible organization.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Visits from Older Men Benefit God's People|magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 15, 1979|pages=20|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1979127|quote=In a world where people are tossed about by confusing winds of religious doctrine, Jehovah's people need to be stable, full-grown Christians. (Eph. 4:13, 14) Their position must be steadfast, not shifting quickly because of independent thinking or emotional pressures.}}</ref> and would \"cause division\".<ref>{{cite magazine|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Building a Firm Foundation in Christ|magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 1, 1964|pages=277\u2013278|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1964324|quote=It is through the columns of The Watchtower that Jehovah provides direction and constant Scriptural counsel to his people, and it requires careful study and attention to details in order to apply this information, to get a full understanding of the principles involved, and to assure ourselves of right thinking on these matters. It is in this way that we \"are thoroughly able to grasp mentally with all the holy ones\" the fullness of our commission and of the preaching responsibility that Jehovah has placed on all Christians as footstep followers of his Son. Any other course would produce independent thinking and cause division.}}</ref> Those who openly disagree with official teachings are condemned as \"apostates\" who are \"mentally diseased\".<ref name=\"Holden163\" /><ref>See also Raymond Franz, ''In Search of Christian Freedom'', pg. 358.</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 2011 |title=Will You Heed Jehovah's Clear Warnings? |page=15 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2011524 }}</ref>\n\nFormer members Heather and [[Gary Botting]] compare the cultural paradigms of the denomination to [[George Orwell]]'s ''[[Nineteen Eighty-four]]'',<ref>''The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses'', Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1984, ''passim''.</ref> and Alan Rogerson describes the group's leadership as [[totalitarianism|totalitarian]].<ref>Alan Rogerson, ''Millions Now Living Will Never Die'', Constable, 1969, page 50.</ref> Other critics charge that by disparaging individual decision-making, the group's leaders cultivate a system of unquestioning obedience<ref name=\"Bevindependent\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=204, 221}}, ''The habit of questioning or qualifying Watch Tower doctrine is not only under-developed among the Witnesses: it is strenuously combated at all organizational levels''</ref> in which Witnesses abrogate all responsibility and rights over their personal lives.<ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather|author2=Gary Botting|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|page=[https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott/page/90 90]|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2|quote=Most Witnesses, although ''capable'' of intelligent, reasonable thought, have as part of the payment for paradise delegated authority to the organization for directing their lives ... and finally abrogate ''all'' responsibility and rights over their personal lives\u2014in effect, allowing the society to do their thinking for them.}}</ref><ref>Alan Rogerson, ''Millions Now Living Will Never Die'', Constable, 1969, page 178, \"The newly converted Witness must conform immediately to the doctrines of the Watchtower Society, thus whatever individuality of mind he possessed before conversion is liable to be eradicated if he stays in the movement.\".</ref> Critics also accuse the group's leaders of exercising \"intellectual dominance\" over Witnesses,<ref>James A. Beverley, ''Crisis of Allegiance'', Welch Publishing Company, Burlington, Ontario, 1986, {{ISBN|0-920413-37-4}}, pages 25\u201326, 101.</ref> controlling information<ref name=\"Muramoto\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=153}}</ref><ref>Alan Rogerson, ''Millions Now Living Will Never Die'', Constable, 1969, page 2, \"In addition to the prevalent ignorance outside the Witness movement, there is much ignorance within it. It will soon become obvious to the reader that the Witnesses are an indoctrinated people whose beliefs and thoughts are shaped by the Watchtower Society.\"</ref> and creating \"mental isolation\", which former Governing Body member [[Raymond Franz]] argued were all elements of [[mind control]].<ref>R. Franz, \"In Search of Christian Freedom\", chapter 12</ref>\n\nJehovah's Witness publications state that consensus of faith aids unity, and deny that unity restricts individuality or imagination.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Maintaining our Christian Oneness|magazine=The Watchtower|date=August 15, 1988|pages=28\u201330|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1988608}}</ref> Historian James Irvin Lichti has rejected the description of the denomination as \"totalitarian\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=vsrJLASVC3QC&pg=359&Ipg=PA359#v=onepage ''The Routledge History of the Holocaust'', Routledge, 2010], \"Labeling the Jehovah's Witnesses as totalitarian trivializes the term totalitarian and defames the Jehovah's Witnesses.\"</ref>\n\nSociologist [[Rodney Stark]] states that Jehovah's Witness leaders are \"not always very democratic\" and that members \"are expected to conform to rather strict standards,\" but adds that \"enforcement tends to be very informal, sustained by the close bonds of friendship within the group\", and that Jehovah's Witnesses see themselves as \"part of the power structure rather than subject to it.\"<ref name=\"Stark\"/> Sociologist Andrew Holden states that most members who join millenarian movements such as Jehovah's Witnesses have made an informed choice.<ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|pages=x, 7}}</ref> However, he also states that defectors \"are seldom allowed a dignified exit\",<ref name=\"Holden163\" /> and describes the administration as [[autocracy|autocratic]].<ref name=\"Holden22\" />\n\n===New World Translation===\n{{Main|New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures}}\nVarious Bible scholars, including [[Bruce M. Metzger]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Metzger |first1=Bruce |date=July 1, 1964 |title=Book Review: New World Translation of the Christian Greek Scriptures |url=http://www.ubs-translations.org/tbt/1964/03/TBT196403.html?seq=49 |journal=The Bible Translator |volume=15 |issue=3 |pages=151 |access-date=October 30, 2018 | quote=On the whole, one gains a tolerably good impression of the scholarly equipment of the translators (their names are not divulged.). They refer not only to modern translations, including various English, German, French, Spanish, Italian, and Portuguese translations, but to ancient versions as well, including the Old Latin, Old Syriac, Vulgate, Armenian and Ethiopoc versions. Frequently an intelligent use of critical information is apparent.}}</ref> and [[MacLean Gilmour]],<ref>{{cite journal |last=Gilmour |first=MacLean |date=September 1966 |title=The Use and Abuse of the Book of Revelation|journal=Andover Newton Quarterly |volume=7 |issue=1|pages=25\u201326 |quote=The New World translation was made by a committee whose membership has never been revealed-a committee that possessed an unusual competence in Greek ... It is clear that doctrinal considerations influenced many turns of phrase, but the work is no crack-pot or pseudo-historical fraud.* ... *See Robert M. McCoy 'Jehovah's Witnesses and Their New Testament', Andover Newton Quarterly, Jan., 1963, Vol. 3, No. 3, pp. 15\u201331}}</ref> have said that while scholarship is evident in ''New World Translation'', its rendering of certain texts are inaccurate and biased in favor of Witness practices and doctrines.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Metzger|first=Bruce M.|date=April 1, 1953|title=The Jehovah's Witnesses and Jesus Christ|journal=Theology Today|volume=10|issue=1|page=74|doi=10.1177/004057365301000110|bibcode=1998ThT....55..305G}} See also Metzger, \"The New World Translation of the Christian Greek Scriptures,\" ''The Bible Translator'' (July 1964).</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=McCoy |first=Robert |date=January 1963 |title=Jehovah's Witnesses and Their New Testament|journal=Andover Newton Quarterly |volume=3|issue=3|pages=15\u201331|quote=The translation of the New Testament is evidence of the presence in the movement of scholars qualified to deal intelligently with the many problems of Biblical translation. ... In not a few instances the New World Translation contains passages which must be considered as 'theological translations.'}}</ref><ref name=\"haas\">{{cite journal|last=Haas|first=Samuel S.|date=December 1955|title=Book Review: ''New World Translation of the Hebrew Scriptures, Vol. I'' by New World Bible Translation Committee|journal=Journal of Biblical Literature|volume=74|issue=4|pages=282\u2013283|doi=10.2307/3261681|quote=this work indicates a great deal of effort and thought as well as considerable scholarship, it is to be regretted that religious bias was allowed to colour many passages.|jstor=3261681}} See also {{cite journal|last=Owens|first=John Joseph|date=April 1, 1956|title=Book Review: New World Translation of the Hebrew Scriptures|journal=Review & Expositor|volume=53|issue=2|pages=253\u2013254|doi=10.1177/003463735605300239}}</ref><ref name=\"Ankerberg\">{{cite book|author1=John Ankerberg|author2=John Weldon|author3=Dillon Burroughs|title=The Facts on Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rLHuulPCiTgC&pg=PA43|year=2008|publisher=Harvest House Publishers|location=Eugene, OR|isbn=978-0-7369-3907-2|pages=43\u201345}} See also John Ankerberg and John Weldon, 2003, ''The New World Translation of the Jehovah's Witnesses'', accessible [https://web.archive.org/web/20121029043702/http://www.johnankerberg.org/Articles/ATRI-Bible-School/Fall-Bible-School/fall-bible-school-jw-new-world-translation.htm online]</ref><ref name=\"pentonbible\" >{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=wmsdmva7u6kC&id=38SYXalMLeQC&pg=PA175 174\u2013176]}}</ref> Critics of the group such as Edmund C. Gruss,<ref>Edmond C. Gruss, ''Apostles of Denial'', p. 211: \"the honest mind can only conclude that this work, although outwardly scholarly, is plainly in many places, just the opposite.\"</ref> and Christian writers such as [[Ray Stedman|Ray C. Stedman]],<ref>Stedman, R.C., \"The New World Translation of the Christian Greek Scriptures,\" Our Hope 50; 34, July 1953. 30 as quoted in Edmond C. Gruss, ''Apostles of Denial'', p. 209: \"A close examination, which gets beneath the outward veneer of scholarship, reveals a veritable shambles of bigotry, ignorance, prejudice, and biais which violates every rule of biblical criticism and every standard of scholarly integrity.\"</ref> [[Walter Ralston Martin|Walter Martin]], Norman Klann<ref>Martin, W., & Klann, N., Jehovah of the Watchtower, (Minneapolis: Bethany, 1974 161)</ref> and [[Anthony A. Hoekema|Anthony Hoekema]]<ref>Hoekema, A., The Four Major Cults (Exeter: Paternoster, 1963) 208-9</ref> state that the ''New World Translation'' exhibits scholastic dishonesty. Most criticism of the ''New World Translation'' relates to its rendering of the New Testament, particularly regarding the introduction of the name ''Jehovah'' and in passages related to the Trinity doctrine.<ref>G. H\u00c9BERT/EDS, \"Jehovah's Witnesses\", ''The New Catholic Encyclopedia'', Gale, 2005<sup>2</sup>, Vol. 7, p. 751.</ref><ref>Anthony A. Hoekema, The Four Major Cults, Christian Science, Jehovah's Witnesses, Mormonism, Seventh-day Adventism, William B. Eerdmans, 1963, {{ISBN|0802831176}}, pp. 208\u2013209</ref>\n\n===Unfulfilled predictions===\n{{Main|Watch Tower Society unfulfilled predictions}}\nWatch Tower Society publications have claimed that God has used Jehovah's Witnesses (and formerly, the International Bible Students) to declare his will<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 1, 1997 |title=Messengers of Godly Peace Pronounced Happy |page=21 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1997325 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1993|page=708|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101993043}}</ref> and has provided advance knowledge about [[Armageddon]] and the establishment of [[God's kingdom]].<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 15, 1980 |title=Execution of the 'Great Harlot' Nears |page=17 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1980765 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 2010 |title=What Jehovah's Day Will Reveal |page=5 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2010521 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 1960 |title=Staying Awake with the \"Faithful and Discreet Slave\" |page=444 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1960525 |quote=In 1942 the faithful and discreet slave guided by Jehovah's unerring spirit made known that the democracies would win World War II and that there would be a United Nations organization set up ... Once again the faithful and discreet slave has been tipped off ahead of time for the guidance of all lovers of God.}} (Footnote cites the booklet ''Peace\u2014Can It Last'', 1942, pages 21,22.)</ref> Some publications also claimed that God has used Jehovah's Witnesses and the International Bible Students as a modern-day prophet.<ref group=note>Raymond Franz cites numerous examples. In ''Crisis of Conscience'', 2002, pg. 173, he quotes from {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 1, 1972 |title=They Shall Know That a Prophet Was Among Them |pages=197\u2013200 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1972241}} which states that God had raised Jehovah's Witnesses as a prophet \"to warn (people) of dangers and declare things to come\". He also cites {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 1, 1997 |title=Identifying the Right Kind of Messenger |page=8 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1997323 }} which identifies the Witnesses as his \"true messengers ... by making the messages he delivers through them come true\", in contrast to \"false messengers\", whose predictions fail. In ''In Search of Christian Freedom,'' 2007, he quotes {{cite book|title=Commissioned to Speak in the Divine Name|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1971|pages=70, 292|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101971004}} which describes Witnesses as the modern Ezekiel class, \"a genuine prophet within our generation\". The Watch Tower book noted: \"Concerning the message faithfully delivered by the Ezekiel class, Jehovah positively states that it 'must come true' ... those who wait undecided until it does 'come true' will also have to know that a prophet himself had proved to be in the midst of them.\" He also cites {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 15, 1980 |title=Execution of the Great Harlot Nears |page=17 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1980765 }} which claims God gives the Witnesses \"special knowledge that others do not have ... advance knowledge about this system's end\".</ref> [[George D. Chryssides]] stated, \"while prediction may be part of a biblical prophet's role, the root meaning of prophecy is that of proclaiming God's word.\" He went on to say that, \"Jehovah's Witnesses ... are the recipients of prophecy, who regard themselves as invested with the interpretation of biblical writings.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Chryssides|first=George|title=Jehovah's Witnesses Continuity and Change|publisher=Ashgate|year=2016|location=England|page=224|isbn=978-1-4094-5608-7}}</ref><ref group=note>In ''Jehovah's Witnesses Continuity and Change'' Chryssides states, after discussing the April 1, 1972 ''Watchtower'' article, that, \"It would be tedious to comment on each passage in which Watch Tower literature explains the Jehovah's Witnesses' position on prophecy. Some of it may lack the precision that its detractors appear to demand, but the Society's position is quite clear. Jehovah's Witnesses do not claim to have any new revelation or people who are designated as prophets. As cessationists, they identify the ability to prophesy as a gift that died out with the first generation of Christians, but prophetic utterances remain in the Bible, which serves as the key source of authority. ... since the Bible is held to contain predictive prophecy, Jehovah's Witnesses claim to see into the future through the Society's interpretation of scripture.\" pg 225.</ref> With these interpretations, Jehovah's Witnesses' publications have made various predictions about world events they believe were prophesied in the Bible.<ref name=WT59>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=January 15, 1959 |title=Down with the Old-Up with the New! |pages=39\u201341 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1959041 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Crompton|first=Robert|title=Counting the Days to Armageddon|publisher=James Clarke & Co|year=1996|location=Cambridge|pages=9, 115|isbn=978-0-227-67939-5}}</ref> Failed predictions have led to the alteration or abandonment of some doctrines.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1993|pages=78, 632|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101993008}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=219\u2013221}}</ref> Some failed predictions had been presented as \"beyond doubt\" or \"approved by God\".<ref>James A. Beverley, ''Crisis of Allegiance'', Welch Publishing Company, Burlington, Ontario, 1986, {{ISBN|0-920413-37-4}}, page 86\u201391.</ref>\n\nThe Watch Tower Society rejects accusations that it is a [[false prophet]],<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite magazine |magazine=Awake!|date=March 22, 1993 |title=Why So Many False Alarms? |pages=3\u20134 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/101993201}} footnote</ref> stating that its interpretations are not inspired or infallible,<ref>{{cite book|title=Revelation\u2014Its Grand Climax|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1988|page=9|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101988002}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Reasoning From the Scriptures|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|chapter=False Prophets\u2014Have not Jehovah's Witnesses made errors in their teachings?|page=137|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989228}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=To Whom Shall We Go but Jesus Christ?|magazine=Watchtower|date=March 1, 1979|page=23|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1979167|quote=the \"faithful and discreet slave\" has alerted all of God's people to the sign of the times indicating the nearness of God's Kingdom rule. In this regard, however, it must be observed that this \"faithful and discreet slave\" was never inspired, never perfect. Those writings by certain members of the \"slave\" class that came to form the Christian part of God's Word were inspired and infallible [the bible], but that is not true of other writings since.}}</ref> and that it has not claimed its predictions were \"the words of Jehovah.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Chryssides has suggested that with the exception of statements about 1914, 1925 and 1975, the changing views and dates of the Jehovah's Witnesses are largely attributable to changed understandings of biblical chronology rather than to failed predictions.<ref name=\"Georgie\"/> Chryssides further states, \"it is therefore simplistic and na\u00efve to view the Witnesses as a group that continues to set a single end-date that fails and then devise a new one, as many counter-cultists do.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|author=George D. Chryssides|year=2008|page=xiv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xx6nUwZzeCsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=jehovah's+witnesses#v=onepage&q=simplistic|isbn=9780810862692}}</ref> However, sociologist Andrew Holden states that since the foundation of the movement around 140 years ago, \"Witnesses have maintained that we are living on the precipice of the end of time.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=7}}</ref>\n\n===Handling of sexual abuse cases===\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses' handling of child sex abuse}}\nJehovah's Witnesses have been accused of having policies and culture that help to conceal cases of sexual abuse within the organization.<ref name=\"ousted\">{{cite news|last=Goodstein|first=Laurie|title=Ousted members say Jehovah's Witnesses' policy on abuse hides offenses|newspaper=The New York Times|date=August 11, 2002|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/08/11/us/ousted-members-say-jehovah-s-witnesses-policy-on-abuse-hides-offenses.html |accessdate=October 1, 2015}}</ref> The group has been criticized for its \"two witness rule\" for church discipline, based on its application of scriptures at Deuteronomy 19:15 and Matthew 18:15\u201317, which requires sexual abuse to be substantiated by secondary evidence if the accused person denies any wrongdoing.<ref name=\"sexmedia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jw-media.org/aboutjw/article23.htm|title=Jehovah's Witnesses and Child Protection|publisher=Jehovah's Witnesses Official Media website|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091123144858/http://www.jw-media.org/aboutjw/article23.htm|archivedate=November 23, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/file-list/Case%20Study%2029%20-%20Transcript%20-%20Jehovahs%20Witnesses%20-%20Day%20152%20-%2004082015.pdf|title=Public Hearing - Case Study 29 (Day 152)|page=67,72|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse, Australia|quote=in the absence of a confession or circumstantial evidence or other indicators, would we act judicially on one witness as the courts would do, the answer would be no, and I don't see that changing, in harmony with the scriptures. ... Q. Insofar as a second witness is concerned, is that requirement covered by, for example, scientific evidence? A. Certainly. Q. So if there was some external forensic scientific or direct evidence which is not of an observer to the incident, but someone who observes some corroborative aspect to the incident, that would be sufficient, would it? A. The answer is yes... we, as the case files will show, have disfellowshipped people for being in an inappropriate setting where there is some allegation.}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/file-list/Case%20Study%2029%20-%20Transcript%20-%20Jehovahs%20Witnesses%20-%20Day%20155%20-%2014082015.pdf|title=Public Hearing - Case Study 29 (Day 155)|page=44,45|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse, Australia}}</ref> In cases where corroboration is lacking, the Watch Tower Society's instruction is that \"the elders will leave the matter in Jehovah's hands\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Shepherd the Flock of God|publisher=Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|year=2010|location=Brooklyn, New York|page=72}}</ref> A former member of the headquarters staff, Barbara Anderson, says the policy effectively requires that there be another witness to an act of molestation, \"which is an impossibility\". Anderson says the policies \"protect pedophiles rather than protect the children.\"<ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|author1=[[Lisa Myers]]|author2=Richard Greenberg|title=New evidence in Jehovah's Witness allegations|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/21917798|publisher=[[NBC News]]|location=New York, NY|date=November 21, 2007}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses maintain that they have a strong policy to protect children, adding that the best way to protect children is by educating parents; they also state that they do not sponsor activities that separate children from parents.<ref name=\"sexmedia\"/><ref name=\"cpt_E\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jw.org/en/news/legal/legal-resources/information/packet-jw-scripturally-based-position-child-protection|title=Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses\u2019 Scripturally Based Position on Child Protection|website=Official Website of Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=Awake!|title=How to Protect Your Children|date=October 2007|pages=4\u20138|url=http://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/102007362}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/file-list/Case%20Study%2029%20-%20Findings%20Report%20-%20Jehovahs%20Witnesses.pdf|title=Report of case study no.29|page=9,28|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse, Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe group's failure to report abuse allegations to authorities has also been criticized.<ref name=\"MediaWales\">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Ciaran|date=June 29, 2014|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/jehovahs-witnesses-destroyed-documents-showing-7340603|title=Jehovah's Witnesses destroyed documents showing child abuse allegations against church elder|publisher=[[Media Wales]]|location=Cardiff, UK|website=Wales Online}}</ref> The Watch Tower Society's policy is that elders inform authorities when required by law to do so, but otherwise leave that action up to the victim and his or her family.<ref name=\"sexmedia\" /><ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/file-list/Case%20Study%2029%20-%20Transcript%20-%20Jehovahs%20Witnesses%20-%20Day%20152%20-%2004082015.pdf|title=Public Hearing - Case Study 29 (Day 152)|pages=24\u201326|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse, Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Shepherd the Flock of God|publisher=Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|year=2010|location=Brooklyn, New York|pages=131\u2013132}}</ref> The Australian [[Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse]] found that of 1,006 alleged perpetrators of child sexual abuse investigated by Jehovah's Witness elders since 1950, \"not one was reported by the church to secular authorities.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/> The Royal Commission also found that the Watch Tower Society legal department routinely provided incorrect information to elders based on an incorrect understanding about what constitutes a legal obligation to report crimes in Australia.<ref>{{cite report|title=Report of Case Study No. 29|page=62|quote=The Royal Commission heard evidence that, before the public hearing of this case study, the Jehovah's Witness organisation did not consider that concealment offences were independent of obligations under mandatory reporting laws to report child sexual abuse.}}</ref><ref>\"Case Study 29\", Day 153 p.16, 41&mdash;44, ''Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse'', July 2015.]</ref> William Bowen, a former Jehovah's Witness elder who established the [[Silentlambs]] organization to assist sex abuse victims within the denomination, has claimed Witness leaders discourage followers from reporting incidents of sexual misconduct to authorities, and other critics claim the organization is reluctant to alert authorities in order to protect its \"crime-free\" reputation.<ref name=\"ousted\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Cutrer|first=Corrie|title=Witness leaders accused of shielding molesters|journal=Christianity Today|date=March 5, 2001|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2001/004/11.23.html|quote=Paul Carden, executive director for the Centers for Apologetics Research in San Juan Capistrano, California, says this protective attitude is prevalent in the WTBTS. \"There is a fortress mentality,\" Carden says. \"The Watchtower Society is loath to admit wrongdoing of any sort. Because they portray themselves as being Jehovah's sole mouthpiece to mankind, they have sought to present themselves as being above question.\"}}</ref> In court cases in the United Kingdom and the United States the Watch Tower Society has been found to have been negligent in its failure to protect children from known sex offenders within the congregation,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://appellatecases.courtinfo.ca.gov/search/case/mainCaseScreen.cfm?dist=1&doc_id=2025979&doc_no=A136641&request_token=NiIwLSInLkg9W0BJSSJNSEhIMFw6UVxfICM%2BXz5TICAgCg%3D%3D |title=Jane Doe (Candace Conti) v. The Watchtower Bible and Tract Society of New York Inc. et al.|publisher=[[California courts of appeal#First District|California Court of Appeal, First Appellate District, Division Three]] |date=April 13, 2015}} [http://www.courts.ca.gov/opinions/archive/A136641.PDF Court of Appeal Opinion] <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Former Jehovah's Witness Takes on Church Over Sex Abuse Allegations|url=https://www.youtube.com/embed/OPcYn4AiwQE?rel=0&autoplay=1|format=VIDEO|publisher=[[ABC News]]|location=New York, NY|date=March 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-33201010|title=Jehovah's Witnesses to compensate woman over sex abuse|work=[[BBC News]]|location=London, UK|date=June 19, 2015}}</ref> and the Society has settled other child abuse lawsuits out of court, reportedly paying as much as $780,000 to one plaintiff without admitting wrongdoing.<ref name=\"NBC\" />\n\nIn 2017, the [[Charity Commission for England and Wales]] began an inquiry into Jehovah's Witnesses' handling of allegations of child sexual abuse in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"BBCBuchanan\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40719773 |title=Jehovah's Witnesses let sex offender interrogate victims|website=BBC News |date=July 26, 2017|author=Michael Buchanan |accessdate= November 20, 2017|quote=One particular concern is the Church's policy of dismissing an allegation if it fails its two-witness policy, which states two people need to have seen the abuse for the Church to proceed with a full investigation. There are also calls for the independent child abuse inquiry to examine the Church's policy.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/manchester-new-moston-congregation-of-jehovahs-witnesses-inquiry-report/manchester-new-moston-congregation-of-jehovahs-witnesses |title=Decision: Manchester New Moston Congregation of Jehovah's Witnesses|website=Charity Commission for England and Wales|date=July 26, 2017 |author= |accessdate= November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{details|Bibliography of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n* {{cite book |first=Gary |last=Botting |authorlink=Gary Botting  |title=Fundamental Freedoms and Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=University of Calgary Press|year=1993  |isbn=978-1-895176-06-3}}\n* {{cite book  |first=Heather and Gary |last=Botting  |authorlink=Gary Botting  |title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott |url-access=registration |publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984  |isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2}}\n* {{cite book  |first=George D. |last=Chryssides  |authorlink=George Chryssides  |title=Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2008  |isbn=978-0-8108-6074-2}}\n* {{cite book|first=George D.|last=Chryssides|authorlink=George Chryssides|title=Jehovah's Witnesses: Continuity and Change|publisher=Routledge|year=2016|isbn=9781409456087}}\n* Crompton, Robert. ''Counting the Days to Armageddon''. James Clarke & Co, Cambridge, 1996. {{ISBN|0-227-67939-3}}\n** A detailed examination of the development of Jehovah's Witnesses' eschatology.\n* {{cite book  |last=Holden |first=Andrew  |title=Jehovah's Witnesses: Portrait of a Contemporary Religious Movement  |url=https://archive.org/details/jehovahswitnesse00andr |url-access=registration |publisher=Routledge  |year=2002  |isbn=978-0-415-26610-9}}\n** An academic study on the sociological aspects of Jehovah's Witnesses phenomenon.\n* Kaplan, William. ''State and Salvation'' Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1989. {{ISBN|0-8020-5842-6}}\n** Documents the Witnesses' fight for civil rights in Canada and the US amid political persecution during World War II.\n* {{cite book|last=Knox|first=Zoe|title=Jehovah's Witnesses and the Secular World: From the 1870s to the Present|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=London|year=2018|isbn=9781137396044}}\n* {{cite book |last=Penton|first=M. James  |authorlink=James Penton  |title=Apocalypse Delayed: The Story of Jehovah's Witnesses  |publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1997 |isbn=978-0-8020-7973-2}}\n** Penton, professor emeritus of history at University of Lethbridge and a former member of the group, examines the history of Jehovah's Witnesses, and their doctrines.\n* Rogerson, Alan. ''Millions Now Living Will Never Die''. London: Constable & Co, 1969. {{ISBN|978-0094559400}}\n** Detailed history of the Watch Tower movement, particularly its early years, a summary of Witness doctrines and the organizational and personal framework in which Witnesses conduct their lives\n* {{cite book|last=Schulz|first=B. W.|title=A Separate Identity: Organizational Identity Among Readers of Zion's Watch Tower: 1870-1887|publisher=Fluttering Wings Press|year=2014|isbn=978-1304969408}}\n** Detailed history of the Watch Tower movement's earliest years written to an academic standard. Based on fresh research into original documents of the era. This is volume one of a planned two volume work.\n* Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania. ''Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom'' (1993)\n** Official history of Jehovah's Witnesses.\n* Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania. ''Faith In Action'' (2-DVD series), (2010\u20132011)\n** Official history of Jehovah's Witnesses.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n<!-- Please discuss any links you wish to add to this list on this article's talk page before adding them. To avoid spam, link creep, and keep the resources in this section of high quality, we want to discuss any external resource inclusion before it is added. Thank you! -->\n* {{Official website|https://www.jw.org/en/}}\n* [https://tv.jw.org/#en/ JW Broadcasting] \u2014 Official video streaming site\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/witnesses/ BBC - Religion: Jehovah's Witnesses]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-28166192/ Jehovah's Witnesses new method] - BBC News Magazine article\n\n{{Christianity footer}}\n{{New Religious Movements}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1870 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Jehovah's Witnesses| ]]\n[[Category:Apocalyptic groups]]\n[[Category:Bible Student movement]]\n[[Category:Christian groups with annihilationist beliefs]]\n[[Category:Christian new religious movements]]\n[[Category:Nontrinitarian denominations]]\n[[Category:Premillennialism]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1870]]\n[[Category:Restorationism (Christianity)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|Christian denomination}}\n{{Infobox Christian denomination\n| name          = Jehovah's Witnesses\n| image         = Jw headquart.jpg\n| imagewidth    =\n| caption       = World headquarters in [[Warwick, New York|Warwick]], New York\n| main_classification = [[Restorationism|Restorationist]]\n| structure     = [[Organizational structure of Jehovah's Witnesses|Hierarchical]]<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Cobb v. Brede |court=California Superior Court, San Mateo County|date=February 22, 2012|quote=I am general counsel for the National Organization of Jehovah's Witnesses out of Brooklyn, New York. ... We are a hierarchical religion structured just like the Catholic Church}}</ref>\n| orientation   = [[Premillennialism|Premillennialist]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2019|page=164|isbn=9781538119525|quote=Jehovah's Witnesses are pre-millennialist}}</ref>\n| theology      =  [[Nontrinitarianism|Nontrinitarian]]\n| founder       = [[Charles Taze Russell]]<ref name=\"Gale\" />\n| founded_date  = 1870s\n| founded_place = [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|headquarters  = [[Warwick, New York|Warwick]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| governance    = [[Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses|Governing Body]]\n| branched_from = [[Bible Student movement]]\n| separations   = [[Jehovah's Witnesses splinter groups]]\n| area          = Worldwide\n| congregations = 119,712\n| members       = 8,683,117\n| footnotes     = Statistics from ''2019 Grand Totals''<ref name=\"report2018\" />\n| website       = {{URL|https://jw.org/}}\n}}\n\n'''Jehovah's Witnesses''' is a [[Millenarianism|millenarian]] [[Restorationism|restorationist]] [[Christian denomination]] with [[Nontrinitarianism|nontrinitarian]] beliefs distinct from mainstream [[Christianity]].<ref>Sources for descriptors:\n*''Millenarian'': {{cite book|last=Beckford|first=James A.|authorlink=James A. Beckford|title=The Trumpet of Prophecy: A Sociological Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Basil Blackwell|location=Oxford|year=1975|isbn=978-0-631-16310-7|ref=harv|pages=118\u2013119, 151, 200\u2013201}}\n*''Restorationist'': {{cite journal|last1=Stark|first1=Rodney|last2=Iannaccone|first2=Laurence R.|authorlink1=Rodney Stark|authorlink2=Laurence Iannaccone|title=Why the Jehovah's Witnesses Grow so Rapidly: A Theoretical Application|journal=[[Journal of Contemporary Religion]]|date=1997|volume=12|issue=2|pages=133\u2013157|doi=10.1080/13537909708580796|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/6295/f3db6a97bbd6909aa18df688e24a8fe945a9.pdf|accessdate=December 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228112238/https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/6295/f3db6a97bbd6909aa18df688e24a8fe945a9.pdf|archive-date=December 28, 2017|url-status=dead}}\n*''Christian'': {{cite web|title=Who is a Christian?|url=http://www.religioustolerance.org/chr_defn.htm|website=www.religioustolerance.org|publisher=[[Ontario Consultants on Religious Tolerance]]|accessdate=December 27, 2017}} {{cite web|title=Religious Landscape Study|url=http://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study|website=Pew Research Center's Religion & Public Life Project|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|accessdate=December 27, 2017|date=May 11, 2015}}{{cite book|title=World Almanac and Book of Facts|publisher=Infobase Learning|location=New York, NY|year=2011|isbn=978-1-60057-133-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/worldalmanacbook01newy/page/704 704\u2013705]|url=https://archive.org/details/worldalmanacbook01newy/page/704}}\n*''Denomination'': {{cite news|title=Jehovah's Witnesses at a glance|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/witnesses/ataglance/glance.shtml|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[BBC]]|date=September 29, 2009}}{{cite web|title=Jehovah's Witness|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/Jehovah's+Witness|website=TheFreeDictionary.com|publisher=[[The American Heritage Dictionary]]|accessdate=December 27, 2017}}{{cite web|title=Imprisoned for Their Faith: Jehovah's Witnesses in Auschwitz|url=http://auschwitz.org/en/museum/news/imprisoned-for-their-faith-jehovahs-witnesses-in-auschwitz,351.html|website=auschwitz.org|publisher=[[Auschwitz-Birkenau State Museum]]|accessdate=December 27, 2017|date=February 5, 2004}}</ref> The group reports a worldwide membership of approximately 8.68&nbsp;million adherents involved in [[evangelism]] and an annual [[Jehovah's Witnesses practices#Memorial of Christ's death|Memorial]] attendance of over 20&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"report2018\">{{cite web|title=2019 Grand Totals|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2019|url=https://www.jw.org/en/library/books/2019-service-year-report/2019-grand-totals/}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses are directed by the [[Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses]], a group of [[Elder (Christianity)#Jehovah's Witnesses|elders]] in [[Warwick, New York|Warwick]], New York, United States, which establishes all doctrines<ref>{{cite book|last=Beckford|first=James A.|authorlink=James A. Beckford|title=The Trumpet of Prophecy: A Sociological Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Basil Blackwell|location=Oxford|year=1975|isbn=978-0-631-16310-7|ref=harv|pages=221|quote=Doctrine has always emanated from the Society's elite in Brooklyn and has never emerged from discussion among, or suggestion from, rank-and-file Witnesses.}}</ref> based on its interpretations of the [[Bible]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|editor=Paul Lagasse|title=Jehovah's Witnesses|encyclopedia=The Columbia Encyclopedia|url=https://archive.org/details/columbiaencyclop00laga|edition=6th|year=2000|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-7876-5015-5|quote=The Witnesses base their teaching on the Bible}}</ref><ref name=\"Penton 1997 61\u201362\" /> They believe that the destruction of the present world system at [[Armageddon]] is imminent, and that the establishment of [[Kingship and kingdom of God|God's kingdom]] over the earth is the only solution for all problems faced by humanity.<ref name=\"Britannica Concise Encyclopedia\">{{cite book|title=Britannica Concise Encyclopedia|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.|year=2007|chapter=Jehovah's Witness|isbn=978-1-59339-293-2}}</ref>\n\nThe group emerged from the [[Bible Student movement]] founded in the late 1870s by [[Charles Taze Russell]], who also co-founded [[Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|Zion's Watch Tower Tract Society]] in 1881 to organize and print the movement's publications.<ref name=\"Gale\">{{cite encyclopedia|editor=Stanley I. Kutler|editor-link=Stanley Kutler|title=Jehovah's Witnesses|encyclopedia=Dictionary of American History|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/philosophy-and-religion/christianity/protestant-denominations/jehovahs-witnesses#1G23401802183|edition=3rd|year=2003|publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons|location=New York|isbn=978-0-684-80533-7}}</ref> A [[Watch Tower Society presidency dispute (1917)|leadership dispute]] after Russell's death resulted in several groups breaking away, with [[Joseph Franklin Rutherford]] retaining control of the Watch Tower Society and its properties.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Embryonic State of a Religious Sect's Development: The Jehovah's Witnesses|journal=Sociological Yearbook of Religion in Britain|editor=Michael Hill|year=1972|issue=5|pages=11\u201312|quote=Joseph Franklin Rutherford succeeded to Russell's position as President of Zion's Watch Tower Tract Society, but only at the expense of antagonizing a large proportion of the Watch Towers subscribers. Nevertheless, he persisted in moulding the Society to suit his own programme of activist evangelism under systematic central control, and he succeeded in creating the administrative structure of the present-day sect of Jehovah's Witnesses.}}</ref> Rutherford made significant organizational and doctrinal changes, including adoption of the name ''Jehovah's witnesses''<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=1 November 1961|page=654|title=Bearers of the Fear-inspiring Name|publisher=Watch Tower Society|quote=in 1931, ... embracing the name ... Jehovah's witnesses}}</ref><ref group=\"note\">Based on [https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=isaiah+43%3A10-12&version=ASV Isaiah 43:10&ndash;12 (ASV)], the name was restyled as Jehovah's Witnesses (with capital W) in the 1970s.</ref> in 1931 to distinguish them from other Bible Student groups and symbolize a break with the legacy of [[Charles Taze Russell#Theology and teachings|Russell's traditions]].<ref name=\"name1\" /><ref name=\"name2\" /><ref name=\"name3\" /><ref>{{cite journal|author=Leo P. Chall|title=Sociological Abstracts|volume=26|issue=1\u20133|journal=Sociology of Religion|year=1978|page=193|quote=Rutherford, through the Watch Tower Society, succeeded in changing all aspects of the sect from 1919 to 1932 and created Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014a charismatic offshoot of the Bible student community.}}</ref>\n\nJehovah's Witnesses are best known for their door-to-door preaching, distributing literature such as ''[[The Watchtower]]'' and ''[[Awake!]]'', and for refusing [[military service]] and [[blood transfusion]]s. They consider the use of [[Names of God in Christianity|God's name]] vital for proper worship. They reject [[Trinity|Trinitarianism]], [[Christian conditionalism|inherent immortality]] of the [[Soul (spirit)|soul]], and [[Christian views on Hell|hellfire]], which they consider to be unscriptural doctrines. They do not observe [[Christmas]], [[Easter]], [[birthday]]s or other holidays and customs they consider to have [[paganism|pagan]] origins incompatible with Christianity.<ref>{{cite book|author=Franz, Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|pages=274\u20135|isbn=978-0-914675-16-7}}</ref> They prefer to use their own Bible translation, the ''[[New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures]]'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Edwards|first=Linda|title=A Brief Guide to Beliefs|publisher=Westminster John Knox Press|year=2001|location=Louisville, Kentucky|pages=[https://archive.org/details/unset0000unse_s5t3/page/438 438]|isbn=978-0-664-22259-8|quote=The Jehovah's Witnesses' interpretation of Christianity and their rejection of orthodoxy influenced them to produce their own translation of the Bible, ''The New World Translation''.|url=https://archive.org/details/unset0000unse_s5t3/page/438}}</ref> although their literature occasionally quotes and cites other Bible translations.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=When Was Ancient Jerusalem Destroyed?\u2014Part One|magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 2011|page=26|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2011736|quote=Jehovah's Witnesses produce a reliable Bible translation known as the ''New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures''. However, if you are not one of Jehovah's Witnesses, you may prefer to use other translations when considering Bible subjects. This article quotes from a number of widely accepted Bible translations.}}</ref><ref>Chryssides, George D. ''Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses'', pg. 100 \"Although it is the preferred translation by the Witnesses, they remain willing to use other translations in house-to-house ministry and in countries where a NWT has not yet been published\".</ref> Adherents commonly refer to their body of beliefs as \"The Truth\" and consider themselves to be \"in the Truth\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Singelenberg|first=Richard|title=It Separated the Wheat From the Chaff: The 1975 Prophecy and its Impact Among Dutch Jehovah's Witnesses|journal=Sociological Analysis|volume=50|issue=Spring 1989|pages=23\u201340|year=1989|quote='The Truth' is Witnesses' jargon, meaning the Society's belief system.|doi=10.2307/3710916|jstor=3710916}}</ref> They consider secular [[society]] to be morally corrupt and under the influence of [[Satan]], and most limit their social interaction with non-Witnesses.<ref>{{cite book|last=Penton|first=M.J.|authorlink=James Penton|title=Apocalypse Delayed: The Story of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1997|isbn=978-0-8020-7973-2|ref=harv|pages=280\u2013283|quote=Most Witnesses tend to think of society outside their own community as decadent and corrupt ... This in turn means to Jehovah's Witnesses that they must keep themselves apart from Satan's 'doomed system of things.' Thus most tend to socialize largely, although not totally, within the Witness community.}}</ref> [[Church discipline|Congregational disciplinary actions]] include ''[[Jehovah's Witnesses and congregational discipline#Disfellowshipping|disfellowshipping]]'', their term for formal expulsion and [[shunning]], a last resort for what they consider serious offences.<ref>{{cite book|last=Chryssides|first=George D.|authorlink=George Chryssides|title=Exploring New Religions|publisher=Continuum|year=1999|location=London|pages=5|isbn=978-0-8264-5959-6|quote=The Jehovah's Witnesses are well known for their practice of 'disfellowshipping' wayward members.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses: Continuity and Change|last=Chryssides|first=George D.|publisher=Routledge|year=2016|isbn=9781409456087|location=|pages=139, 140|quote=The transgressor is invariably given the opportunity to repent and to be counselled for his or her weaknesses: disfellowshipping is a last resort, and is effectively a formal recognition that a Witness has placed himself or herself beyond the pale, and does not accept the fundamental teachings and practices of the organisation.}}</ref> Baptized individuals who formally leave are considered ''disassociated'' and are also shunned. Disfellowshipped and disassociated individuals may eventually be reinstated if deemed repentant.<ref name=\"shepherd\">{{cite book|title=Shepherd the Flock of God|page=119|publisher=Watch Tower Society|quote=The committee should be careful to allow sufficient time, perhaps many months, a year, or even longer, for the disfellowshipped person to prove that his profession of repentance is genuine.}}</ref>\n\nThe group's position regarding [[Conscientious objector|conscientious objection]] to military service and refusal to [[salute]] state symbols (like [[national anthem]]s and [[flag]]s) has brought it into conflict with some governments.<ref name=aa>{{cite web|author=|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201306170026.html |title=Tanzania: Dons Fault Court Over Suspension of Students (Page 1 of 2) |publisher=allAfrica.com |date=June 17, 2013 |accessdate=June 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=cit>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecitizen.co.tz/magazine/sound-living/-/1843780/1958398/-/s1lvpy/-/index.html |title=How much of our religion must we bring to school? |work=The Citizen |first=Esther |last=Kibakaya |date=August 18, 2013 |accessdate=June 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102008085|title=Flag Salute, Voting, and Civilian Service|work=Watchtower ONLINE LIBRARY|access-date=July 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101983034#h=17|title=Flag Salute, Anthems and Voting|work=Watchtower ONLINE LIBRARY|access-date=July 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Those About to Die|date=1958|first=Daniel P.|last=Mannix|page=135}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Render Unto Caesar, The Flag-Salute Controversy|date=1962|page=32|first=David R.|last=Manwaring}}</ref> Consequently, some Jehovah's Witnesses have been persecuted and their activities are banned or restricted in some countries. Persistent [[Supreme Court cases involving Jehovah's Witnesses by country|legal challenges by Jehovah's Witnesses]] have influenced legislation related to [[Civil and political rights|civil rights]] in several countries.<ref>[[Gary Botting]], ''Fundamental Freedoms and Jehovah's Witnesses'' (Calgary: University of Calgary Press, 1993), pg 1\u201313.</ref>\n\nThe organization has [[Criticism of Jehovah's Witnesses|received criticism]] regarding biblical translation, doctrines, and alleged coercion of its members. The Watch Tower Society has made various unfulfilled predictions about major biblical events such as Christ's [[Second Coming]], the advent of [[God's Kingdom]], and [[Armageddon]]. Their policies for [[Jehovah's Witnesses' handling of child sex abuse|handling cases of child sexual abuse]] have been the subject of various formal inquiries.\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n{{Christianity|expand-nontrinitarian=yes|portalicon=ichthys}}\n\n===Background (1870\u20131916)===\n{{See also|Bible Student movement}}\n[[File:C.T. Russell.gif|left|182px|thumb|[[Charles Taze Russell|Pastor Russell]], founder of the [[Bible Student movement|Watch Tower Society]]]]\nIn 1870, [[Charles Taze Russell]] and others formed a group in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]] to study the Bible.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rogerson|first=Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable & Co, London|year=1969|pages=6|isbn=978-0094559400}}</ref> During the course of his ministry, Russell disputed many beliefs of mainstream Christianity including immortality of the soul, hellfire, predestination, the fleshly return of Jesus Christ, the Trinity, and the burning up of the world.<ref name=\"beckford1874\">{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|page=2}}</ref> In 1876, Russell met [[Nelson H. Barbour]]; later that year they jointly produced the book ''[[Three Worlds (book)|Three Worlds]],'' which combined restitutionist views with [[end time]] prophecy. The book taught that God's dealings with humanity were divided [[Dispensationalism|dispensationally]], each ending with a \"harvest,\" that Christ had returned as an invisible spirit being in 1874<ref name=\"beckford1874\" /> inaugurating the \"harvest of the Gospel age,\" and that 1914 would mark the end of a 2520-year period called \"the Gentile Times,\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Crompton|first=Robert|title=Counting the Days to Armageddon|publisher=James Clarke & Co|year=1996|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-227-67939-5|pages=37\u201339}}</ref> at which time world society would be replaced by the full establishment of God's kingdom on earth.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Bible Examiner|date=October 1876|title=Gentile Times: When Do They End? |pages=27\u201328 |quote=The seven times will end in A.D. 1914; when Jerusalem shall be delivered forever ... when Gentile Governments shall have been dashed to pieces; when God shall have poured out of his fury upon the nations and they acknowledge him King of Kings and Lord of Lords.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Studies in the Scriptures|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1897|page=xii|volume=IV The Battle of Armageddon}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Time is at Hand|last=Russell|first=Charles|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society |year=1889|page=101}}</ref> Beginning in 1878 Russell and Barbour jointly edited a religious journal, ''Herald of the Morning''.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|last1=Botting|first1=Heather|last2=Botting|first2=Gary|publisher=University of Toronto Press |year=1884|page=36}}</ref> In June 1879 the two split over doctrinal differences, and in July, Russell began publishing the magazine ''[[The Watchtower|Zion's Watch Tower and Herald of Christ's Presence]]'',<ref name=\"Holden18\">{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=18}}</ref> stating that its purpose was to demonstrate that the world was in \"the last days,\" and that a new age of earthly and human restitution under the reign of Christ was imminent.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Zion's Watch Tower|date=July 1, 1879|page=1 |title=Prospectus|quote=This is the first number of the first volume of \"Zion's Watch Tower,\" and it may not be amiss to state the object of its publication. That we are living \"in the last days\"\u2014\"the day of the Lord\"\u2014\"the end\" of the Gospel age, and consequently, in the dawn of a \"new\" age. }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1879, ''Watch Tower'' supporters gathered as autonomous congregations to study the Bible topically. Thirty congregations were founded, and during 1879 and 1880, Russell visited each to provide the format he recommended for conducting meetings.<ref>{{cite book|title=1975 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|chapter=Part 1 &mdash; United States of America|year=1975|page=38|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/301975002}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Zion's Watch Tower|date=September 1884|pages=7\u20138|title=The Ecclesia.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Russell|first=Charles|title=Studies in the Scriptures|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1904|volume=VI The New Creation|pages=195\u2013272}}</ref> In 1881, ''Zion's Watch Tower Tract Society'' was presided over by [[William Henry Conley]], and in 1884, Russell incorporated the society as a non-profit business to distribute tracts and Bibles.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Russell|first=Charles |magazine=Zion's Watch Tower|date=April 25, 1894 |title=A Conspiracy Exposed |pages=55\u201360 |quote=This is a business association merely ... it has no creed or confession ... it is merely a business convenience in disseminating the truth. }}</ref><ref>''Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses'' by [[George D. Chryssides]], Scarecrow Press, 2008, page xxxiv, \"Russell wanted to consolidate the movement he had started. ...In 1880, Bible House, a four-story building in Allegheny, was completed, with printing facilities and meeting accommodation, and it became the organization's headquarters. The next stage of institutionalization was legal incorporation. In 1884, Russell formed the Zion's Watch Tower Tract Society, which was incorporated in Pennsylvania... Russell was concerned that his supporters should feel part of a unified movement.\"</ref><ref>''Religion in the Twentieth Century'' by Vergilius Ture Anselm Ferm, Philosophical Library, 1948, page 383, \"As the [unincorporated Watch Tower] Society expanded, it became necessary to incorporate it and build a more definite organization. In 1884, a charter was granted recognizing the Society as a religious, non-profit corporation.\"</ref> By about 1900, Russell had organized thousands of part- and full-time [[colporteur]]s,<ref name=\"Holden18\" /> and was appointing foreign [[missionaries]] and establishing branch offices. By the 1910s, Russell's organization maintained nearly a hundred \"pilgrims,\" or traveling preachers.<ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=19}}</ref> Russell engaged in significant global publishing efforts during his ministry,<ref>''A Chronology and Glossary of Propaganda in the United States'' Greenwood Press: 1996. pg. 35: \"Russell is naturally media literate, and the amount of literature he circulates proves staggering. Books, booklets, and tracts are distributed by the hundreds of millions. This is supplemented by well-publicized speaking tours and a masterful press relations effort, which gives him widespread access to general audiences.\"</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=26\u201329}}</ref> and by 1912, he was the most distributed Christian author in the United States.<ref>''The Overland Monthly'', January 1910 pg. 130</ref><ref>W.T. Ellis, ''The Continent'', McCormick Publishing Company, vol. 43, no. 40, October 3, 1912 pg. 1354</ref>\n\nRussell moved the Watch Tower Society's headquarters to [[Brooklyn]], New York, in 1909, combining printing and corporate offices with a house of worship; volunteers were housed in a nearby residence he named ''Bethel''. He identified the religious movement as \"Bible Students,\" and more formally as the [[Bible Student movement#International Bible Students Association|International Bible Students Association]].<ref>''Religious Diversity and American Religious History'' by Walter H. Conser, Sumner B. Twiss, University of Georgia Press, 1997, page 136, \"The Jehovah's Witnesses...has maintained a very different attitude toward history. Established initially in the 1870s by Charles Taze Russell under the title International Bible Students Association, this organization has proclaimed...\"</ref> By 1910, about 50,000 people worldwide were associated with the movement<ref>The New Schaff\u2013Herzog Encyclopedia of Religious Knowledge, 1910, vol 7, pg 374</ref> and congregations re-elected him annually as their \"pastor.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=26}}</ref> Russell died October 31, 1916, at the age of 64 while returning from a ministerial speaking tour.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rogerson|first=Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable & Co, London|year=1969|page=31|isbn=978-0094559400}}</ref>\n\n===Reorganization (1917\u20131942)===\n[[File:J.F. Rutherford.gif|thumb|right|182px|[[Joseph Franklin Rutherford|Joseph F. Rutherford]], founder of Jehovah's Witnesses]]\nIn January 1917, the Watch Tower Society's legal representative, [[Joseph Franklin Rutherford]], was elected as its next president. His [[Watch Tower Society presidency dispute (1917)|election was disputed]], and members of the Board of Directors accused him of acting in an autocratic and secretive manner.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=53}}</ref><ref>A.N. Pierson et al., ''Light After Darkness'', 1917, page 4.</ref> The divisions between his supporters and opponents triggered a major turnover of members over the next decade.<ref name=\"Penton 1997 61\u201362\" >{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=58,&nbsp;61\u201362}}</ref><ref name=\"crompton101\" >{{cite book|last=Crompton|first=Robert|title=Counting the Days to Armageddon|publisher=James Clarke & Co|year=1996|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-227-67939-5|pages=101\n}}</ref> In June 1917, he released ''The Finished Mystery'' as a seventh volume of Russell's ''[[Studies in the Scriptures]]'' series. The book, published as the posthumous work of Russell, was a compilation of his commentaries on the Bible books of [[Book of Ezekiel|Ezekiel]] and [[Book of Revelation|Revelation]], plus numerous additions by Bible Students Clayton Woodworth and George Fisher.<ref>{{Citation|title = The Bible Students Monthly|volume = 9|issue = 9|pages = 1, 4| quote=The following article is extracted mainly from Pastor Russell's posthumous volume entitled \"THE FINISHED MYSTERY,\" the 7th in the series of his STUDIES IN THE SCRIPTURES and published subsequent to his death.}}</ref><ref>Lawson, John D., ''American State Trials'', vol 13, Thomas Law Book Company, 1921, pg viii: \"After his death and after we were in the war they issued a seventh volume of this series, entitled \"The Finished Mystery,\" which, under the guise of being a posthumous work of Pastor Russell, included an attack on the war and an attack on patriotism, which were not written by Pastor Russell and could not have possibly been written by him.\"</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Crompton|first=Robert|title=Counting the Days to Armageddon|publisher=James Clarke & Co|year=1996|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-227-67939-5|pages=84\u201385|quote=One of Rutherford's first actions as president ... was, without reference either to his fellow directors or to the editorial committee which Russell had nominated in his will, to commission a seventh volume of ''Studies in the Scriptures''. Responsibility for preparing this volume was given to two of Russell's close associates, George H. Fisher and Clayton J. Woodworth. On the face of it, their brief was to edit for publication the notes left by Russell ... and to draw upon his published writings ... It is obvious ... that it was not in any straightforward sense the result of editing Russell's papers, rather it was in large measure the original work of Woodworth and Fisher at the behest of the new president.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Finished Mystery|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1917|chapter-url=http://www.strictlygenteel.co.uk/finishedmystery/fmtitles.html|chapter=Publisher's Preface|quote=But the fact is, he did write it. This book may properly be said to be a posthumous publication of Pastor Russell. Why?... This book is chiefly a compilation of things which he wrote and which have been brought together in harmonious style by properly applying the symbols which he explained to the Church.}}</ref> It strongly criticized Catholic and Protestant clergy and Christian involvement in the [[World War I|Great War]].<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=55}}</ref> As a result, Watch Tower Society directors were jailed for [[sedition]] under the ''[[Espionage Act of 1917|Espionage Act]]'' in 1918 and members were subjected to mob violence; the directors were released in March 1919 and charges against them were dropped in 1920.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rogerson|first=Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable & Co, London|year=1969|page=44|isbn=978-0094559400}}</ref>\n\nRutherford centralized organizational control of the Watch Tower Society. In 1919, he instituted the appointment of a director in each congregation, and a year later all members were instructed to report their weekly preaching activity to the Brooklyn headquarters.<ref name=\"Franz, Raymond 2007\">{{cite book|author=Franz, Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|chapter=Chapter 4|isbn=978-0-914675-16-7}}</ref> At an international convention held at [[Cedar Point]], Ohio, in September 1922, a new emphasis was made on house-to-house preaching.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom|chapter=7. Advertise the King and the Kingdom! (1919-1941)|publisher=Watch Tower Bible & Tract Society|year=1993|pages=72\u201377|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101993008}}</ref> Significant changes in doctrine and administration were regularly introduced during Rutherford's twenty-five years as president, including the 1920 announcement that the Hebrew patriarchs (such as [[Abraham]] and [[Isaac]]) would be resurrected in 1925, marking the beginning of [[Christ]]'s [[Millennialism|thousand-year earthly Kingdom]].<ref name=\"Rutherford1920\">{{cite book|last=Rutherford|first=Joseph F.|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die!|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uFn7PQJeorwC&pg=PA89|year=1920|publisher=International Bible Students Association|location=Brooklyn, New York|isbn=978-1-4116-2898-4|pages=89\u201390}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Chryssides|first=George D.|authorlink=George Chryssides|title=How Prophecy Succeeds: The Jehovah's Witnesses and Prophetic Expectations|journal=International Journal for the Study of New Religions|volume=1|issue=1|pages=27\u201348|year=2010|issn=2041-952X|doi=10.1558/ijsnr.v1i1.27}}</ref><ref name=\"christian144\">{{cite book|last=Franz|first=Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|year=2007|page=144|isbn=978-0-914675-16-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Salvation|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|chapter=|year=1939|page=76|others=as cited in ''Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom''}}</ref> Because of disappointment over the changes and [[Watch Tower Society unfulfilled predictions#1925: Resurrection of the patriarchs|unfulfilled predictions]], tens of thousands of defections occurred during the first half of Rutherford's tenure, leading to the formation of several Bible Student organizations independent of the Watch Tower Society,<ref>{{cite book|last=Rogerson|first=Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable & Co, London|year=1969|pages=39, 52|isbn=978-0094559400}}</ref><ref>Herbert H. Stroup, ''The Jehovah's Witnesses'', Columbia University Press, New York, 1945, pg 14,15: \"Following his election the existence of the movement was threatened as never before. Many of those who remembered wistfully the halcyon days of Mr Russell's leadership found that the new incumbent did not fulfill their expectations of a saintly leader. Various elements split off from the parent body, and such fission continued throughout Rutherford's leadership.\"</ref><ref name=\"Penton, 1997, 58\" >{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=wmsdmva7u6kC&id=38SYXalMLeQC&pg=PA58 58], [https://books.google.com/books?id=wmsdmva7u6kC&id=38SYXalMLeQC&pg=PA61 61]}}</ref><ref name=\"Gruss2001\">{{cite book|last=Gruss|first=Edmond C.|title=Jehovah's Witnesses: Their Claims, Doctrinal Changes, and Prophetic Speculation. What Does the Record Show?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kSZL8BWc9KcC&pg=PA218|year=2001|publisher=Xulon Press|isbn=978-1-931232-30-2|page=218}}</ref> most of which still exist.<ref>Reed, David, [https://web.archive.org/web/20110909064529/http://journal.equip.org/articles/whither-the-watchtower- Whither the Watchtower?] ''Christian Research Journal'', Summer 1993, pg 27: \"By gradually replacing locally elected elders with his own appointees, he managed to transform a loose collection of semi-autonomous, democratically run congregations into a tight-knit organizational machine controlled from his office. Some local congregations broke away, forming such groups as the Chicago Bible Students, the Dawn Bible Students, and the Laymen's Home Missionary Movement, all of which continue to this day.\"</ref> By mid-1919, as many as one in seven of Russell-era Bible Students had ceased their association with the Society, and as many as three-quarters by the end of the 1920s.<ref name=\"Penton, 1997, 58\" /><ref>''Thirty Years a Watchtower Slave'', William J. Schnell, Baker, Grand Rapids, 1956, as cited by Rogerson, page 52. Rogerson notes that it is not clear exactly how many Bible Students left, but quotes Rutherford (''Jehovah'', 1934, page 277) as saying \"only a few\" who left other religions were then \"in God's organization\".</ref><ref>''The Present Truth and Herald of Christ's Epiphany'', P.S.L. Johnson (April 1927, pg 66). Johnson stated that between late 1923 and early 1927, \"20,000 to 30,000 Truth people the world over have left the Society.\"</ref><ref>Tony Wills (''A People For His Name'', pg. 167) cites ''The Watch Tower'' (December 1, 1927, pg 355) in which Rutherford states that \"the larger percentage\" of original Bible Students had by then departed.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Gruss|first=Edmond C.|title=Apostles of Denial: An Examination and Expos\u00e9 of the History, Doctrines and Claims of the Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/stream/ApostlesOfDenial/1970_Apostles_Of_Denial#page/n275/mode/1up|year=1970|publisher=Presbyterian and Reformed Publishing Co.|isbn=978-0-87552-305-7|pages=265}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 1931, at a convention in [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]], Ohio, Rutherford introduced the new name \u2013 ''Jehovah's witnesses'' \u2013 based on [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] 43:10: \"'You are my witnesses,' declares Jehovah, 'Yes, my servant whom I have chosen, So that you may know and have faith in me And understand that I am the same One. Before me no God was formed, And after me there has been none.'\" (New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures 2013 Edition) \u2014which was adopted by resolution. The name was chosen to distinguish his group of Bible Students from other independent groups that had severed ties with the Society, as well as symbolize the instigation of new outlooks and the promotion of fresh evangelizing methods.<ref name=\"name1\">{{cite book|author=Rogerson, Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable|location=London|year=1969|page=55|quote=In 1931, came an important milestone in the history of the organization. For many years Rutherford's followers had been called a variety of names: 'International Bible Students', 'Russellites', or 'Millennial Dawners'. In order to distinguish clearly his followers from the other groups who had separated in 1918 Rutherford proposed that they adopt an entirely new name\u2014''Jehovah's witnesses''.}}</ref><ref name=\"name2\">James A. Beckford, ''The Trumpet of Prophecy'', 1975, page 30, \"The new title symbolized a break with the legacy of Russell's traditions, the instigation of new outlooks and the promotion of fresh methods of administering evangelism.\"</ref><ref name=\"name3\">{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watch Tower|title=A New Name|date=October 1, 1931|page=291|quote=Since the death of Charles T. Russell there have arisen numerous companies formed out of those who once walked with him, each of these companies claiming to teach the truth, and each calling themselves by some name, such as \"Followers of Pastor Russell\", \"those who stand by the truth as expounded by Pastor Russell,\" \"Associated Bible Students,\" and some by the names of their local leaders. All of this tends to confusion and hinders those of good will who are not better informed from obtaining a knowledge of the truth.}}</ref> In 1932, Rutherford eliminated the system of locally elected elders and in 1938, introduced what he called a \"theocratic\" (literally, ''God-ruled'') organizational system, under which appointments in congregations worldwide were made from the Brooklyn headquarters.<ref name=\"Franz, Raymond 2007\"/>\n\nFrom 1932, it was taught that the \"little flock\" of 144,000 would not be the only people to survive Armageddon. Rutherford explained that in addition to the 144,000 \"anointed\" who would be resurrected\u2014or transferred at death\u2014to live in heaven to rule over earth with Christ, a separate class of members, the \"great multitude,\" would live in a paradise restored on earth; from 1935, new converts to the movement were considered part of that class.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|page=31}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=71\u201372}}</ref> By the mid-1930s, the timing of the beginning of Christ's presence (Greek: ''parous\u00eda''), his enthronement as king, and the start of the \"[[end times|last days]]\" were each moved to 1914.<ref>{{cite book|last=Crompton|first=Robert|title=Counting the Days to Armageddon|publisher=James Clarke & Co|year=1996|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-227-67939-5|pages=109\u2013110}}</ref>\n[[File:NathanHomerKnorr-WTPres.png|thumb|right|182px|[[Nathan Homer Knorr|Nathan H. Knorr]], the third president of the [[Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|Watch Tower Society]]]]\nAs their interpretations of the Bible evolved, Witness publications decreed that saluting national flags is a form of idolatry, which led to a new outbreak of mob violence and government opposition in the United States, [[Canada]], [[Germany]], and other countries.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|page=35}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Garbe|first=Detlef|title=Between Resistance and Martyrdom: Jehovah's Witnesses in the Third Reich|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|year=2008|location=Madison, Wisconsin|pages=145|isbn=978-0-299-20794-6}}</ref>\n\nWorldwide membership of Jehovah's Witnesses reached 113,624 in 5,323 congregations by the time of Rutherford's death in January 1942.<ref>{{cite book|title=1943 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watch Tower Bible & Tract Society|year=1942|pages=221\u2013222}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses in the Divine Purpose|publisher=Watch Tower Bible & Tract Society|year=1959|pages=312\u2013313}}</ref>\n\n===Continued development (1942\u2013present)===\n{{See also|Development of Jehovah's Witnesses doctrine|Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n[[Nathan H. Knorr|Nathan Knorr]] was appointed as third president of the Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society in 1942. Knorr commissioned a new translation of the Bible, the ''[[New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures]]'', the full version of which was released in 1961. He organized large international assemblies, instituted new training programs for members, and expanded missionary activity and branch offices throughout the world.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=47\u201352}}</ref> Knorr's presidency was also marked by an increasing use of explicit instructions guiding Witnesses in their lifestyle and conduct, and a greater use of [[Church discipline|congregational judicial procedures]] to enforce a strict moral code.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=52\u201355}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=89\u201390}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1966, Witness publications and convention talks built anticipation of the possibility that Christ's thousand-year reign might begin in late 1975<ref name=\"Georgie\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cesnur.org/2010/to-chryssides.htm|title=\u2018They keep changing the dates\u2019: Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses Changing Chronology - Cryssides|website=www.cesnur.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=George D.|last=Chryssides|authorlink=George Chryssides|title=Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0-8108-6074-2|ref={{harvid|Chryssides|Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses}}|page=19}}</ref> or shortly thereafter.<ref name=\"Penton, 1997, 95\" >{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=95}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather|author2=[[Gary Botting]]|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|pages=[https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott/page/46 46]|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Awake!|publisher=Watch Tower Bible & Tract Society|page=14|date=October 8, 1968|quote=\"Does this mean that the above evidence positively points to 1975 as the complete end of this system of things? Since the Bible does not specifically state this, no man can say... If the 1970s should see intervention by Jehovah God to bring an end to a corrupt world drifting toward ultimate disintegration, that should surely not surprise us.\"|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Our Kingdom Ministry]]|date=May 1974|title=How Are You Using Your Life?|page=63|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/201974163|quote=Reports are heard of brothers selling their homes and property and planning to finish out the rest of their days in this old system in the pioneer service. Certainly, this is a fine way to spend the short time remaining before the wicked world's end.|ref=harv}}</ref> The number of baptisms increased significantly, from about 59,000 in 1966 to more than 297,000 in 1974. By 1975, the number of active members exceeded two million. Membership declined during the late 1970s after expectations for 1975 were proved wrong.<ref>{{cite book |title=Crisis of Conscience |author=Franz, Raymond |chapter=1975\u2014The Appropriate Time for God to Act |pages=[https://archive.org/details/crisisofconscien00raym/page/237 237\u2013253] |chapter-url=http://users.volja.net/izobcenec4/coc/9.pdf |accessdate=July 27, 2006 |chapter-format=PDF |isbn=978-0-914675-23-5 |url-status=dead |year=2002 |url=https://archive.org/details/crisisofconscien00raym/page/237 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Singelenberg, Richard|url=http://www.watchtowerinformationservice.org/index.php/dates/the-1975-prophecy-and-its-impact-among-dutch-jehovahs-witnesses/|title=The '1975'-prophecy and its impact among Dutch Jehovah's Witnesses|journal=Sociological Analysis|issue=1|year=1989|pages=23\u201340|volume=50|doi=10.2307/3710916|jstor=3710916|ref=harv}} Notes a nine percent drop in total publishers (door-to-door preachers) and a 38 per cent drop in pioneers (full-time preachers) in the Netherlands.</ref><ref name=\"Stark\">{{cite journal|journal=[[Journal of Contemporary Religion]]|title=Why the Jehovah's Witnesses Grow So Rapidly: A Theoretical Application|url=http://www.kotiposti.net/raamattu/jt/doc/study-why-jw-grow-so-rapidly.pdf|year=1997|pages=142\u2013143|format=PDF|accessdate=July 16, 2013|author=Stark and Iannoccone|ref=harv|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412073649/http://www.kotiposti.net/raamattu/jt/doc/study-why-jw-grow-so-rapidly.pdf|archive-date=April 12, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=January 30, 1982|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Defectors Feel 'Witness' Wrath: Critics say Baptism Rise Gives False Picture of Growth|author=Dart, John|page=B4}} Cited statistics showing a net increase of publishers worldwide from 1971 to 1981 of 737,241, while baptisms totaled 1.71 million for the same period.</ref> Watch Tower Society literature did not state dogmatically that 1975 would definitely mark the end,<ref name=\"Penton, 1997, 95\" /> but in 1980 the Watch Tower Society admitted its responsibility in building up hope regarding that year.<ref name=\"Hans\" >{{cite book|last=Hesse|first=Hans|title=Persecution and Resistance of Jehovah's Witnesses During the Nazi-Regime|publisher=Edition Temmen c/o|year=2001|location=Chicago|pages=296, 298|isbn=978-3-861-08750-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=The Watchtower|date=March 15, 1980|pages=17\u201318|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1980207|quote=With the appearance of the book ''Life Everlasting\u2014in Freedom of the Sons of God'', ... considerable expectation was aroused regarding the year 1975. ... there were other statements published that implied that such realization of hopes by that year was more of a probability than a mere possibility. It is to be regretted that these latter statements apparently overshadowed the cautionary ones and contributed to a buildup of the expectation already initiated. ... ''persons having to do with the publication of the information'' ... contributed to the buildup of hopes centered on that date.|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe offices of elder and ministerial servant were restored to Witness congregations in 1972, with appointments made from headquarters<ref>{{harvnb|Chryssides|Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|pages=32,112}}</ref> (and later, also by branch committees). It was announced that, starting in September 2014, appointments would be made by traveling overseers. In a major organizational overhaul in 1976, the power of the Watch Tower Society president was diminished, with authority for doctrinal and organizational decisions passed to the [[Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses|Governing Body]].<ref>{{harvnb|Chryssides|Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|page=64}}</ref> Since Knorr's death in 1977, the position of president has been occupied by [[Frederick William Franz|Frederick Franz]] (1977\u20131992) and [[Milton George Henschel|Milton Henschel]] (1992\u20132000), both members of the Governing Body, and since 2000 by others who are not Governing Body members. In 1995, Jehovah's Witnesses abandoned the idea that Armageddon must occur during the lives of the generation that was alive in 1914 and in 2010 changed their teaching on the \"generation\".<ref>{{Citation|journal=Newsweek|volume=236|issue=3146|pages=24|title=Apocalypse Later|date=December 18, 1995|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/104359|author=Joel P. Engardio|bibcode=2017NewSc.236Q..24L|doi=10.1016/S0262-4079(17)31969-3}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|p=317}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-11-04-me-64883-story.html|title=Jehovah's Witnesses Abandon Key Tenet : Doctrine: Sect has quietly retreated from prediction that those alive in 1914 would see end of world.|date=November 4, 1995|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jw.org/en/publications/magazines/w20140115/let-your-kingdom-come/|title=\"Let Your Kingdom Come\"\u2014But When? - Study|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|website=Official website of Jehovah's Witnesses}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\n{{Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n{{Main|Organizational structure of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\nJehovah's Witnesses are organized [[Hierarchy|hierarchically]], in what the leadership calls a \"theocratic organization\", reflecting their belief that it is God's \"visible organization\" on earth.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=January 15, 2001|page=16|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2001049|title=Overseers and Ministerial Servants Theocratically Appointed|quote=Theocratic appointments come from Jehovah through his Son and God's visible earthly channel, \"the faithful and discreet slave\" and its Governing Body.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 1967 |title=Following Faithful Shepherds with Life in View |pages=591\u201392 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1967723 |quote=Make haste to identify the visible theocratic organization of God that represents his king, Jesus Christ. It is essential for life. Doing so, be complete in accepting its every aspect. We cannot claim to love God, yet deny his Word and channel of communication. Therefore, in submitting to Jehovah's visible theocratic organization, we must be in full and complete agreement with every feature of its apostolic procedure and requirements.}}</ref><ref name=\"pentongov\" >{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=211}}</ref> The organization is led by the [[Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses|Governing Body]]\u2014an all-male group that varies in size, but since January 2018 has comprised eight members,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jw.org/en/jehovahs-witnesses/faq/governing-body |title=What Is the Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses? |website=Official website of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania}}</ref> all of whom profess to be of the \"anointed\" class with a hope of heavenly life\u2014based in the Watch Tower Society's Warwick headquarters.<ref>{{cite book|title=2007 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|author=Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|pages=4, 6|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/302007001}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather & Gary|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2}}</ref> There is no election for membership; new members are selected by the existing body.<ref>{{cite book|last=Franz|first=Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|page=123|isbn=978-0-914675-17-4}}</ref> Until late 2012, the Governing Body described itself as the representative<ref name=\"GB2008\">{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 15, 2008 |title=How the Governing Body Is Organized |page=29 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2008367 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 15, 2008 |title=Seek God's guidance in all things |page=11 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2008282}}</ref> and \"spokesman\" for God's \"[[faithful and discreet slave]] class\" (then approximately 10,000 self-professed [[Jehovah's Witnesses and salvation#The 'anointed'|\"anointed\" Jehovah's Witnesses]]).<ref>{{cite book|last=Franz|first=Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|page=153|isbn=978-0-914675-17-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=2010 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2010|chapter=Preaching and Teaching Earth Wide &mdash; 2009 Grand Totals|page=42|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/302010015}}</ref> At the 2012 Annual Meeting of the Watch Tower Society, the \"faithful and discreet slave\" was defined as referring to the Governing Body only.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jw.org/en/news/events-activities/annual-meeting-report-2012|title=Annual Meeting Report|website=Official website of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=The Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania}}</ref> The Governing Body directs several committees that are responsible for administrative functions, including publishing, assembly programs and evangelizing activities.<ref name=pentongov /> It appoints all branch committee members and traveling overseers, after they have been recommended by local branches, with traveling overseers supervising circuits of congregations within their jurisdictions. Traveling overseers appoint local elders and ministerial servants, and while branch offices may appoint regional committees for matters such as [[Kingdom Hall]] construction or disaster relief.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=101,&nbsp;233\u2013235}}</ref> The leadership and supporting staff lives in properties owned by the organization worldwide referred to as \"Bethel\" where they operate as a religious community and administrative unit.<ref>{{harvnb|Chryssides|Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|pages=17\u201318}}</ref> Their living expenses and those of other full-time volunteers are covered by the organization along with a basic monthly [[stipend]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Penton |first=M. James |date=2015 |title=Apocalypse delayed: the story of Jehovah's Witnesses |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zNfTBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA326 |edition=3rd |publisher=University of Toronto Press |pages=326, 460\u2013461 |isbn=978-1442616059 |ref=harv | quote=For many years they received only $14 per month, but that has been increased during the last several decades to $100 or more per month, and their clothing allowance has also been increased significantly. Barbara Anderson relates that she and her husband received $100 a month, were given board and room, and had a yearly clothing allowance of $250 during the years they were at Bethel until they left in 1997. Although Bethelites may receive somewhat more today, they are certainly not paid anything like 'real wages.'}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather|author2=[[Gary Botting]]|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|pages=[https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott/page/32 32]|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2|quote=Missionaries, circuit overseers, district overseers, special pioneers, and branch-office workers receive small allowances each month. }}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Watchtower Society |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of American Religion and Politics |pages=466|quote=The religious order of Jehovah's Witnesses caters to the needs of all volunteers who have taken a vow of poverty and obedience. }}</ref>\n\nEach congregation has a body of appointed unpaid male elders and ministerial servants. Elders maintain general responsibility for congregational governance, setting meeting times, selecting speakers and conducting meetings, directing the public preaching work, and creating \"judicial committees\" to investigate and decide disciplinary action for cases involving sexual misconduct or doctrinal breaches.<ref name=\"alternative\">{{Citation|last=Gallagher|first=Eugene V.|last2=Ashcraft|first2=W. Michael|title=Introduction to New and Alternative Religions in America|place=Westport, Connecticut|publisher=Greenwood Press|volume=2|year=2006|page=69|isbn=978-0-275-98712-1}}</ref> New elders are appointed by a traveling overseer after recommendation by the existing body of elders. Ministerial servants\u2014appointed in a similar manner to elders\u2014fulfill clerical and attendant duties, but may also teach and conduct meetings.<ref name=pentongov /> Witnesses do not use ''elder'' as a title to signify a formal clergy-laity division,<ref>{{cite book|last=Taylor|first=Elizabeth J.|title=Religion: A Clinical Guide for Nurses|publisher=Springer Publishing Company|year=2012|pages=163|isbn=978-0-8261-0860-9}}</ref> though elders may employ [[ecclesiastical privilege]] regarding confession of sins.<ref>{{cite book|publisher=Watch Tower Society|title=Pay Attention to Yourselves and to All the Flock|year=1981|page=147}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/file-list/Case%20Study%2029%20-%20Transcript%20-%20Jehovahs%20Witnesses%20-%20Day%20147%20-%2027072015.pdf|title=\"Case Study 29: Transcript (day 147)\", page 16, ''Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse'', 27 July 2015.}}</ref>\n\n[[Baptism]] is a requirement for being considered a member of Jehovah's Witnesses. Jehovah's Witnesses do not practice infant baptism,<ref>{{cite book|last=Hoekema|first=Anthony A.|authorlink=Anthony A. Hoekema|title=The Four Major Cults|publisher=William B. Eerdmans|location=Grand Rapids, Michigan|year=1963|isbn=978-0-8028-3117-0|ref=harv|pages=291}}</ref> and previous baptisms performed by other denominations are not considered valid.<ref name=\"RFbaptism\">{{cite book|author=Franz, Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|pages=116\u2013120|isbn=978-0-914675-16-7}}</ref> Individuals undergoing baptism must affirm publicly that dedication and baptism identify them \"as one of Jehovah's Witnesses in association with God's spirit-directed organization,\"<ref name=\"RFbaptism\" /> though Witness publications say baptism symbolizes personal dedication to God and not \"to a man, work or organization.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Chryssides|Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|page=14}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=What Does the Bible Really Teach|chapter=Baptism and Your Relationship With God|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|page=182|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102005148|quote=Going beneath the water symbolizes that you have died to your former life course. Being raised up out of the water indicates that you are now alive to do the will of God. Remember, too, that you have made a dedication to Jehovah God himself, not to a work, a cause, other humans, or an organization.}}</ref> Their literature emphasizes the need for members to be obedient and loyal to Jehovah and to \"his organization,\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Franz|first=Raymond|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|pages=449\u2013464|isbn=978-0-914675-16-7}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=32}}, \"The structure of the movement and the intense loyalty demanded of each individual at every level demonstrates the characteristics of totalitarianism.\"</ref><ref group=note>Raymond Franz (''In Search of Christian Freedom'', 2007, p.449) cites various Watch Tower Society publications that stress loyalty and obedience to the organization, including:<br /> {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 1967|title=Following Faithful Shepherds with Life in View|page=591|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1967723|quote=Make haste to identify the visible theocratic organization of God that represents his king, Jesus Christ. It is essential for life. Doing so, be complete in accepting its every aspect.}}<br /> {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=September 1, 2006 |title=Jehovah's Word Is Alive - Highlights From Book Five of Psalms |page=15 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2006643 |quote=Have we formed a loyal attachment to the organization that Jehovah is using today?}}<br /> {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=June 15, 2006|title=Your Reminders Are What I Am Fond Of |page=26 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2006446 |quote=We too should remain faithful to Jehovah and to his organization regardless of injustices we suffer and regardless of what others do.}}<br /> {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 15, 2006 |title=Are You Prepared for Survival? |page=22 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2006366 |quote=Just as Noah and his God-fearing family were preserved in the ark, survival of individuals today depends on their faith and their loyal association with the earthly part of Jehovah's universal organization.}}<br /> {{cite book|title=Worship The Only True God|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2002|page=134|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102002074|quote=Jehovah is guiding us today by means of his visible organization under Christ. Our attitude toward this arrangement demonstrates how we feel about the issue of sovereignty ... By being loyal to Jehovah's organization, we show that Jehovah is our God and that we are united in worship of him.}}</ref> stating that individuals must remain part of it to receive God's favor and to survive Armageddon.<ref>{{cite book|title=You Can Live Forever in Paradise on Earth|chapter=30. What You Must Do to Live Forever|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1989|page=255|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989120|quote=It is simply not true that all religions lead to the same goal. (Matthew 7:21\u201323; 24:21) You must be part of Jehovah's organization, doing God's will, in order to receive his blessing of everlasting life.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 15, 1983 |title=You Can Live Forever in Paradise on Earth\u2014But How? |page=12 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1983124 |quote=Jehovah is using only one organization today to accomplish his will. To receive everlasting life in the earthly Paradise we must identify that organization and serve God as part of it.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=November 15, 1992 |title=Serving Jehovah Loyally |page=21 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1992845 |quote=I determined to stay by the faithful organization. How else can one get Jehovah's favor and blessing?\" There is nowhere else to go for divine favor and life eternal.}}</ref>\n\n===Publishing===\nThe organization produces a significant amount of literature as part of its evangelism activities.<ref name=\"pub_titans\">{{cite magazine|last=Meyers|first=Jim|date=October 2010|title=Jehovah's Witnesses &mdash; Publishing Titans|url=https://archive.org/download/Newsmax/TourDeGardeNewsmax.pdf#page=2|format=PDF|magazine=Newsmax|location=West Palm Beach, FL|publisher=Newsmax Media}}</ref> The Watch Tower Society has produced over 227 million copies of the ''New World Translation'' in whole or in part in over 185 languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jw.org/en/publications/bible|title=Online Bible|publisher=The Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|website=Official website of Jehovah's Witnesses}}</ref> ''[[The Watchtower]]'' and ''[[Awake!]]'' are the most widely distributed magazines in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-most-widely-read-magazine-in-the-world-is-the-monthly-pub-of-jehovahs-witnesses-2010-9?IR=T|title=Did You Know The Most Widely Circulated Magazine In The World Is The Monthly Publication Of Jehovah's Witnesses?|author=Joe Pompeo|date=September 30, 2010|work=Business Insider}}</ref> Translation of Witness publications is done by over 2,000 volunteers worldwide, producing literature in 1,000 languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jw.org/en/news/jw/region/global/Jehovahs-Witnesses-Reach-New-Preaching-Milestone-JWORG-Now-Features-Content-in-1000-Languages/|title=Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses Reach New Preaching Milestone\u2014JW.ORG Now Features Content in 1,000 Languages|publisher=The Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|website=Official website of Jehovah's Witnesses}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=God's Kingdom Rules!|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|chapter=8. Tools for Preaching &mdash; Producing Literature for the Worldwide Field|year=2014|page=79|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102014247}}</ref> Publications are also available online at the organization's official website.\n\n===Funding===\nMuch of their funding is provided by [[donation]]s, primarily from members. There is no [[tithe|tithing]] or collection.<ref name=\"Hans\" /> In 2001 ''[[Newsday]]'' listed the Watch Tower Society as one of [[New York City|New York]]'s forty richest corporations, with revenues exceeding $950 million.<ref name=\"pub_titans\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/business/technology/at-the-top-nyc-company-profiles-nyc-40-1.365255|title=AT THE TOP / NYC COMPANY PROFILES / NYC 40|website=Newsday}}</ref> The organization reported for the same year that it \"spent over $70.9 million in caring for special pioneers, missionaries, and traveling overseers in their field service assignments.\"<ref>{{cite book|title =2002 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2002|page=31|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/302002003}}</ref><ref group=\"note\">{{cite book|title=2013 Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|page=178|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/302013019|quote=During the 2012 service year, Jehovah's Witnesses spent over $184 million in caring for special pioneers, missionaries, and traveling overseers in their field service assignments.}}</ref>\n\n==Beliefs==\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses beliefs}}\n\n===Sources of doctrine===\nJehovah's Witnesses believe their denomination is a restoration of [[Christianity in the 1st century|first-century Christianity]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Van Voorst, Robert E.|title=RELG: World (with Religion CourseMate with eBook Printed Access Card)|publisher=Cengage Learning|page=288|year=2012|isbn=978-1-1117-2620-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QvNWxEEaf50C&pg=PT303}}</ref> [[Doctrine]]s of Jehovah's Witnesses are established by the [[Governing Body of Jehovah's Witnesses|Governing Body]], which assumes responsibility for [[exegesis|interpreting]] and applying scripture.<ref name=\"Penton 1997 61\u201362\" /><ref>{{cite book|title=Organized to Do Jehovah's Will|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2015|pages=17\u201319|chapter=Remember Those Who Are Taking the Lead Among You|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102014933}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=March 15, 1990 |title=Cooperating With the Governing Body Today |page=19 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1990204}}</ref> The Governing Body does not issue any single, comprehensive \"statement of faith\", but prefers to express its doctrinal position in a variety of ways through publications published by the Watch Tower Society.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|page=119}}</ref> Their publications teach that doctrinal changes and refinements result from a process of progressive [[revelation]], in which God gradually reveals his will and purpose,<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|title=Focus on the Goodness of Jehovah's Organization|page=22|date=July 15, 2006|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2006525|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=March 1, 1965 |title=Impart God's Progressive Revelation to Mankind |pages=158\u2013159 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1965166}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=165\u2013171}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 15, 1995 |title=Flashes of Light\u2014Great and Small |page=15 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1995363}}</ref> and that such enlightenment or \"new light\"<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=December 1, 1981 |title=The Path of the Righteous Does Keep Getting Brighter |pages=26\u201331 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1981889}}</ref> results from the application of [[reason]] and [[biblical studies|study]],<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=165}}</ref> the guidance of the [[holy spirit]], and direction from [[Jesus Christ]] and [[angels]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Rutherford|first=Joseph|title=Preparation|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1933|pages=64, 67|quote=Enlightenment proceeds from Jehovah by and through Christ Jesus and is given to the faithful anointed on earth at the temple, and brings great peace and consolation to them. Again Zechariah talked with the angel of the Lord, which shows that the remnant are instructed by the angels of the Lord. The remnant do not hear audible sounds, because such is not necessary. Jehovah has provided his own good way to convey thoughts to the minds of his anointed ones ... Those of the remnant, being honest and true, must say, We do not know; and the Lord enlightens them, sending his angels for that very purpose.}}</ref> The Society also teaches that members of the Governing Body are helped by the holy spirit to discern \"deep truths\", which are then considered by the entire Governing Body before it makes doctrinal decisions.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 2010 |title=The Spirit Searches into the Deep Things of God |page=23 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2010524|quote=When the time comes to clarify a spiritual matter in our day, holy spirit helps responsible representatives of 'the faithful and discreet slave' at world headquarters to discern deep truths that were not previously understood. The Governing Body as a whole considers adjusted explanations. What they learn, they publish for the benefit of all.}}</ref> The group's leadership, while disclaiming divine inspiration and [[infallibility of the Church|infallibility]],<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Do We Need Help to Understand the Bible?|magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 15, 1981|page=19|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1981127|quote=\"True, the brothers preparing these publications are not infallible. Their writings are not inspired as are those of Paul and the other Bible writers. (2 Tim. 3:16) And so, at times, it has been necessary, as understanding became clearer, to correct views. (Prov. 4:18)\"}}</ref> is said to provide \"divine guidance\"<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 15, 2011 |title=Do You See the Evidence of God's Guidance? |pages=3\u20135|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2011286|quote=How, then, do we react when we receive divine direction? Do we try to apply it \"right afterward\"? Or do we continue doing things just as we have been accustomed to doing them? Are we familiar with up-to-date directions, such as those regarding conducting home Bible studies, preaching to foreign speaking people, regularly sharing in family worship, cooperating with Hospital Liaison Committees, and conducting ourselves properly at conventions? ... Do you clearly discern the evidence of divine guidance? Jehovah uses his organization to guide us, his people, through \"the wilderness\" during these last days of Satan's wicked world.}}</ref> through its teachings described as \"based on God's Word thus ... not from men, but from Jehovah.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=September 15, 2010 |title=Unity Identifies True Worship |page=13 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2010683}}</ref><ref name=\"voice\">{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=June 15, 1957 |title=Overseers of Jehovah's People |pages=369\u2013375 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1957446|quote=Let us now unmistakably identify Jehovah's channel of communication for our day, that we may continue in his favor ... It is vital that we appreciate this fact and respond to the directions of the \"slave\" as we would to the voice of God, because it is His provision.}}</ref>\n\nThe entire Protestant [[Biblical canon|canon of scripture]] is considered the [[Biblical inspiration|inspired]], [[Biblical inerrancy|inerrant]] word of God.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=172}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses consider the Bible to be [[Criticism of the Bible#The Bible and science|scientifically]] and [[The Bible and history|historically]] accurate and reliable<ref>{{cite book|title=All Scripture is Inspired of God|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1990|page=336|chapter=Archaeology and the Inspired Record|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101990136}}</ref> and interpret much of it [[Biblical literalism|literally]], but accept parts of it as [[Allegorical interpretation of the Bible|symbolic]].<ref>{{cite book|title=All Scripture is Inspired of God|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1990|page=9|chapter=All Scripture Is Inspired of God and Beneficial|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101990061}}</ref> They consider the Bible to be the final authority for all their beliefs,<ref>{{cite book|title=Reasoning From The Scriptures|chapter=Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1989|pages=199\u2013208|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989239}}</ref> although sociologist Andrew Holden's [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] study of the group concluded that pronouncements of the Governing Body, through Watch Tower Society publications, carry almost as much weight as the Bible.<ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=67}}, \"Materials such as ''The Watchtower'' are almost as significant to the Witnesses as the Bible, since the information is presented as the inspired work of theologians, and they are, therefore, believed to contain as much truth as biblical texts.\"</ref> Regular personal Bible reading is frequently recommended; Witnesses are discouraged from formulating doctrines and \"private ideas\" reached through Bible research independent of Watch Tower Society publications, and are cautioned against reading other religious literature.<ref name=\"Bevindependent\">James A. Beverley, ''Crisis of Allegiance'', Welch Publishing Company, Burlington, Ontario, 1986, {{ISBN|0-920413-37-4}}, pages 25\u201326, 101, \"For every passage in Society literature that urges members to be bold and courageous in critical pursuits, there are many others that warn about independent thinking and the peril of questioning the organization ... Fear of disobedience to the Governing Body keeps Jehovah's Witnesses from carefully checking into biblical doctrine or allegations concerning false prophecy, faulty scholarship, and injustice. Witnesses are told not to read books like this one.\"</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=March 15, 2006 |title=Keep Clear of False Worship! |pages=27\u201331 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2006208|quote=True Christians keep clear of false worship, rejecting false religious teachings. This means that we avoid exposure to religious programs on radio and television as well as religious literature that promotes lies about God and his Word.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 1, 1984|page=31|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1984330|title=Questions From Readers\u2014Why do Jehovah's Witnesses decline to exchange their Bible study aids for the religious literature of people they meet|quote=So it would be foolhardy, as well as a waste of valuable time, for Jehovah's Witnesses to accept and expose themselves to false religious literature that is designed to deceive.}}</ref> Adherents are told to have \"complete confidence\" in the leadership, avoid skepticism about what is taught in the Watch Tower Society's literature, and \"not advocate or insist on personal opinions or harbor private ideas when it comes to Bible understanding.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=September 2007 |title=Question Box |page=3 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202007325|quote=Throughout the earth, Jehovah's people are receiving ample spiritual instruction and encouragement at congregation meetings, assemblies, and conventions, as well as through the publications of Jehovah's organization. Under the guidance of his holy spirit and on the basis of his Word of truth, Jehovah provides what is needed so that all of God's people may be fitly united in the same mind and in the same line of thought and remain stabilized in the faith. Surely we are grateful for Jehovah's spiritual provisions in these last days. Thus, the faithful and discreet slave does not endorse any literature, meetings, or Web sites that are not produced or organized under its oversight. }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=August 1, 2001 |title=Make Your Advancement Manifest |page=14 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2001563 |quote=Since oneness is to be observed, a mature Christian must be in unity and full harmony with fellow believers as far as faith and knowledge are concerned. He does not advocate or insist on personal opinions or harbor private ideas when it comes to Bible understanding. Rather, he has complete confidence in the truth as it is revealed by Jehovah God through his Son, Jesus Christ, and the faithful and discreet slave.}}</ref><ref>Testimony by Fred Franz, Transcript, Lord Strachan vs. Douglas Walsh, 1954. page 123, Q: \"Did you imply that the individual member has the right of reading the books and the Bible and forming his own view as to the proper interpretation of Holy Writ? A:\" .... No....The Scripture is there given in support of the statement, and therefore the individual when he looks up the Scripture and thereby verifies the statement,...search[es] the Scripture to see whether these things were so.\"</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 15, 1981 |title=Do We Need Help to Understand the Bible? |page=19 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1981127|quote=Jesus' disciples wrote many letters to Christian congregations, to persons who were already in the way of the truth. But nowhere do we read that those brothers first, in a skeptical frame of mind, checked the Scriptures to make certain that those letters had Scriptural backing, that the writers really knew what they were talking about. We can benefit from this consideration. If we have once established what instrument God is using as his 'slave' to dispense spiritual food to his people, surely Jehovah is not pleased if we receive that food as though it might contain something harmful. We should have confidence in the channel God is using.}}</ref> The organization makes no provision for members to criticize or contribute to official teachings<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=84, 89, 92, 119\u2013120}}</ref> and all Witnesses must abide by its doctrines and organizational requirements.<ref name=\"w89_0401_1\">{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 1, 1986 |title=Questions From Readers |pages=30\u201331 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1986249}}</ref>\n\n===Jehovah===\n[[File:YHWH.svg|thumb|left|142px|The [[Tetragrammaton]]]]\nJehovah's Witnesses emphasize the use of God's name, and they prefer the form ''[[Jehovah]]''&mdash;a vocalization of [[God in Christianity|God]]'s name based on the [[Tetragrammaton]].<ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=24}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor-last1=Ringnes|editor-first1=Hege Kristin|editor-last2=S\u00f8dal|editor-first2=Helje Kringlebotn|title=Jehovas vitner: en flerfaglig studie|language=Norwegian|publisher=Universitetsforlaget|year=2009|location=Oslo|page=27|isbn=978-82-15-01453-1|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Holden, A.|year=2002|title=Cavorting With the Devil: Jehovah's Witnesses Who Abandon Their Faith|page=Endnote [i]|publisher=Department of Sociology, Lancaster University, Lancaster LA1 4YL, UK|url=http://www.lancaster.ac.uk/fass/resources/sociology-online-papers/papers/holden-cavorting-with-the-devil.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=April 4, 2017}}</ref> They believe that Jehovah is the only true God, the creator of all things, and the \"Universal Sovereign\". They believe that all worship should be directed toward him, and that he is not part of a [[Trinity]];<ref>{{cite book|author=Alan Rogerson|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die|publisher=Constable|year=1969|page=87}}</ref> consequently, the group places more emphasis on God than on Christ.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|page=105}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Revelation Its Grand Climax|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1988|page=36|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101988007|quote=In the songbook produced by Jehovah's people in 1905, there were twice as many songs praising Jesus as there were songs praising Jehovah God. In their 1928 songbook, the number of songs extolling Jesus was about the same as the number extolling Jehovah. But in the latest songbook of 1984, Jehovah is honored by four times as many songs as is Jesus. This is in harmony with Jesus' own words: 'The Father is greater than I am.' Love for Jehovah must be preeminent, accompanied by deep love for Jesus and appreciation of his precious sacrifice and office as God's High Priest and King.}}</ref> They believe that the [[Holy Spirit in Christianity|Holy Spirit]] is God's applied power or \"active force\", rather than a person.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alan Rogerson|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die|publisher=Constable|year=1969|page=90}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 2009|page=5|title=What is the Holy Spirit?|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2009721|quote=There is a close connection between the holy spirit and the power of God. The holy spirit is the means by which Jehovah exerts his power. Put simply, the holy spirit is God's applied power, or his active force.}}</ref>\n\n===Jesus===\n\nJehovah's Witnesses believe that [[Jesus in Christianity|Jesus]] is God's only direct creation, that everything else was created through Christ by means of God's power, and that the initial unassisted act of creation uniquely identifies Jesus as God's \"only-begotten Son\".<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|page=262}}</ref> Jesus served as a [[Redeemer (Christianity)|redeemer]] and a [[Ransom theory of atonement|ransom sacrifice]] to pay for the sins of humanity.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=276\u2013277}}</ref> They believe Jesus died on a [[Instrument of Jesus' crucifixion|single upright post]] rather than the traditional [[Crucifixion of Jesus|cross]].<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=372}}</ref> Biblical references to the [[Michael (archangel)|Archangel Michael]], [[Abaddon]] (Apollyon), and [[Christ the Logos|the Word]] are interpreted as names for Jesus in various roles.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|page=270}}</ref> Jesus is considered to be the only [[Intercession|intercessor]] and [[high priest]] between God and humanity, and appointed by God as the king and judge of his kingdom.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=November 15, 1995 |title=Stay in the \"City of Refuge\" and Live! |page=19 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1995844 }}</ref> His role as a mediator (referred to in 1 Timothy 2:5) is applied to the 'anointed' class, though the 'other sheep' are said to also benefit from the arrangement.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=188\u2013189}}</ref>\n\n===Satan===\nJehovah's Witnesses believe that [[Devil in Christianity|Satan]] was originally a perfect [[angel]] who developed feelings of self-importance and craved worship. Satan influenced [[Adam and Eve]] to disobey God, and humanity subsequently became participants in a challenge involving the competing claims of Jehovah and Satan to universal sovereignty.<ref name=\"pentonsatan\" >{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=188\u2013190}}</ref> Other angels who sided with Satan became [[demon]]s.\n\nJehovah's Witnesses teach that Satan and his demons were cast down to earth from heaven after October 1, 1914,<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=298\u2013299}}</ref> at which point the [[end time]]s began. They believe that Satan is the ruler of the current world order,<ref name=\"pentonsatan\" /> that human society is influenced and misled by Satan and his demons, and that they are a cause of human suffering. They also believe that human governments are controlled by Satan,<ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=25}}</ref> but that he does not directly control each human ruler.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 1, 2004|page=5|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2004241|title=Identifying the Wild Beast and Its Mark|quote=This does not mean, however, that every human ruler is a direct tool of Satan.}}</ref>\n\n===Life after death===\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses and salvation}}\nJehovah's Witnesses believe death is a state of non-existence with no [[consciousness]]. There is no [[Christian views on hell|Hell]] of fiery torment; [[Christian views on Hades|Hades]] and [[Sheol]] are understood to refer to the condition of death, termed the ''common grave''.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=322\u2013324}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses consider the [[Soul (spirit)|soul]] to be a life or a living body that can die.<ref name=\"hoeksin\">{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=265\u2013269}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses believe that humanity is in a [[Christian views of sin#Protestant views|sinful]] state,<ref name=\"hoeksin\" /> from which release is only possible by means of Jesus' shed blood as a ransom, or [[substitutionary atonement|atonement]], for the sins of humankind.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=186}}</ref>\n\nWitnesses believe that a \"little flock\" of 144,000 selected humans go to heaven, but that the majority (the \"other sheep\") are to be resurrected by God to a cleansed earth after Armageddon. They interpret [[Book of Revelation|Revelation]] 14:1\u20135 to mean that the number of Christians going to heaven is limited to exactly 144,000, who will rule with Jesus as kings and priests over earth.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=193\u2013194}}</ref> They believe that baptism as one of Jehovah's Witnesses is vital for salvation<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|edition=study|date=March 2016|page=4|title=Young Ones&mdash;Are You Ready to Get Baptized|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2016201|quote=It is a great privilege to get baptized as one of Jehovah's Witnesses. Moreover, baptism is a requirement for Christians, and it is a vital step toward gaining salvation.}}</ref> and that only they meet scriptural requirements for surviving Armageddon, but that God is the final judge.<ref name=onlyjw>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=September 1, 1989 |title=Remaining Organized for Survival Into the Millennium |page=19 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1989647|quote=Only Jehovah's Witnesses, those of the anointed remnant and the 'great crowd,'as a united organization under the protection of the Supreme Organizer, have any Scriptural hope of surviving the impending end of this doomed system dominated by Satan the Devil. }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title =You Can Live Forever in Paradise on Earth|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1989|page=255|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989120|quote=Do not conclude that there are different roads, or ways, that you can follow to gain life in God's new system. There is only one ... there will be only one organization\u2014God's visible organization\u2014that will survive the fast-approaching 'great tribulation.' It is simply not true that all religions lead to the same goal. You must be part of Jehovah's organization, doing God's will, in order to receive his blessing of everlasting life.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=November 1, 2008 |title=Our Readers Ask: Do Jehovah's Witnesses Believe That They Are the Only Ones Who Will Be Saved? |page=28 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2008814|quote=Jehovah's Witnesses hope to be saved. However, they also believe that it is not their job to judge who will be saved. Ultimately, God is the Judge. He decides. }}</ref> During Christ's [[Millennialism|millennial reign]], most people who died prior to Armageddon will be resurrected with the prospect of living forever; they will be taught the proper way to worship God to prepare them for their final test at the end of the millennium.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=315\u2013319}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title =Insight on the Scriptures|volume=1|chapter=Declare Righteous|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1988|page=606|chapter-url=http://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1200001142}}</ref>\n\n===God's Kingdom===\nJehovah's Witnesses believe that [[Kingdom of God|God's Kingdom]] is a literal government in heaven, ruled by Jesus Christ and 144,000 \"spirit-anointed\" Christians drawn from the earth, which they associate with Jesus' reference to a \"new covenant\".<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=January 15, 2012 |title=A Royal Priesthood to Benefit All Mankind |pages=26\u201330 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2012046 }}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=295\u2013296}}</ref> The kingdom is viewed as the means by which God will accomplish his original purpose for the earth, transforming it into a paradise without sickness or death.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alan Rogerson|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die|publisher=Constable|year=1969|page=106}}</ref> It is said to have been the focal point of Jesus' ministry on earth.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 15, 2000 |title=God's Kingdom\u2014Earth's New Rulership |page=10 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2000763 }}</ref> They believe the kingdom was established in heaven in 1914,<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|page=298}}</ref> and that Jehovah's Witnesses serve as representatives of the kingdom on earth.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alan Rogerson|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die|publisher=Constable|year=1969|page=105}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=November 1, 1993 |title=Daniel's Prophetic Days and Our Faith|pages=8\u20139 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1993802|quote=In 1914 the appointed times of the nations ended, and the time of the end for this world began. The Davidic Kingdom was restored, not in earthly Jerusalem, but invisibly in \"the clouds of the heavens.\" ... Who would represent on earth the restored Davidic Kingdom? ... Without any doubt at all, it was the small body of anointed brothers of Jesus who in 1914 were known as the Bible Students but since 1931 have been identified as Jehovah's Witnesses. }}</ref>\n\n===Eschatology===\n{{Main|Eschatology of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\nA central teaching of Jehovah's Witnesses is that the current world era, or \"system of things\", entered the \"[[End time|last days]]\" in 1914 and faces imminent destruction through intervention by God and Jesus Christ, leading to deliverance for those who worship God acceptably.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|page=297}}</ref> They consider all other present-day religions to be false, identifying them with \"[[Whore of Babylon#Jehovah's Witnesses|Babylon the Great]]\", or the \"harlot\", of Revelation&nbsp;17,<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=286}}</ref> and believe that they will soon be destroyed by the [[United Nations]], which they believe is represented in scripture by the [[Jehovah's Witnesses and the United Nations|scarlet-colored wild beast]] of Revelation chapter 17. This development will mark the beginning of the \"[[great tribulation]]\".<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 2013|pages=4&ndash;5|title=Tell Us, When Will These Things Be?|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2013530|quote=In the larger fulfillment, the \"standing\" will occur when the United Nations (the modern-day \"disgusting thing\") attacks Christendom (which is holy in the eyes of nominal Christians) and the rest of Babylon the Great. The same attack is described at Revelation 17:16-18. That event will be the beginning of the great tribulation.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|title=Apocalypse\u2014When?|date=February 15, 1986|page=6}}</ref> Satan will subsequently use world governments to attack Jehovah's Witnesses, an action that will prompt God to begin the war of [[Armageddon]], during which all forms of government and all people not counted as Christ's \"sheep\" will be destroyed. After Armageddon, God will extend his heavenly kingdom to include earth, which will be transformed into a paradise similar to the [[Garden of Eden]].<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=180}}</ref> Most of those who had died before God's intervention will gradually be resurrected during the [[Millenarianism|thousand year]] \"judgment day\". This judgment will be based on their actions after resurrection rather than past deeds. At the end of the thousand years, Christ will hand all authority back to God. Then a final test will take place when Satan is released to mislead perfect mankind. Those who fail will be destroyed, along with Satan and his demons. The end result will be a fully tested, glorified human race on earth.<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|pages=307\u2013321}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=November 1, 1952|page=670|title=Questions From Readers|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1952809}}</ref>\n\nJehovah's Witnesses believe that Jesus Christ began to rule in heaven as king of God's kingdom in October 1914, and that Satan was subsequently ousted from heaven to the earth, resulting in \"woe\" to humanity. They believe that Jesus rules invisibly, from heaven, perceived only as a series of \"signs\". They base this belief on a rendering of the Greek word ''[[parousia]]''\u2014usually translated as \"coming\" when referring to Christ\u2014as \"presence\". They believe Jesus' presence includes an unknown period beginning with his inauguration as king in heaven in 1914, and ending when he comes to bring a final judgment against humans on earth. They thus depart from the mainstream Christian belief that the \"[[second coming]]\" of [[Matthew 24]] refers to a single moment of arrival on earth to judge humans.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=17\u201319}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 1992|page=16|title=The Messiah's Presence and His Rule|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1992723}}</ref>\n\n==Practices==\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses practices}}\n\n===Worship===\n[[File:Reuni\u00e3o em Sal\u00e3o do Reino.jpg|thumb|right|Worship at a [[Kingdom Hall]]]]\nMeetings for worship and study are held at [[Kingdom Hall]]s, which are typically functional in character, and do not contain religious symbols.<ref name=holdenhall /> Witnesses are assigned to a congregation in whose \"territory\" they usually reside and attend weekly services they refer to as \"meetings\" as scheduled by congregation elders. The meetings are largely devoted to study of Watch Tower Society literature and the Bible. The format of the meetings is established by the group's headquarters, and the subject matter for most meetings is the same worldwide.<ref name=holdenhall>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|pages=64\u201369}}</ref> Congregations meet for two sessions each week comprising four distinct meetings that total about three-and-a-half hours, typically gathering mid-week (two meetings) and on the weekend (two meetings). Prior to 2009, congregations met three times each week; these meetings were condensed, with the intention that members dedicate an evening for \"family worship\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2010|page=6|chapter=Highlights of the Past Year|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/302010009}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 15, 2011|title=Christian Families\u2014\"Keep Ready\" |page=14 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2011364 }}</ref> Gatherings are opened and closed with [[kingdom songs]] ([[hymns]]) and brief prayers. Twice each year, Witnesses from a number of congregations that form a \"circuit\" gather for a one-day assembly. Larger groups of congregations meet once a year for a three-day \"regional convention\", usually at rented stadiums or auditoriums.<ref>{{cite book|title=Organized to Do Jehovah's Will|year=2015|pages=63&ndash;64|publisher=Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society}}</ref> Their most important and solemn event is the commemoration of the \"Lord's Evening Meal\", or \"[[Jehovah's Witnesses practices#Memorial of Christ's death|Memorial of Christ's Death]]\" on the date of the Jewish [[Passover]].<ref>{{harvnb|Hoekema|1963|page=292}}</ref>\n\n===Evangelism===\n{{See also|Jehovah's Witnesses publications}}\n[[File:Jehovah's Witnesses outside the British Museum 02.jpg|thumb|Jehovah's Witnesses outside the British Museum, 2017]]\nJehovah's Witnesses are perhaps best known for their [[Proselytism|efforts to spread their beliefs]], most notably by visiting people from house to house,<ref>{{cite book|last=Crompton|first=Robert|title=Counting the Days to Armageddon|publisher=James Clarke & Co|year=1996|location=Cambridge|pages=5|isbn=978-0-227-67939-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Rogerson|first=Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable & Co, London|year=1969|pages=1|isbn=978-0094559400}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Whalen|first=William J.|title=Armageddon Around the Corner: A Report on Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=John Day Company|year=1962|location=New York|page=15,18}}</ref> distributing literature published by the Watch Tower Society in 700 languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jw.org/en/jehovahs-witnesses/activities/publishing/global-printing/|title=Global Printing\u2014Helping People to Learn About God|publisher=Watch Tower Society}}</ref> The objective is to start a regular \"Bible study\" with any person who is not already a member,<ref>{{harvnb|Ringnes|S\u00f8dal|2009|p=43}}</ref> with the intention that the student be baptized as a member of the group;<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Be \"Intensely Occupied\" With Your Ministry|quote=Your goal is to help the student achieve greater insight into the truth, qualify as an unbaptized publisher, and become a dedicated and baptized Witness of Jehovah|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=April 2001|page=3|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202001124}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=What Does the Bible Really Teach?|chapter=18&mdash;Baptism and Your Relationship With God|pages=174\u2013183|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102005148}}</ref> Witnesses are advised to consider discontinuing Bible studies with students who show no interest in becoming members.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=October 1996|title=Question Box: How long should a formal Bible study be conducted with an individual in the Knowledge book?|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/201996367|quote=We want people to receive a basic knowledge of the truth. Yet it is expected that within a relatively short period of time, an effective teacher will be able to assist a sincere average student to acquire sufficient knowledge to make an intelligent decision to serve Jehovah... Appreciation for taking in even a basic knowledge of the truth should motivate the student to attend Christian meetings. This could lead the student to giving some clear evidence of his desire to serve Jehovah. If such spiritual appreciation is not evident after the study in the ''Knowledge'' book has been conducted for an extended period, it may be advisable to discontinue the study.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather|author2=[[Gary Botting]]|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|pages=[https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott/page/77 77]|quote=The society states explicitly that all Bible studies should quickly show signs of 'real progress' to be deemed worthy of pursuit ... unless the potential converts are willing to give clear indication that they accept both the doctrines and the consequent responsibilities of attending meetings and going from door to door themselves, the study should be discontinued.|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2}}</ref> Witnesses are taught they are under a biblical command to engage in public preaching.<ref>{{cite book|title=Bearing Thorough Witness About God's Kingdom|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2009|page=63|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102009050|quote=Do you obey the command to bear thorough witness, even if the assignment causes you some apprehension?}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=December 15, 2008 |title=Determined to bear thorough witness |page=19 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2008923|quote=When the resurrected Jesus spoke to disciples gathered in Galilee, likely 500 of them, he commanded: 'Go therefore and make disciples of people of all the nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and of the Son and of the holy spirit, teaching them to observe all the things I have commanded you.' That command applies to all true Christians today. }}</ref> They are instructed to devote as much time as possible to their ministry and are required to submit an individual monthly \"Field Service Report\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather|author2=Gary Botting|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|page=[https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott/page/52 52]|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=December 2002 |title=Do You Contribute to an Accurate Report? |page=8 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202002448 |quote=Jehovah's organization today instructs us to report our field service activity each month ... At the end of the month, the book study overseer makes sure that all in the group have followed through on their responsibility to report their activity.}}</ref> Baptized members who fail to report a month of preaching are termed \"irregular\" and may be counseled by elders;<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=May 1984 |title=Regularity in Service Brings Blessings |page=7 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/201984167 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Helping Irregular Publishers|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=December 1987|page=7|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/201987447|ref=harv}}</ref> those who do not submit reports for six consecutive months are termed \"inactive\".<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=October 1982|page=1|title=Keep the Word of Jehovah Moving Speedily|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/201982361|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n===Ethics and morality===\n{{See also|Jehovah's Witnesses and congregational discipline#Discipline involving \"serious sin\"|label 1= Jehovah's Witnesses list of \"serious sins\"}}\nAll sexual relations outside of marriage are grounds for expulsion if the individual is not deemed repentant;<ref>{{cite book|author=Chryssides, G.D.|year=1999|title=Exploring New Religions|page=103|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-304-33651-7}}</ref><ref name=\"The Watchtower 1998, page 16\">{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=August 1, 1998 |title=Imitate Jehovah\u2014Exercise Justice and Righteousness |page=16 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1998563 }}</ref> [[homosexuality|homosexual]] activity is considered a serious sin, and [[same-sex marriage]]s are forbidden. [[Abortion]] is considered [[murder]].<ref name=\"holdenmorals\" >{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|pages=26\u201327, 173}}</ref> [[Suicide]] is considered to be \"self-murder\" and a sin against God.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=June 15, 2002|pages=30, 31|title=Questions From Readers|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2002447}}</ref> Modesty in dress and grooming is frequently emphasized. [[Gambling]], drunkenness, illegal drugs, and tobacco use are forbidden.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=152,&nbsp;180}}</ref> Drinking of [[alcoholic beverage]]s is permitted in moderation.<ref name=\"holdenmorals\" />\n\nThe family structure is [[Patriarchy|patriarchal]]. The husband is considered to have authority on family decisions, but is encouraged to solicit his wife's thoughts and feelings, as well as those of his children. Marriages are required to be [[Monogamy|monogamous]] and legally [[Civil registry|registered]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=''The Bible's Viewpoint'' What Does It Mean to Be the Head of the House?|magazine=Awake!|date=July 8, 2004|page=26|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/102004484}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 15, 1984|page=11|title=Christian Weddings That Bring Joy|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1984284}}</ref> Marrying a non-believer, or endorsing such a union, is strongly discouraged and carries religious sanctions.<ref>{{cite book|title=Shepherd the Flock of God|pages=37\u201338, 124\u2013125}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=March 15, 1982|page=31|title=How should individual Christians and the congregation as a whole view the Bible advice to marry \"only in the Lord\"?|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1982212}}</ref>\n\n[[Divorce]] is discouraged, and remarriage is forbidden unless a divorce is obtained on the grounds of [[adultery]], which they refer to as \"a scriptural divorce\".<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=110\u2013112}}</ref> If a divorce is obtained for any other reason, remarriage is considered adulterous unless the prior spouse has died or is since considered to have committed [[sexual ethics|sexual immorality]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Insight on the Scriptures|chapter=Adultery|page=53|volume=1|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1200000123}}</ref> Extreme physical abuse, willful non-support of one's family, and what the denomination terms \"absolute endangerment of spirituality\" are considered grounds for legal separation.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Awake|date=July 8, 1993 |title=Marriage\u2014Why Many Walk Out |page=6 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/101993482 |quote=A legal divorce or a legal separation may provide a measure of protection from extreme abuse or willful nonsupport.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Watchtower|date=November 1, 1988|page=22|title=When Marital Peace Is Threatened|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1988807}}</ref>\n\n===Disciplinary action===\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses and congregational discipline}}\nFormal discipline is administered by congregation elders. When a baptized member is accused of committing a [[Mortal sin#Jehovah's Witnesses|serious sin]]\u2014usually cases of sexual misconduct<ref name=\"alternative\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=54\u201355}}</ref> or charges of [[apostasy]] for disputing Jehovah's Witness doctrines<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=106\u2013108}}</ref><ref name=\"Muramoto\">{{cite journal|author=Osamu Muramoto|title=Bioethics of the refusal of blood by Jehovah's Witnesses: Part 1. Should bioethical deliberation consider dissidents' views?|journal=Journal of Medical Ethics|date=August 1998|volume=24|issue=4|pages=223\u2013230|pmc=1377670|pmid=9752623|doi=10.1136/jme.24.4.223}}</ref>\u2014a judicial committee is formed to determine guilt, provide help and possibly administer discipline. [[Jehovah's Witnesses and congregational discipline#Disfellowshipping|Disfellowshipping]], a form of [[shunning]], is the strongest form of discipline, administered to an offender deemed unrepentant.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 15, 1988 |title=Discipline That Can Yield Peaceable Fruit |pages=26\u201331 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1988287 }}</ref> Contact with disfellowshipped individuals is limited to direct family members living in the same home, and with congregation elders who may invite disfellowshipped persons to apply for reinstatement;<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|title=Display Christian Loyalty When a Relative Is Disfellowshipped|pages=3\u20134|date=August 2002|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202002285}}</ref> formal business dealings may continue if contractually or financially obliged.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|title=Disfellowshipping-How to View It|date=September 15, 1981|page=24|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1981688}}</ref> Witnesses are taught that avoiding social and spiritual interaction with disfellowshipped individuals keeps the congregation free from immoral influence and that \"losing precious fellowship with loved ones may help [the shunned individual] to come 'to his senses,' see the seriousness of his wrong, and take steps to return to Jehovah.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Keep Yourselves in God's Love|chapter=Appendix: How to Treat a Disfellowshipped person|pages=207\u2013209|year=2008|publisher=Jehovah's Witnesses|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102008083}}</ref> The practice of shunning may also serve to deter other members from dissident behavior.<ref name=\"Holden163\">{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=163}}</ref> Members who disassociate (formally resign) are described in Watch Tower Society literature as wicked and are also shunned.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=September 15, 1981 |title=Disfellowshiping\u2014How to View It |page=23 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1981688 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 15, 2011 |title=Do You Hate Lawlessness? |page=31|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2011129 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Crisis of Conscience|author=Franz, Raymond|page=358}}</ref> Expelled individuals may eventually be reinstated to the congregation if deemed repentant by elders in the congregation in which the disfellowshipping was enforced.<ref name=\"shepherd\" /> Reproof is a lesser form of discipline given formally by a judicial committee to a baptized Witness who is considered repentant of serious sin; the reproved person temporarily loses conspicuous privileges of service, but suffers no restriction of social or spiritual fellowship.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=January 1, 1983 |title=Questions From Readers |pages=30\u201331 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1983008 }}</ref> [[Jehovah's Witnesses and congregational discipline#Marking|Marking]], a curtailing of social but not spiritual fellowship, is practiced if a baptized member persists in a course of action regarded as a violation of Bible principles but not a serious sin.<ref group=note>A common example given is a baptized Witness who dates a non-Witness; see {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 1999 |title=Questions From Readers |page=30 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1999527 }}</ref>\n\n===Separateness===\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses and governments}}\nJehovah's Witnesses believe that the Bible condemns the mixing of religions, on the basis that there can only be one truth from God, and therefore reject interfaith and ecumenical movements.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=December 15, 1953|title=Should the Religions Unite?|magazine=The Watchtower|pages=741\u2013742|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1953921}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|date=February 1, 1952|title=Is Interfaith God's Way?|magazine=The Watchtower|page=69|ref=harv|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1952081}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|page=202}}, \"The ideological argument states that, since absolute truth is unitary and exclusive of all relativisation, there can only 'logically' be one human organization to represent it. Consequently, all other religious organizations are in error and are to be strictly avoided. The absolutist view of truth further implies that, since anything less than absolute truth can only corrupt and destroy it, there can be no justification for Jehovah's witnesses having any kind of association with other religionists, however sincere the motivation might be.\"</ref> They believe that only Jehovah's Witnesses represent true Christianity, and that other religions fail to meet all the requirements set by God and will soon be destroyed.<ref>{{cite book|title=What Does The Bible Really Teach?|page=145|chapter=Worship That God Approves|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102005145}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses are taught that it is vital to remain \"separate from the world.\" The Witnesses' literature defines the \"world\" as \"the mass of mankind apart from Jehovah's approved servants\" and teach that it is morally contaminated and ruled by Satan.<ref>{{cite book|title=World|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1989|page=|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989279}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 1989 |title=Live a Balanced, Simple Life |page=11 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1989523 }}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=12}}</ref> Witnesses are taught that association with \"worldly\" people presents a \"danger\" to their faith,<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 15, 1994|page=23|title=Keep Your Distance When Danger Threatens|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1994124|quote=Steering Clear of Danger ... We must also be on guard against extended association with worldly people. Perhaps it is a neighbor, a school friend, a workmate, or a business associate. ... What are some of the dangers of such a friendship? We could begin to minimize the urgency of the times we live in or take a growing interest in material rather than spiritual things. Perhaps, because of a fear of displeasing our worldly friend, we would even desire to be accepted by the world.}}</ref> and are instructed to minimize social contact with non-members to better maintain their own standards of morality.<ref name=holdensocial >{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|pages=109\u2013112}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Franz|first=Raymond|authorlink=Raymond Franz|title=In Search of Christian Freedom|publisher=Commentary Press|year=2007|page=409|isbn=978-0-914675-17-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=March 15, 2006 |title=Each One Will Carry His Own Load |page=23 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2006206 }}</ref><ref>Bryan R. Wilson, \"The Persistence of Sects\", ''Diskus'', Journal of the British Association for the Study of Religions, Vol 1, No. 2, 1993, \"They have extensive contact with the wider public, [in Britain in 1989, 108,000 publishers undertook 23 million hours of house-calls]. Yet, they remain little affected by that exposure\u2014they confine their contacts to their single-minded purpose and avoid all other occasions for association.\"</ref> Attending [[university]] is discouraged and [[Vocational school|trade schools]] are suggested as an alternative.<ref>{{cite book|first=George D.|last=Chryssides|authorlink=George Chryssides|title=Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0-8108-6074-2|page=47|quote=Most Witnesses do not pursue higher education. It is not forbidden but is a matter of conscience. Higher education creates the risk of detracting from one's spiritual work and can result in harmful associations with fellow students who may lack integrity. It is therefore recommended that, if possible, Witnesses who undergo should continue to live at home. Those who seek education beyond school level are urged to consider their motives for doing so: education should not be for personal status or for a high salary}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Parents-What Future Do You Want for Your Children?|magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 2005|pages=26\u201331|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2005726}}</ref>\n\nJehovah's Witnesses believe their highest allegiance belongs to God's kingdom, which is viewed as an actual government in heaven, with Christ as king. They remain politically neutral, do not seek public office, and are discouraged from voting, though individual members may participate in uncontroversial community improvement issues.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=November 1, 1999 |title=Questions From Readers |page=28 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1999807|quote=As to whether they will personally vote for someone running in an election, each one of Jehovah's Witnesses makes a decision based on his Bible-trained conscience and an understanding of his responsibility to God and to the State. }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=March 1, 1983 |title=Questions From Readers |page=30 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1983169 }}</ref> Although they do not take part in politics, they respect the authority of the governments under which they live.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jw.org/en/jehovahs-witnesses/faq/political-neutrality|title=Why Do Jehovah's Witnesses Maintain Political Neutrality?|publisher=Watch Tower Society}}</ref> They do not celebrate religious holidays such as Christmas and Easter, nor do they observe birthdays, national holidays, or other celebrations they consider to honor people other than Jesus. They feel that these and many other customs have pagan origins or reflect a nationalistic or political spirit. Their position is that these traditional holidays reflect Satan's control over the world.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date= |title=Reasoning From The Scriptures |page=178 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989235 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=August 15, 2009 |title=Keep Yourselves in God's Love |page=22 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2009604 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=September 15, 1968 |title=The Seriousness of It |page=6 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1968686 }}</ref> Witnesses are told that spontaneous giving at other times can help their children to not feel deprived of birthdays or other celebrations.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 15, 1992 |title=Work to Preserve Your Family Into God's New World |page=21 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1992763 }}</ref>\n\nThey do not work in industries associated with the military, do not serve in the armed services,<ref>{{cite book|title=Worship the Only True God|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2002|page=159|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1102002078}}</ref> and refuse national military service, which in some countries may result in their arrest and imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jw-media.org/kor/20071004.htm|title=Korea government promises to adopt alternative service system for conscientious objectors|date=October 4, 2007|website=Jehovah's Witnesses Official Media Web Site|publisher=Office of Public Information of Jehovah's Witnesses|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091224152134/http://www.jw-media.org/kor/20071004.htm|archivedate=December 24, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> They do not salute or pledge allegiance to flags or sing [[national anthems]] or patriotic songs.<ref>{{cite book|title=Education|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=2002|pages=20\u201323|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101995044}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses see themselves as a worldwide brotherhood that transcends national boundaries and ethnic loyalties.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Owens|first=Gene|title=Trials of a Jehovah's Witness.(The Faith of Journalists)|journal=Nieman Reports|date=September 1997}}</ref> Sociologist Ronald Lawson has suggested the group's intellectual and organizational isolation, coupled with the intense indoctrination of adherents, rigid internal discipline and considerable persecution, has contributed to the consistency of its sense of urgency in its apocalyptic message.<ref>Ronald Lawson, \"Sect-state relations: Accounting for the differing trajectories of Seventh-Day Adventists and Jehovah's Witnesses\", ''Sociology of Religion'', Winter 1995, \"The urgency of the Witness's apocalyptic has changed very little over time. The intellectual isolation of the Witness leaders has allowed them to retain their traditional position, and it is they who continue to be the chief purveyors of the radical eschataology ....This commitment (to principle) was bolstered by their organizational isolation, intense indoctrination of adherents, rigid internal discipline, and considerable persecution.\"</ref>\n\n===Rejection of blood transfusions===\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses and blood transfusions}}\nJehovah's Witnesses refuse [[blood transfusion]]s, which they consider a violation of God's law based on their interpretation of [[Acts 15|Acts&nbsp;15]]:28,&nbsp;29 and other scriptures.<ref>{{harvnb|Penton|1997|page=i}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Reasoning From the Scriptures|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1989|pages=70\u201375|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989215}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=91}}</ref> Since 1961 the willing acceptance of a blood transfusion by an unrepentant member has been grounds for expulsion from the group.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=BMJ|title=Bioethical aspects of the recent changes in the policy of refusal of blood by Jehovah's Witnesses|date=January 6, 2001|pages=37\u201339|pmid=11141155|doi=10.1136/bmj.322.7277.37|author=Muramoto, O.|volume=322|issue=7277|pmc=1119307|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1993|page=183|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101993015}}</ref> Members are directed to refuse blood transfusions, even in \"a life-or-death situation\".<ref>{{cite book|title=United in Worship of the Only True God|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1983|pages=156\u2013160|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101983100}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Bowman|first=R. M.|author2=[[E. Calvin Beisner|Beisner, E. C.]]|author3=Ehrenborg, T.|title=Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Zondervan|year=1995|page=[https://archive.org/details/jehovahswitnesse00bowm_0/page/13 13]|isbn=978-0-310-70411-9|url=https://archive.org/details/jehovahswitnesse00bowm_0/page/13}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather|author2=Gary Botting|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|pages=[https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott/page/29 29\u201330]|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses accept non-blood alternatives and other medical procedures in lieu of blood transfusions, and their literature provides information about non-blood medical procedures.<ref>{{cite book|title=How Blood Can Save Your Life|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1990|pages=13\u201317|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101990002}}</ref>\n\nThough Jehovah's Witnesses do not accept blood transfusions of whole blood, they may accept some [[Blood plasma fractionation|blood plasma fractions]] at their own discretion.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=June 15, 2000|title=Questions From Readers\u2014Do Jehovah's Witnesses accept any medical products derived from blood?|magazine=The Watchtower|page=30|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2000447|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Sniesinski|journal=Anesthesia & Analgesia|title=Coagulopathy After Cardiopulmonary Bypass in Jehovah's Witness Patients: Management of Two Cases Using Fractionated Components and Factor VIIa|url=http://www.freeminds.org/doctrine/sniecinski_analgesia2.pdf|date=April 2007|volume=104|doi=10.1213/01.ane.0000250913.45299.f3|format=PDF|accessdate=December 30, 2008|pmid=17377078|last2=Chen|first2=EP|last3=Levy|first3=JH|last4=Szlam|first4=F|last5=Tanaka|first5=KA|issue=4|ref=harv|pages=763\u20135|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|date=August 2006|title=The Real Value of Blood|magazine=Awake!|page=11|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/102006283|ref=harv}}</ref> The Watch Tower Society provides pre-formatted [[Power of attorney#Durable power of attorney|durable power of attorney]] documents prohibiting major blood components, in which members can specify which allowable fractions and treatments they will personally accept.<ref>{{cite book|title=Durable Power of Attorney form|publisher=Watch Tower Society|date=January 2001|page=1}} Examples of permitted fractions are: [[Interferon]], [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Immune_Serum_Globulins Immune Serum Globulins] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106083752/http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Immune_Serum_Globulins |date=January 6, 2008 }} and [[Factor VIII]]; preparations made from [[Hemoglobin]] such as [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Polyheme PolyHeme] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723234940/http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Polyheme |date=July 23, 2008 }} and [[Hemopure]]. Examples of permitted procedures involving the medical use of one's own blood include: [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Intraoperative_blood_salvage cell salvage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706171315/http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Intraoperative_blood_salvage |date=July 6, 2008 }}, [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Acute_Normovolemic_Hemodilution hemodilution] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907143504/http://noblood.org/wiki/Acute_Normovolemic_Hemodilution |date=September 7, 2008 }}, [[heart lung machine]], [[dialysis]], [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Epidural_Blood_Patch epidural blood patch] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905212647/http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Epidural_Blood_Patch |date=September 5, 2008 }}, [[plasmapheresis]], [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Blood_cell_scintigraphy blood labeling or tagging] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106084037/http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Blood_cell_scintigraphy |date=January 6, 2008 }} and [http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Platelet_Gel platelet gel] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106083757/http://www.noblood.org/wiki/Platelet_Gel |date=January 6, 2008 }} ([[autologous]])</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|date=November 2006|title=Our Kingdom Ministry|format=PDF|pages=5\u20136|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202006400|ref=harv}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses have established [[Jehovah's Witnesses and blood transfusions#Hospital Liaison Committees|Hospital Liaison Committees]] as a cooperative arrangement between individual Jehovah's Witnesses and medical professionals and hospitals.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Jehovah's Witnesses and Medical Profession Cooperate|magazine=Awake!|date=November 22, 1993|pages=24\u201327|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/101993847}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/article.aspx?articleID=070515_1_A9_hThef38217|title=Kim Archer, \"Jehovah's Witness liaisons help surgeons adapt\", ''Tulsa World'', May 15, 2007.}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Main|Demographics of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n[[File:JWStats1931-2015.png|366px|right]]\nJehovah's Witnesses have an active presence in most countries, but do not form a large part of the population of any country.\n\nFor 2018, Jehovah's Witnesses reported approximately 8.7&nbsp;million ''publishers''\u2014the term they use for members actively involved in preaching\u2014in about 120,000 congregations.<ref name=\"report2018\" /> For the same year, they reported over 2&nbsp;billion hours spent in preaching activity, and conducted Bible studies with more than 10 million individuals (including those conducted by Witness parents with their children<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=November 2003|title=Question Box&ndash;Should a family Bible study be reported to the congregation?|publisher=Watch Tower Society|page=3|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202003406}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Our Kingdom Ministry|date=September 2008|title=Question Box&mdash;May both parents report the time used for the regular family study?|page=3|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/202008324}}</ref>).<ref name=\"report2018\" /> Jehovah's Witnesses estimate their worldwide annual growth since 2018 to be 1.3%.<ref name=\"report2018\" />\n\nThe official published membership statistics, such as those mentioned above, include only those who submit reports for their personal ministry;<ref name=\"jwmediastats\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jw-media.org/aboutjw/article41.htm |title=Jehovah's Witnesses Official Media Web Site: Our History and Organization: Membership |publisher=Office of Public Information of Jehovah's Witnesses |quote=While other religious groups count their membership by occasional or annual attendance, this figure reflects only those who are actively involved in the public Bible educational work [of Jehovah's Witnesses]. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204211516/http://www.jw-media.org/aboutjw/article41.htm#membership |archivedate=December 4, 2012}}<!-- This quote addresses a common question; please do not remove--></ref> official statistics do not include ''inactive'' and ''disfellowshipped'' individuals or others who might attend their meetings. As a result, only about half of those who self-identified as Jehovah's Witnesses in independent demographic studies are considered ''active'' by the faith itself.<ref>{{cite journal|title=U.S. Religious Landscape Survey Religious Affiliation: Diverse and Dynamic|publisher=Pew Forum on Religion &amp; Public Life|date=February 2008|pages=9, 30|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thearda.com/Denoms/D_1101.asp|title=Advent Christian Church- Religious Groups - The Association of Religion Data Archives|publisher=}}</ref> The 2008 US [[Pew Research Center|Pew Forum on Religion & Public Life]] survey found a low retention rate among members of the denomination: about 37% of people raised in the group continued to identify themselves as Jehovah's Witnesses;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1716987,00.html|title=America's Unfaithful Faithful|first=David Van|last=Biema|date=February 25, 2008|via=content.time.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pewforum.org/files/2013/05/report-religious-landscape-study-full.pdf |title=PEW Forum on Religion and Public Life. U.S. Religious Landscape Survey: Religious Affiliation: Diverse and Dynamic |access-date=June 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170417032920/http://www.pewforum.org/files/2013/05/report-religious-landscape-study-full.pdf |archive-date=April 17, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the next lowest retention rates were for Buddhism at 50% and Catholicism at 68%. The study also found that 65% of adult Jehovah's Witnesses in the US are converts.<ref name=\"pewfact\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2016/04/26/a-closer-look-at-jehovahs-witnesses-living-in-the-u-s|title=A closer look at Jehovah's Witnesses living in the U.S.|publisher=Pew Research Center}}</ref>\n\n==Sociological analysis==\n{{See also|Sociological classifications of religious movements}}\nSociologist [[James A. Beckford]], in his 1975 study of Jehovah's Witnesses, classified the group's organizational structure as ''Totalizing'', characterized by an assertive leadership, specific and narrow objectives, control over competing demands on members' time and energy, and control over the quality of new members. Other characteristics of the classification include likelihood of friction with secular authorities, reluctance to co-operate with other religious organizations, a high rate of membership turnover, a low rate of doctrinal change, and strict uniformity of beliefs among members.<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=92, 98\u2013100}}</ref> Beckford identified the group's chief characteristics as ''historicism'' (identifying historical events as relating to the outworking of God's purpose), ''absolutism'' (conviction that Jehovah's Witness leaders dispense absolute truth), ''activism'' (capacity to motivate members to perform missionary tasks), ''rationalism'' (conviction that Witness doctrines have a rational basis devoid of mystery), ''authoritarianism'' (rigid presentation of regulations without the opportunity for criticism) and ''world indifference'' (rejection of certain secular requirements and medical treatments).<ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=196\u2013207}}</ref>\n\nSociologist [[Bryan R. Wilson]], in his consideration of five religious groups including Jehovah's Witnesses, noted that each of the denominations:<ref>Bryan R. Wilson, \"The Persistence of Sects\", ''Diskus'', Journal of the British Association for the Study of Religions, Vol 1, No. 2, 1993</ref>\n# \"exists in a state of tension with the wider society;\"\n# \"imposes tests of merit on would-be members;\"\n# \"exercises stern discipline, regulating the declared beliefs and the life habits of members and prescribing and operating sanctions for those who deviate, including the possibility of expulsion;\"\n# \"demands sustained and total commitment from its members, and the subordination, and perhaps even the exclusion of all other interests.\"\n\nA sociological comparative study by the [[Pew Research Center]] found that Jehovah's Witnesses in the [[United States]] ranked highest in statistics for getting no further than high school graduation, belief in God, importance of religion in one's life, frequency of religious attendance, frequency of prayers, frequency of Bible reading outside of religious services, belief their prayers are answered, belief that their religion can only be interpreted one way, belief that theirs is the only one true faith leading to eternal life, opposition to abortion, and opposition to homosexuality. In the study, Jehovah's Witnesses ranked lowest in statistics for having an interest in politics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewforum.org/2008/06/01/u-s-religious-landscape-survey-religious-beliefs-and-practices|title=Religious Beliefs and Practices|work=U.S. Religious Landscape Survey|publisher=Pew Research Center|accessdate=December 14, 2017|date=June 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/compare/educational-distribution/by/religious-tradition/|title=Educational distribution by religious group|work=U.S. Religious Landscape Survey|publisher=Pew Research Center|accessdate=December 14, 2017|date=June 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/religious-tradition/jehovahs-witness|title=Jehovah's Witnesses|work=U.S. Religious Landscape Survey|publisher=Pew Research Center|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> It was also among the most ethnically diverse religious groups in the US.<ref name=\"pewfact\"/><!--The small sample size of JWs (215) in comparison to other groups surveyed\u2014over 9000 Evangelicals, over 8000 Catholics, over 7000 'mainline' churches, etc, total 35556) may skew these results-->\n\n==Opposition==\nControversy surrounding various beliefs, doctrines and practices of Jehovah's Witnesses has led to opposition from governments, communities, and religious groups. Religious commentator Ken Jubber wrote that \"Viewed globally, this persecution has been so persistent and of such intensity that it would not be inaccurate to regard Jehovah's Witnesses as the most persecuted group of Christians of the twentieth century.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Jubber|first=Ken|title=The Persecution of Jehovah's Witnesses in Southern Africa|journal=Social Compass|volume=24|issue=1|pages=121\u2013134|year=1977|doi=10.1177/003776867702400108}}</ref>\n\n===Persecution===\n{{Main|Persecution of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n{{See also|Persecution of Jehovah's Witnesses in Nazi Germany}}\n[[File:Purple Triangle.JPG|thumb|right|Jehovah's Witness prisoners were identified by [[purple triangle]] [[Nazi concentration camp badges|badges in Nazi concentration camps]].]]\nPolitical and religious animosity against Jehovah's Witnesses has at times led to [[mob action]] and [[government]] oppression in various countries.\nTheir stance regarding political neutrality and their refusal to serve in the military has led to imprisonment of members who refused conscription during [[World War II]] and at other times where [[national service]] has been compulsory. Their religious activities are currently banned or restricted in some countries, including [[China]], [[Vietnam]] and some Islamic states.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1993|page=490|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101993030}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Yearbook of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1991|page=222|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/301991017}}</ref>\n\n* In 1933, there were approximately 20,000 Jehovah's Witnesses in [[Nazi Germany]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Penton|first=James|title=Jehovah's witnesses and the third reich|url=https://archive.org/details/jehovahswitnesse0000pent_f0s7|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=2004|isbn=978-0802086785|page=[https://archive.org/details/jehovahswitnesse0000pent_f0s7/page/376 376]}}</ref> of whom about 10,000 were imprisoned. Of those, 2,000 were sent to [[Nazi concentration camps]], where they were identified by [[purple triangle]]s; as many as 1,200 died, including 250 who were executed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Garbe|first=Detlef|title=Between Resistance and Martyrdom: Jehovah's Witnesses in the Third Reich|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|year=2008|location=Madison, Wisconsin|page=484|isbn=978-0-299-20794-6}}</ref><ref name=Shulman>Shulman, William L. ''A State of Terror: Germany 1933\u20131939''. Bayside, New York: Holocaust Resource Center and Archives.</ref><ref>[http://www.holocaust-trc.org/Jehovah.htm Holocaust Education Foundation website].</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Hesse|first=Hans|title=Persecution and Resistance of Jehovah's Witnesses During the Nazi Regime|publisher=Edition Temmen|year=2001|location=|isbn=978-3-86108-750-2|page=12}}</ref>\n* In [[Canada]] during World War II, Jehovah's Witnesses were interned in camps<ref>{{cite book|last=Kaplan|first=William|title=State and Salvation|location=Toronto|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1989}}</ref> along with political dissidents and people of Chinese and Japanese descent.<ref>{{cite news|last=Yaffee|first=Barbara|title=Witnesses Seek Apology for Wartime Persecution|work=The Globe and Mail|date=September 9, 1984|page=4}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses faced discrimination in [[Quebec]] until the [[Quiet Revolution]], including bans on distributing literature or holding meetings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canlii.org/en/ca/scc/doc/1953/1953canlii3/1953canlii3.html|title=Saumur v Quebec (City of)|last=Supreme Court of Canada|date=|website=|series=[1953] 2 SCR 299|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706012152/http://www.canlii.org/en/ca/scc/doc/1953/1953canlii3/1953canlii3.html|archive-date=July 6, 2011|url-status=dead|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canlii.org/en/ca/scc/doc/1959/1959canlii50/1959canlii50.html|title=Roncarelli v Duplessis|last=Supreme Court of Canada|date=|website=|series=[1959] SCR 121|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112043742/http://www.canlii.org/en/ca/scc/doc/1959/1959canlii50/1959canlii50.html|archive-date=January 12, 2013|url-status=dead|access-date=}}</ref>\n* In 1951, about 9,300 Jehovah's Witnesses in the [[Soviet Union]] were deported to [[Siberia]] as part of [[Operation North]] in April 1951.<ref name=\"passat\">\u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041f\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0442 .\"\u0422\u0440\u0443\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u044b \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 \u041c\u043e\u043b\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b (1940\u20131950)\". \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430: \u0418\u0437\u0434. Terra, 1994 {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n* In April 2017, the [[Supreme Court of Russia]] labeled Jehovah's Witnesses an extremist organization, banned its activities in [[Russia]] and issued an order to confiscate the organization's assets.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-religion-jehovah-s-idUSKBN17M1ZT|title=Russian court bans Jehovah's Witnesses as extremist|publisher=delfi.lt |accessdate=April 20, 2017|newspaper=Reuters|date=April 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAuthors including [[William J. Whalen|William Whalen]], Shawn Francis Peters and former Witnesses [[Barbara Grizzuti Harrison]], Alan Rogerson and William Schnell have claimed the arrests and mob violence in the United States in the 1930s and 1940s were the consequence of what appeared to be a deliberate course of provocation of authorities and other religious groups by Jehovah's Witnesses. Whalen, Harrison and Schnell have suggested Rutherford invited and cultivated opposition for publicity purposes in a bid to attract dispossessed members of society, and to convince members that persecution from the outside world was evidence of the truth of their struggle to serve God.<ref>{{cite book|last=Peters|first=Shawn Francis|title=Judging Jehovah's Witnesses: Religious Persecution and the Dawn of the Rights Revolution|url=https://archive.org/details/judgingjehovahsw0000pete|url-access=registration|publisher=University Press of Kansas|year=2000|pages=[https://archive.org/details/judgingjehovahsw0000pete/page/82 82], 116\u20139|isbn=978-0-7006-1008-2}}</ref><ref>Barbara Grizzuti Harrison, ''Visions of Glory'', 1978, chapter 6.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Whalen|first=William J.|title=Armageddon Around the Corner: A Report on Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=John Day Company|year=1962|location=New York|page=190}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Schnell|first=William|title=30 Years a Watchtower Slave|publisher=Baker Book House, Grand Rapids|year=1971|pages=104\u2013106|isbn=978-0-8010-6384-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Rogerson|first=Alan|title=Millions Now Living Will Never Die: A Study of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Constable & Co, London|year=1969|page=59|isbn=978-0094559400}}</ref> Watch Tower Society literature of the period directed that Witnesses should \"never seek a controversy\" nor resist arrest, but also advised members not to co-operate with police officers or courts that ordered them to stop preaching, and to prefer jail rather than pay fines.<ref>{{cite book|title=Advice for Kingdom Publishers|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1939|pages=5\u20136, 14}}</ref>\n\n===Legal challenges===\n{{Main|Supreme Court cases involving Jehovah's Witnesses by country}}\nSeveral cases involving Jehovah's Witnesses have been heard by Supreme Courts throughout the world.<ref>[[Gary Botting]], ''Fundamental Freedoms and Jehovah's Witnesses'' (Calgary: University of Calgary Press, 1993)</ref> The cases generally relate to their right to practice their religion, displays of patriotism and military service, and blood transfusions.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1993|pages=679\u2013701|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101993041}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, legal challenges by Jehovah's Witnesses prompted a series of state and federal court rulings that reinforced judicial protections for civil liberties.<ref>Botting, ''Fundamental Freedoms and Jehovah's Witnesses'', pp. 1\u201314; Shawn Francis Peters, ''Judging Jehovah's Witnesses'', University Press of Kansas: 2000, pages 12\u201316.</ref> Among the rights strengthened by Witness court victories in the United States are the protection of religious conduct from federal and state interference, the right to abstain from patriotic rituals and military service, the right of patients to refuse medical treatment, and the right to engage in public discourse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knocking.org/Jehovahs_Witness_History_Civil_Rights.html|title=Jehovah's Witnesses and civil rights|publisher=Knocking.org|accessdate=August 16, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901075011/http://www.knocking.org/Jehovahs_Witness_History_Civil_Rights.html|archivedate=September 1, 2012}}</ref> Similar cases in their favor have been heard in Canada.<ref>Botting, ''Fundamental Freedoms...'', pp. 15\u2013201</ref>\n\n==Criticism and controversy==\n{{Main|Criticism of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\nJehovah's Witnesses have received criticism from mainstream Christianity, members of the medical community, former members and commentators regarding [[Jehovah's Witnesses beliefs|their beliefs]] and [[Jehovah's Witnesses practices|practices]]. The movement has been accused of doctrinal inconsistency and reversals, failed predictions, mistranslation of the Bible, harsh treatment of former members and autocratic and coercive leadership. Criticism has also focused on their rejection of [[blood transfusion]]s, particularly in life-threatening medical situations, and failing to report cases of [[sexual abuse]] to the authorities. Many of the claims are denied by Jehovah's Witnesses and some have also been disputed by courts and religious scholars.\n\n===Free speech and thought===\nDoctrines of Jehovah's Witnesses are established by the Governing Body.<ref name=\"Holden22\">{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=22}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/case-studies/case-study-29-jehovahs-witnesses|title=Case Study 29: Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses|date=July 27, 2015|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse}}</ref> The denomination does not tolerate dissent over doctrines and practices;<ref name=\"voice\" /><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 1, 1967 |title=Following Faithful Shepherds with Life in View |page=591 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1967723 |quote=Make haste to identify the visible theocratic organization of God that represents his king, Jesus Christ. It is essential for life. Doing so, be complete in accepting its every aspect ... in submitting to Jehovah's visible theocratic organization, we must be in full and complete agreement with every feature of its apostolic procedure and requirements.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 1, 2007 |title=Loyal to Christ and His Faithful Slave |page=24 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2007245 |quote=When we loyally submit to the direction of the faithful slave and its Governing Body, we are submitting to Christ, the slave's Master.}}</ref><ref name=\"Beckford dissent\">{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=89, 95, 103, 120, 204, 221}}</ref> members who openly disagree with the group's teachings are expelled and shunned.<ref name=\"Muramoto\" /> Witness publications strongly discourage followers from questioning doctrine and counsel received from the Governing Body, reasoning that it is to be trusted as part of \"God's organization\".<ref name=\"Beckford dissent\" /><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=January 15, 1983 |title='Exposing the Devil's Subtle Designs' and 'Armed for the Fight Against Wicked Spirits' |pages=18\u201327 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1983046 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=August 15, 1981 |title=Serving Jehovah Shoulder to Shoulder |page=28 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1981609 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 1, 1952 |title=Jehovah's Theocratic Organization Today |pages=79\u201381 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1952083 }}</ref> It also warns members to \"avoid independent thinking\", claiming such thinking \"was introduced by Satan the Devil\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Exposing the Devil's Subtle Designs|magazine=The Watchtower|date=January 15, 1983|pages=27|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1983046|quote=From the very outset of his rebellion Satan called into question God's way of doing things. He promoted independent thinking. ... How is such independent thinking manifested? A common way is by questioning the counsel that is provided by God's visible organization.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Visits from Older Men Benefit God's People|magazine=The Watchtower|date=February 15, 1979|pages=20|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1979127|quote=In a world where people are tossed about by confusing winds of religious doctrine, Jehovah's people need to be stable, full-grown Christians. (Eph. 4:13, 14) Their position must be steadfast, not shifting quickly because of independent thinking or emotional pressures.}}</ref> and would \"cause division\".<ref>{{cite magazine|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Building a Firm Foundation in Christ|magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 1, 1964|pages=277\u2013278|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1964324|quote=It is through the columns of The Watchtower that Jehovah provides direction and constant Scriptural counsel to his people, and it requires careful study and attention to details in order to apply this information, to get a full understanding of the principles involved, and to assure ourselves of right thinking on these matters. It is in this way that we \"are thoroughly able to grasp mentally with all the holy ones\" the fullness of our commission and of the preaching responsibility that Jehovah has placed on all Christians as footstep followers of his Son. Any other course would produce independent thinking and cause division.}}</ref> Those who openly disagree with official teachings are condemned as \"apostates\" who are \"mentally diseased\".<ref name=\"Holden163\" /><ref>See also Raymond Franz, ''In Search of Christian Freedom'', pg. 358.</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 2011 |title=Will You Heed Jehovah's Clear Warnings? |page=15 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2011524 }}</ref>\n\nFormer members Heather and [[Gary Botting]] compare the cultural paradigms of the denomination to [[George Orwell]]'s ''[[Nineteen Eighty-four]]'',<ref>''The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses'', Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1984, ''passim''.</ref> and Alan Rogerson describes the group's leadership as [[totalitarianism|totalitarian]].<ref>Alan Rogerson, ''Millions Now Living Will Never Die'', Constable, 1969, page 50.</ref> Other critics charge that by disparaging individual decision-making, the group's leaders cultivate a system of unquestioning obedience<ref name=\"Bevindependent\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=204, 221}}, ''The habit of questioning or qualifying Watch Tower doctrine is not only under-developed among the Witnesses: it is strenuously combated at all organizational levels''</ref> in which Witnesses abrogate all responsibility and rights over their personal lives.<ref>{{cite book|last=Botting|first=Heather|author2=Gary Botting|title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott|url-access=registration|publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984|page=[https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott/page/90 90]|isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2|quote=Most Witnesses, although ''capable'' of intelligent, reasonable thought, have as part of the payment for paradise delegated authority to the organization for directing their lives ... and finally abrogate ''all'' responsibility and rights over their personal lives\u2014in effect, allowing the society to do their thinking for them.}}</ref><ref>Alan Rogerson, ''Millions Now Living Will Never Die'', Constable, 1969, page 178, \"The newly converted Witness must conform immediately to the doctrines of the Watchtower Society, thus whatever individuality of mind he possessed before conversion is liable to be eradicated if he stays in the movement.\".</ref> Critics also accuse the group's leaders of exercising \"intellectual dominance\" over Witnesses,<ref>James A. Beverley, ''Crisis of Allegiance'', Welch Publishing Company, Burlington, Ontario, 1986, {{ISBN|0-920413-37-4}}, pages 25\u201326, 101.</ref> controlling information<ref name=\"Muramoto\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=153}}</ref><ref>Alan Rogerson, ''Millions Now Living Will Never Die'', Constable, 1969, page 2, \"In addition to the prevalent ignorance outside the Witness movement, there is much ignorance within it. It will soon become obvious to the reader that the Witnesses are an indoctrinated people whose beliefs and thoughts are shaped by the Watchtower Society.\"</ref> and creating \"mental isolation\", which former Governing Body member [[Raymond Franz]] argued were all elements of [[mind control]].<ref>R. Franz, \"In Search of Christian Freedom\", chapter 12</ref>\n\nJehovah's Witness publications state that consensus of faith aids unity, and deny that unity restricts individuality or imagination.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Maintaining our Christian Oneness|magazine=The Watchtower|date=August 15, 1988|pages=28\u201330|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1988608}}</ref> Historian James Irvin Lichti has rejected the description of the denomination as \"totalitarian\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=vsrJLASVC3QC&pg=359&Ipg=PA359#v=onepage ''The Routledge History of the Holocaust'', Routledge, 2010], \"Labeling the Jehovah's Witnesses as totalitarian trivializes the term totalitarian and defames the Jehovah's Witnesses.\"</ref>\n\nSociologist [[Rodney Stark]] states that Jehovah's Witness leaders are \"not always very democratic\" and that members \"are expected to conform to rather strict standards,\" but adds that \"enforcement tends to be very informal, sustained by the close bonds of friendship within the group\", and that Jehovah's Witnesses see themselves as \"part of the power structure rather than subject to it.\"<ref name=\"Stark\"/> Sociologist Andrew Holden states that most members who join millenarian movements such as Jehovah's Witnesses have made an informed choice.<ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|pages=x, 7}}</ref> However, he also states that defectors \"are seldom allowed a dignified exit\",<ref name=\"Holden163\" /> and describes the administration as [[autocracy|autocratic]].<ref name=\"Holden22\" />\n\n===New World Translation===\n{{Main|New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures}}\nVarious Bible scholars, including [[Bruce M. Metzger]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Metzger |first1=Bruce |date=July 1, 1964 |title=Book Review: New World Translation of the Christian Greek Scriptures |url=http://www.ubs-translations.org/tbt/1964/03/TBT196403.html?seq=49 |journal=The Bible Translator |volume=15 |issue=3 |pages=151 |access-date=October 30, 2018 | quote=On the whole, one gains a tolerably good impression of the scholarly equipment of the translators (their names are not divulged.). They refer not only to modern translations, including various English, German, French, Spanish, Italian, and Portuguese translations, but to ancient versions as well, including the Old Latin, Old Syriac, Vulgate, Armenian and Ethiopoc versions. Frequently an intelligent use of critical information is apparent.}}</ref> and [[MacLean Gilmour]],<ref>{{cite journal |last=Gilmour |first=MacLean |date=September 1966 |title=The Use and Abuse of the Book of Revelation|journal=Andover Newton Quarterly |volume=7 |issue=1|pages=25\u201326 |quote=The New World translation was made by a committee whose membership has never been revealed-a committee that possessed an unusual competence in Greek ... It is clear that doctrinal considerations influenced many turns of phrase, but the work is no crack-pot or pseudo-historical fraud.* ... *See Robert M. McCoy 'Jehovah's Witnesses and Their New Testament', Andover Newton Quarterly, Jan., 1963, Vol. 3, No. 3, pp. 15\u201331}}</ref> have said that while scholarship is evident in ''New World Translation'', its rendering of certain texts are inaccurate and biased in favor of Witness practices and doctrines.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Metzger|first=Bruce M.|date=April 1, 1953|title=The Jehovah's Witnesses and Jesus Christ|journal=Theology Today|volume=10|issue=1|page=74|doi=10.1177/004057365301000110|bibcode=1998ThT....55..305G}} See also Metzger, \"The New World Translation of the Christian Greek Scriptures,\" ''The Bible Translator'' (July 1964).</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=McCoy |first=Robert |date=January 1963 |title=Jehovah's Witnesses and Their New Testament|journal=Andover Newton Quarterly |volume=3|issue=3|pages=15\u201331|quote=The translation of the New Testament is evidence of the presence in the movement of scholars qualified to deal intelligently with the many problems of Biblical translation. ... In not a few instances the New World Translation contains passages which must be considered as 'theological translations.'}}</ref><ref name=\"haas\">{{cite journal|last=Haas|first=Samuel S.|date=December 1955|title=Book Review: ''New World Translation of the Hebrew Scriptures, Vol. I'' by New World Bible Translation Committee|journal=Journal of Biblical Literature|volume=74|issue=4|pages=282\u2013283|doi=10.2307/3261681|quote=this work indicates a great deal of effort and thought as well as considerable scholarship, it is to be regretted that religious bias was allowed to colour many passages.|jstor=3261681}} See also {{cite journal|last=Owens|first=John Joseph|date=April 1, 1956|title=Book Review: New World Translation of the Hebrew Scriptures|journal=Review & Expositor|volume=53|issue=2|pages=253\u2013254|doi=10.1177/003463735605300239}}</ref><ref name=\"Ankerberg\">{{cite book|author1=John Ankerberg|author2=John Weldon|author3=Dillon Burroughs|title=The Facts on Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rLHuulPCiTgC&pg=PA43|year=2008|publisher=Harvest House Publishers|location=Eugene, OR|isbn=978-0-7369-3907-2|pages=43\u201345}} See also John Ankerberg and John Weldon, 2003, ''The New World Translation of the Jehovah's Witnesses'', accessible [https://web.archive.org/web/20121029043702/http://www.johnankerberg.org/Articles/ATRI-Bible-School/Fall-Bible-School/fall-bible-school-jw-new-world-translation.htm online]</ref><ref name=\"pentonbible\" >{{harvnb|Penton|1997|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=wmsdmva7u6kC&id=38SYXalMLeQC&pg=PA175 174\u2013176]}}</ref> Critics of the group such as Edmund C. Gruss,<ref>Edmond C. Gruss, ''Apostles of Denial'', p. 211: \"the honest mind can only conclude that this work, although outwardly scholarly, is plainly in many places, just the opposite.\"</ref> and Christian writers such as [[Ray Stedman|Ray C. Stedman]],<ref>Stedman, R.C., \"The New World Translation of the Christian Greek Scriptures,\" Our Hope 50; 34, July 1953. 30 as quoted in Edmond C. Gruss, ''Apostles of Denial'', p. 209: \"A close examination, which gets beneath the outward veneer of scholarship, reveals a veritable shambles of bigotry, ignorance, prejudice, and biais which violates every rule of biblical criticism and every standard of scholarly integrity.\"</ref> [[Walter Ralston Martin|Walter Martin]], Norman Klann<ref>Martin, W., & Klann, N., Jehovah of the Watchtower, (Minneapolis: Bethany, 1974 161)</ref> and [[Anthony A. Hoekema|Anthony Hoekema]]<ref>Hoekema, A., The Four Major Cults (Exeter: Paternoster, 1963) 208-9</ref> state that the ''New World Translation'' exhibits scholastic dishonesty. Most criticism of the ''New World Translation'' relates to its rendering of the New Testament, particularly regarding the introduction of the name ''Jehovah'' and in passages related to the Trinity doctrine.<ref>G. H\u00c9BERT/EDS, \"Jehovah's Witnesses\", ''The New Catholic Encyclopedia'', Gale, 2005<sup>2</sup>, Vol. 7, p. 751.</ref><ref>Anthony A. Hoekema, The Four Major Cults, Christian Science, Jehovah's Witnesses, Mormonism, Seventh-day Adventism, William B. Eerdmans, 1963, {{ISBN|0802831176}}, pp. 208\u2013209</ref>\n\n===Unfulfilled predictions===\n{{Main|Watch Tower Society unfulfilled predictions}}\nWatch Tower Society publications have claimed that God has used Jehovah's Witnesses (and formerly, the International Bible Students) to declare his will<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 1, 1997 |title=Messengers of Godly Peace Pronounced Happy |page=21 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1997325 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1993|page=708|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101993043}}</ref> and has provided advance knowledge about [[Armageddon]] and the establishment of [[God's kingdom]].<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 15, 1980 |title=Execution of the 'Great Harlot' Nears |page=17 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1980765 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 2010 |title=What Jehovah's Day Will Reveal |page=5 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/2010521 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=July 15, 1960 |title=Staying Awake with the \"Faithful and Discreet Slave\" |page=444 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1960525 |quote=In 1942 the faithful and discreet slave guided by Jehovah's unerring spirit made known that the democracies would win World War II and that there would be a United Nations organization set up ... Once again the faithful and discreet slave has been tipped off ahead of time for the guidance of all lovers of God.}} (Footnote cites the booklet ''Peace\u2014Can It Last'', 1942, pages 21,22.)</ref> Some publications also claimed that God has used Jehovah's Witnesses and the International Bible Students as a modern-day prophet.<ref group=note>Raymond Franz cites numerous examples. In ''Crisis of Conscience'', 2002, pg. 173, he quotes from {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=April 1, 1972 |title=They Shall Know That a Prophet Was Among Them |pages=197\u2013200 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1972241}} which states that God had raised Jehovah's Witnesses as a prophet \"to warn (people) of dangers and declare things to come\". He also cites {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=May 1, 1997 |title=Identifying the Right Kind of Messenger |page=8 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1997323 }} which identifies the Witnesses as his \"true messengers ... by making the messages he delivers through them come true\", in contrast to \"false messengers\", whose predictions fail. In ''In Search of Christian Freedom,'' 2007, he quotes {{cite book|title=Commissioned to Speak in the Divine Name|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1971|pages=70, 292|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101971004}} which describes Witnesses as the modern Ezekiel class, \"a genuine prophet within our generation\". The Watch Tower book noted: \"Concerning the message faithfully delivered by the Ezekiel class, Jehovah positively states that it 'must come true' ... those who wait undecided until it does 'come true' will also have to know that a prophet himself had proved to be in the midst of them.\" He also cites {{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=October 15, 1980 |title=Execution of the Great Harlot Nears |page=17 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1980765 }} which claims God gives the Witnesses \"special knowledge that others do not have ... advance knowledge about this system's end\".</ref> [[George D. Chryssides]] stated, \"while prediction may be part of a biblical prophet's role, the root meaning of prophecy is that of proclaiming God's word.\" He went on to say that, \"Jehovah's Witnesses ... are the recipients of prophecy, who regard themselves as invested with the interpretation of biblical writings.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Chryssides|first=George|title=Jehovah's Witnesses Continuity and Change|publisher=Ashgate|year=2016|location=England|page=224|isbn=978-1-4094-5608-7}}</ref><ref group=note>In ''Jehovah's Witnesses Continuity and Change'' Chryssides states, after discussing the April 1, 1972 ''Watchtower'' article, that, \"It would be tedious to comment on each passage in which Watch Tower literature explains the Jehovah's Witnesses' position on prophecy. Some of it may lack the precision that its detractors appear to demand, but the Society's position is quite clear. Jehovah's Witnesses do not claim to have any new revelation or people who are designated as prophets. As cessationists, they identify the ability to prophesy as a gift that died out with the first generation of Christians, but prophetic utterances remain in the Bible, which serves as the key source of authority. ... since the Bible is held to contain predictive prophecy, Jehovah's Witnesses claim to see into the future through the Society's interpretation of scripture.\" pg 225.</ref> With these interpretations, Jehovah's Witnesses' publications have made various predictions about world events they believe were prophesied in the Bible.<ref name=WT59>{{cite magazine |magazine=The Watchtower|date=January 15, 1959 |title=Down with the Old-Up with the New! |pages=39\u201341 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1959041 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Crompton|first=Robert|title=Counting the Days to Armageddon|publisher=James Clarke & Co|year=1996|location=Cambridge|pages=9, 115|isbn=978-0-227-67939-5}}</ref> Failed predictions have led to the alteration or abandonment of some doctrines.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1993|pages=78, 632|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101993008}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Beckford|1975|pages=219\u2013221}}</ref> Some failed predictions had been presented as \"beyond doubt\" or \"approved by God\".<ref>James A. Beverley, ''Crisis of Allegiance'', Welch Publishing Company, Burlington, Ontario, 1986, {{ISBN|0-920413-37-4}}, page 86\u201391.</ref>\n\nThe Watch Tower Society rejects accusations that it is a [[false prophet]],<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite magazine |magazine=Awake!|date=March 22, 1993 |title=Why So Many False Alarms? |pages=3\u20134 |url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/101993201}} footnote</ref> stating that its interpretations are not inspired or infallible,<ref>{{cite book|title=Revelation\u2014Its Grand Climax|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|year=1988|page=9|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101988002}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Reasoning From the Scriptures|publisher=Watchtower Bible and Tract Society|chapter=False Prophets\u2014Have not Jehovah's Witnesses made errors in their teachings?|page=137|chapter-url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1101989228}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=To Whom Shall We Go but Jesus Christ?|magazine=Watchtower|date=March 1, 1979|page=23|url=https://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1979167|quote=the \"faithful and discreet slave\" has alerted all of God's people to the sign of the times indicating the nearness of God's Kingdom rule. In this regard, however, it must be observed that this \"faithful and discreet slave\" was never inspired, never perfect. Those writings by certain members of the \"slave\" class that came to form the Christian part of God's Word were inspired and infallible [the bible], but that is not true of other writings since.}}</ref> and that it has not claimed its predictions were \"the words of Jehovah.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Chryssides has suggested that with the exception of statements about 1914, 1925 and 1975, the changing views and dates of the Jehovah's Witnesses are largely attributable to changed understandings of biblical chronology rather than to failed predictions.<ref name=\"Georgie\"/> Chryssides further states, \"it is therefore simplistic and na\u00efve to view the Witnesses as a group that continues to set a single end-date that fails and then devise a new one, as many counter-cultists do.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|author=George D. Chryssides|year=2008|page=xiv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xx6nUwZzeCsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=jehovah's+witnesses#v=onepage&q=simplistic|isbn=9780810862692}}</ref> However, sociologist Andrew Holden states that since the foundation of the movement around 140 years ago, \"Witnesses have maintained that we are living on the precipice of the end of time.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Holden|2002|Portrait|page=7}}</ref>\n\n===Handling of sexual abuse cases===\n{{Main|Jehovah's Witnesses' handling of child sex abuse}}\nJehovah's Witnesses have been accused of having policies and culture that help to conceal cases of sexual abuse within the organization.<ref name=\"ousted\">{{cite news|last=Goodstein|first=Laurie|title=Ousted members say Jehovah's Witnesses' policy on abuse hides offenses|newspaper=The New York Times|date=August 11, 2002|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/08/11/us/ousted-members-say-jehovah-s-witnesses-policy-on-abuse-hides-offenses.html |accessdate=October 1, 2015}}</ref> The group has been criticized for its \"two witness rule\" for church discipline, based on its application of scriptures at Deuteronomy 19:15 and Matthew 18:15\u201317, which requires sexual abuse to be substantiated by secondary evidence if the accused person denies any wrongdoing.<ref name=\"sexmedia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jw-media.org/aboutjw/article23.htm|title=Jehovah's Witnesses and Child Protection|publisher=Jehovah's Witnesses Official Media website|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091123144858/http://www.jw-media.org/aboutjw/article23.htm|archivedate=November 23, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/file-list/Case%20Study%2029%20-%20Transcript%20-%20Jehovahs%20Witnesses%20-%20Day%20152%20-%2004082015.pdf|title=Public Hearing - Case Study 29 (Day 152)|page=67,72|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse, Australia|quote=in the absence of a confession or circumstantial evidence or other indicators, would we act judicially on one witness as the courts would do, the answer would be no, and I don't see that changing, in harmony with the scriptures. ... Q. Insofar as a second witness is concerned, is that requirement covered by, for example, scientific evidence? A. Certainly. Q. So if there was some external forensic scientific or direct evidence which is not of an observer to the incident, but someone who observes some corroborative aspect to the incident, that would be sufficient, would it? A. The answer is yes... we, as the case files will show, have disfellowshipped people for being in an inappropriate setting where there is some allegation.}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/file-list/Case%20Study%2029%20-%20Transcript%20-%20Jehovahs%20Witnesses%20-%20Day%20155%20-%2014082015.pdf|title=Public Hearing - Case Study 29 (Day 155)|page=44,45|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse, Australia}}</ref> In cases where corroboration is lacking, the Watch Tower Society's instruction is that \"the elders will leave the matter in Jehovah's hands\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Shepherd the Flock of God|publisher=Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|year=2010|location=Brooklyn, New York|page=72}}</ref> A former member of the headquarters staff, Barbara Anderson, says the policy effectively requires that there be another witness to an act of molestation, \"which is an impossibility\". Anderson says the policies \"protect pedophiles rather than protect the children.\"<ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|author1=[[Lisa Myers]]|author2=Richard Greenberg|title=New evidence in Jehovah's Witness allegations|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/21917798|publisher=[[NBC News]]|location=New York, NY|date=November 21, 2007}}</ref> Jehovah's Witnesses maintain that they have a strong policy to protect children, adding that the best way to protect children is by educating parents; they also state that they do not sponsor activities that separate children from parents.<ref name=\"sexmedia\"/><ref name=\"cpt_E\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jw.org/en/news/legal/legal-resources/information/packet-jw-scripturally-based-position-child-protection|title=Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses\u2019 Scripturally Based Position on Child Protection|website=Official Website of Jehovah\u2019s Witnesses.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=Awake!|title=How to Protect Your Children|date=October 2007|pages=4\u20138|url=http://wol.jw.org/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/102007362}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/file-list/Case%20Study%2029%20-%20Findings%20Report%20-%20Jehovahs%20Witnesses.pdf|title=Report of case study no.29|page=9,28|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse, Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe group's failure to report abuse allegations to authorities has also been criticized.<ref name=\"MediaWales\">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Ciaran|date=June 29, 2014|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/jehovahs-witnesses-destroyed-documents-showing-7340603|title=Jehovah's Witnesses destroyed documents showing child abuse allegations against church elder|publisher=[[Media Wales]]|location=Cardiff, UK|website=Wales Online}}</ref> The Watch Tower Society's policy is that elders inform authorities when required by law to do so, but otherwise leave that action up to the victim and his or her family.<ref name=\"sexmedia\" /><ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/file-list/Case%20Study%2029%20-%20Transcript%20-%20Jehovahs%20Witnesses%20-%20Day%20152%20-%2004082015.pdf|title=Public Hearing - Case Study 29 (Day 152)|pages=24\u201326|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse, Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Shepherd the Flock of God|publisher=Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania|year=2010|location=Brooklyn, New York|pages=131\u2013132}}</ref> The Australian [[Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse]] found that of 1,006 alleged perpetrators of child sexual abuse investigated by Jehovah's Witness elders since 1950, \"not one was reported by the church to secular authorities.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/> The Royal Commission also found that the Watch Tower Society legal department routinely provided incorrect information to elders based on an incorrect understanding about what constitutes a legal obligation to report crimes in Australia.<ref>{{cite report|title=Report of Case Study No. 29|page=62|quote=The Royal Commission heard evidence that, before the public hearing of this case study, the Jehovah's Witness organisation did not consider that concealment offences were independent of obligations under mandatory reporting laws to report child sexual abuse.}}</ref><ref>\"Case Study 29\", Day 153 p.16, 41&mdash;44, ''Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse'', July 2015.]</ref> William Bowen, a former Jehovah's Witness elder who established the [[Silentlambs]] organization to assist sex abuse victims within the denomination, has claimed Witness leaders discourage followers from reporting incidents of sexual misconduct to authorities, and other critics claim the organization is reluctant to alert authorities in order to protect its \"crime-free\" reputation.<ref name=\"ousted\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Cutrer|first=Corrie|title=Witness leaders accused of shielding molesters|journal=Christianity Today|date=March 5, 2001|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2001/004/11.23.html|quote=Paul Carden, executive director for the Centers for Apologetics Research in San Juan Capistrano, California, says this protective attitude is prevalent in the WTBTS. \"There is a fortress mentality,\" Carden says. \"The Watchtower Society is loath to admit wrongdoing of any sort. Because they portray themselves as being Jehovah's sole mouthpiece to mankind, they have sought to present themselves as being above question.\"}}</ref> In court cases in the United Kingdom and the United States the Watch Tower Society has been found to have been negligent in its failure to protect children from known sex offenders within the congregation,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://appellatecases.courtinfo.ca.gov/search/case/mainCaseScreen.cfm?dist=1&doc_id=2025979&doc_no=A136641&request_token=NiIwLSInLkg9W0BJSSJNSEhIMFw6UVxfICM%2BXz5TICAgCg%3D%3D |title=Jane Doe (Candace Conti) v. The Watchtower Bible and Tract Society of New York Inc. et al.|publisher=[[California courts of appeal#First District|California Court of Appeal, First Appellate District, Division Three]] |date=April 13, 2015}} [http://www.courts.ca.gov/opinions/archive/A136641.PDF Court of Appeal Opinion] <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Former Jehovah's Witness Takes on Church Over Sex Abuse Allegations|url=https://www.youtube.com/embed/OPcYn4AiwQE?rel=0&autoplay=1|format=VIDEO|publisher=[[ABC News]]|location=New York, NY|date=March 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-33201010|title=Jehovah's Witnesses to compensate woman over sex abuse|work=[[BBC News]]|location=London, UK|date=June 19, 2015}}</ref> and the Society has settled other child abuse lawsuits out of court, reportedly paying as much as $780,000 to one plaintiff without admitting wrongdoing.<ref name=\"NBC\" />\n\nIn 2017, the [[Charity Commission for England and Wales]] began an inquiry into Jehovah's Witnesses' handling of allegations of child sexual abuse in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"BBCBuchanan\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40719773 |title=Jehovah's Witnesses let sex offender interrogate victims|website=BBC News |date=July 26, 2017|author=Michael Buchanan |accessdate= November 20, 2017|quote=One particular concern is the Church's policy of dismissing an allegation if it fails its two-witness policy, which states two people need to have seen the abuse for the Church to proceed with a full investigation. There are also calls for the independent child abuse inquiry to examine the Church's policy.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/manchester-new-moston-congregation-of-jehovahs-witnesses-inquiry-report/manchester-new-moston-congregation-of-jehovahs-witnesses |title=Decision: Manchester New Moston Congregation of Jehovah's Witnesses|website=Charity Commission for England and Wales|date=July 26, 2017 |author= |accessdate= November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{details|Bibliography of Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n* {{cite book |first=Gary |last=Botting |authorlink=Gary Botting  |title=Fundamental Freedoms and Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=University of Calgary Press|year=1993  |isbn=978-1-895176-06-3}}\n* {{cite book  |first=Heather and Gary |last=Botting  |authorlink=Gary Botting  |title=The Orwellian World of Jehovah's Witnesses|url=https://archive.org/details/orwellianworldof0000bott |url-access=registration |publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1984  |isbn=978-0-8020-6545-2}}\n* {{cite book  |first=George D. |last=Chryssides  |authorlink=George Chryssides  |title=Historical Dictionary of Jehovah's Witnesses|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2008  |isbn=978-0-8108-6074-2}}\n* {{cite book|first=George D.|last=Chryssides|authorlink=George Chryssides|title=Jehovah's Witnesses: Continuity and Change|publisher=Routledge|year=2016|isbn=9781409456087}}\n* Crompton, Robert. ''Counting the Days to Armageddon''. James Clarke & Co, Cambridge, 1996. {{ISBN|0-227-67939-3}}\n** A detailed examination of the development of Jehovah's Witnesses' eschatology.\n* {{cite book  |last=Holden |first=Andrew  |title=Jehovah's Witnesses: Portrait of a Contemporary Religious Movement  |url=https://archive.org/details/jehovahswitnesse00andr |url-access=registration |publisher=Routledge  |year=2002  |isbn=978-0-415-26610-9}}\n** An academic study on the sociological aspects of Jehovah's Witnesses phenomenon.\n* Kaplan, William. ''State and Salvation'' Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1989. {{ISBN|0-8020-5842-6}}\n** Documents the Witnesses' fight for civil rights in Canada and the US amid political persecution during World War II.\n* {{cite book|last=Knox|first=Zoe|title=Jehovah's Witnesses and the Secular World: From the 1870s to the Present|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=London|year=2018|isbn=9781137396044}}\n* {{cite book |last=Penton|first=M. James  |authorlink=James Penton  |title=Apocalypse Delayed: The Story of Jehovah's Witnesses  |publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1997 |isbn=978-0-8020-7973-2}}\n** Penton, professor emeritus of history at University of Lethbridge and a former member of the group, examines the history of Jehovah's Witnesses, and their doctrines.\n* Rogerson, Alan. ''Millions Now Living Will Never Die''. London: Constable & Co, 1969. {{ISBN|978-0094559400}}\n** Detailed history of the Watch Tower movement, particularly its early years, a summary of Witness doctrines and the organizational and personal framework in which Witnesses conduct their lives\n* {{cite book|last=Schulz|first=B. W.|title=A Separate Identity: Organizational Identity Among Readers of Zion's Watch Tower: 1870-1887|publisher=Fluttering Wings Press|year=2014|isbn=978-1304969408}}\n** Detailed history of the Watch Tower movement's earliest years written to an academic standard. Based on fresh research into original documents of the era. This is volume one of a planned two volume work.\n* Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania. ''Jehovah's Witnesses\u2014Proclaimers of God's Kingdom'' (1993)\n** Official history of Jehovah's Witnesses.\n* Watch Tower Bible and Tract Society of Pennsylvania. ''Faith In Action'' (2-DVD series), (2010\u20132011)\n** Official history of Jehovah's Witnesses.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jehovah's Witnesses}}\n<!-- Please discuss any links you wish to add to this list on this article's talk page before adding them. To avoid spam, link creep, and keep the resources in this section of high quality, we want to discuss any external resource inclusion before it is added. Thank you! -->\n* {{Official website|https://www.jw.org/en/}}\n* [https://tv.jw.org/#en/ JW Broadcasting] \u2014 Official video streaming site\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/witnesses/ BBC - Religion: Jehovah's Witnesses]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-28166192/ Jehovah's Witnesses new method] - BBC News Magazine article\n\n{{Christianity footer}}\n{{New Religious Movements}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1870 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Jehovah's Witnesses| ]]\n[[Category:Apocalyptic groups]]\n[[Category:Bible Student movement]]\n[[Category:Christian groups with annihilationist beliefs]]\n[[Category:Christian new religious movements]]\n[[Category:Nontrinitarian denominations]]\n[[Category:Premillennialism]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1870]]\n[[Category:Restorationism (Christianity)]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:ee30:fae0:611e:8475:c8df:8a74", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jehovah%27s_Witnesses"}
{"title_page": "Nova Scotia killings", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n|      label1      = Portapique, Nova Scotia\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.4015|-63.6977}}\n|  label-pos1      = bottom\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = Portapique, NS\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n|      label2      = Enfield, Nova Scotia\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title2       = Enfield, NS\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass shooting]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[arson]], [[mass murder]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 19 (including the perpetrator)\n| injuries         = At least 2\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nOn April 18 and April 19, 2020, Gabriel Wortman shot and killed at least 18 people and set fire to at least five buildings in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]] before being killed by the police following a vehicle pursuit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19 &#124; CBC News}}</ref>\n\nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nAt 11:32 p.m. (UTC-3) on April 18,<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> police responded to multiple [[9-1-1|911]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\"/><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> They found several dead and injured inside and outside of a home, but no suspect.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The investigation overnight led police to multiple separate crime scenes that were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> By the morning of April 19, police announced that they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.{{cn}}\n\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. Two residents and a neighbour were later confirmed to be victims. Another victim was then allegedly shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road between Wentworth and Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Teacher, family of 3 and RCMP officer among victims of N.S. shooting rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nResidents were advised by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) to stay indoors, while a portion of Portapique was evacuated.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|publisher=MassLive|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was identified as the shooter at 8:54 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Between 10:04 and 11:24, he was seen in or near [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], and [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref> During this time, police warned that he was [[police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer]] and operating a replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline of what we know about Nova Scotia killing spree that left RCMP officer, 16 others dead|publisher=Global News|last=Shah|first=Maryam|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|last=Lopez-Martinez|first=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The public was urged to avoid these areas,<ref name=global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s>{{Cite news|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|last=Quon|first=Alexander|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and to call 9-1-1 immediately if they spotted the fake RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"ABC\" /> An hour later, officials said that Wortman had switched to a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[sports utility vehicle]] (SUV).<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAround this time, the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]] was named as the site of a \"serious criminal event.\"<ref name=\"CBC\" /> A resident of the community reported that they saw two burning vehicles along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2]], including at least one police car, and that they heard an exchange of gunfire between an RCMP officer and a man who ran toward them.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Officials later said this was where Wortman shot and killed RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, and that one of the burning cars was Wortman's replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNearly 12 hours after police first received the firearms complaint,<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|last=Collins|first=Sean|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was killed by police outside an [[Irving Oil]] gas station restaurant in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Investigation==\nNo motive has been established for the killings, and it is not considered by police to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nBy the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires. He said he expected the death toll to continue to rise as these crime scenes were investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\n[[Nova Scotia]]'s [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would be conducting an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, and a second police use-of-force incident.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CBC6\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/sirt-investigate-discharge-firearm-rcmp-officers|title=SIRT TO INVESTIGATE DISCHARGE OF FIREARM BY RCMP OFFICERS|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were raised about why Nova Scotia didn't use its emergency alert system to warn the public about the killings. The RCMP used Twitter to provide updates, but the areas affected had poor Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not use social media. Usage of Nova Scotia's emergency alert system would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors. Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process to alert the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|publisher=CBC News|last=Gorman|first=Michael|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nAt least 17 people were killed (excluding Wortman), one of them RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, a 23-year veteran. A second RCMP officer was injured and is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of the first victims had connections to Wortman, but as the killings continued, the targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The victims, who included an elementary school teacher and a nurse,<ref name=\"BBC\" /> are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" /> The RCMP expects to find more victims within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref name=\"CTV4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|first=Meredith|last=MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\nThe RCMP identified Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area, on April 19 after he was pronounced dead. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Residents described Wortman as a polite man who often spent his time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman was shown to have had a degree of obsession for policing, with a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called Wortman's home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with [[alcoholism]], and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/20/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Police Seek Motive for Canada Killing Spree by Amiable Denture Fitter, as Dumbstruck Families Mourn|first=Iliana|last=Magra|date=April 20, 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Flags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|publisher=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing| website=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=http://archive.is/7qFSQ| archive-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]]\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of killings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n|      label1      = Portapique, Nova Scotia\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.4015|-63.6977}}\n|  label-pos1      = bottom\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = Portapique, NS\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n|      label2      = Enfield, Nova Scotia\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title2       = Enfield, NS\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree killer|Spree shooting]], [[mass shooting]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[arson]], [[mass murder]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 19 (including the perpetrator)\n| injuries         = At least 2\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nOn April 18 and April 19, 2020, Gabriel Wortman shot and killed at least 18 people and set fire to at least five buildings in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]] before being killed by the police following a vehicle pursuit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19 &#124; CBC News}}</ref>\n\nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nAt 11:32 p.m. (UTC-3) on April 18,<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> police responded to multiple [[9-1-1|911]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\"/><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> They found several dead and injured inside and outside of a home, but no suspect.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The investigation overnight led police to multiple separate crime scenes that were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> By the morning of April 19, police announced that they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.{{cn}}\n\nThen, at around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. Two residents and a neighbour were later confirmed to be victims. Another victim was then allegedly shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road between Wentworth and Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Teacher, family of 3 and RCMP officer among victims of N.S. shooting rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nResidents were advised by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) to stay indoors, while a portion of Portapique was evacuated.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|publisher=MassLive|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was identified as the shooter at 8:54 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Between 10:04 and 11:24, he was sighted in or near [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], and [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref> During this time, police warned that he was [[police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer]] and operating a replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline of what we know about Nova Scotia killing spree that left RCMP officer, 16 others dead|publisher=Global News|last=Shah|first=Maryam|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|last=Lopez-Martinez|first=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The public was urged to avoid these areas,<ref name=global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s>{{Cite news|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|last=Quon|first=Alexander|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and to call 9-1-1 immediately if they spotted the fake RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"ABC\" /> An hour later, officials said that Wortman had switched to a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[sports utility vehicle]] (SUV).<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAround this time, the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]] was named as the site of a \"serious criminal event.\"<ref name=\"CBC\" /> A resident of the community reported that they saw two burning vehicles along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2]], including at least one police car, and that they heard an exchange of gunfire between an RCMP officer and a man who ran toward them.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Officials later said this was where Wortman shot and killed RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, and that one of the burning cars was Wortman's replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNearly 12 hours after police first received the firearms complaint,<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|last=Collins|first=Sean|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was killed by police outside a gas station restaurant at the [[Irving Oil]] Big Stop in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Investigation==\nNo motive has been established for the killings, and it is not considered by police to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nBy the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires. He said he expected the death toll to continue to rise as these crime scenes were investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\n[[Nova Scotia]]'s [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would be conducting an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, and a second police use-of-force incident.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CBC6\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/sirt-investigate-discharge-firearm-rcmp-officers|title=SIRT TO INVESTIGATE DISCHARGE OF FIREARM BY RCMP OFFICERS|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were raised about why Nova Scotia didn't use its emergency alert system to warn the public about the killings. The RCMP used Twitter to provide updates, but the areas affected had poor Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not use social media. Usage of Nova Scotia's emergency alert system would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors. Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process to alert the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|publisher=CBC News|last=Gorman|first=Michael|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\nAt least 17 people were killed (excluding Wortman), one of them RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, a 23-year veteran. A second RCMP officer was injured and is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of the first victims had connections to Wortman, but as the killings continued, the targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The victims, who included an elementary school teacher and a nurse,<ref name=\"BBC\" /> are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" /> The RCMP expects to find more victims within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref name=\"CTV4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|first=Meredith|last=MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\nThe RCMP identified Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area, on April 19 after he was pronounced dead. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Residents described Wortman as a polite man who often spent his time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman was shown to have had a degree of obsession for policing, with a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called Wortman's home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with [[alcoholism]], and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/20/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Police Seek Motive for Canada Killing Spree by Amiable Denture Fitter, as Dumbstruck Families Mourn|first=Iliana|last=Magra|date=April 20, 2020|work=The New York Times|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening gun control.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> Flags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|publisher=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing| website=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=http://archive.is/7qFSQ| archive-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]]\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Ben MacLeod", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTimeline:copyedit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_killings"}
{"title_page": "History of Penang", "text_new": "{{about|the history of the State of Penang|the detailed history of its capital city|History of George Town, Penang}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Gurney Drive, George Town in 2018.jpg|thumb|[[George Town, Penang|George Town]], the capital city of the [[Penang|State of Penang]], at dusk]]\nThe [[Penang|State of Penang]], one of the most developed and urbanised [[States and federal territories of Malaysia|Malaysian states]], is located at the nation's northwest coast along the [[Strait of Malacca|Malacca Strait]]. Unlike most Malaysian states, the '''history of modern Penang''' was shaped by British colonialism, beginning with the acquisition of [[Penang Island]] from the [[Kedah Sultanate|Sultanate]] of [[Kedah]] by the [[East India Company|British East India Company]] in 1786.<ref name=\":30\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sabrizain.org/malaya/straits1.htm|title=The Founding of Penang|website=sabrizain.org|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.visitpenang.gov.my/portal3/about-penang/history.html|title=History of Penang|year=2008|website=Visit Penang|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> Developed into a free port, the city state was subsequently governed as part of the [[Straits Settlements]], together with [[Singapore]] and [[Malacca City|Malacca]]; the state capital, [[George Town, Penang|George Town]], briefly became the capital of this political entity between 1826 and 1832.<ref name=\"Jackson201322\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Rv7AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA7|title=Buildings of Empire|author=Ashley Jackson|date=November 2013|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-958938-8|pages=7\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"eresources.nlb.gov.sg\">{{Cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/e9600931-19db-4a18-8366-8ae5aea35464|title=Singapore becomes admin centre of the Straits Settlements - Singapore History|website=eresources.nlb.gov.sg|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> By the end of the 19th century, George Town prospered and became one of the major [[entrep\u00f4t]]s in [[Southeast Asia]].\n\nDuring [[World War II]], Penang was conquered and occupied by the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese Empire]] from 1941 to 1945. At the end of the war, Penang was also the first state in the [[Malay Peninsula]] to be liberated by the British, under [[Operation Jurist]]. The Straits Settlements was dissolved in the following year and Penang was merged into the [[Federation of Malaya]]. In spite of a secessionist movement within Penang, the merger with Malaya went ahead and the federation attained independence from the [[British Empire]] in 1957.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=2370&name=penang_the_rebel_state_part_one|title=Penang: The Rebel State (Part One)|last=Koay|first=Su Lin|date=September 2016|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=1287&name=penang_the_rebel_state_part_two|title=Penang: The Rebel State (Part Two)|last=Koay|first=Su Lin|date=October 2016|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=A Modern History of Southeast Asia: Decolonization, Nationalism and Separatism|last=Christie|first=Clive|publisher=I.B.Tauris|year=1998|isbn=978-1-86064-354-5|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19481231.2.64.aspx|title=Newspaper Article - \"Gallup Poll\" On Penang Secession|website=eresources.nlb.gov.sg|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> Malaya later evolved into the present-day [[Malaysia]] in 1963.\n\nFollowing the revocation of George Town's free port status in the 1960s, the state suffered economic decline and massive unemployment.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":37\">{{Cite journal|last=Daniel Goh|first=P. S.|year=2014|title=Between History and Heritage: Post-Colonialism, Globalisation, and the Remaking of Malacca, Penang and Singapore|url=http://profile.nus.edu.sg/fass/socgohd/trans_2.1.pdf|journal=Trans-Regional and -National Studies of Southeast Asia|volume=2}}</ref><ref name=\":132\">{{Cite book|title=Kuala Lumpur, Melaka and Penang|last=Brash|first=Celeste|publisher=Lonely Planet|year=2008|isbn=978-1-74104-485-0|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref> The [[Government of Penang|state government]] at the time led a push to reorient the economy towards hi-tech manufacturing, successfully recovering Penang's economy and lending the state its moniker the '''Silicon Valley of the East''<nowiki/>'.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|title=History of Industrial Development Strategies in Penang since Independence: A Study of the SMEs|journal=Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia|url=http://www.ccsenet.org/journal/index.php/ass/article/viewFile/27013/16497}}</ref> Growing recognition of George Town as a bustling tourist destination, particularly since the city's inscription as a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] in 2008, also boosted the state's services sector, and today, both the manufacturing and services sectors are the two strongest economic pillars of Penang.<ref name=\"UNESCO Heritage\">{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/450|title=Eight new sites, from the Straits of Malacca, to Papua New Guinea and San Marino, added to UNESCO's World Heritage List|date=7 July 2008|publisher=[[UNESCO]] ([[World Heritage Site]])|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906101950/https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/450/|archivedate=6 September 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=8 July 2008}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|title=Penang Economic Indicators|url=http://www.investpenang.gov.my/files/investment-updates/31/Penang%20Economic%20Indicator%20Q2%202015.1432708522.pdf|journal=Penang Monthly}}</ref><ref name=\":62\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.todayonline.com/world/asia/big-read-penang-takes-leaf-spore-and-bids-become-competitor|title=The Big Read: Penang takes a leaf from S'pore, and bids to become a competitor|work=TODAYonline|access-date=2017-03-06}}</ref> Moreover, the state enjoys one of the lowest unemployment rates and [[Gini coefficient]]s within Malaysia, as well as the second highest [[Gross domestic product|gross domestic product (GDP)]] per capita within the country after [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref name=\":36\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.malaysiakini.com/news/358071|title=CM: Penang's 1.5pct unemployment one of the lowest in country \u2013 Malaysiakini|website=[[Malaysiakini]]|access-date=16 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/398201|title=Penang's economy is healthy and strong|date=2017-10-13|work=[[Malaysiakini]]|access-date=2017-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dosm.gov.my/v1/index.php?r=column/cthemeByCat&cat=102&bul_id=VS9Gckp1UUpKQUFWS1JHUnJZS2xzdz09&menu_id=TE5CRUZCblh4ZTZMODZIbmk2aWRRQT09|title=Department of Statistics Malaysia Official Portal|website=dosm.gov.my|access-date=2017-11-23}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; margin:10px\"\n!style=\"background: FireBrick;\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">'''Historical affiliations'''</span>\n!style=\"background: FireBrick;\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">'''Period'''</span>\n|-\n|style=\"background:Cornsilk;\" | {{flagicon image|Flag of Kedah (18th century - 1912).svg}} '''[[Kedah Sultanate]]'''\n|style=\"background:Ivory;\" | 1136\u20131786\n|-\n|style=\"background:Cornsilk;\"| {{flagicon image|Flag of the British East India Company (1801).svg}} [[East India Company|'''British East India Company''']]\n|style=\"background:Ivory;\"| 1786\u20131867\n|-\n|style=\"background:Cornsilk;\"| {{flagicon|Straits Settlements}} '''[[Straits Settlements]]'''\n|style=\"background:Ivory;\"| 1826\u20131941; 1945\u20131946\n|-\n| style=\"background:Cornsilk;\" | {{flagicon|Empire of Japan}} '''[[Japanese occupation of Malaya|Empire of Japan]]'''\n| style=\"background:Ivory;\" |1941\u20131945\n|-\n| style=\"background:Cornsilk;\" |{{flagicon|Malayan Union}} '''[[Malayan Union]]'''\n| style=\"background:Ivory;\" | 1946\u20131948\n|-\n| style=\"background:Cornsilk;\" |{{flagicon|Malaya}} '''[[Federation of Malaya]]'''\n| style=\"background:Ivory;\" | 1948\u20131963\n|-\n| style=\"background:Cornsilk;\" | {{flagicon|Malaysia}} '''[[Malaysia]]'''\n| style=\"background:Ivory;\" | 1963\u2013Present\n|}\n{{Major urban areas in Penang}}\n\n== Ancient Penang ==\nEvidence of prehistoric human settlement in what is now Penang has been discovered in Guar Kepah within [[Seberang Perai]] (formerly ''Province Wellesley''), the mainland half of Penang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/04/26/penang-to-seek-unesco-heritage-status-for-guar-kepah-neolithic-site/|title=Penang to seek Unesco heritage status for Guar Kepah neolithic site \u2013 Nation {{!}} The Star Online|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.todayonline.com/world/asia/prehistoric-human-skeleton-found-penang-neolithic-site|title=Prehistoric human skeleton found at Penang neolithic site|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref> Human remains, dating back to about 5,000 to 6,000 years ago, have been found at the site south of the [[Muda River]], along with seashells, pottery and hunting tools. These indicate that Seberang Perai had been inhabited by nomadic [[Melanesians]] from as early as the [[Neolithic]] era.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Perspectives In Human Biology: Humans In The Australasian Region|last=Freedman Leonard|first=Rousham Emily|publisher=World Scientific|year=1996|isbn=9789814497862|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nSeberang Perai also became part of the [[Bujang Valley]] civilisation. The [[Cherok Tok Kun]] [[megalith]] in [[Bukit Mertajam]], discovered in 1845, contains [[Pali]] inscriptions, indicating that an early [[Hinduism|Hindu]]-[[Buddhism|Buddhist]] political entity in what is now [[Kedah]] had established control over parts of Seberang Perai sometime between the 5th and 6th centuries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2013/12/09/lembah-bujang-covers-a-larger-area-it-is-not-practical-to-gazette-the-entire-enclave-says-historian/|title=Lembah Bujang covers a larger area \u2013 Nation {{!}} The Star Online|last=Habibu|first=Sira|access-date=2017-05-01}}</ref> The entirety of what is now Penang would later form part of the [[Kedah|Sultanate of Kedah]] up until the late 18th century.\n[[File:Mao Kun map - Langkawi, Kedah, Penang.png|left|thumb|[[Penang Island]] (\u68b9\u6994\u5dbc) is indicated in the [[Mao Kun map]] from ''[[Wubei Zhi]],'' which is based on the Admiral [[Zheng He]]'s navigation maps.]]\nMeanwhile, [[Penang Island]] was first documented by Chinese sailors of the [[Ming dynasty]] in the 15th century. At the time, Ming Emperor [[Yongle Emperor|Yongle]] was in the midst of launching [[Treasure voyages|naval expeditions]] that would eventually reach all the way to eastern [[Africa]]. The island, known as ''B\u012bnl\u00e1ng Y\u00f9'' ({{zh|s=\u68b9\u6994\u5c7f|t=\u68b9\u6994\u5dbc}}), was mapped by Admiral [[Zheng He]]'s fleet in the '[[Mao Kun map|''Nautical Charts of Zheng He'']]'.\n\nOne of the first Englishmen to arrive on Penang Island was the privateer Sir James Lancaster who commanded the ''Edward Bonadventure''. He landed at [[Batu Ferringhi]] in June 1592 and remained on the island until September, pillaging every vessel he encountered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/328997/Sir-James-Lancaster|title=Sir James Lancaster (English merchant) \u2013 Britannica Online Encyclopedia|work=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nPenang Island was also indicated as ''Pulo Pinaom'' in Portuguese historian [[Emanuel Godinho de Eredia]]'s 1613 map of the [[Malay Peninsula]].<ref name=\"sabrizain.org2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sabrizain.org/malaya/straits4.htm|title=Betel Nut Island|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 18th century, ethnic [[Minangkabau people|Minangkabaus]] from [[Sumatra]], led by Haji Muhammad Salleh (also known as Nakhoda Intan), landed on Penang Island, establishing a seaside settlement at [[Batu Uban]] in 1734.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utusan.com.my/utusan/info.asp?y=2006&dt=1012&pub=Utusan_Malaysia&sec=Rencana&pg=re_06.htm|title=Sejarah dari sudut Timur|author=Dr. A. Murad Merican|date=12 October 2006|website=|publisher=Utusan Melayu (M) Bhd|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> They were followed by the [[Arabs]], who subsequently intermarried with the Minangkabau; this gave rise to the Arab-Minangkabau admixture now described as [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malay]], as they have assimilated into the local Malay community.\n\n== Founding of Penang ==\nThe history of modern Penang only began in earnest in the late 18th century. Up until then, the [[Kedah|Sultanate of Kedah]], which had control over Penang, had maintained turbulent diplomatic relations with [[Thonburi Kingdom|Siam]] to the north. In the 1770s, the [[East India Company|British East India Company]] instructed [[Francis Light]] to establish trade relations in the [[Malay Peninsula]].<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Light subsequently landed in Kedah, which at that point was threatened by both Siam and [[Konbaung dynasty|Burma]], as well as an internal [[Bugis]] rebellion.<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\"question2\">{{cite web|url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/g/genpub/APF3019.0001.001?rgn=main;view=fulltext|title=Map to illustrate the Siamese question|author1=Swettenham|author2=Frank Athelstane|year=1850\u20131946|work=W. & A.K. Johnston Limited|publisher=[[University of Michigan Library]]|accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref>[[File:Fort Cornwallis Penang Dec 2006 002.jpg|thumb|[[Fort Cornwallis]], in the heart of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]], was constructed at the spot where [[Francis Light]] first set foot on [[Penang Island]].]]\n[[File:Georgetown FrancisLight.JPG|left|thumb|A bronze statue of [[Francis Light]] still stands within [[Fort Cornwallis]] to this day.]]\n[[File:Allan Ramsay - King George III in coronation robes - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|George Town was named after [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George III]], who ruled the [[British Empire]] between 1760 and 1801.]]\n\nAware of this situation, Light formed friendly relations with the then Sultan of Kedah, [[Muhammad Jiwa Zainal Adilin II of Kedah|Sultan Muhammad Jiwa Zainal Adilin II]], and promised British military protection.<ref name=\":143\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Francis-Light|title=Francis Light {{!}} British military officer|work=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|access-date=2017-12-27}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Cities in Motion: Urban Life and Cosmopolitanism in Southeast Asia, 1920\u20131940|last=Lewis|first=Su Lin|publisher=[[Cambridge University]]|year=2016|isbn=9781107108332|location=[[United Kingdom]]|pages=}}</ref> As part of his promises, Light assisted in the quelling of the Bugis revolt by recapturing a Bugis-held fort for the Sultan.<ref name=\":30\" /> The Sultan reciprocated by offering [[Penang Island]] to Light.<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":242\">{{Cite news|url=https://arecabooks.com/product/penang-notebook-2/|title=Penang Notebook|date=2015-12-10|access-date=2017-12-27}}</ref> Light subsequently wrote to his superiors regarding the offer, arguing that Penang Island could serve as a \"''convenient magazine for trade''\" and its strategic location would allow the British to check Dutch and French territorial gains in [[Southeast Asia]]. He also made the case that, with the other ports in the region, such as [[Banda Aceh|Aceh]] and [[Phuket City|Phuket]], riddled with piracy and despotic governments, the British East India Company could seize the opportunity to establish a tranquil harbour on Penang Island conducive for free trade, noting that if \"''Malay, Bugis and Chinese will come to reside here, it will become the Exchange of the East if not loaded with impositions and restrictions''\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHowever, nothing transpired until 1786, when by that point the British were [[American Revolutionary War|fighting the Thirteen American Colonies]], which were backed by [[Kingdom of France|France]] and the [[Dutch Republic|Netherlands]].<ref name=\":30\" /> Faced with the Dutch dominance of the [[Dutch East Indies|East Indies]] (now [[Indonesia]]) and a growing French threat, Light, who by then had risen to the rank of Captain, was ordered to acquire Penang Island from Kedah.<ref name=\":143\" /><ref name=\":242\" /> The British East India Company sought control of Penang Island as a [[Royal Navy]] base, and a trading post between [[Qing dynasty|China]] and the [[Indian subcontinent]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nLight negotiated with the new Sultan of Kedah, [[Abdullah Mukarram Shah|Sultan Abdullah Mukarram Shah]], regarding the cession of Penang Island to the British East India Company in exchange for British military assistance and a lease of 6,000 [[Spanish dollar]]s to cancel Kedah's debts to Siam.<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":28\" /> With the agreement between Light and the Kedah Sultan successfully concluded, Light and his entourage sailed on to Penang Island, where they arrived on 17 July 1786.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penang.gov.my/dmedia/3035-fort-cornwallis-228th-anniversary-celebration|title=Portal Rasmi Kerajaan Negeri Pulau Pinang \u2013 Fort Cornwallis 228th Anniversary Celebration|last=Zabidi|first=Nor Diana|website=penang.gov.my|language=ms-my|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite book|title=Penang: An Inside Guide to Its Historic Homes, Buildings, Monuments and Parks.|last=Hockton|first=Keith|publisher=MPH Group Publishing|year=2012|isbn=9789674153038|location=Kuala Lumpur|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref> [[Fort Cornwallis]] would later be built at the spot where Light first set foot.\n\nThe area where Light first landed was originally a mangrove swamp covered in thick jungle.<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Once enough land was cleared, creating what is now the [[Esplanade, Penang|Esplanade]], a ceremony was held on 11 August, during which the [[Union Jack]] was raised for the first time. This signified the formal possession of Penang Island by the [[British East India Company]] in the name of [[King George III]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The A to Z of Malaysia|last=Ooi|first=Keat Gin|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2010|isbn=9780810876415|location=|pages=}}</ref> The island was renamed the '''''Prince of Wales Island''''' after the [[George IV of the United Kingdom|heir to the British throne]], while the new settlement of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] was established in honour of [[King George III]]. Thus, George Town became the first British settlement in Southeast Asia and a springboard for future British territorial expansion in the region, while its establishment by the British East India Company marked the start of a period of British imperialism in the Malay Peninsula.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:Penang.gif|left|thumb|British acquisition and expansion of [[Penang]] (in yellow) occurred between 1786 and 1874, when the final alterations to Penang's boundaries came into effect.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/maps_building_plans/record-details/f96da40d-115c-11e3-83d5-0050568939ad|title=Map of Prince of Wales Island, or Pulo Penang and Province \u2026|website=nas.gov.sg|access-date=2017-09-02}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/>]]Unbeknownst to the Kedah Sultan, however, Light had acted without the authority or consent of his superiors in [[British Raj|India]].<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":28\" /> When Light reneged on his promise of British military protection against Siam, the Kedah Sultan in 1791 assembled an army in what is now [[Seberang Perai]] to retake the ''Prince of Wales Island''. The Sultan's force was also assisted by a fleet of pirates.<ref name=\":30\" /> Fortunately for Light, his garrison on the island was reinforced by two companies from [[Kolkata|Calcutta]]. After failing to persuade the Sultan to disband his forces, the British East India Company launched amphibious assaults at night, destroying Kedah's military installations in [[Perai]], and defeating both the pirates and the Sultan's army.<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Ooi|first=Keat Gin|title=Disparate Identities: Penang from a Historical Perspective, 1780\u20131941|url=http://web.usm.my/km/33(Supp.2)2015/km33s22015_03.pdf|url-status=dead|journal=Universiti Sains Malaysia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207031500/http://web.usm.my/km/33%28Supp.2%292015/km33s22015_03.pdf|archivedate=7 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1800, the first [[List of governors of Penang|Lieutenant-Governor of the ''Prince of Wales Island'']], Sir [[George Alexander William Leith|George Leith]], gained a {{Convert|189.3|km2|abbr=on}} strip of Seberang Perai from the Kedah Sultan and renamed it '''''Province Wellesley'''''.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":33\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mpsp.gov.my/index.php/en/proposed-bicycle-lanes/general-info/history|title=History|website=mpsp.gov.my|access-date=2017-05-01}}</ref> The newly acquired land covered an area south of the [[Perai River]], turning the river into the international border between the British-controlled ''Province Wellesley'' and Kedah.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=http://butterworthguide.com.my/index.php/prai-discover-secrets-of-a-town-s-forgotten-heyday/51-a-brief-history-of-prai|title=P 01. A brief history of Prai|website=butterworthguide.com.my|access-date=2017-05-01}}</ref> At the time, ''Province Wellesley'' was heavily forested and sparsely populated, with a total population of only 5,000.<ref name=\":33\" /> In exchange to this acquisition, the annual payment to the Kedah Sultan was increased to 10,000 Spanish dollars per annum. To this day, the [[Government of Malaysia|Malaysian federal government]] still pays Kedah, on behalf of Penang, RM10,000 annually as a symbolic gesture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/sideviews/article/mindless-call-for-penangs-return-to-kedah-joshua-woo|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021020929/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/sideviews/article/mindless-call-for-penangs-return-to-kedah-joshua-woo|archivedate=21 October 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=2015-10-21|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/unconstitutional-to-wipe-penang-off-malaysias-map-kedah-told|title=Unconstitutional to wipe Penang off Malaysia's map, Kedah told|date=2017-02-11|access-date=2017-03-04}}</ref>\n[[File:Francis-light-grave.jpg|thumb|[[Francis Light]]'s grave in the [[Old Protestant Cemetery, George Town|Old Protestant Cemetery]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]].]]\nFollowing the original acquisition in 1800, ''Province Wellesley'' was gradually expanded up to its present-day boundaries in 1874, when the [[Pangkor Treaty of 1874|Pangkor Treaty]], which included the delineation of ''Province Wellesley''<nowiki/>'s southern borders, was signed between the British and the neighbouring [[Perak|Sultanate of Perak]]. Province Wellesley thus gained the town of [[Sungai Acheh (state constituency)|Sungai Acheh]] from Perak.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fas.nus.edu.sg/hist/eia/documents_archive/pangkor-treaty.php|title=Documents Archive {{!}} Empire in Asia|website=www.fas.nus.edu.sg|access-date=2017-05-01}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/maps_building_plans/record-details/fbc7d2ca-115c-11e3-83d5-0050568939ad|title=Plan Of Prince Of Wales Island And Province Wellesley|website=nas.gov.sg|access-date=2017-09-02}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/maps_building_plans/record-details/f97bad5c-115c-11e3-83d5-0050568939ad|title=Map Of Prince Of Wales Island And Province Wellesley, \u2026|website=nas.gov.sg|access-date=2017-09-02}}</ref>\n\nLight died from malaria in 1794 and was buried within the [[Old Protestant Cemetery, George Town|Old Protestant Cemetery]] in George Town. To this day, Light is honoured as the founding father of [[Penang]].\n\n== Early growth ==\n[[File:The Map of Early Penang Showing the Malay Town on the South of the Town Center by Popham 1799.jpg|thumb|left|A 1799 map of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]]][[File:Penang Museum historical painting M141b.jpg|thumb|An 1810 engraving depicting the eastern side of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]]]\n[[File:Penang Museum historical painting N171b.jpg|thumb|An 1811 painting of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]]][[File:Penang Museum historical painting N172b.jpg|thumb|1814 print of a view overlooking [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]|left]]\n[[File:Penang Museum historical painting K126b.jpg|thumb|An 1818 painting depicting [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] and ''[[Seberang Perai|Province Wellesley]]'' (in the horizon), as seen from a hilltop.]]\n[[File:St. George's Church Penang Dec 2006 005.jpg|thumb|[[St. George's Church, Penang|St. George's Church]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] is the oldest [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] church in [[Southeast Asia]].|left]]\n[[File:High Court, Penang (2008).jpg|thumb|The [[Penang High Court|High Court of Penang]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] was established in 1808, making it the birthplace of Malaysia's modern-day judiciary.]]\n[[Francis Light]] had established [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] as a free port, thus allowing merchants to trade without having to pay any form of tax or duties. In effect, this measure was intended to entice merchants from the Dutch ports in the region.<ref name=\"Jackson201322\"/> As a result, the number of incoming vessels increased exponentially from 85 in 1786 to 3,569 in 1802; George Town's population had also risen to 10,000 by 1792.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nordin|first=Hussin|title=Malaysian Journal of Society and Space|url=http://www.ukm.edu.my/geografia/images/upload/6.2007-NORDIN-(english)-1-baru1.pdf|journal=Charting the Early History of Penang Trading Networks and Its Connections with the New ASEAN Growth Triangle (Malaysia-Indonesia-Thailand)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nordin|first=Hussin|date=1 December 2005|title=Networks of Malay Merchants and the Rise of Penang as a Regional Trading Centre|url=http://ci.nii.ac.jp/naid/110004067699/en|journal=Southeast Asian Studies|volume=43|issue=3|pages=215\u2013237|issn=0563-8682}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://100pfs.blogspot.my/2015/08/early-penag-society-contd-pg-3.html|title=pg.3 \u2013 Chapter 1 \u2013 Early Penang Society (contd)|website=100pfs.blogspot.my|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> Immigrants came from various parts of [[Asia]]; in 1801, the then [[List of governors of Penang|Lieutenant-Governor of the ''Prince of Wales Island'']], Sir [[George Alexander William Leith|George Leith]], remarked that \"''there is not, probably, any part of the world where, in so small a space, so many different people are assembled together or so great a variety of languages spoken''\".<ref name=\":1\" /> A committee of assessors was also established for George Town in 1800, making it the first local government to be established within [[British Malaya]].<ref name=\":31\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=4390&name=a_history_of_local_elections_in_penangpart_i_democracy_comes_early|title=A history of local elections in Penang Part I: Democracy Comes Early|last=Koay Su Lin|first=Steven Sim|year=2014|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Prince of Wales Island'', together with ''Province Wellesley'', had been administered under the [[Bengal Presidency]] until 1805, when Penang was made a separate Presidency on par with [[Madras Presidency|Madras]], [[Bombay Presidency|Bombay]] and Bengal.<ref name=\":1\" /> By then, [[Penang]] also served as a penal station; in 1796, 700 Indian convicts were shipped in from the [[Andaman Islands]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asthabharati.org/Dia_Jan%2009/RVR.htm|title=Penal System in Andaman|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> The practice of employing Indian convicts continued throughout the 19th century as a means to provide the necessary labour for public infrastructure works, such as the construction of roads, drains and public buildings.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":332\">{{Cite book|title=Streets of George Town, Penang|last=Khoo|first=Su Nin|publisher=Areca Books|year=2007|isbn=978-983-9886-00-9|location=Penang|pages=|via=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/streetsofgeorget00khoo}}</ref>\n\nIn 1807, a [[Royal Charter]] to provide for the establishment of a Supreme Court and a police force in Penang was granted. The Supreme Court of Penang was first opened at [[Fort Cornwallis]] in George Town in 1808, with [[Edmond Stanley]] assuming office as its first ''Recorder'' (Judge).<ref name=\":111\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangbar.org/brief-history/|title=Brief History \u2013 Penang Bar Committee|website=penangbar.org|access-date=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":210\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kehakiman.gov.my/en/node/410|title=History of The Malaysian Judiciary {{!}} Chief Registrar's Office Federal Court of Malaysia Official Website|website=www.kehakiman.gov.my|access-date=17 November 2016}}</ref> In the decades that followed, Penang's judiciary and the police force were progressively applied to the [[Straits Settlements]], and later copied throughout British Malaya.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/data/archives/2013/07/04/16/24/keepers-of-the-peace/|title=Keepers of the peace|last=Bernard See|date=18 March 2007|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]}}</ref><ref name=\":110\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2005/05/17/brief-history-of-the-royal-malaysia-police/|title=Brief history of the Royal Malaysia Police|date=17 May 2005|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]}}</ref> Hence, Penang was the birthplace of the present-day [[Judiciary of Malaysia|Malaysian judiciary system]], as well as the [[Royal Malaysia Police|Royal Malaysian Police]].<ref name=\":111\" /><ref name=\":210\" /><ref name=\":03\" /><ref name=\":110\" />\n\nIn the early 19th century, Penang became a centre of spice production and trade within [[Southeast Asia]]. The cultivation of pepper began soon after the founding of George Town in 1786.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Hinterlands and Commodities: Place, Space, Time and the Political Economic Development of Asia over the Long Eighteenth Century|last=Souza|first=George Bryan|publisher=BRILL|year=2014|isbn=9789004283909|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref> The production of spices, including [[nutmeg]] and [[clove]], gradually grew more varied and the booming spice trade led to the opening of spice farms all over Penang. The export of spices through the [[Port of Penang]] also enabled the British East India Company to cover the administrative costs of Penang.<ref name=\":332\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=4394&name=when_penang_became_a_spice_island|title=When Penang Became A Spice Island|last=Ooi|first=Kee Beng|year=2014|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref> Furthermore, the agricultural plantations would fuel the growth of several villages, such as [[Air Itam]] and [[Balik Pulau]] on the island, and [[Bukit Mertajam]] in ''Province Wellesley''.<ref name=\":332\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.istaybalikpulau.com/index.php/balik-pulau/9-image/image2/13-2|title=History Of Balik Pulau|last=Administrator|website=istaybalikpulau.com|access-date=2016-10-20}}</ref> Malay refugees fleeing the Siamese invasion of [[Kedah]] and Chinese immigrants formed the bulk of workers in these agricultural estates. Other areas, such as [[Bayan Lepas]] on the island and [[Kepala Batas, Penang|Kepala Batas]] in ''Province Wellesley'', were founded as rice-producing estates.\n\n== Straits Settlements ==\n[[File:Penang_Museum_historical_painting_556.jpg|thumb|''Edinburgh House'', at the site of present [[Dewan Sri Pinang]], was occupied by the [[Alfred, Duke of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Duke of Edinburgh]] on his 1869 visit<ref>\nSalma Nasution Khoo, [https://books.google.com/books?id=giWb_8UjPU4C&pg=PA111 Streets of George Town, Penang]</ref>]]\n[[File:Flag of the British Straits Settlements (1904\u20131925).svg|left|thumb|Original flag of the [[Straits Settlements]], in use between 1874 and 1925]]\n[[File:Flag of the British Straits Settlements (1925\u20131946).svg|left|thumb|Flag of the [[Straits Settlements]] between 1925 and 1941]]\n[[File:Penang Harbour HMS Magpie 1884 Penang map.jpg|thumb|An 1884 map of the [[Penang Island|''Prince of Wales Island'']] and [[Seberang Perai|''Province Wellesley'']]]][[File:View of Penang from Tie Sin's Tower (7886247166).jpg|thumb|Panoramic image of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] in the late 19th century, with the city's [[Esplanade, Penang|Esplanade]] in the foreground.|left]]\n[[File:KITLV - 80020 - Kleingrothe, C.J. - Medan - Quay in Penang - circa 1910.tif|thumb|The [[Port of Penang]] at [[Weld Quay, George Town|Weld Quay]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] in 1910. Weld Quay was reclaimed from the sea in the 1880s.<ref name=\":16\" />]]\n[[File:Rapid Ferry (Pulau Undan).jpg|left|thumb|A [[Rapid Ferry]] in [[Butterworth, Penang|Butterworth]]'s [[Sultan Abdul Halim Ferry Terminal|Ferry Terminal]]. Rapid Ferry is a successor to the original cross-strait ferry service, which began in 1894.]][[File:Beach Street Penang Dec 2006 011.jpg|thumb|[[Standard Chartered]] and [[HSBC]] (left) at [[Beach Street, George Town|Beach Street]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]. To this day, Beach Street, where several international banks are based, still serves as the [[George Town CBD, Penang|city's main Central Business District]].]]\n[[File:Pinang Peranakan Mansion.JPG|left|thumb|The [[Pinang Peranakan Mansion]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] is an exquisite example of [[Peranakan]] architecture and interior design.]][[File:Jewish Cemetery Penang Dec 2006 018.jpg|left|thumb|The Jewish Cemetery in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]. Today, the [[History of the Jews in Malaysia|Jewish community in Penang]] no longer exists, with the passing of the last Jew in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2013/07/06/leaving-only-tombs-behind-the-jewish-community-in-penang-is-all-but-gone-with-the-death-of-its-last/|title=The Jewish community in Penang is all but gone leaving only tombs behind \u2013 Community {{!}} The Star Online|website=The Star|location=Malaysia|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref>]]In 1826, the [[East India Company|British East India Company]] amalgamated the territories of Penang, [[Singapore in the Straits Settlements|Singapore]] (acquired from [[Johor Sultanate|Johor]] in 1819) and [[Malacca City|Malacca]] (acquired from the [[Netherlands]] in 1824) into a single political entity, the [[Straits Settlements]]. George Town was made the administrative and judicial capital of the new entity. However, owing to Singapore's more strategic geographical location between the [[Strait of Malacca|Malacca Strait]] and the [[South China Sea]], the [[Port of Singapore]] rapidly surpassed the [[Port of Penang]] as the preeminent harbour in the region. Consequently, Singapore replaced George Town as the capital of the Straits Settlements in 1832.<ref name=\"eresources.nlb.gov.sg\"/>\n\nNonetheless, George Town continued to retain its importance as a vital British [[entrep\u00f4t]] by funneling the exports meant for global shipping lines which had bypassed other regional harbours.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=Turnbull|first=C. M.|title=The Penang Story|journal=Penang's Changing Role in the Straits Settlements, 1826\u20131946}}</ref><ref name=\":47\">{{Cite book|title=Penang and Its Region: The Story of an Asian Entrep\u00f4t|last=Khoo|first=Salma Nasution|publisher=National University of Singapore|year=2009|isbn=978-9971-69-423-4|location=Singapore|pages=|via=}}</ref> In the latter half of the 19th century, the tin mining boom within the neighbouring [[Perak|Sultanate of Perak]] and [[Rattanakosin Kingdom|Siam]] brought more prosperity to Penang. Tin produced from within the [[Kinta Valley]] and southern Siam were transported to George Town for smelting, before being exported via the Port of Penang to European and American industries.<ref name=\":15\" /> The Port of Penang subsequently became a major tin-exporting harbour within [[British Malaya]], directly challenging the Port of Singapore.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Penang Chinese Commerce in the 19th Century: The Rise and Fall of the Big Five|last=Wong|first=Yee Tuan|publisher=ISEAS-Yusof Ishak Institute|year=2015|isbn=978-981-4515-02-3|location=Singapore|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite book|title=George Town's Historic Commercial and Civic Precints|last=Langdon|first=Marcus|publisher=George Town World Heritage Incorporated|year=2014|isbn=|location=Penang|pages=|via=}}</ref> The opening of the [[Suez Canal]] in 1869 and the advent of steamships further cemented the Port of Penang's importance as a major entrep\u00f4t within British Malaya.<ref name=\":15\" /> By the end of the 19th century, George Town also evolved into a leading financial centre of British Malaya, as mercantile firms and international banks, including [[Standard Chartered]] and [[HSBC]], flocked into the city.<ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\":16\" />\n\nBy then, Penang became home to a myriad of ethnicities and religious affinities. Aside from the sizeable [[Penangite Chinese|Chinese]], [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malay]], [[Malaysians of Indian descent in Penang|Indian]], [[Peranakan]], [[Eurasian (mixed ancestry)|Eurasian]] and [[Thai people|Siamese]] communities, the colony's multi-ethnic and multi-religious society included significant minorities of [[Bamar people|Burmese]], [[British people|British]], Javanese, [[Japanese people|Japanese]], [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]], [[Jews|Jewish]], [[Germans|German]] and [[Armenians|Armenian]] origin.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\"penangstory.net.my\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.penangstory.net.my/mino-content-papermanecksha.html|title=An Indulgent Minority|date=2014-07-05|work=Penang Tourism|access-date=2017-09-15}}</ref>\n\nAt the time, each ethnic community had a tendency to specialise in specific trades and economic sectors.<ref name=\":3\" /> While the Europeans predominated in the various professional fields, as well as occupying managerial positions in mercantile and shipping firms, the Peranakans and the Eurasians tended to enter the nascent civil service as lawyers, engineers, architects and clerks. Some of the newer Chinese arrivals, labelled condescendingly by the Peranakans as '''Sinkheh''<nowiki/>' ([[Chinese language|Chinese]]: \u65b0\u5ba2; meaning new guests), were coolies and agricultural farmers, although many eventually entered into commercial, trading and real estate enterprises within the city; certain dialect communities, such as the [[Cantonese people|Cantonese]] and the [[Hakka people|Hakka]], predominated as artisans, blacksmiths, carpenters and cooks. The Indians, who were first brought in as convict workers for public works, also began competing with the Chinese in commercial, trading and shipping stevedore activities.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":332\" /> Ethnic Malays, meanwhile, were primarily engaged in agricultural occupations, including rice farming and fishing. Other ethnic communities, such as the Jews and the Armenians, were mainly engaged in mercantile and commercial ventures; the latter community was notable for the establishment of the [[Eastern & Oriental Hotel]], for instance.\n\nThe rapid population growth that resulted from the booming economy led to several social problems, chiefly the inadequate sanitation and public health facilities, as well as rampant crime. The latter was brought about by an influx of Chinese immigrants, which led to the formation of feuding triads and secret societies.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|title=Asian Studies|journal=Government Legislation for Chinese Secret Societies in the Straits Settlements in the Late 19th. Century}}</ref> Turf wars between the triads worsened, and when the Straits Settlements authorities attempted to put a stop to the triad activities in 1857, the Chinese triads came into conflict against the British-led police force as well. This culminated in the Penang Riots of 1867 in the streets of George Town, when the ''Kean Teik Tong'', led by [[Khoo Thean Teik]] and the Red Flag, clashed against the alliance of the ''[[Ghee Hin Kongsi]]'' and the White Flag.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2013/04/20/a-cowboy-town-that-was-old-penang_1/|title=A cowboy town that was old Penang \u2013 Community {{!}} The Star Online|website=The Star|location=Malaysia|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article28607543|title=THE DISTURBANCES AT PENANG. \u2013 The Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 \u2013 1954) \u2013 16 Sep 1867|website=Trove|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref> The resulting civil unrest lasted for 10 days, before the turf war was eventually quelled by the Straits Settlements authorities under newly appointed Lieutenant-Governor [[Edward Anson]], who were assisted by European residents and reinforcements from Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://friendsofhastingscemetery.org.uk/ansonae.html|title=Anson A E|website=friendsofhastingscemetery.org.uk|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wongchunwai.com/2013/06/caught-between-two-triads/|title=Caught between two triads {{!}} Wong Chun Wai|website=wongchunwai.com|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref>\n\nAlso in the same year, the Straits Settlements was made a [[Crown colony|British crown colony]], thereby placing the administration of Penang, Singapore and Malacca directly under the [[Colonial Office]] in [[London]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/57f1cda6-b5e7-4646-bd4f-14cb08181bfe|title=Formation of the Straits Settlements \u2013 Singapore History|website=eresources.nlb.gov.sg|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2014-07-30_084623.html|title=Straits Settlements {{!}} Infopedia|last=Singapore|first=National Library Board|website=eresources.nlb.gov.sg|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref> Direct [[British Empire|British]] rule meant better enforcement of the rule of law, as Penang's police force was vastly beefed up and the secret societies that had plagued George Town during the preceding decades were gradually outlawed.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nMeanwhile, in ''Province Wellesley'', new railway lines were being constructed, with the first railroad being the [[Bukit Mertajam]]-[[Perai]] line in 1899.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=2856&name=the_history_of_bukit_mertajam_part_i_from_agrarian_village_to_economic_hub|title=The history of Bukit Mertajam Part I \u2013 From agrarian village to economic hub|last=Nicholas Chan|date=June 2015|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref> The town of [[Butterworth, Penang|Butterworth]] was also established in the mid-19th century as the transportation hub within ''Province Wellesley''. In 1894, the first cross-strait ferry service between George Town and Butterworth commenced operations, and would eventually evolve into the present-day [[Rapid Ferry]].<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite book|title=Penang: 500 Early Postcards|last=Cheah|first=Jin Seng|publisher=Editions Didier Millet|year=2013|isbn=9789671061718|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nWith improved access to education and rising living standards, Penang soon enjoyed substantial press freedom and there was a greater degree of participation in municipal affairs by its Asian residents.<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":15\" /> Penang's representatives in the [[Legislative Council of the Straits Settlements|Straits Settlements Legislative Council]] gained a reputation for their assertive contestation of the policies made by the Singapore-based British authorities, which sometimes went against Penang's interests.\n\nOn top of that, George Town, perceived as being more intellectually receptive than Singapore, also served as a magnet for well known English authors, Asian intellectuals and reformists.<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://travel.cnn.com/explorations/escape/stories-behind-southeast-asias-top-heritage-hotels-735148/|title=Then and now: The stories behind Southeast Asia's heritage hotels {{!}} CNN|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref> For instance, the Chinese revolutionary leader, [[Sun Yat-sen]], chose to relocate his Southeast Asian base from Singapore to George Town, where he continued his efforts to reorganise and raise funds for the Chinese revolutionary movement against the [[Qing dynasty]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_845__2009-01-07.html|title=Sun Yat Sen {{!}} Infopedia|last=Singapore|first=National Library Board|website=eresources.nlb.gov.sg|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref> These efforts culminated in the famous [[1910 Penang conference]], which paved the way to the ultimately triumphant [[Wuchang uprising]] that overthrew the [[Manchu people|Manchu]] imperial government of China.<ref name=\":332\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2010/11/13/dr-sun-yat-sens-historic-penang-conference/|title=Dr Sun Yat Sen's historic Penang conference \u2013 Business News {{!}} The Star Online|last=Andrew Sheng|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref>\n\n== World wars ==\n\n=== World War I ===\n{{Main|Battle of Penang}}[[File:When the Emden Raided Penang, Map, fromThe New York Times, Dec.jpg|thumb|A 1914 map from the [[The New York Times|New York Times]] depicting the [[Battle of Penang]].]]\n[[File:GEORGETOWN PENANG ISLAND MALAYSIA JAN 2012 (6815563818).jpg|left|thumb|The [[Cenotaph, Penang|Cenotaph]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] was built in honour of fallen [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] servicemen of [[World War I]].]]\nOn 28 October 1914, the [[Battle of Penang]] occurred, during which an [[Imperial German Navy]] cruiser, ''[[SMS Emden]]'', covertly sailed into [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] and sank the [[Imperial Russian Navy]] cruiser, [[Russian cruiser Zhemchug|''Zhemchug'']]. The [[French Navy]] destroyer, [[French destroyer Mousquet|''Mousquet'']], set off in pursuit, before being sunk by ''SMS Emden'' as well off the northwestern tip of [[Penang Island]]. 147 [[French Navy|French]] and [[Imperial Russian Navy|Russian]] sailors perished, while the survivors were rescued by local Malay fishermen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rbth.com/arts/2015/05/20/battle_of_penang_when_malay_fishermen_rescued_russian_sailors_46165.html|title=Battle of Penang: When Malay fishermen rescued Russian sailors|author=Ajay Kamalakaran|date=20 May 2015|publisher=[[Russia Beyond the Headlines]]|accessdate=12 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAside from the naval battle, [[Penang]], as well as the [[Straits Settlements]], was largely unaffected by the events of [[World War I]].\n\n===World War II===\n{{See also|Operation Jurist}}[[File:Japanese submarine I-10 at Penang port in 1942.jpg|thumb|An [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] submarine at the [[Port of Penang]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] in 1942.]]\n[[File:Ten dollar note issued by the Japanese Government during the occupation of Malaya, North Borneo, Sarawak and Brunei (1942, obverse).jpg|left|thumb|The [[Japanese government-issued dollar in Malaya and Borneo|Japanese-issued 'banana' dollar]], so labelled due to the banana tree motif on notes such as this.]]\n[[World War II]], on the other hand, unleashed unprecedented social and political upheaval to Penang. The swift British retreat, coupled with the brutal massacres of [[Penangite Chinese|Penang's Chinese residents]], would severely dent British sense of prestige and dominance in the eyes of the locals.\n\nFrom 9 until 18 December 1941, Japanese warplanes indiscriminately strafed and bombed George Town, in the process eliminating the obsolete [[Royal Air Force]] and [[Royal Australian Air Force]] squadrons based in [[RMAF Butterworth|RAF Butterworth]] and the Bayan Lepas Aerodrome (now [[Penang International Airport]]).<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|title=Penang At War : A History of Penang During and Between the First and Second World Wars 1914\u20131945|last=Barber|first=Andrew|publisher=AB&B|year=2010|isbn=|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Warren2006\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zosKzAoocu8C&pg=PA109|title=Britain's Greatest Defeat: Singapore 1942|author=Alan Warren|publisher=A&C Black|year=2006|isbn=978-1-85285-597-0|pages=109\u2013}}</ref> It was estimated that 600 civilians were killed as a result of the Japanese bombardment, with an additional 1,100 wounded.\n\nNotwithstanding the fact that the [[British Army during the Second World War|British Army]] had earlier designated [[Penang Island]] as a fortress, Lieutenant-General [[Arthur Percival]] then ordered a withdrawal from Penang. Not only did the British Army abandon the [[Batu Maung]] Fort on the island, they also surreptitiously evacuated Penang's European population, leaving the colony's Asian populace to the mercy of the impending Japanese occupation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article75131511|title=Penang Evacuated \u2013 British Garrison Withdrawn NEW JAP THRUSTS IN MALAYA London, December 19 \u2013 Northern Times (Carnarvon, WA : 1905\u20131952) \u2013 20 Dec 1941|website=Trove|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> To this day, it has been agreed that the withdrawal and the covert evacuation of Europeans led to the loss of the British sense of invincibility, and that \"''the moral collapse of British rule in [[Southeast Asia]] came not in [[Singapore in the Straits Settlements|Singapore]], but in Penang''\".<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite book|title=Forgotten Armies: The Fall of British Asia, 1941\u20131945|last=Bayly|first=Christopher|publisher=Harvard University|year=2005|isbn=|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nPenang fell to the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] on 19 December 1941, marking the start of a period of [[Japanese occupation of Malaya|Japanese occupation]].<ref name=\":22\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ww2db.com/battle_spec.php?battle_id=47|title=Invasion of Malaya and Singapore|last=Chen|first=C. Peter|newspaper=WW2DB|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> Penang Island was renamed ''Tojo-to'', after the [[Prime Minister of Japan|Japanese Prime Minister]] at the time, [[Hideki Tojo]].<ref name=\":34\" /> George Town's harbour facilities were also put to use as a major [[Axis powers|Axis]] submarine base in Southeast Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uboat.net/ops/monsun3.htm|title=uboat.net \u2013 U-boat Operations- The Monsun U-boats \u2013 3. Monsun boats|website=uboat.net|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.navy.gov.au/history/feature-histories/german-u-boat-operations-australian-waters|title=German U-Boat Operations in Australian Waters|website=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2511249/Nazi-U-boat-sunk-Second-World-War-discovered-divers-Indonesia--complete-skeletons-doomed-crew.html|title=Nazi U-boat sunk during Second World War is discovered off Indonesia|newspaper=Daily Mail|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.icsm.it/regiamarina/orienteng.htm|title=Italian Royal Navy in World War Two: Italian surface units in Far East|last=Borsa|first=Arnaldo|website=icsm.it|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historynet.com/world-war-ii-yanagi-missions-japans-underwater-convoys.htm|title=World War II: Yanagi Missions \u2013 Japan's Underwater Convoys {{!}} HistoryNet|website=www.historynet.com|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Japanese enacted dissimilar policies with each ethnic community. Ethnic Chinese residents arguably suffered the most brutal treatment, as the Imperial Japanese Army massacred thousands of Chinese as part of the ''[[Sook Ching]]'' campaign to rid what was perceived as anti-Japanese elements in the society.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://anilnetto.com/society/malaysian-history/old-penang-the-sook-ching-massacres-of-world-war-ii/|title=Old Penang: The Sook Ching massacres of World War II |last=Netto|first=Anil|date=6 October 2013|newspaper=anilnetto.com|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> Penang's womenfolk were also coerced to work as [[comfort women]] by the Imperial Japanese Army.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.malaysiakini.com/news/4269|title=Researcher details shattered lives of local comfort women|date=2001-08-11|work=Malaysiakini|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205208397|title=THE ALLIED REOCCUPATION OF THE ANDAMAN ISLANDS, 1945|publisher=Imperial War Museum|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Japanese_surrender_Penang.jpg|left|thumb|Japanese officials signing the surrender of [[Penang]] documents on board [[HMS Nelson (28)|''HMS Nelson'']] on 2 September 1945.]]\n[[File:Royal_Marines_Parade_in_Penang_(5316034010).jpg|thumb|[[Royal Marines|British Royal Marines]] liberating George Town on 3 September 1945.]]\n[[File:Reoccupation of Penang (5315445771).jpg|thumb|Japanese [[Prisoner of war|prisoners of war]] being marched through the streets of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] by their British captors on 3 September 1945.]]Penang's residents also had to endure economic hardship during the Japanese occupation, with [[hyperinflation]] caused by the oversupply of the [[Japanese government-issued dollar in Malaya and Borneo|Japanese-issued 'banana' dollars]], and the acute shortage of food and raw materials, due to a combination of Japanese wartime rationing and an Allied blockade of Japanese shipping.<ref>[http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/syonantimes19420223-1.2.17.1 Currency replacement and price freeze], Syonan Shimbun, 23 February 1942, Page 3</ref><ref name=\"Huff\">''Financing Japan\u2019s World War II Occupation of Southeast Asia'', Gregg Huff and Shinobu Majima, Pembroke College \u2013 University of Oxford and Faculty of Economics \u2013 Gakushuin University, pp. 7\u201319</ref><ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/image/88380751/?terms=malaya Japan needs ships], ''The Decatur Daily Review'', Decatur, Illinois, Saturday, July 31, 1943 \u2013 p. 4</ref> Households were forced to turn to secondary crops such as sweet potatoes, yam and tapioca for their own subsistence. Beginning in 1942, a standardised Japanese curricula was enforced in all schools throughout Penang, with [[Japanese language|Japanese]] as the official language. In fact, social lifestyles were also greatly impacted, as it became compulsory to bow to Japanese soldiers on guard duty and to sing the [[Kimigayo|Japanese national anthem]], whilst whole streets and shops were renamed in Japanese.<ref>[http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/syonantimes19420309-1.2.11 Privilege To Bow To Sentry On Duty], Syonan Shimbun, 9 March 1942, Page 3. Retrieved 31 March 2017</ref>\n\nBetween 1944 and 1945, Royal Air Force and [[United States Army Air Forces|United States Army Air Force]] bomber squadrons based in [[British Raj|India]] repeatedly launched [[Bombing of South-East Asia (1944\u201345)|bombing raids on George Town]], seeking to destroy naval and administrative facilities.<ref name=\":22\" /> The destruction of the Penang Secretariat building by the Allied bombardment caused the loss of a large part of the British and Japanese records concerning Penang Island, complicating post-war efforts to compile a comprehensive history of Penang.<ref>{{Cite book|title=War and Occupation in Penang, 1941\u20131945|last=Kratoska|first=Paul|publisher=National University of Singapore|year=|isbn=|location=Singapore|pages=|via=}}</ref> The [[Penang Strait]] was also mined as part of efforts to constrict Japanese shipping.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bePxcx7BFLEC&pg=PA296|title=The Japanese Occupation of Malaya: A Social and Economic History|author=Paul H. Kratoska|publisher=C. Hurst & Co. Publishers|year=1998|isbn=978-1-85065-284-7|pages=296\u2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrender]] on 15 August 1945, the ''Penang Shimbun'', a Japanese newspaper, published the proclamation of surrender issued by the [[Emperor of Japan]]. Under [[Operation Jurist]], a [[Royal Navy|British Royal Navy]] fleet accepted the surrender of the Japanese garrison in Penang on 2 September 1945. A [[Royal Marines|British Royal Marines]] contingent recaptured Penang Island on the following day, making George Town the first city in [[British Malaya|Malaya]] to be liberated at the end of the war.\n\n==Post-war==\n[[File:Flag of Penang (1946-1949).svg|left|thumb|Flag of the [[Crown Colony of Penang]], which was in use between 1946 and 1949.]]\n[[Penang]] was placed under a [[British Military Administration (Malaya)|military administration]] until 1946, as the British sought to restore order in the face of an [[Malayan Emergency|emerging Communist insurgency]].<ref name=\":22\" /> The British also dissolved the [[Straits Settlements]] in April 1946, with Sir [[Shenton Thomas]] being its last [[List of governors of the Straits Settlements|Governor]]; [[Crown Colony of Penang|Penang]] and [[Crown Colony of Malacca|Malacca]] were then merged with the [[Federated Malay States]] and the [[Unfederated Malay States]] to form the [[Malayan Union]] (the new [[Colony of Singapore]], excluded from this union, was to remain firmly under British rule). The Malayan Union was replaced by the [[Federation of Malaya]] in 1948. As the gradual withdrawal of the Western colonial powers in [[Southeast Asia]] continued taking shape, the independence of Malaya as a united political entity seemed a foregone conclusion.\n\nHowever, the merger of the British crown colony of Penang into the vast Malay heartland alarmed some quarters of Penang's population. Questions were raised over economic and ethnic issues, such as the citizenship of non-Malays, greater trade regulations imposed on Penang by the central government in [[Kuala Lumpur]] and the introduction of export [[Duty (economics)|duties]] for trade with the rest of Malaya.<ref name=\":7\" /> Consequently, the Penang Secession Committee, formed in 1948, proposed to exclude Penang from the Federation of Malaya, which would allow Penang to either retain its links with the [[British Empire]] or form a political union with Singapore.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> The movement was led by D.A. Mackay, then the chairman of the Penang Chamber of Commerce, and included the Penang Muslim Chamber of Commerce, the Penang Chinese Chamber of Commerce, the Penang Straits Chinese Association, the Penang Eurasian Association and the Penang Indian Chamber of Commerce.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Journal of Southeast Asian Studies|journal=The Penang Secession Movement, 1948\u20131951}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Noordin Sopiee|first1=M.|year=1973|title=The Penang Secession Movement, 1948\u20131951|journal=Journal of Southeast Asian Studies|volume=4|issue=1|pages=52\u201371|doi=10.1017/S0022463400016416}}</ref>\n\nUltimately, the Penang Secession Committee failed to attain its goals and petered out. A secession motion tabled in the Penang Settlement Council in 1949 was narrowly dismissed by British official votes, while another petition sent to [[London]] in 1951 also met with British disapproval.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> While some British and American observers were sympathetic to the secessionists' cause, the British administrators were reluctant to jeopardise their own plans to gradually grant independence to a united Malayan polity. Moreover, the British government allayed the fears raised by the secessionists by guaranteeing [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]'s free port status and by reintroducing municipal elections for the city in 1951.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOn 1 January 1957, George Town, the capital of Penang, was granted city status by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] in 1957, becoming the first city within the Federation of Malaya, and by extension, [[Malaysia]]. George Town continued to be the only city within Malaysia (other than [[City of Singapore (historical entity)|Singapore]] between 1963 and its Separation in 1965) until 1972, when Kuala Lumpur was also conferred city status.\n\nPenang, as part of the Federation of Malaya, gained independence from the British Empire on 31 August 1957, and subsequently became a member state of Malaysia in 1963.\n\n==Post-independence==\n\n=== 1957 \u2013 1969 ===\n[[Penang]]'s political landscape immediately after the independence of [[Federation of Malaya|Malaya]] became relatively fractured. The new [[Government of Penang|Penang state government]] was dominated by the [[Alliance Party (Malaysia)|Alliance coalition]] (now succeeded by [[Barisan Nasional]]), the same ruling coalition that controlled the Malayan federal government. [[Wong Pow Nee]] of the [[Malaysian Chinese Association]] (MCA), one of the major component parties of the Alliance, became Penang's first [[List of Chief Ministers of Penang|Chief Minister]], a position that he held until 1969. On the other hand, the [[Labour Party of Malaya|Labour Party]], a left-wing opposition party, took control of the George Town City Council soon after the Malayan independence.<ref name=\":47\" /> Penang's voters tended to leave the control of the state government in the hands of the Alliance, while consistently electing the Labour Party to run the city council.\n\nAt the time, the George Town City Council was the only fully elected local authority in Malaya, as well as the country's richest, with an annual revenue that was double that of the Penang state government by 1965.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=2698&name=george_town_from_city_to_municipality_to_culture_centre|title=George Town \u2013 From city to municipality to culture centre|last=Ooi|first=Kee Beng|date=January 2015|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> This solidified the financial autonomy of the city council, with its revenue going into social welfare projects within [[George Town, Penang|George Town]].<ref name=\":47\" /><ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=4160&name=a_history_of_local_elections_in_penang_part_ii_a_legacy_to_protect|title=A history of local elections in Penang Part II: A legacy to protect|last=Steven Sim|first=Koay Su Lyn|date=December 2014|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> Meanwhile, the Penang state government attempted to boost the state's manufacturing sector by opening new industrial estates in [[Seberang Perai]], such as in [[Perai]] and [[Mak Mandin]].<ref name=\":47\" /><ref name=\":18\"/> Exacerbated by the opposing political affinities and ideologies, conflicts frequently arose between the state government and the city council over differences in policies and budget allocations.<ref name=\":47\" /><ref name=\":19\" /><ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=4287&name=when_labour_ruled_the_council|title=When Labour ruled the council|last=Su Lyn|first=Koay|date=April 2014|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\nAs previously guaranteed by the British authorities, George Town's free port status was untouched in the years immediately after the Malayan independence. The earlier fears by the secessionists eventually came true, however, when in 1969, the free port status was suddenly revoked by the [[Government of Malaysia|Malaysian federal government]].<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":132\"/> Consequently, 16.4% of Penang's working population became unemployed as the [[Port of Penang]]'s trade volume plummeted, adversely affecting George Town's services sector.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/11/25/the-man-behind-penangs-economic-transformation/|title=The man behind Penang's economic transformation|website=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref><ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=2568&name=where_the_sea_meets_the_city_is_where_the_world_meets_penang|title=Where the Sea Meets the City is Where the World Meets Penang|last=Evelyn Teh|date=July 2016|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> In the long run, this also marked the beginning of George Town's slow, decades-long decline, which was only recently reversed.<ref name=\":142\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/05/travel/05georgetown-nextstop.html|title=In Malaysia, Tourists Are Lured by George Town's Colorful Past|last=Eckhardt|first=Robyn|date=2 December 2010|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=16 October 2016|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe revocation of George Town's free port status, coupled with an unsuccessful, bloody strike by Penang's unions in 1967, led to a loss of popular support for the Alliance amongst Penangites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=4381&name=penangs_forgotten_protest_the_1967_hartal|title=Penang's forgotten protest: The 1967 Hartal|last=Koay|first=Su Lyn|date=August 2014|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> During the [[Malaysian state elections, 1969|1969 State Elections]], [[Parti Gerakan Rakyat Malaysia|Gerakan]], then an opposition party, was voted into power in Penang, replacing the Alliance. The party's founder, [[Lim Chong Eu]], succeeded Wong Pow Nee as the Chief Minister of Penang. However, the [[13 May Incident|violent race riots in Kuala Lumpur]] following the concurrent [[Malaysian general election, 1969|Malaysian General Elections]] led to the nationwide imposition of martial law and the functions of the Penang state government were taken over by the National Operations Council until 1971.\n\n=== 1970 \u2013 1990 ===\n[[File:Penang Bridge main span taxi.jpg|left|thumb|Completed in 1985, the [[Penang Bridge]] was then the longest bridge in [[Southeast Asia]].]]\n[[File:Komtar, Georgetown, Penang, Malaysia.JPG|thumb|Constructed in 1974, the [[Komtar|Komtar Tower]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] is [[List of tallest buildings in Penang Island|Penang's tallest skyscraper]].]]\n[[File:Bayan Baru.jpg|thumb|The township of [[Bayan Baru]] was first developed by the Penang Development Corporation in the 1970s following the establishment of the adjacent [[Bayan Lepas Free Industrial Zone]].<ref name=\"Ooi 2010\">{{Cite book|title=Pilot Studies for a New Penang|last=Ooi|first=Kee Beng|publisher=[[Institute of Southeast Asian Studies]]|year=2010|isbn=9789814279697|location=[[Singapore]]|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Regional Growth and Sustainable Development in Asia|last=Peter Nijkamp|first=Amitrajeet A. Batabyal|publisher=Springer|year=2016|isbn=9783319275895|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":26\">{{Cite book|title=Globalization and New Intra-Urban Dynamics in Asian Cities|last=Sue-Ching Jou, Hsin-Huang Michael Hsiao|first=Natacha Aveline-Dubach|publisher=[[National Taiwan University]]|year=2014|isbn=9789863500216|location=[[Taipei]]|pages=}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Butterworth 1.jpg|left|thumb|The [[Port of Penang]] was relocated to [[Butterworth, Penang|Butterworth]] (pictured here) in 1974, significantly boosting the town's economy.<ref name=\":53\">{{Cite news|url=http://penangmonthly.com/the-mainland-awakens/|title=The Mainland Awakens|date=2016-09-01|newspaper=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-02-10}}</ref>]]\nIn 1973, [[Parti Gerakan Rakyat Malaysia|Gerakan]] joined [[Barisan Nasional]], thus returning the [[Government of Penang|Penang state government]] back into the hands of the ruling coalition.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=7680&name=tun_lim_chong_eu_the_past_is_not_pass|title=Tun Lim Chong Eu: The past is not pass\u00e9|last=Ooi|first=Kee Beng|date=December 2009|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\nTo revive [[Penang]]'s economy, [[Lim Chong Eu]] created the [[Bayan Lepas Free Industrial Zone]] and courted foreign [[multinational corporation]]s for investments.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":25\">{{Cite web|url=http://wongchunwai.com/2013/03/transformation-of-bayan-lepas-into-free-trade-area-does-not-diminish-its-attractions/|title=Transformation of Bayan Lepas into free trade area does not diminish its attractions {{!}} Wong Chun Wai|website=wongchunwai.com|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> Pioneer tax status was granted to multinational firms seeking to establish assembly plants within Bayan Lepas, which was formerly the rice bowl of Penang.<ref name=\":21\" /> Major electronic and engineering firms, including [[Motorola]], [[Bosch Rexroth|Bosch]], [[Hewlett-Packard]] and [[Hitachi]], flocked in, setting up assembly plants within the area. Complemented by cheap labour, the Bayan Lepas Free Industrial Zone, one of the major electronics manufacturing zones in [[Asia]], grew to become the ''Silicon Valley of the East'' and was instrumental in pulling Penang out from its economic slump, greatly propelling the state's economy as one of the main economic powerhouses within [[Malaysia]]''.''<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":25\" /> To this day, manufacturing remains one of Penang's two largest economic sectors, contributing as much as 47.4% of Penang's [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] {{As of|2015|lc=y}}.<ref name=\":12\"/>\n\nDuring Lim's tenure, several major infrastructure projects were completed. The [[Penang Bridge]], then the longest bridge in [[Southeast Asia]], was completed in 1985, thus providing for the first time a road link between [[Penang Island]] and the [[Malay Peninsula]]. More controversial was the {{Convert|250|metre|feet|abbr=on|adj=on}}-tall [[Komtar]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]], to this day the [[List of tallest buildings in Penang Island|tallest skyscraper in Penang]]. Launched in 1974 as part of his vision to reverse George Town's declining fortunes, Komtar was constructed in the expense of hundreds of shophouses, schools and temples, as well as whole streets, which were bulldozed for the project.<ref name=\":37\" /> However, instead of arresting George Town's decline, Komtar itself became a white elephant by the early 2000s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.failedarchitecture.com/komtar-malaysias-monument-to-failed-modernism/|title=Komtar: Malaysia's Monument to Failed Modernism \u2014 Failed Architecture|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/penangs-iconic-komtar-gets-rm50m-facelift|title=Penang's iconic Komtar gets RM50m facelift|date=29 October 2013|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2015/04/25/much-of-komtars-charm-is-gone-some-pioneer-traders-want-out-of-oncebustling-iconic-retail-centre/|title=Much of Komtar's charm is gone \u2013 Nation {{!}} The Star Online|last=Loh|first=Arnold|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, in 1974, the [[Port of Penang]] was relocated from George Town to the town of [[Butterworth, Penang|Butterworth]], directly across the [[Penang Strait]], to allow for the berthing of larger container and cargo vessels.<ref name=\":53\" /> By then, the maritime traffic through Penang had been greatly diminished since the revocation of George Town's free port status, with increasing volumes of maritime trade being directed towards [[Port Klang]] near [[Kuala Lumpur]] instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=7135&name=can_penang_port_be_saved?|title=Can Penang Port be saved?|last=Andrew Yong|date=September 2012|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jacobsen|first=Michael|date=November 2010|title=Interdependency versus Notions of Decoupling in a Globalising World: Assessing the Impact of Global Economics on Industrial Developments and Inter-Ethnic Relations in Penang, Malaysia|journal=Copenhagen Business School}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the 1970s and 80s, the [[Government of Malaysia|Malaysian federal government]] proceeded with the rapid development of Kuala Lumpur and nearby Port Klang, by controlling investments in communication, transport, education and health.<ref name=\":37\" /> Kuala Lumpur soon outstripped George Town as Malaysia's largest city and financial centre, while Port Klang quickly became the country's busiest seaport. Consequently, Penang began to suffer considerable brain drain as younger Penangites started emigrating for better employment opportunities.<ref name=\":23\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/the+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20091110-178889.html|title=Brain-drain debate after Penang loses $4b deal|website=news.asiaone.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019202527/http://news.asiaone.com/News/the+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20091110-178889.html|archivedate=19 October 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=15 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":112\">{{Cite journal|title=Higher Education in Regional and City Development : State of Penang, Malaysia|journal=OECD}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/opinions/79059|title=Watching Penang 'grow'|date=2008-03-03|work=Malaysiakini|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, the George Town City Council was merged with the Penang Island Rural District Council to form the Penang Island Municipal Council, while the five local authorities within [[Seberang Perai]], including the Butterworth and [[Bukit Mertajam]] town councils, were merged into the [[Seberang Perai Municipal Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesundaily.my/node/252772|title=The Penang Island City agenda|website=The Sun|location=Malaysia|access-date=2017-12-09}}</ref> By then, local elections, suspended since 1965, became a thing of the past, with the municipal councillors being appointed by the Penang state government ever since.<ref name=\":19\" /> The merger of the local governments on Penang Island also led to a decades-long dispute over George Town's city status.<ref name=\":192\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/where-is-george-town|title=Where is George Town?|date=4 April 2015|work=[[Malay Mail]]|access-date=2017-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=9315&name=remember_the_city_status_of_george_town|title=Remember the city status of George Town|last=Goh|first=Ban Lee|date=February 2010|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-12-09}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Malaysian state elections, 1990|1990 State Elections]], Lim Chong Eu as the incumbent lost the [[Padang Kota (state constituency)|Padang Kota]] constituency to [[Lim Kit Siang]] of the [[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|Democratic Action Party]] (DAP), forcing him into retirement. Although Barisan Nasional remained in power, Lim Chong Eu was succeeded by [[Koh Tsu Koon]] as the [[List of Chief Ministers of Penang|Chief Minister of Penang]].\n\n=== 1991 \u2013 2008 ===\n[[File:Tanjungtokongwave.png|left|thumb|[[Tanjung Tokong]] was among the worst hit areas during the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|Indian Ocean tsunami]] on 26 December 2004. Within Penang, 52 lives were lost.]]\n[[Koh Tsu Koon]]'s tenure as the [[List of Chief Ministers of Penang|Chief Minister of Penang]] was marked by inept development and urban planning policies, rampant pollution, and the deteriorating general state of affairs within [[Penang]]. Political tussles complicated development policies, while simmering discontent from Penang's vocal [[Non-governmental organization|non-governmental organisations]] (NGOs) and residents over the state's decline would eventually lead to an unprecedented political change within the state.<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":28\">{{Cite book|title=Contested Space: Cultural Heritage and Identity Reconstructions : Conservation Strategies Within a Developing Asian City|last=Jenkins|first=Gwynn|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|year=2008|isbn=9783825813666|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, plans for the development of [[Penang Hill]] were drawn up by the [[Government of Penang|Penang state government]], drawing considerable backlash from Penang's civil societies over the potential environmental degradation of the forested hill.<ref name=\":37\" /> The plan was eventually axed. Meanwhile, the Rent Control Act, which until then had protected the low-income residents within the [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] city centre from eviction by preventing any arbitrary hike in rents, was repealed by 2001.<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":27\">{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/se-asia/BF29Ae01.html|title=Asia Times: Wreckers ball rips heart out of city: Car Rentals at www.The-Car-Reservations-Desk.com|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> This consequently led to the further hollowing out of the city centre, as residents, and [[Small and medium-sized enterprises|smaller businesses]], were unable to cope with the rental hikes and moved out. Unscrupulous private developers began demolishing several pre-war heritage buildings within the city centre for redevelopment, while other historic buildings fell under disrepair. Concerned over the impending loss of George Town's heritage architecture, NGOs based within the city started to mobilise public support for the conservation of these historic buildings.\n\nBy the early 2000s, Penang's economic growth began to lose steam, with the city-state recording the lowest monthly household income growth rate amongst the [[States and federal territories of Malaysia|Malaysian states]].<ref name=\"Ooi 2010\"/> The decades of brain drain also took its toll. For instance, while [[Kuala Lumpur]] was granted several mega-projects, including the [[Petronas Towers]] and the [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]], Penang suffered a shortage of qualified engineers and architects as professionals continued gravitating towards the [[Greater Kuala Lumpur]] area.<ref name=\":26\" /><ref name=\":28\" /> Moreover, the lack of a coherent urban planning policy and poor traffic management meant that little was done to curb the worsening traffic congestion within Penang.<ref name=\":29\">{{Cite web|url=https://aliran.com/archives/monthly/2004b/11d.html|title=Tsunami impact in Penang, Malaysia: Our island, our world|website=aliran.com|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref> Even the state's reputation for cleanliness was not spared, as reports of coastal pollution and dirty streets within Penang made headline news.<ref name=\":29\" /> As early as 1996, the then [[Prime Minister of Malaysia|Malaysian Prime Mninister]], [[Mahathir Mohamad]], had even labelled Penang a \"''garbage state''\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ww1.utusan.com.my/utusan/info.asp?y=2001&dt=0107&pub=utusan_malaysia&sec=Muka_Hadapan&pg=fp_06.htm|title=Akta Warisan akan diperkenal|website=Utusan Online|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.buletinmutiara.com/garbage-dump-to-shining-city/|title=Garbage dump to shining city|last=Lilian Chan|date=22 January 2015|work=Buletin Mutiara|location=George Town}}</ref>\n\nWidespread dissatisfaction over Penang's decline and neglect sparked a media campaign to restore Penang to its former glory in 2004.<ref name=\":29\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2004/11/07/penang-losing-its-tourism-lustre/|title=Penang losing its tourism lustre|last=Ng|first=Su-Ann|date=7 November 2004|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2004/12/07/cm-work-hard--to-bring-lustre-back-to-penang/|title=CM: Work hard to bring lustre back to Penang|last=Habibu|first=Sira|date=7 December 2004|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/letters/32226|title=Penang \u2013 who should stop the rot?|date=16 December 2004|work=[[Malaysiakini]]|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wongchunwai.com/2004/12/act-fast-to-boost-islands-sagging-image/|title=Act fast to boost island's sagging image|last=Wong|first=Chun Wai|date=12 December 2004|website=Wong Chun Wai|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref> It has since been speculated that the public outcry over the neglect of the city once known as the '''Pearl of the Orient''<nowiki/>', combined with Penang's relatively lively political scene, contributed to the defeat of Barisan Nasional in the [[Penang state election, 2008|2008 State Election]] by the federal opposition pact, [[Pakatan Rakyat]].<ref name=\":47\" /><ref name=\":28\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=March 8: Eclipsing May 13|last=Saravanamuttu Jayaratnam, Lee Hock Guan|first=Ooi Kee Beng|publisher=[[Institute of Southeast Asian Studies]]|year=2008|isbn=9789812308962|location=[[Singapore]]|pages=}}</ref> The opposition coalition, led by the [[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|DAP]], subsequently took over the Penang state government, with [[Lim Guan Eng]] succeeding Koh as the Chief Minister of Penang.\n\nIn late 2004, Penang was hit by the massive [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|Indian Ocean tsunami]]. Out of the 68 deaths within [[Malaysia]], 52 were in Penang.<ref name=\":29\" /> Northern coastal areas, such as [[Batu Ferringhi]] and [[Gurney Drive, George Town|Gurney Drive]] in George Town, were among the worst hit places within the state. In the aftermath of the tsunami, a network of sirens has been installed throughout Penang as part of a national tsunami warning system designed to alert the public of such calamities in the future.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/how-ready-is-penang-for-another-tsunami-after-10-years#0L04xcV4t6wgKk3e.97|title=How ready is Penang for another tsunami after 10 years?|date=2014-12-26|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref>\n\n=== 2008 ===\n[[File:Old town of Georgetown..JPG|thumb|The historic city centre of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] has been gazetted as a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] since 2008.]]\n[[File:Cmglee Penang Second Bridge aerial.jpg|left|thumb|The [[Sultan Abdul Halim Muadzam Shah Bridge|Second Penang Bridge]], at {{Convert|24|km|mi|abbr=on}} long, is the longest bridge in [[Southeast Asia]].]]\n\n[[File:LinkBike, George Town, Penang.jpg|left|thumb|A [[LinkBike]] station in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]. This [[Bicycle-sharing system|public-bicycle sharing service]] is an initiative of the [[Government of Penang|Penang state government]] to alleviate traffic congestion in the city.]]\nThe swearing in of the new [[Government of Penang|Penang state government]], now led by [[Pakatan Rakyat]], in 2008, heralded various positive policy changes. During that year, the [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] city centre, along with [[Malacca City|Malacca]], was inscribed as a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]], as a result of years of conservation efforts led by the city's [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]]<nowiki/>s. The new state government subsequently spearheaded efforts to improve hygiene, cleanliness and [[Pedestrian zone|pedestrianisation]], as well as the use of public transportation and the promotion of the city's cultural diversity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/metro/community/2017/06/01/payment-card-launched-for-bike-sharing-system/|title=Payment card launched for bike sharing system|date=1 June 2017|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/metro/views/2016/05/10/stop-walkers-crossing-pedestrian-is-king-drive-needs-greater-awareness-to-make-island-more-pedestria/|title=Stop! Walkers crossing|date=10 May 2016|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/guan-eng-lifts-from-singapore-playbook-in-ambitious-bid-to-make-penang-worl#sF4IgJozHejwlMFI.97|title=Guan Eng lifts from Singapore playbook in ambitious bid to make Penang world class|last=Eileen Ng|date=14 May 2016|work=[[Malay Mail]]|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref> By 2010, George Town was ranked the most liveable city in [[Malaysia]] by [[ECA International]], coming in at eighth place within [[Asia]] as well.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/05/23/penangs-capital-is-eighth-most-liveable-city-in-asia-on-par-with-kl-and-bangkok/|title=Penang's capital is eighth most liveable city in Asia, on par with KL and Bangkok|date=23 May 2010|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]}}</ref> Moreover, in 2017, the city was also ranked the second cleanest within Malaysia, behind only [[Ipoh]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/08/14/ipoh-is-malaysias-cleanest-city/|title=Ipoh is Malaysia's cleanest city|date=14 August 2017|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the economic front, the present state government has emphasised efforts to attract [[foreign direct investment]]s and to push Penang up the economic value chain, as well as policies to root out corruption.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/special-report-penang-manufacturing-ready-industry-40|title=Special Report: Penang manufacturing ready for Industry 4.0?|last=Amarthalingam|first=Sangeetha|date=12 October 2017|work=[[The Edge (Malaysia)|The Edge]]|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|year=2011|title=Higher Education in Regional and City Development Higher Education in Regional and City Development: State of Penang, Malaysia 2011|journal=[[OECD]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://penanginstitute.org/v3/resources/articles/in-penang-monthly/333-a-post-industrial-future-for-penang|title=A post-industrial future for Penang?|last=[[Zairil Khir Johari]]|date=August 2012|publisher=Penang Institute|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://penanginstitute.org/v3/media-centre/penang-institute-in-the-news/215-guan-eng-open-tenders-key-to-penang-s-efficiency|title=Guan Eng: Open tenders key to Penang's efficiency|last=R B Bhattacharjee|date=12 December 2011|publisher=Penang Institute|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref> In 2010, Penang recorded the highest amount of capital investments within Malaysia, attracting RM12.2&nbsp;billion, or 26%, of the nation's total investments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?sec=nation&file=/2011/1/20/nation/7831229|title=Penang tops total capital investment list for 2010|work=The Star|date=20 January 2011|work=The Star|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110121034407/http://www.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2011%2F1%2F20%2Fnation%2F7831229&sec=nation|archivedate=21 January 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=27 January 2011}}</ref> Penang's stunning economic recovery, particularly since 2008, was described by [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] as Malaysia's \"''biggest economic success''\" despite the [[Government of Malaysia|Malaysian federal government]]'s focus on other states such as [[Johor]] and [[Sarawak]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://limguaneng.com/index.php/2012/02/22/1-6-million-penangites-deserve-full-credit-for-the-historic-feat-of-penang-being-no-1-in-malaysia-in-manufacturing-investment-for-the-2nd-consecutive-year-in-2011-enbmcn/|title=1.6 Million Penangites Deserve Full Credit for the Historic Feat of Penang Being No. 1 in Malaysia in Manufacturing Investment for the 2nd Consecutive Year in 2011|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> On top of that, the [[Penang State Executive Council|Penang state government]] was able to decrease Penang's public debt by 95%, from RM630&nbsp;million in 2008 to RM30&nbsp;million by late 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/you-too-can-be-like-penang-guan-eng-tells-malaysia/|title=You too can be like Penang, Guan Eng tells Malaysia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140820081529/https://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/you-too-can-be-like-penang-guan-eng-tells-malaysia/|archivedate=20 August 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=13 September 2014|df=dmy}}</ref> In addition, in 2016, George Town was rated as the most attractive destination for commercial property investment within Malaysia by [[Knight Frank]], surpassing even [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Malaysia Commercial Real Estate Investment Sentiment Survey 2016|url=http://content.knightfrank.com/research/795/documents/en/malaysia-sentiment-survey-2016-3567.pdf|journal=[[Knight Frank]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the Malaysian federal government elevated the Penang Island Municipal Council into the present-day [[Penang Island City Council]], thereby expanding the jurisdiction of George Town to encompass the entire Penang Island, as well as five of the surrounding islets.<ref name=\"island\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.buletinmutiara.com/download/2015/BuletinMutiaraMay12015-BM.pdf|title=George Town meliputi 'pulau', jelas Datuk Bandar|date=1 May 2015|work=Buletin Mutiara}}</ref> This also made George Town the only Malaysian city to have been conferred its city status twice.\n\nThe [[Sultan Abdul Halim Muadzam Shah Bridge|Second Penang Bridge]], currently the longest bridge in [[Southeast Asia]], was opened in 2013. Straddling a length of {{Convert|24|km|mi|abbr=on}}, it provides a second road link between Penang Island and [[Seberang Perai]], and has spurred the development of new industrial areas such as [[Batu Kawan]].{{wide image|Skyline of George Town, Penang.jpg|1000px|Skyline of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] as of 2017, as seen from [[Gurney Drive, George Town|Gurney Drive]].|align-cap=center}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of George Town, Penang|History of George Town]]\n*[[Straits Settlements]]\n*[[List of governors of Penang]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Citation  |last=Sandhu |first=Kernial Singh |title=Indians in Malaya-immigration and settlement |publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1969 |page=29}}\n*{{Citation  |last=Sinnappah |first=Anasanatnam |title=Indians in Malaysia and Singapore |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Kulala Lumpur|year=1979 |page=19}}\n*{{Citation  |last=Snider |first=Nancy |title=What Happened in Penang |journal=Asian Survey|volume=8 |issue=12 |year=1968 |pages=960\u2013975 |doi=10.1525/as.1968.8.12.01p0433y}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n\n{{Penang}}\n{{British overseas territories}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of Penang}}\n[[Category:History of Penang|* 1]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the history of the State of Penang|the detailed history of its capital city|History of George Town, Penang}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Gurney Drive, George Town in 2018.jpg|thumb|[[George Town, Penang|George Town]], the capital city of the [[Penang|State of Penang]], at dusk]]\nThe [[Penang|State of Penang]], one of the most developed and urbanised [[States and federal territories of Malaysia|Malaysian states]], is located at the nation's northwest coast along the [[Strait of Malacca|Malacca Strait]]. Unlike most Malaysian states, the '''history of modern Penang''' was shaped by British colonialism, beginning with the acquisition of [[Penang Island]] from the [[Kedah Sultanate|Sultanate]] of [[Kedah]] by the [[East India Company|British East India Company]] in 1786.<ref name=\":30\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sabrizain.org/malaya/straits1.htm|title=The Founding of Penang|website=www.sabrizain.org|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.visitpenang.gov.my/portal3/about-penang/history.html|title=History of Penang|last=|first=|date=2008|website=Visit Penang|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> Developed into a free port, the city state was subsequently governed as part of the [[Straits Settlements]], together with [[Singapore]] and [[Malacca City|Malacca]]; the state capital, [[George Town, Penang|George Town]], briefly became the capital of this political entity between 1826 and 1832.<ref name=\"Jackson201322\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Rv7AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA7|title=Buildings of Empire|author=Ashley Jackson|date=November 2013|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-958938-8|pages=7\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"eresources.nlb.gov.sg\">{{Cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/e9600931-19db-4a18-8366-8ae5aea35464|title=Singapore becomes admin centre of the Straits Settlements - Singapore History|website=eresources.nlb.gov.sg|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> By the end of the 19th century, George Town prospered and became one of the major [[entrep\u00f4t]]s in [[Southeast Asia]].\n\nDuring [[World War II]], Penang was conquered and occupied by the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese Empire]] from 1941 to 1945. At the end of the war, Penang was also the first state in the [[Malay Peninsula]] to be liberated by the British, under [[Operation Jurist]]. The Straits Settlements was dissolved in the following year and Penang was merged into the [[Federation of Malaya]]. In spite of a secessionist movement within Penang, the merger with Malaya went ahead and the federation attained independence from the [[British Empire]] in 1957.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=2370&name=penang_the_rebel_state_part_one|title=Penang: The Rebel State (Part One)|last=Koay|first=Su Lin|date=September 2016|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=1287&name=penang_the_rebel_state_part_two|title=Penang: The Rebel State (Part Two)|last=Koay|first=Su Lin|date=October 2016|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=A Modern History of Southeast Asia: Decolonization, Nationalism and Separatism|last=Christie|first=Clive|publisher=I.B.Tauris|year=1998|isbn=978-1-86064-354-5|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19481231.2.64.aspx|title=Newspaper Article - \"Gallup Poll\" On Penang Secession|website=eresources.nlb.gov.sg|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> Malaya later evolved into the present-day [[Malaysia]] in 1963.\n\nFollowing the revocation of George Town's free port status in the 1960s, the state suffered economic decline and massive unemployment.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":37\">{{Cite journal|last=Daniel Goh|first=P. S.|date=2014|title=Between History and Heritage: Post-Colonialism, Globalisation, and the Remaking of Malacca, Penang and Singapore|url=http://profile.nus.edu.sg/fass/socgohd/trans_2.1.pdf|journal=Trans-Regional and -National Studies of Southeast Asia|volume=2|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":132\">{{Cite book|title=Kuala Lumpur, Melaka and Penang|last=Brash|first=Celeste|publisher=Lonely Planet|year=2008|isbn=978-1-74104-485-0|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref> The [[Government of Penang|state government]] at the time led a push to reorient the economy towards hi-tech manufacturing, successfully recovering Penang's economy and lending the state its moniker the '''Silicon Valley of the East''<nowiki/>'.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|title=History of Industrial Development Strategies in Penang since Independence: A Study of the SMEs|journal=Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia|url=http://www.ccsenet.org/journal/index.php/ass/article/viewFile/27013/16497}}</ref> Growing recognition of George Town as a bustling tourist destination, particularly since the city's inscription as a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] in 2008, also boosted the state's services sector, and today, both the manufacturing and services sectors are the two strongest economic pillars of Penang.<ref name=\"UNESCO Heritage\">{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/450|title=Eight new sites, from the Straits of Malacca, to Papua New Guinea and San Marino, added to UNESCO's World Heritage List|date=7 July 2008|publisher=[[UNESCO]] ([[World Heritage Site]])|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906101950/https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/450/|archivedate=6 September 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=8 July 2008}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|title=Penang Economic Indicators|url=http://www.investpenang.gov.my/files/investment-updates/31/Penang%20Economic%20Indicator%20Q2%202015.1432708522.pdf|journal=Penang Monthly}}</ref><ref name=\":62\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.todayonline.com/world/asia/big-read-penang-takes-leaf-spore-and-bids-become-competitor|title=The Big Read: Penang takes a leaf from S'pore, and bids to become a competitor|work=TODAYonline|access-date=2017-03-06|language=en}}</ref> Moreover, the state enjoys one of the lowest unemployment rates and [[Gini coefficient]]s within Malaysia, as well as the second highest [[Gross domestic product|gross domestic product (GDP)]] per capita within the country after [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref name=\":36\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.malaysiakini.com/news/358071|title=CM: Penang's 1.5pct unemployment one of the lowest in country \u2013 Malaysiakini|website=[[Malaysiakini]]|access-date=16 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/398201|title=Penang's economy is healthy and strong|date=2017-10-13|work=[[Malaysiakini]]|access-date=2017-11-23|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dosm.gov.my/v1/index.php?r=column/cthemeByCat&cat=102&bul_id=VS9Gckp1UUpKQUFWS1JHUnJZS2xzdz09&menu_id=TE5CRUZCblh4ZTZMODZIbmk2aWRRQT09|title=Department of Statistics Malaysia Official Portal|website=www.dosm.gov.my|language=en|access-date=2017-11-23}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; margin:10px\"\n!style=\"background: FireBrick;\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">'''Historical affiliations'''</span>\n!style=\"background: FireBrick;\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">'''Period'''</span>\n|-\n|style=\"background:Cornsilk;\" | {{flagicon image|Flag of Kedah (18th century - 1912).svg}} '''[[Kedah Sultanate]]'''\n|style=\"background:Ivory;\" | 1136\u20131786\n|-\n|style=\"background:Cornsilk;\"| {{flagicon image|Flag of the British East India Company (1801).svg}} [[East India Company|'''British East India Company''']]\n|style=\"background:Ivory;\"| 1786\u20131867\n|-\n|style=\"background:Cornsilk;\"| {{flagicon|Straits Settlements}} '''[[Straits Settlements]]'''\n|style=\"background:Ivory;\"| 1826\u20131941; 1945\u20131946\n|-\n| style=\"background:Cornsilk;\" | {{flagicon|Empire of Japan}} '''[[Japanese occupation of Malaya|Empire of Japan]]'''\n| style=\"background:Ivory;\" |1941\u20131945\n|-\n| style=\"background:Cornsilk;\" |{{flagicon|Malayan Union}} '''[[Malayan Union]]'''\n| style=\"background:Ivory;\" | 1946\u20131948\n|-\n| style=\"background:Cornsilk;\" |{{flagicon|Malaya}} '''[[Federation of Malaya]]'''\n| style=\"background:Ivory;\" | 1948\u20131963\n|-\n| style=\"background:Cornsilk;\" | {{flagicon|Malaysia}} '''[[Malaysia]]'''\n| style=\"background:Ivory;\" | 1963\u2013Present\n|}\n{{Major urban areas in Penang}}\n\n== Ancient Penang ==\nEvidence of prehistoric human settlement in what is now Penang has been discovered in Guar Kepah within [[Seberang Perai]] (formerly ''Province Wellesley''), the mainland half of Penang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/04/26/penang-to-seek-unesco-heritage-status-for-guar-kepah-neolithic-site/|title=Penang to seek Unesco heritage status for Guar Kepah neolithic site \u2013 Nation {{!}} The Star Online|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.todayonline.com/world/asia/prehistoric-human-skeleton-found-penang-neolithic-site|title=Prehistoric human skeleton found at Penang neolithic site|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref> Human remains, dating back to about 5,000 to 6,000 years ago, have been found at the site south of the [[Muda River]], along with seashells, pottery and hunting tools. These indicate that Seberang Perai had been inhabited by nomadic [[Melanesians]] from as early as the [[Neolithic]] era.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Perspectives In Human Biology: Humans In The Australasian Region|last=Freedman Leonard|first=Rousham Emily|publisher=World Scientific|year=1996|isbn=9789814497862|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nSeberang Perai also became part of the [[Bujang Valley]] civilisation. The [[Cherok Tok Kun]] [[megalith]] in [[Bukit Mertajam]], discovered in 1845, contains [[Pali]] inscriptions, indicating that an early [[Hinduism|Hindu]]-[[Buddhism|Buddhist]] political entity in what is now [[Kedah]] had established control over parts of Seberang Perai sometime between the 5th and 6th centuries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2013/12/09/lembah-bujang-covers-a-larger-area-it-is-not-practical-to-gazette-the-entire-enclave-says-historian/|title=Lembah Bujang covers a larger area \u2013 Nation {{!}} The Star Online|last=Habibu|first=Sira|access-date=2017-05-01}}</ref> The entirety of what is now Penang would later form part of the [[Kedah|Sultanate of Kedah]] up until the late 18th century.\n[[File:Mao Kun map - Langkawi, Kedah, Penang.png|left|thumb|[[Penang Island]] (\u68b9\u6994\u5dbc) is indicated in the [[Mao Kun map]] from ''[[Wubei Zhi]],'' which is based on the Admiral [[Zheng He]]'s navigation maps.]]\nMeanwhile, [[Penang Island]] was first documented by Chinese sailors of the [[Ming dynasty]] in the 15th century. At the time, Ming Emperor [[Yongle Emperor|Yongle]] was in the midst of launching [[Treasure voyages|naval expeditions]] that would eventually reach all the way to eastern [[Africa]]. The island, known as ''B\u012bnl\u00e1ng Y\u00f9'' ({{zh|s=\u68b9\u6994\u5c7f|t=\u68b9\u6994\u5dbc}}), was mapped by Admiral [[Zheng He]]'s fleet in the '[[Mao Kun map|''Nautical Charts of Zheng He'']]'.\n\nOne of the first Englishmen to arrive on Penang Island was the privateer Sir James Lancaster who commanded the ''Edward Bonadventure''. He landed at [[Batu Ferringhi]] in June 1592 and remained on the island until September, pillaging every vessel he encountered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/328997/Sir-James-Lancaster|title=Sir James Lancaster (English merchant) \u2013 Britannica Online Encyclopedia|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nPenang Island was also indicated as ''Pulo Pinaom'' in Portuguese historian [[Emanuel Godinho de Eredia]]'s 1613 map of the [[Malay Peninsula]].<ref name=\"sabrizain.org2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sabrizain.org/malaya/straits4.htm|title=Betel Nut Island|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 18th century, ethnic [[Minangkabau people|Minangkabaus]] from [[Sumatra]], led by Haji Muhammad Salleh (also known as Nakhoda Intan), landed on Penang Island, establishing a seaside settlement at [[Batu Uban]] in 1734.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utusan.com.my/utusan/info.asp?y=2006&dt=1012&pub=Utusan_Malaysia&sec=Rencana&pg=re_06.htm|title=Sejarah dari sudut Timur|author=Dr. A. Murad Merican|date=12 October 2006|website=|publisher=Utusan Melayu (M) Bhd|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> They were followed by the [[Arabs]], who subsequently intermarried with the Minangkabau; this gave rise to the Arab-Minangkabau admixture now described as [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malay]], as they have assimilated into the local Malay community.\n\n== Founding of Penang ==\nThe history of modern Penang only began in earnest in the late 18th century. Up until then, the [[Kedah|Sultanate of Kedah]], which had control over Penang, had maintained turbulent diplomatic relations with [[Thonburi Kingdom|Siam]] to the north. In the 1770s, the [[East India Company|British East India Company]] instructed [[Francis Light]] to establish trade relations in the [[Malay Peninsula]].<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Light subsequently landed in Kedah, which at that point was threatened by both Siam and [[Konbaung dynasty|Burma]], as well as an internal [[Bugis]] rebellion.<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\"question2\">{{cite web|url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/g/genpub/APF3019.0001.001?rgn=main;view=fulltext|title=Map to illustrate the Siamese question|author1=Swettenham|author2=Frank Athelstane|year=1850\u20131946|work=W. & A.K. Johnston Limited|publisher=[[University of Michigan Library]]|accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref>[[File:Fort Cornwallis Penang Dec 2006 002.jpg|thumb|[[Fort Cornwallis]], in the heart of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]], was constructed at the spot where [[Francis Light]] first set foot on [[Penang Island]].]]\n[[File:Georgetown FrancisLight.JPG|left|thumb|A bronze statue of [[Francis Light]] still stands within [[Fort Cornwallis]] to this day.]]\n[[File:Allan Ramsay - King George III in coronation robes - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|George Town was named after [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George III]], who ruled the [[British Empire]] between 1760 and 1801.]]\n\nAware of this situation, Light formed friendly relations with the then Sultan of Kedah, [[Muhammad Jiwa Zainal Adilin II of Kedah|Sultan Muhammad Jiwa Zainal Adilin II]], and promised British military protection.<ref name=\":143\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Francis-Light|title=Francis Light {{!}} British military officer|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-12-27|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Cities in Motion: Urban Life and Cosmopolitanism in Southeast Asia, 1920\u20131940|last=Lewis|first=Su Lin|publisher=[[Cambridge University]]|year=2016|isbn=9781107108332|location=[[United Kingdom]]|pages=}}</ref> As part of his promises, Light assisted in the quelling of the Bugis revolt by recapturing a Bugis-held fort for the Sultan.<ref name=\":30\" /> The Sultan reciprocated by offering [[Penang Island]] to Light.<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":242\">{{Cite news|url=https://arecabooks.com/product/penang-notebook-2/|title=Penang Notebook|date=2015-12-10|access-date=2017-12-27|language=en-US}}</ref> Light subsequently wrote to his superiors regarding the offer, arguing that Penang Island could serve as a \"''convenient magazine for trade''\" and its strategic location would allow the British to check Dutch and French territorial gains in [[Southeast Asia]]. He also made the case that, with the other ports in the region, such as [[Banda Aceh|Aceh]] and [[Phuket City|Phuket]], riddled with piracy and despotic governments, the British East India Company could seize the opportunity to establish a tranquil harbour on Penang Island conducive for free trade, noting that if \"''Malay, Bugis and Chinese will come to reside here, it will become the Exchange of the East if not loaded with impositions and restrictions''\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHowever, nothing transpired until 1786, when by that point the British were [[American Revolutionary War|fighting the Thirteen American Colonies]], which were backed by [[Kingdom of France|France]] and the [[Dutch Republic|Netherlands]].<ref name=\":30\" /> Faced with the Dutch dominance of the [[Dutch East Indies|East Indies]] (now [[Indonesia]]) and a growing French threat, Light, who by then had risen to the rank of Captain, was ordered to acquire Penang Island from Kedah.<ref name=\":143\" /><ref name=\":242\" /> The British East India Company sought control of Penang Island as a [[Royal Navy]] base, and a trading post between [[Qing dynasty|China]] and the [[Indian subcontinent]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nLight negotiated with the new Sultan of Kedah, [[Abdullah Mukarram Shah|Sultan Abdullah Mukarram Shah]], regarding the cession of Penang Island to the British East India Company in exchange for British military assistance and a lease of 6,000 [[Spanish dollar]]s to cancel Kedah's debts to Siam.<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":28\" /> With the agreement between Light and the Kedah Sultan successfully concluded, Light and his entourage sailed on to Penang Island, where they arrived on 17 July 1786.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penang.gov.my/dmedia/3035-fort-cornwallis-228th-anniversary-celebration|title=Portal Rasmi Kerajaan Negeri Pulau Pinang \u2013 Fort Cornwallis 228th Anniversary Celebration|last=Zabidi|first=Nor Diana|website=www.penang.gov.my|language=ms-my|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite book|title=Penang: An Inside Guide to Its Historic Homes, Buildings, Monuments and Parks.|last=Hockton|first=Keith|publisher=MPH Group Publishing|year=2012|isbn=9789674153038|location=Kuala Lumpur|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref> [[Fort Cornwallis]] would later be built at the spot where Light first set foot.\n\nThe area where Light first landed was originally a mangrove swamp covered in thick jungle.<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Once enough land was cleared, creating what is now the [[Esplanade, Penang|Esplanade]], a ceremony was held on 11 August, during which the [[Union Jack]] was raised for the first time. This signified the formal possession of Penang Island by the [[British East India Company]] in the name of [[King George III]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The A to Z of Malaysia|last=Ooi|first=Keat Gin|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2010|isbn=9780810876415|location=|pages=}}</ref> The island was renamed the '''''Prince of Wales Island''''' after the [[George IV of the United Kingdom|heir to the British throne]], while the new settlement of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] was established in honour of [[King George III]]. Thus, George Town became the first British settlement in Southeast Asia and a springboard for future British territorial expansion in the region, while its establishment by the British East India Company marked the start of a period of British imperialism in the Malay Peninsula.<ref name=\":1\" />\n[[File:Penang.gif|left|thumb|British acquisition and expansion of [[Penang]] (in yellow) occurred between 1786 and 1874, when the final alterations to Penang's boundaries came into effect.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/maps_building_plans/record-details/f96da40d-115c-11e3-83d5-0050568939ad|title=Map of Prince of Wales Island, or Pulo Penang and Province \u2026|website=www.nas.gov.sg|access-date=2017-09-02}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/>]]Unbeknownst to the Kedah Sultan, however, Light had acted without the authority or consent of his superiors in [[British Raj|India]].<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":28\" /> When Light reneged on his promise of British military protection against Siam, the Kedah Sultan in 1791 assembled an army in what is now [[Seberang Perai]] to retake the ''Prince of Wales Island''. The Sultan's force was also assisted by a fleet of pirates.<ref name=\":30\" /> Fortunately for Light, his garrison on the island was reinforced by two companies from [[Kolkata|Calcutta]]. After failing to persuade the Sultan to disband his forces, the British East India Company launched amphibious assaults at night, destroying Kedah's military installations in [[Perai]], and defeating both the pirates and the Sultan's army.<ref name=\":30\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Ooi|first=Keat Gin|title=Disparate Identities: Penang from a Historical Perspective, 1780\u20131941|url=http://web.usm.my/km/33(Supp.2)2015/km33s22015_03.pdf|url-status=dead|journal=Universiti Sains Malaysia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207031500/http://web.usm.my/km/33%28Supp.2%292015/km33s22015_03.pdf|archivedate=7 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1800, the first [[List of governors of Penang|Lieutenant-Governor of the ''Prince of Wales Island'']], Sir [[George Alexander William Leith|George Leith]], gained a {{Convert|189.3|km2|abbr=on}} strip of Seberang Perai from the Kedah Sultan and renamed it '''''Province Wellesley'''''.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":33\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mpsp.gov.my/index.php/en/proposed-bicycle-lanes/general-info/history|title=History|website=www.mpsp.gov.my|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-05-01}}</ref> The newly acquired land covered an area south of the [[Perai River]], turning the river into the international border between the British-controlled ''Province Wellesley'' and Kedah.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=http://butterworthguide.com.my/index.php/prai-discover-secrets-of-a-town-s-forgotten-heyday/51-a-brief-history-of-prai|title=P 01. A brief history of Prai|website=butterworthguide.com.my|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-05-01}}</ref> At the time, ''Province Wellesley'' was heavily forested and sparsely populated, with a total population of only 5,000.<ref name=\":33\" /> In exchange to this acquisition, the annual payment to the Kedah Sultan was increased to 10,000 Spanish dollars per annum. To this day, the [[Government of Malaysia|Malaysian federal government]] still pays Kedah, on behalf of Penang, RM10,000 annually as a symbolic gesture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/sideviews/article/mindless-call-for-penangs-return-to-kedah-joshua-woo|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021020929/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/sideviews/article/mindless-call-for-penangs-return-to-kedah-joshua-woo|archivedate=21 October 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=2015-10-21|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/unconstitutional-to-wipe-penang-off-malaysias-map-kedah-told|title=Unconstitutional to wipe Penang off Malaysia's map, Kedah told|date=2017-02-11|access-date=2017-03-04}}</ref>\n[[File:Francis-light-grave.jpg|thumb|[[Francis Light]]'s grave in the [[Old Protestant Cemetery, George Town|Old Protestant Cemetery]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]].]]\nFollowing the original acquisition in 1800, ''Province Wellesley'' was gradually expanded up to its present-day boundaries in 1874, when the [[Pangkor Treaty of 1874|Pangkor Treaty]], which included the delineation of ''Province Wellesley''<nowiki/>'s southern borders, was signed between the British and the neighbouring [[Perak|Sultanate of Perak]]. Province Wellesley thus gained the town of [[Sungai Acheh (state constituency)|Sungai Acheh]] from Perak.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fas.nus.edu.sg/hist/eia/documents_archive/pangkor-treaty.php|title=Documents Archive {{!}} Empire in Asia|website=www.fas.nus.edu.sg|language=en|access-date=2017-05-01}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/maps_building_plans/record-details/fbc7d2ca-115c-11e3-83d5-0050568939ad|title=Plan Of Prince Of Wales Island And Province Wellesley|website=www.nas.gov.sg|access-date=2017-09-02}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/maps_building_plans/record-details/f97bad5c-115c-11e3-83d5-0050568939ad|title=Map Of Prince Of Wales Island And Province Wellesley, \u2026|website=www.nas.gov.sg|access-date=2017-09-02}}</ref>\n\nLight died from malaria in 1794 and was buried within the [[Old Protestant Cemetery, George Town|Old Protestant Cemetery]] in George Town. To this day, Light is honoured as the founding father of [[Penang]].\n\n== Early growth ==\n[[File:The Map of Early Penang Showing the Malay Town on the South of the Town Center by Popham 1799.jpg|thumb|left|A 1799 map of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]]][[File:Penang Museum historical painting M141b.jpg|thumb|An 1810 engraving depicting the eastern side of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]]]\n[[File:Penang Museum historical painting N171b.jpg|thumb|An 1811 painting of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]]][[File:Penang Museum historical painting N172b.jpg|thumb|1814 print of a view overlooking [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]|left]]\n[[File:Penang Museum historical painting K126b.jpg|thumb|An 1818 painting depicting [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] and ''[[Seberang Perai|Province Wellesley]]'' (in the horizon), as seen from a hilltop.]]\n[[File:St. George's Church Penang Dec 2006 005.jpg|thumb|[[St. George's Church, Penang|St. George's Church]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] is the oldest [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] church in [[Southeast Asia]].|left]]\n[[File:High Court, Penang (2008).jpg|thumb|The [[Penang High Court|High Court of Penang]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] was established in 1808, making it the birthplace of Malaysia's modern-day judiciary.]]\n[[Francis Light]] had established [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] as a free port, thus allowing merchants to trade without having to pay any form of tax or duties. In effect, this measure was intended to entice merchants from the Dutch ports in the region.<ref name=\"Jackson201322\"/> As a result, the number of incoming vessels increased exponentially from 85 in 1786 to 3,569 in 1802; George Town's population had also risen to 10,000 by 1792.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nordin|first=Hussin|date=|title=Malaysian Journal of Society and Space|url=http://www.ukm.edu.my/geografia/images/upload/6.2007-NORDIN-(english)-1-baru1.pdf|journal=Charting the Early History of Penang Trading Networks and Its Connections with the New ASEAN Growth Triangle (Malaysia-Indonesia-Thailand)|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nordin|first=Hussin|date=1 December 2005|title=Networks of Malay Merchants and the Rise of Penang as a Regional Trading Centre|url=http://ci.nii.ac.jp/naid/110004067699/en|journal=Southeast Asian Studies|volume=43|issue=3|pages=215\u2013237|issn=0563-8682|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://100pfs.blogspot.my/2015/08/early-penag-society-contd-pg-3.html|title=pg.3 \u2013 Chapter 1 \u2013 Early Penang Society (contd)|website=100pfs.blogspot.my|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> Immigrants came from various parts of [[Asia]]; in 1801, the then [[List of governors of Penang|Lieutenant-Governor of the ''Prince of Wales Island'']], Sir [[George Alexander William Leith|George Leith]], remarked that \"''there is not, probably, any part of the world where, in so small a space, so many different people are assembled together or so great a variety of languages spoken''\".<ref name=\":1\" /> A committee of assessors was also established for George Town in 1800, making it the first local government to be established within [[British Malaya]].<ref name=\":31\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=4390&name=a_history_of_local_elections_in_penangpart_i_democracy_comes_early|title=A history of local elections in Penang Part I: Democracy Comes Early|last=Koay Su Lin|first=Steven Sim|date=2014|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Prince of Wales Island'', together with ''Province Wellesley'', had been administered under the [[Bengal Presidency]] until 1805, when Penang was made a separate Presidency on par with [[Madras Presidency|Madras]], [[Bombay Presidency|Bombay]] and Bengal.<ref name=\":1\" /> By then, [[Penang]] also served as a penal station; in 1796, 700 Indian convicts were shipped in from the [[Andaman Islands]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asthabharati.org/Dia_Jan%2009/RVR.htm|title=Penal System in Andaman|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> The practice of employing Indian convicts continued throughout the 19th century as a means to provide the necessary labour for public infrastructure works, such as the construction of roads, drains and public buildings.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":332\">{{Cite book|title=Streets of George Town, Penang|last=Khoo|first=Su Nin|publisher=Areca Books|year=2007|isbn=978-983-9886-00-9|location=Penang|pages=|via=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/streetsofgeorget00khoo}}</ref>\n\nIn 1807, a [[Royal Charter]] to provide for the establishment of a Supreme Court and a police force in Penang was granted. The Supreme Court of Penang was first opened at [[Fort Cornwallis]] in George Town in 1808, with [[Edmond Stanley]] assuming office as its first ''Recorder'' (Judge).<ref name=\":111\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangbar.org/brief-history/|title=Brief History \u2013 Penang Bar Committee|website=penangbar.org|access-date=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":210\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kehakiman.gov.my/en/node/410|title=History of The Malaysian Judiciary {{!}} Chief Registrar's Office Federal Court of Malaysia Official Website|website=www.kehakiman.gov.my|access-date=17 November 2016}}</ref> In the decades that followed, Penang's judiciary and the police force were progressively applied to the [[Straits Settlements]], and later copied throughout British Malaya.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/data/archives/2013/07/04/16/24/keepers-of-the-peace/|title=Keepers of the peace|last=Bernard See|first=|date=18 March 2007|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":110\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2005/05/17/brief-history-of-the-royal-malaysia-police/|title=Brief history of the Royal Malaysia Police|last=|first=|date=17 May 2005|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|access-date=}}</ref> Hence, Penang was the birthplace of the present-day [[Judiciary of Malaysia|Malaysian judiciary system]], as well as the [[Royal Malaysia Police|Royal Malaysian Police]].<ref name=\":111\" /><ref name=\":210\" /><ref name=\":03\" /><ref name=\":110\" />\n\nIn the early 19th century, Penang became a centre of spice production and trade within [[Southeast Asia]]. The cultivation of pepper began soon after the founding of George Town in 1786.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Hinterlands and Commodities: Place, Space, Time and the Political Economic Development of Asia over the Long Eighteenth Century|last=Souza|first=George Bryan|publisher=BRILL|year=2014|isbn=9789004283909|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref> The production of spices, including [[nutmeg]] and [[clove]], gradually grew more varied and the booming spice trade led to the opening of spice farms all over Penang. The export of spices through the [[Port of Penang]] also enabled the British East India Company to cover the administrative costs of Penang.<ref name=\":332\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=4394&name=when_penang_became_a_spice_island|title=When Penang Became A Spice Island|last=Ooi|first=Kee Beng|date=2014|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref> Furthermore, the agricultural plantations would fuel the growth of several villages, such as [[Air Itam]] and [[Balik Pulau]] on the island, and [[Bukit Mertajam]] in ''Province Wellesley''.<ref name=\":332\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.istaybalikpulau.com/index.php/balik-pulau/9-image/image2/13-2|title=History Of Balik Pulau|last=Administrator|website=www.istaybalikpulau.com|access-date=2016-10-20}}</ref> Malay refugees fleeing the Siamese invasion of [[Kedah]] and Chinese immigrants formed the bulk of workers in these agricultural estates. Other areas, such as [[Bayan Lepas]] on the island and [[Kepala Batas, Penang|Kepala Batas]] in ''Province Wellesley'', were founded as rice-producing estates.\n\n== Straits Settlements ==\n[[File:Penang_Museum_historical_painting_556.jpg|thumb|''Edinburgh House'', at the site of present [[Dewan Sri Pinang]], was occupied by the [[Alfred, Duke of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Duke of Edinburgh]] on his 1869 visit<ref>\nSalma Nasution Khoo, [https://books.google.com/books?id=giWb_8UjPU4C&pg=PA111 Streets of George Town, Penang]</ref>]]\n[[File:Flag of the British Straits Settlements (1904\u20131925).svg|left|thumb|Original flag of the [[Straits Settlements]], in use between 1874 and 1925]]\n[[File:Flag of the British Straits Settlements (1925\u20131946).svg|left|thumb|Flag of the [[Straits Settlements]] between 1925 and 1941]]\n[[File:Penang Harbour HMS Magpie 1884 Penang map.jpg|thumb|An 1884 map of the [[Penang Island|''Prince of Wales Island'']] and [[Seberang Perai|''Province Wellesley'']]]][[File:View of Penang from Tie Sin's Tower (7886247166).jpg|thumb|Panoramic image of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] in the late 19th century, with the city's [[Esplanade, Penang|Esplanade]] in the foreground.|left]]\n[[File:KITLV - 80020 - Kleingrothe, C.J. - Medan - Quay in Penang - circa 1910.tif|thumb|The [[Port of Penang]] at [[Weld Quay, George Town|Weld Quay]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] in 1910. Weld Quay was reclaimed from the sea in the 1880s.<ref name=\":16\" />]]\n[[File:Rapid Ferry (Pulau Undan).jpg|left|thumb|A [[Rapid Ferry]] in [[Butterworth, Penang|Butterworth]]'s [[Sultan Abdul Halim Ferry Terminal|Ferry Terminal]]. Rapid Ferry is a successor to the original cross-strait ferry service, which began in 1894.]][[File:Beach Street Penang Dec 2006 011.jpg|thumb|[[Standard Chartered]] and [[HSBC]] (left) at [[Beach Street, George Town|Beach Street]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]. To this day, Beach Street, where several international banks are based, still serves as the [[George Town CBD, Penang|city's main Central Business District]].]]\n[[File:Pinang Peranakan Mansion.JPG|left|thumb|The [[Pinang Peranakan Mansion]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] is an exquisite example of [[Peranakan]] architecture and interior design.]][[File:Jewish Cemetery Penang Dec 2006 018.jpg|left|thumb|The Jewish Cemetery in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]. Today, the [[History of the Jews in Malaysia|Jewish community in Penang]] no longer exists, with the passing of the last Jew in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2013/07/06/leaving-only-tombs-behind-the-jewish-community-in-penang-is-all-but-gone-with-the-death-of-its-last/|title=The Jewish community in Penang is all but gone leaving only tombs behind \u2013 Community {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref>]]In 1826, the [[East India Company|British East India Company]] amalgamated the territories of Penang, [[Singapore in the Straits Settlements|Singapore]] (acquired from [[Johor Sultanate|Johor]] in 1819) and [[Malacca City|Malacca]] (acquired from the [[Netherlands]] in 1824) into a single political entity, the [[Straits Settlements]]. George Town was made the administrative and judicial capital of the new entity. However, owing to Singapore's more strategic geographical location between the [[Strait of Malacca|Malacca Strait]] and the [[South China Sea]], the [[Port of Singapore]] rapidly surpassed the [[Port of Penang]] as the preeminent harbour in the region. Consequently, Singapore replaced George Town as the capital of the Straits Settlements in 1832.<ref name=\"eresources.nlb.gov.sg\"/>\n\nNonetheless, George Town continued to retain its importance as a vital British [[entrep\u00f4t]] by funneling the exports meant for global shipping lines which had bypassed other regional harbours.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=Turnbull|first=C. M.|date=|title=The Penang Story|url=|journal=Penang's Changing Role in the Straits Settlements, 1826\u20131946|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":47\">{{Cite book|title=Penang and Its Region: The Story of an Asian Entrep\u00f4t|last=Khoo|first=Salma Nasution|publisher=National University of Singapore|year=2009|isbn=978-9971-69-423-4|location=Singapore|pages=|via=}}</ref> In the latter half of the 19th century, the tin mining boom within the neighbouring [[Perak|Sultanate of Perak]] and [[Rattanakosin Kingdom|Siam]] brought more prosperity to Penang. Tin produced from within the [[Kinta Valley]] and southern Siam were transported to George Town for smelting, before being exported via the Port of Penang to European and American industries.<ref name=\":15\" /> The Port of Penang subsequently became a major tin-exporting harbour within [[British Malaya]], directly challenging the Port of Singapore.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Penang Chinese Commerce in the 19th Century: The Rise and Fall of the Big Five|last=Wong|first=Yee Tuan|publisher=ISEAS-Yusof Ishak Institute|year=2015|isbn=978-981-4515-02-3|location=Singapore|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite book|title=George Town's Historic Commercial and Civic Precints|last=Langdon|first=Marcus|publisher=George Town World Heritage Incorporated|year=2014|isbn=|location=Penang|pages=|via=}}</ref> The opening of the [[Suez Canal]] in 1869 and the advent of steamships further cemented the Port of Penang's importance as a major entrep\u00f4t within British Malaya.<ref name=\":15\" /> By the end of the 19th century, George Town also evolved into a leading financial centre of British Malaya, as mercantile firms and international banks, including [[Standard Chartered]] and [[HSBC]], flocked into the city.<ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\":16\" />\n\nBy then, Penang became home to a myriad of ethnicities and religious affinities. Aside from the sizeable [[Penangite Chinese|Chinese]], [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malay]], [[Malaysians of Indian descent in Penang|Indian]], [[Peranakan]], [[Eurasian (mixed ancestry)|Eurasian]] and [[Thai people|Siamese]] communities, the colony's multi-ethnic and multi-religious society included significant minorities of [[Bamar people|Burmese]], [[British people|British]], Javanese, [[Japanese people|Japanese]], [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]], [[Jews|Jewish]], [[Germans|German]] and [[Armenians|Armenian]] origin.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\"penangstory.net.my\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.penangstory.net.my/mino-content-papermanecksha.html|title=An Indulgent Minority|date=2014-07-05|work=Penang Tourism|access-date=2017-09-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAt the time, each ethnic community had a tendency to specialise in specific trades and economic sectors.<ref name=\":3\" /> While the Europeans predominated in the various professional fields, as well as occupying managerial positions in mercantile and shipping firms, the Peranakans and the Eurasians tended to enter the nascent civil service as lawyers, engineers, architects and clerks. Some of the newer Chinese arrivals, labelled condescendingly by the Peranakans as '''Sinkheh''<nowiki/>' ([[Chinese language|Chinese]]: \u65b0\u5ba2; meaning new guests), were coolies and agricultural farmers, although many eventually entered into commercial, trading and real estate enterprises within the city; certain dialect communities, such as the [[Cantonese people|Cantonese]] and the [[Hakka people|Hakka]], predominated as artisans, blacksmiths, carpenters and cooks. The Indians, who were first brought in as convict workers for public works, also began competing with the Chinese in commercial, trading and shipping stevedore activities.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":332\" /> Ethnic Malays, meanwhile, were primarily engaged in agricultural occupations, including rice farming and fishing. Other ethnic communities, such as the Jews and the Armenians, were mainly engaged in mercantile and commercial ventures; the latter community was notable for the establishment of the [[Eastern & Oriental Hotel]], for instance.\n\nThe rapid population growth that resulted from the booming economy led to several social problems, chiefly the inadequate sanitation and public health facilities, as well as rampant crime. The latter was brought about by an influx of Chinese immigrants, which led to the formation of feuding triads and secret societies.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|title=Asian Studies|journal=Government Legislation for Chinese Secret Societies in the Straits Settlements in the Late 19th. Century|volume=}}</ref> Turf wars between the triads worsened, and when the Straits Settlements authorities attempted to put a stop to the triad activities in 1857, the Chinese triads came into conflict against the British-led police force as well. This culminated in the Penang Riots of 1867 in the streets of George Town, when the ''Kean Teik Tong'', led by [[Khoo Thean Teik]] and the Red Flag, clashed against the alliance of the ''[[Ghee Hin Kongsi]]'' and the White Flag.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2013/04/20/a-cowboy-town-that-was-old-penang_1/|title=A cowboy town that was old Penang \u2013 Community {{!}} The Star Online|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article28607543|title=THE DISTURBANCES AT PENANG. \u2013 The Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 \u2013 1954) \u2013 16 Sep 1867|website=Trove|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref> The resulting civil unrest lasted for 10 days, before the turf war was eventually quelled by the Straits Settlements authorities under newly appointed Lieutenant-Governor [[Edward Anson]], who were assisted by European residents and reinforcements from Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://friendsofhastingscemetery.org.uk/ansonae.html|title=Anson A E|website=friendsofhastingscemetery.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wongchunwai.com/2013/06/caught-between-two-triads/|title=Caught between two triads {{!}} Wong Chun Wai|website=wongchunwai.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref>\n\nAlso in the same year, the Straits Settlements was made a [[Crown colony|British crown colony]], thereby placing the administration of Penang, Singapore and Malacca directly under the [[Colonial Office]] in [[London]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/57f1cda6-b5e7-4646-bd4f-14cb08181bfe|title=Formation of the Straits Settlements \u2013 Singapore History|website=eresources.nlb.gov.sg|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2014-07-30_084623.html|title=Straits Settlements {{!}} Infopedia|last=Singapore|first=National Library Board|website=eresources.nlb.gov.sg|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref> Direct [[British Empire|British]] rule meant better enforcement of the rule of law, as Penang's police force was vastly beefed up and the secret societies that had plagued George Town during the preceding decades were gradually outlawed.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nMeanwhile, in ''Province Wellesley'', new railway lines were being constructed, with the first railroad being the [[Bukit Mertajam]]-[[Perai]] line in 1899.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=2856&name=the_history_of_bukit_mertajam_part_i_from_agrarian_village_to_economic_hub|title=The history of Bukit Mertajam Part I \u2013 From agrarian village to economic hub|last=Nicholas Chan|date=June 2015|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref> The town of [[Butterworth, Penang|Butterworth]] was also established in the mid-19th century as the transportation hub within ''Province Wellesley''. In 1894, the first cross-strait ferry service between George Town and Butterworth commenced operations, and would eventually evolve into the present-day [[Rapid Ferry]].<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite book|title=Penang: 500 Early Postcards|last=Cheah|first=Jin Seng|publisher=Editions Didier Millet|year=2013|isbn=9789671061718|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nWith improved access to education and rising living standards, Penang soon enjoyed substantial press freedom and there was a greater degree of participation in municipal affairs by its Asian residents.<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":15\" /> Penang's representatives in the [[Legislative Council of the Straits Settlements|Straits Settlements Legislative Council]] gained a reputation for their assertive contestation of the policies made by the Singapore-based British authorities, which sometimes went against Penang's interests.\n\nOn top of that, George Town, perceived as being more intellectually receptive than Singapore, also served as a magnet for well known English authors, Asian intellectuals and reformists.<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://travel.cnn.com/explorations/escape/stories-behind-southeast-asias-top-heritage-hotels-735148/|title=Then and now: The stories behind Southeast Asia's heritage hotels {{!}} CNN Travel|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref> For instance, the Chinese revolutionary leader, [[Sun Yat-sen]], chose to relocate his Southeast Asian base from Singapore to George Town, where he continued his efforts to reorganise and raise funds for the Chinese revolutionary movement against the [[Qing dynasty]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_845__2009-01-07.html|title=Sun Yat Sen {{!}} Infopedia|last=Singapore|first=National Library Board|website=eresources.nlb.gov.sg|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref> These efforts culminated in the famous [[1910 Penang conference]], which paved the way to the ultimately triumphant [[Wuchang uprising]] that overthrew the [[Manchu people|Manchu]] imperial government of China.<ref name=\":332\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2010/11/13/dr-sun-yat-sens-historic-penang-conference/|title=Dr Sun Yat Sen's historic Penang conference \u2013 Business News {{!}} The Star Online|last=Andrew Sheng|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref>\n\n== World wars ==\n\n=== World War I ===\n{{Main|Battle of Penang}}[[File:When the Emden Raided Penang, Map, fromThe New York Times, Dec.jpg|thumb|A 1914 map from the [[The New York Times|New York Times]] depicting the [[Battle of Penang]].]]\n[[File:GEORGETOWN PENANG ISLAND MALAYSIA JAN 2012 (6815563818).jpg|left|thumb|The [[Cenotaph, Penang|Cenotaph]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] was built in honour of fallen [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] servicemen of [[World War I]].]]\nOn 28 October 1914, the [[Battle of Penang]] occurred, during which an [[Imperial German Navy]] cruiser, ''[[SMS Emden]]'', covertly sailed into [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] and sank the [[Imperial Russian Navy]] cruiser, [[Russian cruiser Zhemchug|''Zhemchug'']]. The [[French Navy]] destroyer, [[French destroyer Mousquet|''Mousquet'']], set off in pursuit, before being sunk by ''SMS Emden'' as well off the northwestern tip of [[Penang Island]]. 147 [[French Navy|French]] and [[Imperial Russian Navy|Russian]] sailors perished, while the survivors were rescued by local Malay fishermen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rbth.com/arts/2015/05/20/battle_of_penang_when_malay_fishermen_rescued_russian_sailors_46165.html|title=Battle of Penang: When Malay fishermen rescued Russian sailors|author=Ajay Kamalakaran|date=20 May 2015|publisher=[[Russia Beyond the Headlines]]|accessdate=12 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAside from the naval battle, [[Penang]], as well as the [[Straits Settlements]], was largely unaffected by the events of [[World War I]].\n\n===World War II===\n{{See also|Operation Jurist}}[[File:Japanese submarine I-10 at Penang port in 1942.jpg|thumb|An [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] submarine at the [[Port of Penang]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] in 1942.]]\n[[File:Ten dollar note issued by the Japanese Government during the occupation of Malaya, North Borneo, Sarawak and Brunei (1942, obverse).jpg|left|thumb|The [[Japanese government-issued dollar in Malaya and Borneo|Japanese-issued 'banana' dollar]], so labelled due to the banana tree motif on notes such as this.]]\n[[World War II]], on the other hand, unleashed unprecedented social and political upheaval to Penang. The swift British retreat, coupled with the brutal massacres of [[Penangite Chinese|Penang's Chinese residents]], would severely dent British sense of prestige and dominance in the eyes of the locals.\n\nFrom 9 until 18 December 1941, Japanese warplanes indiscriminately strafed and bombed George Town, in the process eliminating the obsolete [[Royal Air Force]] and [[Royal Australian Air Force]] squadrons based in [[RMAF Butterworth|RAF Butterworth]] and the Bayan Lepas Aerodrome (now [[Penang International Airport]]).<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|title=Penang At War : A History of Penang During and Between the First and Second World Wars 1914\u20131945|last=Barber|first=Andrew|publisher=AB&B|year=2010|isbn=|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Warren2006\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zosKzAoocu8C&pg=PA109|title=Britain's Greatest Defeat: Singapore 1942|author=Alan Warren|publisher=A&C Black|year=2006|isbn=978-1-85285-597-0|pages=109\u2013}}</ref> It was estimated that 600 civilians were killed as a result of the Japanese bombardment, with an additional 1,100 wounded.\n\nNotwithstanding the fact that the [[British Army during the Second World War|British Army]] had earlier designated [[Penang Island]] as a fortress, Lieutenant-General [[Arthur Percival]] then ordered a withdrawal from Penang. Not only did the British Army abandon the [[Batu Maung]] Fort on the island, they also surreptitiously evacuated Penang's European population, leaving the colony's Asian populace to the mercy of the impending Japanese occupation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article75131511|title=Penang Evacuated \u2013 British Garrison Withdrawn NEW JAP THRUSTS IN MALAYA London, December 19 \u2013 Northern Times (Carnarvon, WA : 1905\u20131952) \u2013 20 Dec 1941|website=Trove|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> To this day, it has been agreed that the withdrawal and the covert evacuation of Europeans led to the loss of the British sense of invincibility, and that \"''the moral collapse of British rule in [[Southeast Asia]] came not in [[Singapore in the Straits Settlements|Singapore]], but in Penang''\".<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite book|title=Forgotten Armies: The Fall of British Asia, 1941\u20131945|last=Bayly|first=Christopher|publisher=Harvard University|year=2005|isbn=|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nPenang fell to the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] on 19 December 1941, marking the start of a period of [[Japanese occupation of Malaya|Japanese occupation]].<ref name=\":22\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ww2db.com/battle_spec.php?battle_id=47|title=Invasion of Malaya and Singapore|last=Chen|first=C. Peter|newspaper=WW2DB|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref> Penang Island was renamed ''Tojo-to'', after the [[Prime Minister of Japan|Japanese Prime Minister]] at the time, [[Hideki Tojo]].<ref name=\":34\" /> George Town's harbour facilities were also put to use as a major [[Axis powers|Axis]] submarine base in Southeast Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uboat.net/ops/monsun3.htm|title=uboat.net \u2013 U-boat Operations- The Monsun U-boats \u2013 3. Monsun boats|website=www.uboat.net|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.navy.gov.au/history/feature-histories/german-u-boat-operations-australian-waters|title=German U-Boat Operations in Australian Waters|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2511249/Nazi-U-boat-sunk-Second-World-War-discovered-divers-Indonesia--complete-skeletons-doomed-crew.html|title=Nazi U-boat sunk during Second World War is discovered off Indonesia|newspaper=Mail Online|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.icsm.it/regiamarina/orienteng.htm|title=Italian Royal Navy in World War Two: Italian surface units in Far East|last=Borsa|first=Arnaldo|website=www.icsm.it|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historynet.com/world-war-ii-yanagi-missions-japans-underwater-convoys.htm|title=World War II: Yanagi Missions \u2013 Japan's Underwater Convoys {{!}} HistoryNet|website=www.historynet.com|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Japanese enacted dissimilar policies with each ethnic community. Ethnic Chinese residents arguably suffered the most brutal treatment, as the Imperial Japanese Army massacred thousands of Chinese as part of the ''[[Sook Ching]]'' campaign to rid what was perceived as anti-Japanese elements in the society.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://anilnetto.com/society/malaysian-history/old-penang-the-sook-ching-massacres-of-world-war-ii/|title=Old Penang: The Sook Ching massacres of World War II - anilnetto.com|last=Netto|first=Anil|date=6 October 2013|newspaper=anilnetto.com|access-date=15 October 2016|language=en-GB}}</ref> Penang's womenfolk were also coerced to work as [[comfort women]] by the Imperial Japanese Army.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.malaysiakini.com/news/4269|title=Researcher details shattered lives of local comfort women|date=2001-08-11|work=Malaysiakini|access-date=2017-05-25|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205208397|title=THE ALLIED REOCCUPATION OF THE ANDAMAN ISLANDS, 1945|website=www.iwm.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-05-25}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Japanese_surrender_Penang.jpg|left|thumb|Japanese officials signing the surrender of [[Penang]] documents on board [[HMS Nelson (28)|''HMS Nelson'']] on 2 September 1945.]]\n[[File:Royal_Marines_Parade_in_Penang_(5316034010).jpg|thumb|[[Royal Marines|British Royal Marines]] liberating George Town on 3 September 1945.]]\n[[File:Reoccupation of Penang (5315445771).jpg|thumb|Japanese [[Prisoner of war|prisoners of war]] being marched through the streets of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] by their British captors on 3 September 1945.]]Penang's residents also had to endure economic hardship during the Japanese occupation, with [[hyperinflation]] caused by the oversupply of the [[Japanese government-issued dollar in Malaya and Borneo|Japanese-issued 'banana' dollars]], and the acute shortage of food and raw materials, due to a combination of Japanese wartime rationing and an Allied blockade of Japanese shipping.<ref>[http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/syonantimes19420223-1.2.17.1 Currency replacement and price freeze], Syonan Shimbun, 23 February 1942, Page 3</ref><ref name=\"Huff\">''Financing Japan\u2019s World War II Occupation of Southeast Asia'', Gregg Huff and Shinobu Majima, Pembroke College \u2013 University of Oxford and Faculty of Economics \u2013 Gakushuin University, pp. 7\u201319</ref><ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/image/88380751/?terms=malaya Japan needs ships], ''The Decatur Daily Review'', Decatur, Illinois, Saturday, July 31, 1943 \u2013 p. 4</ref> Households were forced to turn to secondary crops such as sweet potatoes, yam and tapioca for their own subsistence. Beginning in 1942, a standardised Japanese curricula was enforced in all schools throughout Penang, with [[Japanese language|Japanese]] as the official language. In fact, social lifestyles were also greatly impacted, as it became compulsory to bow to Japanese soldiers on guard duty and to sing the [[Kimigayo|Japanese national anthem]], whilst whole streets and shops were renamed in Japanese.<ref>[http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/syonantimes19420309-1.2.11 Privilege To Bow To Sentry On Duty], Syonan Shimbun, 9 March 1942, Page 3, retrieved 31 March 2017</ref>\n\nBetween 1944 and 1945, Royal Air Force and [[United States Army Air Forces|United States Army Air Force]] bomber squadrons based in [[British Raj|India]] repeatedly launched [[Bombing of South-East Asia (1944\u201345)|bombing raids on George Town]], seeking to destroy naval and administrative facilities.<ref name=\":22\" /> The destruction of the Penang Secretariat building by the Allied bombardment caused the loss of a large part of the British and Japanese records concerning Penang Island, complicating post-war efforts to compile a comprehensive history of Penang.<ref>{{Cite book|title=War and Occupation in Penang, 1941\u20131945|last=Kratoska|first=Paul|publisher=National University of Singapore|year=|isbn=|location=Singapore|pages=|via=}}</ref> The [[Penang Strait]] was also mined as part of efforts to constrict Japanese shipping.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bePxcx7BFLEC&pg=PA296|title=The Japanese Occupation of Malaya: A Social and Economic History|author=Paul H. Kratoska|publisher=C. Hurst & Co. Publishers|year=1998|isbn=978-1-85065-284-7|pages=296\u2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrender]] on 15 August 1945, the ''Penang Shimbun'', a Japanese newspaper, published the proclamation of surrender issued by the [[Emperor of Japan]]. Under [[Operation Jurist]], a [[Royal Navy|British Royal Navy]] fleet accepted the surrender of the Japanese garrison in Penang on 2 September 1945. A [[Royal Marines|British Royal Marines]] contingent recaptured Penang Island on the following day, making George Town the first city in [[British Malaya|Malaya]] to be liberated at the end of the war.\n\n==Post-war==\n[[File:Flag of Penang (1946-1949).svg|left|thumb|Flag of the [[Crown Colony of Penang]], which was in use between 1946 and 1949.]]\n[[Penang]] was placed under a [[British Military Administration (Malaya)|military administration]] until 1946, as the British sought to restore order in the face of an [[Malayan Emergency|emerging Communist insurgency]].<ref name=\":22\" /> The British also dissolved the [[Straits Settlements]] in April 1946, with Sir [[Shenton Thomas]] being its last [[List of governors of the Straits Settlements|Governor]]; [[Crown Colony of Penang|Penang]] and [[Crown Colony of Malacca|Malacca]] were then merged with the [[Federated Malay States]] and the [[Unfederated Malay States]] to form the [[Malayan Union]] (the new [[Colony of Singapore]], excluded from this union, was to remain firmly under British rule). The Malayan Union was replaced by the [[Federation of Malaya]] in 1948. As the gradual withdrawal of the Western colonial powers in [[Southeast Asia]] continued taking shape, the independence of Malaya as a united political entity seemed a foregone conclusion.\n\nHowever, the merger of the British crown colony of Penang into the vast Malay heartland alarmed some quarters of Penang's population. Questions were raised over economic and ethnic issues, such as the citizenship of non-Malays, greater trade regulations imposed on Penang by the central government in [[Kuala Lumpur]] and the introduction of export [[Duty (economics)|duties]] for trade with the rest of Malaya.<ref name=\":7\" /> Consequently, the Penang Secession Committee, formed in 1948, proposed to exclude Penang from the Federation of Malaya, which would allow Penang to either retain its links with the [[British Empire]] or form a political union with Singapore.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> The movement was led by D.A. Mackay, then the chairman of the Penang Chamber of Commerce, and included the Penang Muslim Chamber of Commerce, the Penang Chinese Chamber of Commerce, the Penang Straits Chinese Association, the Penang Eurasian Association and the Penang Indian Chamber of Commerce.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Journal of Southeast Asian Studies|journal=The Penang Secession Movement, 1948\u20131951|volume=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Noordin Sopiee|first1=M.|year=1973|title=The Penang Secession Movement, 1948\u20131951|journal=Journal of Southeast Asian Studies|volume=4|issue=1|pages=52\u201371|doi=10.1017/S0022463400016416|pmc=|pmid=}}</ref>\n\nUltimately, the Penang Secession Committee failed to attain its goals and petered out. A secession motion tabled in the Penang Settlement Council in 1949 was narrowly dismissed by British official votes, while another petition sent to [[London]] in 1951 also met with British disapproval.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> While some British and American observers were sympathetic to the secessionists' cause, the British administrators were reluctant to jeopardise their own plans to gradually grant independence to a united Malayan polity. Moreover, the British government allayed the fears raised by the secessionists by guaranteeing [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]'s free port status and by reintroducing municipal elections for the city in 1951.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOn 1 January 1957, George Town, the capital of Penang, was granted city status by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] in 1957, becoming the first city within the Federation of Malaya, and by extension, [[Malaysia]]. George Town continued to be the only city within Malaysia (other than [[City of Singapore (historical entity)|Singapore]] between 1963 and its Separation in 1965) until 1972, when Kuala Lumpur was also conferred city status.\n\nPenang, as part of the Federation of Malaya, gained independence from the British Empire on 31 August 1957, and subsequently became a member state of Malaysia in 1963.\n\n==Post-independence==\n\n=== 1957 \u2013 1969 ===\n[[Penang]]'s political landscape immediately after the independence of [[Federation of Malaya|Malaya]] became relatively fractured. The new [[Government of Penang|Penang state government]] was dominated by the [[Alliance Party (Malaysia)|Alliance coalition]] (now succeeded by [[Barisan Nasional]]), the same ruling coalition that controlled the Malayan federal government. [[Wong Pow Nee]] of the [[Malaysian Chinese Association]] (MCA), one of the major component parties of the Alliance, became Penang's first [[List of Chief Ministers of Penang|Chief Minister]], a position that he held until 1969. On the other hand, the [[Labour Party of Malaya|Labour Party]], a left-wing opposition party, took control of the George Town City Council soon after the Malayan independence.<ref name=\":47\" /> Penang's voters tended to leave the control of the state government in the hands of the Alliance, while consistently electing the Labour Party to run the city council.\n\nAt the time, the George Town City Council was the only fully elected local authority in Malaya, as well as the country's richest, with an annual revenue that was double that of the Penang state government by 1965.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=2698&name=george_town_from_city_to_municipality_to_culture_centre|title=George Town \u2013 From city to municipality to culture centre|last=Ooi|first=Kee Beng|date=January 2015|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> This solidified the financial autonomy of the city council, with its revenue going into social welfare projects within [[George Town, Penang|George Town]].<ref name=\":47\" /><ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=4160&name=a_history_of_local_elections_in_penang_part_ii_a_legacy_to_protect|title=A history of local elections in Penang Part II: A legacy to protect|last=Steven Sim|first=Koay Su Lyn|date=December 2014|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> Meanwhile, the Penang state government attempted to boost the state's manufacturing sector by opening new industrial estates in [[Seberang Perai]], such as in [[Perai]] and [[Mak Mandin]].<ref name=\":47\" /><ref name=\":18\"/> Exacerbated by the opposing political affinities and ideologies, conflicts frequently arose between the state government and the city council over differences in policies and budget allocations.<ref name=\":47\" /><ref name=\":19\" /><ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=4287&name=when_labour_ruled_the_council|title=When Labour ruled the council|last=Su Lyn|first=Koay|date=April 2014|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\nAs previously guaranteed by the British authorities, George Town's free port status was untouched in the years immediately after the Malayan independence. The earlier fears by the secessionists eventually came true, however, when in 1969, the free port status was suddenly revoked by the [[Government of Malaysia|Malaysian federal government]].<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":132\"/> Consequently, 16.4% of Penang's working population became unemployed as the [[Port of Penang]]'s trade volume plummeted, adversely affecting George Town's services sector.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/11/25/the-man-behind-penangs-economic-transformation/|title=The man behind Penang's economic transformation|website=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref><ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=2568&name=where_the_sea_meets_the_city_is_where_the_world_meets_penang|title=Where the Sea Meets the City is Where the World Meets Penang|last=Evelyn Teh|date=July 2016|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> In the long run, this also marked the beginning of George Town's slow, decades-long decline, which was only recently reversed.<ref name=\":142\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/05/travel/05georgetown-nextstop.html|title=In Malaysia, Tourists Are Lured by George Town's Colorful Past|last=Eckhardt|first=Robyn|date=2 December 2010|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=16 October 2016|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe revocation of George Town's free port status, coupled with an unsuccessful, bloody strike by Penang's unions in 1967, led to a loss of popular support for the Alliance amongst Penangites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=4381&name=penangs_forgotten_protest_the_1967_hartal|title=Penang's forgotten protest: The 1967 Hartal|last=Koay|first=Su Lyn|date=August 2014|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> During the [[Malaysian state elections, 1969|1969 State Elections]], [[Parti Gerakan Rakyat Malaysia|Gerakan]], then an opposition party, was voted into power in Penang, replacing the Alliance. The party's founder, [[Lim Chong Eu]], succeeded Wong Pow Nee as the Chief Minister of Penang. However, the [[13 May Incident|violent race riots in Kuala Lumpur]] following the concurrent [[Malaysian general election, 1969|Malaysian General Elections]] led to the nationwide imposition of martial law and the functions of the Penang state government were taken over by the National Operations Council until 1971.\n\n=== 1970 \u2013 1990 ===\n[[File:Penang Bridge main span taxi.jpg|left|thumb|Completed in 1985, the [[Penang Bridge]] was then the longest bridge in [[Southeast Asia]].]]\n[[File:Komtar, Georgetown, Penang, Malaysia.JPG|thumb|Constructed in 1974, the [[Komtar|Komtar Tower]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] is [[List of tallest buildings in Penang Island|Penang's tallest skyscraper]].]]\n[[File:Bayan Baru.jpg|thumb|The township of [[Bayan Baru]] was first developed by the Penang Development Corporation in the 1970s following the establishment of the adjacent [[Bayan Lepas Free Industrial Zone]].<ref name=\"Ooi 2010\">{{Cite book|title=Pilot Studies for a New Penang|last=Ooi|first=Kee Beng|publisher=[[Institute of Southeast Asian Studies]]|year=2010|isbn=9789814279697|location=[[Singapore]]|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Regional Growth and Sustainable Development in Asia|last=Peter Nijkamp|first=Amitrajeet A. Batabyal|publisher=Springer|year=2016|isbn=9783319275895|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":26\">{{Cite book|title=Globalization and New Intra-Urban Dynamics in Asian Cities|last=Sue-Ching Jou, Hsin-Huang Michael Hsiao|first=Natacha Aveline-Dubach|publisher=[[National Taiwan University]]|year=2014|isbn=9789863500216|location=[[Taipei]]|pages=}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Butterworth 1.jpg|left|thumb|The [[Port of Penang]] was relocated to [[Butterworth, Penang|Butterworth]] (pictured here) in 1974, significantly boosting the town's economy.<ref name=\":53\">{{Cite news|url=http://penangmonthly.com/the-mainland-awakens/|title=The Mainland Awakens|date=2016-09-01|newspaper=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-02-10|language=en-US}}</ref>]]\nIn 1973, [[Parti Gerakan Rakyat Malaysia|Gerakan]] joined [[Barisan Nasional]], thus returning the [[Government of Penang|Penang state government]] back into the hands of the ruling coalition.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=7680&name=tun_lim_chong_eu_the_past_is_not_pass|title=Tun Lim Chong Eu: The past is not pass\u00e9|last=Ooi|first=Kee Beng|date=December 2009|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref>\n\nTo revive [[Penang]]'s economy, [[Lim Chong Eu]] created the [[Bayan Lepas Free Industrial Zone]] and courted foreign [[multinational corporation]]s for investments.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":25\">{{Cite web|url=http://wongchunwai.com/2013/03/transformation-of-bayan-lepas-into-free-trade-area-does-not-diminish-its-attractions/|title=Transformation of Bayan Lepas into free trade area does not diminish its attractions {{!}} Wong Chun Wai|website=wongchunwai.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> Pioneer tax status was granted to multinational firms seeking to establish assembly plants within Bayan Lepas, which was formerly the rice bowl of Penang.<ref name=\":21\" /> Major electronic and engineering firms, including [[Motorola]], [[Bosch Rexroth|Bosch]], [[Hewlett-Packard]] and [[Hitachi]], flocked in, setting up assembly plants within the area. Complemented by cheap labour, the Bayan Lepas Free Industrial Zone, one of the major electronics manufacturing zones in [[Asia]], grew to become the ''Silicon Valley of the East'' and was instrumental in pulling Penang out from its economic slump, greatly propelling the state's economy as one of the main economic powerhouses within [[Malaysia]]''.''<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":25\" /> To this day, manufacturing remains one of Penang's two largest economic sectors, contributing as much as 47.4% of Penang's [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] {{As of|2015|lc=y}}.<ref name=\":122\">{{Cite journal|title=Penang Economic Indicators|url=http://www.investpenang.gov.my/files/investment-updates/31/Penang%20Economic%20Indicator%20Q2%202015.1432708522.pdf|journal=Penang Monthly}}</ref>\n\nDuring Lim's tenure, several major infrastructure projects were completed. The [[Penang Bridge]], then the longest bridge in [[Southeast Asia]], was completed in 1985, thus providing for the first time a road link between [[Penang Island]] and the [[Malay Peninsula]]. More controversial was the {{Convert|250|metre|feet|abbr=on|adj=on}}-tall [[Komtar]] in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]], to this day the [[List of tallest buildings in Penang Island|tallest skyscraper in Penang]]. Launched in 1974 as part of his vision to reverse George Town's declining fortunes, Komtar was constructed in the expense of hundreds of shophouses, schools and temples, as well as whole streets, which were bulldozed for the project.<ref name=\":37\" /> However, instead of arresting George Town's decline, Komtar itself became a white elephant by the early 2000s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.failedarchitecture.com/komtar-malaysias-monument-to-failed-modernism/|title=Komtar: Malaysia's Monument to Failed Modernism \u2014 Failed Architecture|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/penangs-iconic-komtar-gets-rm50m-facelift|title=Penang's iconic Komtar gets RM50m facelift|date=29 October 2013|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2015/04/25/much-of-komtars-charm-is-gone-some-pioneer-traders-want-out-of-oncebustling-iconic-retail-centre/|title=Much of Komtar's charm is gone \u2013 Nation {{!}} The Star Online|last=Loh|first=Arnold|access-date=15 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, in 1974, the [[Port of Penang]] was relocated from George Town to the town of [[Butterworth, Penang|Butterworth]], directly across the [[Penang Strait]], to allow for the berthing of larger container and cargo vessels.<ref name=\":53\" /> By then, the maritime traffic through Penang had been greatly diminished since the revocation of George Town's free port status, with increasing volumes of maritime trade being directed towards [[Port Klang]] near [[Kuala Lumpur]] instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=7135&name=can_penang_port_be_saved?|title=Can Penang Port be saved?|last=Andrew Yong|date=September 2012|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jacobsen|first=Michael|date=November 2010|title=Interdependency versus Notions of Decoupling in a Globalising World: Assessing the Impact of Global Economics on Industrial Developments and Inter-Ethnic Relations in Penang, Malaysia|url=|journal=Copenhagen Business School|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the 1970s and 80s, the [[Government of Malaysia|Malaysian federal government]] proceeded with the rapid development of Kuala Lumpur and nearby Port Klang, by controlling investments in communication, transport, education and health.<ref name=\":37\" /> Kuala Lumpur soon outstripped George Town as Malaysia's largest city and financial centre, while Port Klang quickly became the country's busiest seaport. Consequently, Penang began to suffer considerable brain drain as younger Penangites started emigrating for better employment opportunities.<ref name=\":23\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/the+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20091110-178889.html|title=Brain-drain debate after Penang loses $4b deal|website=news.asiaone.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019202527/http://news.asiaone.com/News/the+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20091110-178889.html|archivedate=19 October 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=15 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":112\">{{Cite journal|title=Higher Education in Regional and City Development : State of Penang, Malaysia|journal=OECD|volume=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/opinions/79059|title=Watching Penang 'grow'|date=2008-03-03|work=Malaysiakini|access-date=2017-11-30|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, the George Town City Council was merged with the Penang Island Rural District Council to form the Penang Island Municipal Council, while the five local authorities within [[Seberang Perai]], including the Butterworth and [[Bukit Mertajam]] town councils, were merged into the [[Seberang Perai Municipal Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesundaily.my/node/252772|title=The Penang Island City agenda|website=www.thesundaily.my|language=en|access-date=2017-12-09}}</ref> By then, local elections, suspended since 1965, became a thing of the past, with the municipal councillors being appointed by the Penang state government ever since.<ref name=\":19\" /> The merger of the local governments on Penang Island also led to a decades-long dispute over George Town's city status.<ref name=\":192\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/where-is-george-town|title=Where is George Town?|last=|first=|date=4 April 2015|work=[[Malay Mail]]|access-date=2017-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://penangmonthly.com/article.aspx?pageid=9315&name=remember_the_city_status_of_george_town|title=Remember the city status of George Town|last=Goh|first=Ban Lee|date=February 2010|website=Penang Monthly|access-date=2017-12-09}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Malaysian state elections, 1990|1990 State Elections]], Lim Chong Eu as the incumbent lost the [[Padang Kota (state constituency)|Padang Kota]] constituency to [[Lim Kit Siang]] of the [[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|Democratic Action Party]] (DAP), forcing him into retirement. Although Barisan Nasional remained in power, Lim Chong Eu was succeeded by [[Koh Tsu Koon]] as the [[List of Chief Ministers of Penang|Chief Minister of Penang]].\n\n=== 1991 \u2013 2008 ===\n[[File:Tanjungtokongwave.png|left|thumb|[[Tanjung Tokong]] was among the worst hit areas during the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|Indian Ocean tsunami]] on 26 December 2004. Within Penang, 52 lives were lost.]]\n[[Koh Tsu Koon]]'s tenure as the [[List of Chief Ministers of Penang|Chief Minister of Penang]] was marked by inept development and urban planning policies, rampant pollution, and the deteriorating general state of affairs within [[Penang]]. Political tussles complicated development policies, while simmering discontent from Penang's vocal [[Non-governmental organization|non-governmental organisations]] (NGOs) and residents over the state's decline would eventually lead to an unprecedented political change within the state.<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":28\">{{Cite book|title=Contested Space: Cultural Heritage and Identity Reconstructions : Conservation Strategies Within a Developing Asian City|last=Jenkins|first=Gwynn|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|year=2008|isbn=9783825813666|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, plans for the development of [[Penang Hill]] were drawn up by the [[Government of Penang|Penang state government]], drawing considerable backlash from Penang's civil societies over the potential environmental degradation of the forested hill.<ref name=\":37\" /> The plan was eventually axed. Meanwhile, the Rent Control Act, which until then had protected the low-income residents within the [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] city centre from eviction by preventing any arbitrary hike in rents, was repealed by 2001.<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":27\">{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/se-asia/BF29Ae01.html|title=Asia Times: Wreckers ball rips heart out of city: Car Rentals at www.The-Car-Reservations-Desk.com|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> This consequently led to the further hollowing out of the city centre, as residents, and [[Small and medium-sized enterprises|smaller businesses]], were unable to cope with the rental hikes and moved out. Unscrupulous private developers began demolishing several pre-war heritage buildings within the city centre for redevelopment, while other historic buildings fell under disrepair. Concerned over the impending loss of George Town's heritage architecture, NGOs based within the city started to mobilise public support for the conservation of these historic buildings.\n\nBy the early 2000s, Penang's economic growth began to lose steam, with the city-state recording the lowest monthly household income growth rate amongst the [[States and federal territories of Malaysia|Malaysian states]].<ref name=\"Ooi 2010\"/> The decades of brain drain also took its toll. For instance, while [[Kuala Lumpur]] was granted several mega-projects, including the [[Petronas Towers]] and the [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]], Penang suffered a shortage of qualified engineers and architects as professionals continued gravitating towards the [[Greater Kuala Lumpur]] area.<ref name=\":26\" /><ref name=\":28\" /> Moreover, the lack of a coherent urban planning policy and poor traffic management meant that little was done to curb the worsening traffic congestion within Penang.<ref name=\":29\">{{Cite web|url=https://aliran.com/archives/monthly/2004b/11d.html|title=Tsunami impact in Penang, Malaysia: Our island, our world|website=aliran.com|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref> Even the state's reputation for cleanliness was not spared, as reports of coastal pollution and dirty streets within Penang made headline news.<ref name=\":29\" /> As early as 1996, the then [[Prime Minister of Malaysia|Malaysian Prime Mninister]], [[Mahathir Mohamad]], had even labelled Penang a \"''garbage state''\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ww1.utusan.com.my/utusan/info.asp?y=2001&dt=0107&pub=utusan_malaysia&sec=Muka_Hadapan&pg=fp_06.htm|title=Akta Warisan akan diperkenal|website=Utusan Online|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.buletinmutiara.com/garbage-dump-to-shining-city/|title=Garbage dump to shining city|last=Lilian Chan|first=|date=22 January 2015|work=Buletin Mutiara|access-date=|location=[[George Town, Penang|George Town]]}}</ref>\n\nWidespread dissatisfaction over Penang's decline and neglect sparked a media campaign to restore Penang to its former glory in 2004.<ref name=\":29\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2004/11/07/penang-losing-its-tourism-lustre/|title=Penang losing its tourism lustre|last=Ng|first=Su-Ann|date=7 November 2004|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2004/12/07/cm-work-hard--to-bring-lustre-back-to-penang/|title=CM: Work hard to bring lustre back to Penang|last=Habibu|first=Sira|date=7 December 2004|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/letters/32226|title=Penang \u2013 who should stop the rot?|last=|first=|date=16 December 2004|work=[[Malaysiakini]]|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wongchunwai.com/2004/12/act-fast-to-boost-islands-sagging-image/|title=Act fast to boost island's sagging image|last=Wong|first=Chun Wai|date=12 December 2004|website=Wong Chun Wai|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref> It has since been speculated that the public outcry over the neglect of the city once known as the '''Pearl of the Orient''<nowiki/>', combined with Penang's relatively lively political scene, contributed to the defeat of Barisan Nasional in the [[Penang state election, 2008|2008 State Election]] by the federal opposition pact, [[Pakatan Rakyat]].<ref name=\":47\" /><ref name=\":28\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=March 8: Eclipsing May 13|last=Saravanamuttu Jayaratnam, Lee Hock Guan|first=Ooi Kee Beng|publisher=[[Institute of Southeast Asian Studies]]|year=2008|isbn=9789812308962|location=[[Singapore]]|pages=}}</ref> The opposition coalition, led by the [[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|DAP]], subsequently took over the Penang state government, with [[Lim Guan Eng]] succeeding Koh as the Chief Minister of Penang.\n\nIn late 2004, Penang was hit by the massive [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|Indian Ocean tsunami]]. Out of the 68 deaths within [[Malaysia]], 52 were in Penang.<ref name=\":29\" /> Northern coastal areas, such as [[Batu Ferringhi]] and [[Gurney Drive, George Town|Gurney Drive]] in George Town, were among the worst hit places within the state. In the aftermath of the tsunami, a network of sirens has been installed throughout Penang as part of a national tsunami warning system designed to alert the public of such calamities in the future.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/how-ready-is-penang-for-another-tsunami-after-10-years#0L04xcV4t6wgKk3e.97|title=How ready is Penang for another tsunami after 10 years?|date=2014-12-26|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref>\n\n=== 2008 ===\n[[File:Old town of Georgetown..JPG|thumb|The historic city centre of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] has been gazetted as a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] since 2008.]]\n[[File:Cmglee Penang Second Bridge aerial.jpg|left|thumb|The [[Sultan Abdul Halim Muadzam Shah Bridge|Second Penang Bridge]], at {{Convert|24|km|mi|abbr=on}} long, is the longest bridge in [[Southeast Asia]].]]\n\n[[File:LinkBike, George Town, Penang.jpg|left|thumb|A [[LinkBike]] station in [[George Town, Penang|George Town]]. This [[Bicycle-sharing system|public-bicycle sharing service]] is an initiative of the [[Government of Penang|Penang state government]] to alleviate traffic congestion in the city.]]\nThe swearing in of the new [[Government of Penang|Penang state government]], now led by [[Pakatan Rakyat]], in 2008, heralded various positive policy changes. During that year, the [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] city centre, along with [[Malacca City|Malacca]], was inscribed as a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]], as a result of years of conservation efforts led by the city's [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]]<nowiki/>s. The new state government subsequently spearheaded efforts to improve hygiene, cleanliness and [[Pedestrian zone|pedestrianisation]], as well as the use of public transportation and the promotion of the city's cultural diversity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/metro/community/2017/06/01/payment-card-launched-for-bike-sharing-system/|title=Payment card launched for bike sharing system|last=|first=|date=1 June 2017|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/metro/views/2016/05/10/stop-walkers-crossing-pedestrian-is-king-drive-needs-greater-awareness-to-make-island-more-pedestria/|title=Stop! Walkers crossing|last=|first=|date=10 May 2016|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/guan-eng-lifts-from-singapore-playbook-in-ambitious-bid-to-make-penang-worl#sF4IgJozHejwlMFI.97|title=Guan Eng lifts from Singapore playbook in ambitious bid to make Penang world class|last=Eileen Ng|first=|date=14 May 2016|work=[[Malay Mail]]|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref> By 2010, George Town was ranked the most liveable city in [[Malaysia]] by [[ECA International]], coming in at eighth place within [[Asia]] as well.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/05/23/penangs-capital-is-eighth-most-liveable-city-in-asia-on-par-with-kl-and-bangkok/|title=Penang's capital is eighth most liveable city in Asia, on par with KL and Bangkok|last=|first=|date=23 May 2010|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|access-date=}}</ref> Moreover, in 2017, the city was also ranked the second cleanest within Malaysia, behind only [[Ipoh]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/08/14/ipoh-is-malaysias-cleanest-city/|title=Ipoh is Malaysia's cleanest city|last=|first=|date=14 August 2017|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn the economic front, the present state government has emphasised efforts to attract [[foreign direct investment]]s and to push Penang up the economic value chain, as well as policies to root out corruption.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/special-report-penang-manufacturing-ready-industry-40|title=Special Report: Penang manufacturing ready for Industry 4.0?|last=Amarthalingam|first=Sangeetha|date=12 October 2017|work=[[The Edge (Malaysia)|The Edge]]|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en-gb}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2011|title=Higher Education in Regional and City Development Higher Education in Regional and City Development: State of Penang, Malaysia 2011|url=|journal=[[OECD]]|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://penanginstitute.org/v3/resources/articles/in-penang-monthly/333-a-post-industrial-future-for-penang|title=A post-industrial future for Penang?|last=[[Zairil Khir Johari]]|date=August 2012|work=Penang Institute|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en-gb}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://penanginstitute.org/v3/media-centre/penang-institute-in-the-news/215-guan-eng-open-tenders-key-to-penang-s-efficiency|title=Guan Eng: Open tenders key to Penang's efficiency|last=R B Bhattacharjee|first=|date=12 December 2011|work=Penang Institute|access-date=2017-12-06|language=en-gb}}</ref> In 2010, Penang recorded the highest amount of capital investments within Malaysia, attracting RM12.2&nbsp;billion, or 26%, of the nation's total investments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?sec=nation&file=/2011/1/20/nation/7831229|title=Penang tops total capital investment list for 2010|author=The Star|date=20 January 2011|publisher=The Star|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110121034407/http://www.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2011%2F1%2F20%2Fnation%2F7831229&sec=nation|archivedate=21 January 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=27 January 2011}}</ref> Penang's stunning economic recovery, particularly since 2008, was described by [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] as Malaysia's \"''biggest economic success''\" despite the [[Government of Malaysia|Malaysian federal government]]'s focus on other states such as [[Johor]] and [[Sarawak]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://limguaneng.com/index.php/2012/02/22/1-6-million-penangites-deserve-full-credit-for-the-historic-feat-of-penang-being-no-1-in-malaysia-in-manufacturing-investment-for-the-2nd-consecutive-year-in-2011-enbmcn/|title=1.6 Million Penangites Deserve Full Credit for the Historic Feat of Penang Being No. 1 in Malaysia in Manufacturing Investment for the 2nd Consecutive Year in 2011|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> On top of that, the [[Penang State Executive Council|Penang state government]] was able to decrease Penang's public debt by 95%, from RM630&nbsp;million in 2008 to RM30&nbsp;million by late 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/you-too-can-be-like-penang-guan-eng-tells-malaysia/|title=You too can be like Penang, Guan Eng tells Malaysia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140820081529/https://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/you-too-can-be-like-penang-guan-eng-tells-malaysia/|archivedate=20 August 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=13 September 2014|df=dmy}}</ref> In addition, in 2016, George Town was rated as the most attractive destination for commercial property investment within Malaysia by [[Knight Frank]], surpassing even [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Malaysia Commercial Real Estate Investment Sentiment Survey 2016|url=http://content.knightfrank.com/research/795/documents/en/malaysia-sentiment-survey-2016-3567.pdf|journal=[[Knight Frank]]|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the Malaysian federal government elevated the Penang Island Municipal Council into the present-day [[Penang Island City Council]], thereby expanding the jurisdiction of George Town to encompass the entire Penang Island, as well as five of the surrounding islets.<ref name=\"island\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.buletinmutiara.com/download/2015/BuletinMutiaraMay12015-BM.pdf|title=George Town meliputi 'pulau', jelas Datuk Bandar|last=|first=|date=1 May 2015|work=Buletin Mutiara|access-date=}}</ref> This also made George Town the only Malaysian city to have been conferred its city status twice.\n\nThe [[Sultan Abdul Halim Muadzam Shah Bridge|Second Penang Bridge]], currently the longest bridge in [[Southeast Asia]], was opened in 2013. Straddling a length of {{Convert|24|km|mi|abbr=on}}, it provides a second road link between Penang Island and [[Seberang Perai]], and has spurred the development of new industrial areas such as [[Batu Kawan]].{{wide image|Skyline of George Town, Penang.jpg|1000px|Skyline of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] as of 2017, as seen from [[Gurney Drive, George Town|Gurney Drive]].|align-cap=center}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of George Town, Penang|History of George Town]]\n*[[Straits Settlements]]\n*[[List of governors of Penang]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Citation  |last=Sandhu |first=Kernial Singh |title=Indians in Malaya-immigration and settlement |publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1969 |page=29}}\n*{{Citation  |last=Sinnappah |first=Anasanatnam |title=Indians in Malaysia and Singapore |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Kulala Lumpur|year=1979 |page=19}}\n*{{Citation  |last=Snider |first=Nancy |title=What Happened in Penang |journal=Asian Survey|volume=8 |issue=12 |year=1968 |pages=960\u2013975 |doi=10.1525/as.1968.8.12.01p0433y}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n\n{{Penang}}\n{{British overseas territories}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of Penang}}\n[[Category:History of Penang|* 1]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 0 bare reference(s) with reFill 2,Script-assisted fixes: perCS1andMOS:ITALICS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Penang"}
{"title_page": "Sing \"Yesterday\" for Me", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese manga series}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Header\n| name            = Sing \"Yesterday\" for Me\n| image           = Sing \"Yesterday\" for Me volume 1 cover.jpg\n| caption         = Cover of ''Sing \"Yesterday\" for Me'' volume 1 by Shueisha\n| ja_kanji        = \u30a4\u30a8\u30b9\u30bf\u30c7\u30a4\u3092\u3046\u305f\u3063\u3066\n| ja_romaji       = Iesutadei o Utatte\n| genre           = [[Coming-of-age story|Coming-of-age]]<ref name=\"ANN1\"/>\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = manga\n| author          = [[Kei Toume]]\n| publisher       = [[Shueisha]]\n| publisher_en    = \n| demographic     = ''[[Seinen manga|Seinen]]''\n| magazine        = [[Business Jump]]<small> (1997-2011)</small><br>[[Grand Jump]]<small> (2011-2015)</small>\n| first           = 1997\n| last            = June 2015\n| volumes         = 11\n| volume_list     = \n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = TV series \n| director        = Yoshiyuki Fujiwara\n| producer        = DMM.futureworks\n| writer          = Yoshiyuki Fujiwara<br>Jin Tanaka\n| music           = \n| studio          = [[Doga Kobo]]\n| licensee        = \n| network         = [[TV Asahi]], [[AbemaTV]], [[TV Asahi|BS Asahi]]\n| first           = April 4, 2020\n| last            = \n| episodes        = 18\n| episode_list    = \n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n{{Nihongo|'''''Sing \"Yesterday\" for Me'''''|\u30a4\u30a8\u30b9\u30bf\u30c7\u30a4\u3092\u3046\u305f\u3063\u3066|Iesutadei o Utatte}} is a Japanese [[manga]] series by [[Kei Toume]]. It began serialization in [[Shueisha]]'s [[seinen manga|''seinen'' manga]] magazine ''[[Business Jump]]'' in 1997, and it moved to Shueisha's ''[[Grand Jump]]'' magazine in November 2011 until it ended in June 2015. It was collected in eleven ''[[tank\u014dbon]]'' volumes. An [[anime]] television series adaptation by [[Doga Kobo]] premiered on April 4, 2020.\n\n==Characters==\n===Main Characters===\n;{{Nihongo|Rikuo Uozumi|\u9b5a\u4f4f \u9678\u751f|Uozumi Rikuo}}\n:{{voiced by|Chikahiro Kobayashi}}<ref name=\"cast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-01-21/sing-yesterday-for-me-anime-reveals-cast-april-4-premiere/.155598|title=Sing 'Yesterday' for Me Anime Reveals Cast, April 4 Premiere|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 21, 2020|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n:Rikuo is a college graduate unsure about his future. He currently works at a convenience store. His hobby is photography. He has feelings for Shinako.\n;{{Nihongo|Haru Nonaka|\u91ce\u4e2d \u6674|Nonaka Haru}}\n:{{voiced by|[[Yume Miyamoto]]}}<ref name=\"cast\"/>\n:Haru is an eccentric girl working at MILK HALL. She adopted a crow and named it Kansuke. Because of the drastic change in her appearance, Rikuo does not remember meeting her five years ago. She often drops by the convenience store before going to work. \n;{{Nihongo|Shinako Morinome|\u68ee\u30ce\u76ee \u6980\u5b50|Morinome Shinako}}\n:{{voiced by|[[Kana Hanazawa]]}}<ref name=\"cast\"/>\n:Shinako is Rikuo's classmate from college. She is currently working as a high school teacher. She is still in love with R\u014d's already deceased older brother. \n;{{Nihongo|R\u014d Hayakawa|\u65e9\u5ddd \u6d6a|Hayakawa R\u014d}}\n:{{voiced by|[[Natsuki Hanae]]}}<ref name=\"cast\"/>\n:R\u014d is Shinako's childhood friend from [[Kanazawa]].\n\n===Rikuo's Circle===\n;{{Nihongo|Kinoshita|\u6728\u30ce\u4e0b|Kinoshita}}\n:{{voiced by|[[Tatsuhisa Suzuki]]}}<ref name=\"cast2\">{{cite web|url=https://singyesterday.com/cast/|title=<nowiki>CAST / STAFF | TV\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u300e\u30a4\u30a8\u30b9\u30bf\u30c7\u30a4\u3092\u3046\u305f\u3063\u3066\u300f\u516c\u5f0f\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8</nowiki>|website=singyesterday.com|accessdate=February 19, 2020|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n:Rikuo's co-worker at a convenience store.\n;{{Nihongo|Takanori Fukuda|\u798f\u7530 \u30bf\u30ab\u30ce\u30ea|Fukuda Takanori}}\n:{{voiced by|[[Takuma Terashima]]}}<ref name=\"cast2\"/>\n:Rikuo and Shinako's college classmate.\n;{{Nihongo|Kozue Fukuda|\u798f\u7530 \u68a2|Fukuda Kozue}}\n:{{voiced by|[[Aya Suzaki]]}}<ref name=\"cast2\"/>\n:Tanakori's wife.\n;{{Nihongo|Chika Yuzuhara|\u67da\u539f \u30c1\u30ab|Yuzuhara Chika}}\n:{{voiced by|[[Eri Kitamura]]}}<ref name=\"cast2\"/>\n:Rikuo's ex-girlfriend.\n\n===Haru's Circle===\n;{{Nihongo|Minato|\u6e4a|Minato}}\n:{{voiced by|[[Y\u016bki Ono]]}}<ref name=\"cast2\"/>\n:Haru's ex-classmate who has been in love with her.\n;{{Nihongo|Ky\u014dko Sayama|\u72ed\u5c71 \u674f\u5b50|Sayama Ky\u014dko}}\n:{{voiced by|[[Maaya Sakamoto]]}}<ref name=\"cast2\"/>\n:Haru's employer. Owner of caf\u00e9 \"MILK HALL\".\n;{{Nihongo|Izawa|\u5c45\u6ca2|Izawa}}\n:{{voiced by|[[Maaya Sakamoto]]}}<ref name=\"cast2\"/>\n:Ky\u014dko's high school classmate who's been in love with her.\n;{{Nihongo|Amamiya|\u96e8\u5bae|Amamiya}}\n:Has been in pursuit of Haru ever since meeting her at a Christmas party.\n;{{Nihongo|Mimori|\u307f\u3082\u308a|Mimori}}\n:Amamiya's childhood friend.\n;{{Nihongo|Y\u014dko Akimoto|\u79cb\u672c \u967d\u5b50|Akimoto Y\u014dko}}\n:Haru's birth mother.\n;{{Nihongo|Sh\u014dgo Kawashima|\u5ddd\u5cf6 \u7701\u543e|Kawashima Sh\u014dgo}}\n:Haru's step-father.\n;{{Nihongo|Kansuke|\u30ab\u30f3\u30b9\u30b1|Kansuke}}\n:{{voiced by|Ry\u014dko Maekawa}}<ref name=\"cast2\"/>\n:Haru's pet crow.\n\n===Shinako's Circle===\n;{{Nihongo|Y\u016b Hayakawa|\u65e9\u5ddd \u6e67|Hayakawa Y\u016b}}\n:Shinako's childhood friend and R\u014d's brother. Died before the start of the series.\n;{{Nihongo|Morita|\u675c\u7530|Morita}}\n:{{voiced by|[[Kaori Nazuka]]}}<ref name=\"cast2\"/>\n:Shinako's co-worker.\n;{{Nihongo|Takako Kinoshita|\u6728\u30ce\u4e0b \u697c\u5b50|Kinoshita Takako}}\n:Shinako's student and Kinoshita's sister.\n;{{Nihongo|Izumi Fukamachi|\u6df1\u753a \u6cc9|Fukamachi Izumi}}\n:Takako's classmate and president of the film club.\n\n===R\u014d's Circle===\n;{{Nihongo|Katsumi Takishita|\u6edd\u4e0b \u514b\u7f8e|Takishita Katsumi}}\n:{{voiced by|[[Shun Horie]]}}<ref name=\"cast2\"/>\n:R\u014d's classmate at prep school.\n;{{Nihongo|Rio|\u8389\u7dd2|Rio}}\n:A model working at R\u014d's prep school. At some point R\u014d's girlfriend.\n;{{Nihongo|Misato Kuzuhara|\u845b\u539f \u672a\u91cc|Kuzuhara Misato}}\n:R\u014d's classmate at prep school. Katsumi's target of affection.\n;{{Nihongo|Natsuki Nakahara|\u4e2d\u539f \u590f\u6a39|Nakahara Natsuki}}\n:R\u014d's classmate at prep school. Funatsuka's girlfriend.\n;{{Nihongo|Funatsuka|\u8239\u585a|Funatsuka}}\n:R\u014d's classmate at prep school. Natsuki's boyfriend.\n\n==Media==\n===Manga===\n\n===Anime===\nAn [[anime]] television series adaptation was announced in the 10th issue of ''Grand Jump'' magazine on April 17, 2019.<ref name=\"ANN1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-04-12/kei-toume-sing-yesterday-for-me-manga-listed-with-tv-anime/.145625|title=Kei Toume's Sing 'Yesterday' for Me Manga Listed With TV Anime|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=April 12, 2019|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref>  The series is animated by [[Doga Kobo]] and directed by Yoshiyuki Fujiwara, with Fujiwara and Jin Tanaka writing the scripts and Junichir\u014d Taniguchi designing the characters.  DMM.futureworks is listed as producer. It premiered on April 4, 2020 on [[TV Asahi]]'s NUManimation block, [[AbemaTV]], and [[TV Asahi|BS Asahi]].<ref name=\"cast\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-11-19/sing-yesterday-for-me-anime-reveals-staff-visual-spring-2020-debut/.153480|title=Sing 'Yesterday' for Me Anime Reveals Staff, Visual, Spring 2020 Debut|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 19, 2019|accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref>  The series will run for 18 episodes, with the first 12 episodes airing on television and the last 6 episodes available through streaming on AbemaTV.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-01-21/sing-yesterday-for-me-anime-reveals-teaser-18-episode-length/.155626|title=Sing 'Yesterday' for Me Anime Reveals Teaser, 18-Episode Length|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 21, 2020|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"plainrowheaders wikitable\" style=\"width:98%; margin:auto; background:#FFF;\"\n|- style=\"border-bottom: 3px solid #CCF;\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n! Title<ref>{{cite web|url=https://singyesterday.com/story/|title=Story TV\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u300e\u30a4\u30a8\u30b9\u30bf\u30c7\u30a4\u3092\u3046\u305f\u3063\u3066\u300f\u516c\u5f0f\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8|accessdate=April 5, 2020|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n!Original air date\n|-\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 1\n| Title               = The Outcasts of Society Aiming to Change Themselves\n| TranslitTitle       = Shakai no Hamidashisha wa jiko henkaku wo mezasu\n| NativeTitle         = \u793e\u4f1a\u306e\u306f\u307f\u51fa\u3057\u8005\u306f\u81ea\u5df1\u5909\u9769\u3092\u76ee\u6307\u3059\n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|2020|4|4}}\n| ShortSummary        = Haru befriends Rikuo and visits him regularly before going to work. While encouraging him to attend the school reunion, Takanori tells Rikuo that Shinako is in town again to work. After Shinako pays him a visit at work he remembers why he liked her. While looking for inspiration for a good album cover, Rikuo comes across Haru who tells him they've met before. Rikuo finds out more about Haru while walking Shinako home. It was also that night that Haru confessed how she spent the last five years before talking to him. The next evening, Rikuo decides to confess his feelings to Shinako and get a closure. She turns him down. The day after that, Rikuo takes a picture of Haru for the album cover commissioned by Kinoshita. \n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 2\n| Title               = A Blind Alley\n| TranslitTitle       = Fukurokouji\n| NativeTitle         = \u888b\u5c0f\u8def\n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate  